<title>Feb_1993: Can Satan read my mind? (Or yours?)</title>
<h1>Can Satan read my mind? (Or yours?)</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>15 Feb 1993 16:43:32 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#138">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#138">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#138">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#138">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0139.html">Steven Timm: "Second International Adventist Worship Conference"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0137.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "The "thinking x's church""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0145.html">Lisa Parry: "Re: Can Satan read my mind? (Or yours?)"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Raylene and I were having a discussion with some friends last Saturcay<br>
afternoon, and the question came up, "Can Satan read a person's mind".<br>
<p>
Some members of the group said "definitely not", but couldn't come up<br>
with any Scriptural evidence, or even any quotes from EGW regarding<br>
this question. I wondered whether it was just wishful thinking to say<br>
that only God can read our thoughts.<br>
<p>
We have been charged with finding the answer before next weekend, so I<br>
thought that SDAnet would provide an invaluable resource in assisting<br>
us. So, to all the walking SOP libraries out there, (and even to those<br>
who just have the CD-ROM :-&gt; ), what is the consensus?<br>
<p>
(From personal experience I am inclined to think that maybe he can and<br>
does read my mind! Then again, maybe I *am* the devil. Who knows.)<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
