<title>Feb_1993: What is a cult ??</title>
<h1>What is a cult ??</h1>
<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>15 Feb 1993 10:48 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#140">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#140">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#140">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#140">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0141.html">Steven Timm: "Women's issues"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0139.html">Steven Timm: "Second International Adventist Worship Conference"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
      I have done quite a bit of reading on this topic and there<br>
    are certain characteristics of "cults" as a "cult" is defined<br>
    in a Christian stance.  One of the most prominent is that "our<br>
    group is God's channel of real truth, while all others are<br>
    lost in error."  When an LDS or Jehovah's Witness comes to my<br>
    door and we talk, I get the impression that they consider it<br>
    a "weakness" that I belong to one of many denominations.  But<br>
    actully I consider it a strength. I am a member of the Evangelical<br>
    Free Church of Hershey.  Neither our local congregation nor our<br>
    Denomination as a whole claim exclusive right to God.  If you were to<br>
    put me in a room with an LDS, a Jehovah's Witness, and someone from<br>
    Worldwide church of God, they would all have something in common.<br>
    They would each either publically or silently be completed convinced<br>
    in his/her mind that there particular group was "truly God's church"<br>
    and that the others were off base and in turn in heretical groups.<br>
    Hmm...how does this work??  Obviously three would be wrong ??<br>
    I believe that God is bigger than my organization.  We have no<br>
    leader's that we must pay homage to.  We are free to worship and serve<br>
    the Lord, without the baggage of "exclusiveness".<br>
<p>
    Well, thats all I have time for........<br>
    Eric Snyder<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
