<title>Feb_1993: Women's issues</title>
<h1>Women's issues</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Feb 1993 10:50:30 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#141">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#141">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#141">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#141">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0142.html">Susan Harrington: "Re:  Second International Adventist Worship Conference"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0140.html">ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "What is a cult ??"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0144.html">MARK BILBY: "Re: Women's issues"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm reminded of an entertaining discussion back in the heady days of the <br>
Washington Institute for Contemporary Issues (which I believe is now<br>
defunct).  Messrs. Londis, Cox, and Branson were among many VIP's who<br>
visited<br>
Pittsburgh for Uplink 88, a congress for the yuppies of the Columbia Union.<br>
They were leading a forum on women in ministry.  After hearing some glowing <br>
descriptions about how well things were going in that hotbed of liberalism<br>
known as Sligo, I felt obliged to give a reality check to these gentlemen.<br>
<p>
I reminded them that they had crossed a set of mountains to get to Pittsburgh<br>
and that things were different on this side.  Then as now ordaining women<br>
elders was basically unthinkable to most of the congregation. (It may<br>
have been attempted this year for the first time, they have changed<br>
officers since I was last there).   Then in the smaller churches one has<br>
the problem that the few qualified women are smart enough not to want<br>
the job. (as opposed to the unqualified men who have no such<br>
restrictions.)<br>
<p>
But now we hear from Susan Harrington, a resident of that same hotbed of<br>
liberalism, that all is not well even in a place like Sligo where there<br>
have<br>
been women on the staff as long as I can remember.  No doubt there is<br>
great disappointment over the 1990 action that was taken not to ordain<br>
women <br>
to the gospel ministry.  <br>
<p>
We must remember that the fight to give equal representation to people of <br>
color in the SDA church was long-fought and is still far from over.  And the <br>
arguments given in that fight were of the same nature.  If the womens<br>
movement is likened to the civil rights movement, where are we today<br>
historically?  I would say about 1965.  By that time some politicians<br>
had started paying lip service to the idea of civil rights and some<br>
legislation had passed, but there were still much more gains to be made.<br>
In the SDA church in 1965, CUC and Southern were still segregated.<br>
<p>
It's my fear that we are already seeing a kind of tokenism for women<br>
such as there is for Blacks in the N. A. church.  It's common knowledge<br>
that certain<br>
positions in the leadership are reserved for people of color, to be specific<br>
the secretaries of most unions.  In this way people can pay lip service to <br>
advancing this group but still retain control.  <br>
<p>
Similarly, we are now seeing the appointment of a woman associate pastor <br>
to the staffs of large liberal churches mainly as a status badge. <br>
Unfortunately, these positions are often the first to fall to the budget<br>
axe, and also place the woman under a great deal of scrutiny.  If any <br>
new and innovative programs are started for women at the expense of<br>
meeting the demands of the saints in the hospice, the woman pastor is<br>
also in trouble.<br>
<p>
The women on this net didn't ignore the fact that a woman posted that<br>
there were problems, and several men posted back with essentially,<br>
"no, everything is OK."  I am not a subscriber to the feminist agenda <br>
in general but I have seen enough of my female friends be victimized by <br>
the sexism in the church to know that there are problems that must be <br>
addressed.  It is easier to defend against a cheap shot sometimes than <br>
to address the underlying issues that caused the person to raise it.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
