<title>Feb_1993: Re: Women's issues</title>
<h1>Re: Women's issues</h1>
MARK BILBY (<i>76460.2613@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>15 Feb 93 14:06:57 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#144">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#144">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#144">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#144">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0145.html">Lisa Parry: "Re: Can Satan read my mind? (Or yours?)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0143.html">Ausberto Castro V.: "Re:  Symposium on networking in the SDA church"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0141.html">Steven Timm: "Women's issues"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0153.html">Lisa Parry: "people not cast"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Another aspect of this issue that has not been addressed is that women<br>
are not the only ones being kept from positions of power within the SDA<br>
church. It has been my observation that if a man does not come from the<br>
proper school, or is not a doctor, than they are treated as second class<br>
citizens and are placed on the deacon track. Once there, I don't recall<br>
ever seeing them become elders. A women married to a doctor is treated<br>
with more dignity. Other such methods of clique tracking include relatives<br>
accomplishments vs. individual achievements. <br>
<p>
I also wonder why the whole issue of women in the ministry is allowed to<br>
distract us from our true mission. I have witnessed attempts from several<br>
groups (most noticeably TEAM) that employ feminist tactics for indoctrinated<br>
without allowing for intelligent discourse. Any reasoning that centers around<br>
societal changes vis-a-vis EGW's day for changing our position seems to me<br>
to be a secularization of the Adventist doctrine to gain political popularity<br>
I also heard a whining that women who chose to major in theology were being<br>
denied job opportunities. I might want to point out that I have been denied<br>
job opportunities because I don't work on the Sabbath. It would be lunacy<br>
to demand that a future employer should bend over backwards because I want<br>
his job. Nothing is keeping any SDA women from ministering outside the <br>
denominational hierachy. But then again, the pay wouldn't be as high, <br>
would it?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
