<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Raylene and I were having a discussion with some friends last Saturcay</i><br>
<i>&gt; afternoon, and the question came up, "Can Satan read a person's mind".</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;...</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; us. So, to all the walking SOP libraries out there, (and even to those</i><br>
<i>&gt; who just have the CD-ROM :-&gt; ), what is the consensus?</i><br>
<p>
I'm no theologian, so this is probably 1 cent worth :)  <br>
<p>
Consider the possibility if Satan cannot read the mind.  Under that<br>
circumstance, he would need to rely on external evidence to find<br>
peculiar weaknesses to play on.  I'd say if this is the case, after<br>
6000 years of practice, he's a pretty good psychologist, expression<br>
reader, handwriting analyst, body language reader, and reader of<br>
other clues that give good ideas as to what is going on in the mind.<br>
<p>
Regardless of whether or not he can read actual thoughts, I doubt if<br>
he's confused often (unless God has some limits on him in this area,<br>
which will probably be confirmed by the SOP libraries if known to man :)<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
"If God is for us, who can be against us?"            Lisa Parry
--Romans 8:31, last sentence                   parry@andrews.edu
</pre>
