<title>Feb_1993: Re: Thinking man's church?</title>
<h1>Re: Thinking man's church?</h1>
Edward W. Fargusson (<i>72450.2430@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>15 Feb 93 12:35:53 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#148">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#148">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#148">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#148">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0149.html">Susan Harrington: "Re:  Second International Adventist Worship Conference"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0147.html">Michael Merginio: "Can Satan Read Minds???"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0126.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Thinking man's church?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl writes valuable points about women in the SDA church. I do not doubt <br>
that these are things she has personally witnessed as I too have witnessed <br>
some of what she mentions. I would not argue that our church has dealt fairly <br>
or honestly in all ways with women's issues. I still believe that the things <br>
she mentions go on in Adventist churches.<br>
<p>
I do wish to point out that many SDA churches are dealing with women's issues.<br>
I have the privilege of pastoring a church in a conservative area in Northern <br>
California which has had ordained women elders since 1978. Women actively <br>
participate in all aspects of church ministry. And interestingly enough, there<br>
are as many men single parents as there are women. Please don't get the idea <br>
that we are in a liberal area or are just and unusual phenomena. Tracy is a <br>
very conservative town in a very conservative area.<br>
<p>
My bragging about my church is not self glorification for I have only been <br>
here for a few months. The credit all goes to dedicated lay people who took it<br>
upon themselves to study scripture and put into practice what they learned. If<br>
our church wishes to deal with issues such as women's ordination and the role <br>
of women in the church, I suggest reading V. Norskov Olsen's book on <br>
priesthood, ordination and the church. I don't recall the exact title but you <br>
can get it through the Adventist Book Center.<br>
<p>
I offer this not as an excuse for our failures toward women, but only as one <br>
example of an SDA church that has and continues to deal with women's issues. I<br>
might add that we also work hard to make certain that our young people have an<br>
active role in the church and its decisions.<br>
<p>
Ed Fargusson (Compuserve 72450,2430)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
