<title>Feb_1993: RE: Women's issues</title>
<h1>RE: Women's issues</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Feb 93 11:27:45 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#150">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#150">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#150">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#150">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0151.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Thinking man's church?  or "The church with the Truth""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0149.html">Susan Harrington: "Re:  Second International Adventist Worship Conference"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I've always been uneasy about racism, sexism, and other "ism's" being <br>
supported by<br>
the church, from the Bible.  I don't think anyone is ever going to <br>
stand up in front of the<br>
GC session and say, "our missionaries have found another country to enter,<br>
and _replace_ their culture with our own."  No one is going to tell the <br>
truth, that prejudice<br>
is alive and well, on our school's campuses.  My high school principal <br>
took my girlfriend<br>
and I aside to encourage us to break up; Not because we were too young <br>
(me a senior),<br>
or sexually involved (which we weren't), but because we were of <br>
different races.<br>
"Well, why do you say that?", I asked.  "Because the Bible and Ellen G. <br>
White said so.",<br>
was the type of reply I got.<br>
<p>
We've got more *important* things to do with our time...<br>
The Numbers Game = educational endowments, tithes, baptisms; tradition, <br>
protecting<br>
"_the_ truth", filing lawsuits against sinners.  It's a bleak picture, <br>
once you really look at it.<br>
<p>
But it doesn't _have_ to be!  Any of us who are PRAYERFUL thinkers, can make a<br>
difference.  Our hearts, as a church are proud.  By surrendering to the <br>
will and character<br>
of God, I believe that many of our "ism's" will be taken away.  By <br>
*beholding* we become<br>
changed, from our earthly likeness, to God's divine likeness.<br>
<p>
It sounds too simple to be true!  Yet, thanks to my pastor doing a <br>
series on "Sin, sinless by<br>
making sin lists", many of us are finally accepting the simple gift of <br>
Christ's cleansing blood,<br>
and the power and fruits it bares in our daily lives.  This, in no way, <br>
means that being a<br>
Christian should make us status quo humans - - to the contrary!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
