<title>Feb_1993: Re:  Women on women</title>
<h1>Re:  Women on women</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Feb 1993 17:32:36 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#152">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#152">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#152">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#152">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0153.html">Lisa Parry: "people not cast"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0151.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Thinking man's church?  or "The church with the Truth""</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0136.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Women on women"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Sue Harrington sue@cuc.edu]<br>
The argument that women like their position and fight to maintain this<br>
subordinate position has been used to say that African-Americans liked<br>
being owned and serving "pink" persons in authority.  Perhaps the reason<br>
oppressed persons fight to maintain that position could be--If a woman<br>
derives her identity as a support system to her man she may be<br>
uncomfortable when other women find their identity in a different way. <br>
She might feel personally threatened.<br>
<p>
If we continue to have the decision making bodies of the church composed<br>
almost entirely of "pink" males our church will continue to address<br>
men's issues and concerns; to allocate resources to projects that favor<br>
men's involvement.  <br>
<p>
Another argument that has been used in this discussion:  why should the<br>
church address women's issues it doesn't address men's issues.  Perhaps<br>
we are not even aware of what are men's issues because for so long they<br>
have been identified as the issues of mankind.  I am using the term here<br>
with my tongue in my cheek.  We claim to be talking about all people<br>
when in fact we are only talking about men.<br>
<p>
Another argument:  things will get better if we just leave it in the<br>
Holy One's hands and be patient.  Well, dear net contributors, it might<br>
be wise to look at the figures and you will see that women have less<br>
involvement now than they had 100 years ago, than they had 10 years ago.<br>
 We are not progressively getting more involvement we are instead being<br>
lulled to sleep by well meaning persons.<br>
<p>
If we are indeed followers of the Holy One who lived among us we must<br>
challenge the leadership as Jesus did.  Withholding financial support<br>
until the leadership of the church reflects the composition of its<br>
membership is perhaps the most effective method available to us.<br>
<p>
Sue Harrington<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
