<title>Feb_1993: people not cast</title>
<h1>people not cast</h1>
Lisa Parry (<i>parry@peter.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Feb 1993 19:51:22 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#153">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#153">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#153">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#153">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What is a cult?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0152.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Women on women"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0144.html">MARK BILBY: "Re: Women's issues"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; church. It has been my observation that if a man does not come from the</i><br>
<i>&gt; proper school, or is not a doctor, than they are treated as second class</i><br>
<i>&gt; citizens and are placed on the deacon track. Once there, I don't recall</i><br>
<i>&gt; ever seeing them become elders. A women married to a doctor is treated</i><br>
<i>&gt; with more dignity. Other such methods of clique tracking include relatives</i><br>
<i>&gt; accomplishments vs. individual achievements. </i><br>
<p>
Hmmm, my father ran into this sort of thing.  He took a year off teaching<br>
to complete his doctoral degree.  He was a carpenter for that year.  I was<br>
at a new school that did not know him and his preaching and teaching abilities.<br>
Once he came to school to pick me up and found the principal fretting over <br>
a worship speaker cancelling out.  My father thought to be of help, and <br>
offered to fill it.  This was received with much surprise and distain.<br>
He was told that they'd find someone to cover it, not to worry.  Well, no<br>
one was found, and the worship was cancelled (just a gradeschool Monday<br>
morning worship).<br>
<p>
It was rather humorous looking from this side of things, but I doubt if<br>
it would be as humorous to a regular carpenter or other manual laborer.<br>
Because a person has not been trained to speak or teach doesn't mean they<br>
haven't learned.  I think it's important to dig for the real person rather<br>
than judging by externals.  Guess this is a growing process with the church<br>
too...<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
"If God is for us, who can be against us?"            Lisa Parry
--Romans 8:31, last sentence                   parry@andrews.edu
</pre>
