<title>Feb_1993: Works vs. Faith and Investigative Judgement</title>
<h1>Works vs. Faith and Investigative Judgement</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Feb 93 17:48:49 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#155">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#155">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#155">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#155">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0156.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What is a cult?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have a question that I would like some enlightened comments.  I DO NOT<br>
want to renew the discussion on salvation by works or faith.  What I want<br>
is for those that have different views on the role of works in salvation<br>
to comment on the purpose of "The Investigative Judgement".<br>
<p>
First, what is the IJ?<br>
What occurs during IJ?<br>
What is reviewed during IJ?<br>
Who is reviewed?<br>
Why are they reviewed?<br>
What decision is made during IJ?<br>
<p>
Then, explain to me (as you understand it) how works fit into this (if it does)?<br>
The obvious dilemma:  if we are saved by grace through faith and works are<br>
irrelevant, why is there an investigative judgement?  If works matter in the<br>
sense of reflecting our commitment and relationship to Christ, what is the<br>
purpose of the IJ?  If works matter a great deal and have impact on whether<br>
we are saved (by your own theology), is the IJ important and why?<br>
<p>
Thanks for your thoughtful replies.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<p>
