<title>Feb_1993: Women and the SDA Church</title>
<h1>Women and the SDA Church</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Feb 93 19:55:59 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#156">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#156">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#156">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#156">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0157.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Satan reading minds"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0155.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Works vs. Faith and Investigative Judgement"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
We've had a lot of responses to my posting about women in the SDA Church.<br>
(Mostly male because most SDAnetters are male.)  But here's one of the<br>
classical male "nonthinking" responses to a very real problem:<br>
<p>
"I also heard a whining that women who chose to major in theology were being<br>
denied job opportunities. I might want to point out that I have been denied<br>
job opportunities because I don't work on the Sabbath. It would be lunacy<br>
to demand that a future employer should bend over backwards because I want<br>
his job. Nothing is keeping any SDA women from ministering outside the<br>
denominational hierachy. But then again, the pay wouldn't be as high,<br>
would it?<br>
<p>
This is the type of thinking that infuriates the oppressed.  Why should<br>
women have to go outside the denomination to minister?  Do SDA men go<br>
to the seminary and plan for a life of ministry OUTSIDE the SDA Church?<br>
How many SDA ministers actually take a ministerial job OUTSIDE the SDA<br>
Church?  And the pay?  The pay would probably be higher OUTSIDE the SDA<br>
Church!  But women who are totally committed to the truths and beliefs<br>
of the SDA Church would have a difficult time ministering under other<br>
doctrinal frameworks just as any SDA male.  Yes, women who major in<br>
theology are being actively and oppressively denied jobs in the SDA<br>
church.  Do they not have an equal duty and right to serve their church<br>
in the way they've been trained?<br>
<p>
A lot of SDAnetters cited numerous churches where women were ordained as<br>
ELDERS.  Well folks, ELDER does not equal PASTOR!  Yes, there are a few<br>
SDA female pastor but they ARE NOT ORDAINED MINISTERS.  These female pastors<br>
can do everything an ordained minister can EXCEPT receive fair compensation<br>
for doing that work.  That's all there is to it.  It don't care if every<br>
elder in America was a women.  Until the SDA church is composed of 50%<br>
female ORDAINED MINISTERS, the SDA church is still a "man's church."  Until<br>
the selfish men at the top relinquish their most cherished power to control<br>
the SDA church, it is a man's church.  When will the SDA church have their<br>
first female conference president?  How about even a local conference<br>
secretary or vice president?  Not until women can be ordained because only<br>
ORDAINED MINISTERS can be employed in that capacity.  How many male ministers<br>
support ordination of women?  How many would be willing to give up their<br>
jobs to even up the stats?  Should they have to give up their jobs?  No, but<br>
shouldn't the seminary accept a disproportionate number of women to start<br>
equalizing the numbers?  Shouldn't there be 2 females hired for every 1 male<br>
minister?  Would there be equal representation in 50 years?  The very weak<br>
objections to the ordination of women in SDA theology smacks sexism.  I<br>
fail to understand how a church that was started by a woman (EGW) and who<br>
recognized a female prophet for over 50 years, could with clear conscience<br>
continue with this obvious discrimination.  To the world, the SDA witness<br>
says that women are equal to men in theory but the men in the church don't<br>
love God and the women enough to make it a reality.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
