<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Tue, 16 Feb 1993 10:02:35 -0500 (EST)" -->
<!-- name="Steven Timm" -->
<!-- email="st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Re: What is a cult?" -->
<!-- id="IfUE8=C00YUoIxUI5=@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="What is a cult?" -->
<title>Feb_1993: Re: What is a cult?</title>
<h1>Re: What is a cult?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Feb 1993 10:02:35 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#158">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#158">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#158">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#158">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0159.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Women and the church of LDS"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0157.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Satan reading minds"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0130.html">cheryl berthelsen: "What is a cult?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Drew Corrigan]<br>
Woody writes:<br>
<i>&gt; Herb Armstrongs Worldwide Church of God, yes, Jehovah's witness no.</i><br>
<p>
As a member of the WCoG I would like to make a comment on this point.<br>
To the best of my knowledge, Mr Armstrong was never associated with the<br>
SDA church other than having read your literature at the time when he<br>
was being called to repentance and was researching the issue of the <br>
Sabbath and other doctrines (even as I and numerous other WCoG members<br>
have probably done).<br>
<p>
[Some SDA folklore I have heard indicates that Armstrong's wife was an SDA<br>
at one time.  Any truth to this?  SCT]<br>
<p>
In fact, Mr Armstrong was ordained a minister of the Oregon (sp?)<br>
Conference of the Church of God 7th Day. The Churches in the Conference<br>
were only loosely associated and essentially autonomous. When a leading<br>
personality (Mr Andrew Dugger) in the Conference decided to reform the<br>
governmental structure along other lines there was disagreement and<br>
the Conference effectively dissolved leaving local congregations to<br>
administer themselves as they saw fit. Mr Armstrong's congregation<br>
supported him in his evangelical campaigns and in time that church chose<br>
to incorporate under the name Radio Church of God and later Worldwide<br>
Church of God in order to distinguish itself from the myriad of other<br>
Churches of God.<br>
<p>
So far as the Church of God 7th Day goes, it is my understanding (having<br>
read histories written by ministers of the CoG7D) that it was not an<br>
"offshoot" of the SDA Church. As I recall the story, prior to the meeting<br>
at Battle Creek (1860s?) when the name "Seventh Day Adventist" was chosen<br>
by Mrs White, there was no generally agreed upon title, though many in<br>
the 7th day movement used the term "Church of God".  When the title<br>
"Seventh Day Adventist" was chosen, a schism occured, a smaller portion of<br>
the Church wishing to retain the title "Church of God", while the majority<br>
chose "Seventh Day Adventist" (on the basis that it was more distinctive).<br>
<p>
[I believe Adventist literature refers to this group as the "Messenger Party"<br>
They developed a separate identity in the mid-1850's before the name <br>
Seventh-day Adventist was chosen.  SCT]<br>
<p>
Those retaining the title "Church of God" eventually became the CoG7D.<br>
They also retained the idea of the millenium being on earth with Jesus<br>
ruling with the saints from the Jerusalem, and chose not to acknowledge <br>
Mrs White as a prophet among other things.<br>
<p>
Thus, we do not consider ourselves as an offshoot of the SDA Church <br>
though we claim a common history prior to the days of the schism.<br>
<p>
On another point, Eric Snyder wrote:<br>
<i>&gt;Neither our local congregation nor our</i><br>
<i>&gt;Denomination as a whole claim exclusive right to God.  If you were to</i><br>
<i>&gt;put me in a room with an LDS, a Jehovah's Witness, and someone from</i><br>
<i>&gt;Worldwide church of God, they would all have something in common.</i><br>
<i>&gt;They would each either publically or silently be completed convinced</i><br>
<i>&gt;in his/her mind that there particular group was "truly God's church"</i><br>
<i>&gt;and that the others were off base and in turn in heretical groups.</i><br>
<p>
Our current understanding and teaching is that the WCoG does *NOT* claim<br>
to have the "corner on the market" with regards to salvation. I will agree<br>
that at times in the past we have claimed to be be God's one true Church,<br>
though even here as I reread some of Mr Armstrong's writings there is a<br>
degree of ambiguity involved because we have never claimed that the CoG7D<br>
(for example) ceased to be a part of God's church as the WCoG took on a<br>
separate identity. At any rate, we now acknowledge that God is bigger than<br>
the WCoG and we do not hold to exclusivist views. To be fair, I would say<br>
however, that we believe we are holding more closely to the original form<br>
of worship and doctrine practised by the NT Church. (If we did not believe<br>
this, there would be no point in us existing as a distinct body of<br>
believers :-))<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I believe that God is bigger than my organization.</i><br>
<p>
Ditto.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;We have no leader's that we must pay homage to.</i><br>
<p>
For the sake of a little humour (though it is quite serious in another<br>
sense) ... the WCoG does pay homage to its Leader. We regard him as a <br>
Prophet (Acts 3:22) and in fact he has been alive for the past 1960+ <br>
years ...<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
