<title>Feb_1993: Re: Women and the SDA Church</title>
<h1>Re: Women and the SDA Church</h1>
Drew Corrigan (<i>Drew.Corrigan@cs.anu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Feb 1993 17:05:37 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#160">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#160">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#160">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#160">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0161.html">Daniel Turk: "thinking [person's] church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0159.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Women and the church of LDS"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0167.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0183.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl, could you briefly describe what role(s) women occupy in the<br>
CoJCoLDS? Can they be ordained as full-fledged ministers?<br>
<p>
For your information, the WCoG does not ordain women as elders. It does <br>
ordain them as deaconesses, but this carries no formal opportunities to<br>
teach or speak. The reason we do not ordain women is because we follow<br>
the NT example where (apparently) only men were ordained as elders. <br>
<p>
I would say that this is not an issue in the WCoG. No one in the WCoG<br>
chooses to be a minister (or deaconess or deacon). Though various ones<br>
are trained in ministerial responsibilities, it is really a matter of<br>
the established ministry perceiving a need somewhere and then (after<br>
prayer and fasting) choosing a man to be a minister or a deacon or a<br>
woman to be a deaconess, as the case may be, to fill that need. (Actually,<br>
we believe it is God who guides the choosing. He "sets us in the Body<br>
where it pleases him".) Race is not a factor in choosing someone for<br>
an office and virtually all racial groups are represented in the ministry.<br>
<p>
When men are ordained as ministers, their wives are regarded as 50% of that<br>
ministry. This was even reflected in the way they were paid at one point <br>
- 50% of salary cheque made out to husband, 50% of salary cheque made out <br>
to wife. (I'm not sure how salaries are handled now that electronic banking<br>
is the norm.)<br>
<p>
The above being said, please do not think that the WCoG "oppresses" women.<br>
Women enjoy the same rights and opportunities as men in the Church and<br>
there is no discrimination on the basis of sex. [Needless to say, being<br>
ordained to an office is not regarded by us as a "right" - it is a position<br>
chosen by God - no issue of "rights" is involved to our way of thinking.]<br>
I think our male/female ratio is probably pretty close to 50/50 - if<br>
anything, there are probably more men than women in the Church. If our <br>
numbers were a lot bigger (presently at an all-time high of near 100,000 <br>
baptised members), maybe this would be an issue - I honestly can't say.<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
