<title>Feb_1993: thinking [person's] church</title>
<h1>thinking [person's] church</h1>
Daniel Turk (<i>turk@peter.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Feb 1993 08:07:00 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#161">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#161">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#161">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#161">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0162.html">Warren C Trenchard: "A Call for Healing"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0160.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hello there!<br>
<p>
I don't write often on SDA net - I mostly read.  But had to respond to<br>
the "Thinking Man's Church" thread.<br>
<p>
First, let me introduce myself.  I currently work at Andrews University,<br>
as an Assistant Professor of Computer Science.  This is my 5th year of<br>
teaching here, after 2 years of working on my MS CS degree.  My wife<br>
(Carol Hurley Turk) works at Andrews Academy, and we both enjoy Berrien<br>
Springs, Michigan, life quite well.  Other than, as one person put it,<br>
"having to climb an apple tree to get a sense of elevation", we wouldn't<br>
change much about the place.  We both like outdoor activities very much<br>
(hiking, backpacking, snow skiiing, rock climbing - in other locales!),<br>
have just celebrated our 8th anniversary, and are looking forward to<br>
many more years together!  We are both fairly active in our local<br>
church, Pioneer Memorial Church (PMC), though would like to be part of<br>
the process of making our SDA church a better place for ourselves and<br>
everyone else who is a part of it.<br>
<p>
Now, back to "thinking people".<br>
<p>
I guess what I'm wanting to say is that however we say it, "thinking<br>
women's church",  "thinking man's", "thinking person's".....  I don't<br>
think that the SDA Church has (at least in my recent memory) been a<br>
place that likes thinking people.  Thus, I'd propose that it isn't a<br>
thinking person's church no matter what word is used to describe the<br>
sexuality of the person of reference.  My main perception (maybe this is<br>
changing now) has been that if you THINK, and if you QUESTION the church<br>
leadership, whether this is at the local, conference, union, or GC<br>
level, then you are not accepted.  I'd like to think that this is<br>
changing, and that someday (soon) the SDA church WILL be a "thinking<br>
person's" church, but right now it is hard to see that coming when<br>
everywhere thinking, questioning, etc is so unaccepted.<br>
<p>
Let me know YOUR thoughts and experiences!  Have a good day!<br>
<p>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Dan Turk     Computer Science &amp; Information Systems     Andrews University<br>
Berrien Springs, MI          turk@andrews.edu               (616) 471-3426<br>
==========================================================================<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
