<title>Feb_1993: Re: Thinking man's church?  or "The church with the Truth"</title>
<h1>Re: Thinking man's church?  or "The church with the Truth"</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Feb 1993 21:50:41 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#163">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#163">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#163">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#163">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0164.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: Women and the church of LDS -- Also blacks"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0162.html">Warren C Trenchard: "A Call for Healing"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0151.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Thinking man's church?  or "The church with the Truth""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave's comments are well taken.  I guess I better expound some more.  I lead<br>
a rather spirited SS class when I teach.  I try *VERY* hard to get the class<br>
to think for them selves.  I tend to be quite philospohical in outlook, and<br>
tend to explore deep subjects (the kind that if you think about them, raise<br>
more and more questions).  I find that I get much intellectual stimulus from<br>
SS, we have some very keen minds that ask really probing questions in our<br>
church.  One does not approach the understanding of Revalation, and Daniel<br>
with a quick glossing over. It takes some real digging, and understanding.<br>
It takes a lot of thinking to put it together.  That is one aspect of<br>
"thinking".  The other aspect of thinking is serious questing for truth, and<br>
understanding.  Again, you can't approach this on a superficial level.  Question<br>
and study for your self.  One should not necessarily take the word of someone<br>
else for something.  Understanding how people relate on one another, is another<br>
facet of the same thing.  Sometime, perhaps I'll get around to sharing with<br>
the net, some research that I did way back in undergrad days that convinced<br>
me to turn off the Television.  Several times in SS class we have gotten into<br>
that topic, and analyzed the where's and whyfore's of TV.  One of my SS<br>
students once said, "when Woody teaches the class, you might not get through<br>
the lesson, but you sure know all the implications and issues".<br>
HOWEVER, I try very hard not to get into doctrine to heavily.  It is a quick<br>
way to lose a new convert.  Doctrine is important, because it is the glue<br>
that really cements the church together, and makes it unique, but you HAVE<br>
to go easy.<br>
<p>
This all reminds me of a story I once heard.  A circuit riding preacher<br>
stopped at his scheduled church one sunday, and was quite dismayed to find<br>
only one old farmer sitting in the church.  Being a dedicated man of the cloth,<br>
the preacher plowed right into the service, and when time came to preach<br>
the sermon, he really got going. An hour and a half later he wound down.<br>
As he was shaking the farmers hand after the service, he asked the man<br>
how the service was.  the farmer said, "when I go to feed the cows, and<br>
only one is there, I feed him, but not the whole bale".  <br>
<p>
or something like that<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
<p>
woody@knapper.cactus.org
woody@chinacat.unicom.com (temporary) is forwareded to woody@knapper
</pre>
