<title>Feb_1993: Re: Women and the SDA Church</title>
<h1>Re: Women and the SDA Church</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Feb 93 12:38:44 -0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#165">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#165">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#165">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#165">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0166.html">Tim Swensen: "women`s ordination"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0164.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: Women and the church of LDS -- Also blacks"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0169.html">Lisa Parry: "Seminary"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Feb 15,  7:55pm, cheryl berthelsen wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Women and the SDA Church</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; A lot of SDAnetters cited numerous churches where women were ordained as</i><br>
<i>&gt; ELDERS.  Well folks, ELDER does not equal PASTOR!  Yes, there are a few</i><br>
<i>&gt; SDA female pastor but they ARE NOT ORDAINED MINISTERS.  These female pastors</i><br>
<i>&gt; can do everything an ordained minister can EXCEPT receive fair compensation</i><br>
<i>&gt; for doing that work.  That's all there is to it.  It don't care if every</i><br>
<i>&gt; elder in America was a women.  Until the SDA church is composed of 50%</i><br>
<i>&gt; female ORDAINED MINISTERS, the SDA church is still a "man's church."</i><br>
<p>
I have to disagree with this last statement.  To say that unless a church has a<br>
female minister, it is not fit for women consumption is taking it abit too far.,<br>
Women are welcome and should be welcome to call it their church regardless of<br>
the sex or race of the ministor/pastor.  What difference should it make?  I am<br>
talking about attendence here, not jobs.  Now as for jobs go, I don't see or<br>
hear of very many women actively going into the ministry.  Until you do, you<br>
won't achieve a 50% ratio that you seek/demand in a very long time.  True, many<br>
may be discourage to go into that profession due to the difficulties their<br>
predicessors encountered, but I still think that not very many women DESIRE to<br>
become ministers.  Some professions are just that way.  I don't see very many<br>
women construction workers or electrical engineers...they exist! but I don't see<br>
50% or even close to that.  When we have &gt;50% women graduating in theology at<br>
the seminary, then we have reason to make this a burning issue.  My point is, I<br>
don't see nearly as many women DESIRING to become ministers as I do men.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Until</i><br>
<i>&gt; the selfish men at the top relinquish their most cherished power to control</i><br>
<i>&gt; the SDA church, it is a man's church.  When will the SDA church have their</i><br>
<i>&gt; first female conference president?</i><br>
<p>
When will we have our first female president of the USA?  Why doesn't more women<br>
run for presidency?  Why do they not make it?  If women were so hot to get a<br>
female president of this country, then why can't they even get one on a major<br>
party ticket to run?  Why did a majority of women still vote for a male<br>
president with a male vp instead of a president with a female vp?<br>
<p>
I believe society as a whole (including women) still prefer a man to hold the<br>
position of leadership of this country.  Why would it be expected to be<br>
different in a subset of this culture called the SDA church?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; How about even a local conference</i><br>
<i>&gt; secretary or vice president?  Not until women can be ordained because only</i><br>
<i>&gt; ORDAINED MINISTERS can be employed in that capacity.  How many male ministers</i><br>
<i>&gt; support ordination of women?  How many would be willing to give up their</i><br>
<i>&gt; jobs to even up the stats?  Should they have to give up their jobs?  No, but</i><br>
<i>&gt; shouldn't the seminary accept a disproportionate number of women to start</i><br>
<i>&gt; equalizing the numbers?  Shouldn't there be 2 females hired for every 1 male</i><br>
<i>&gt; minister?  Would there be equal representation in 50 years?  The very weak</i><br>
<i>&gt; objections to the ordination of women in SDA theology smacks sexism.  I</i><br>
<i>&gt; fail to understand how a church that was started by a woman (EGW) and who</i><br>
<i>&gt; recognized a female prophet for over 50 years, could with clear conscience</i><br>
<i>&gt; continue with this obvious discrimination.  To the world, the SDA witness</i><br>
<i>&gt; says that women are equal to men in theory but the men in the church don't</i><br>
<i>&gt; love God and the women enough to make it a reality.</i><br>
<p>
This is not a matter of love IMHO.  I am not against granting the women that<br>
want to be ministers the ordination they seek provided they meet the<br>
qualifications that a man has to meet up to for the same.  I agree that there is<br>
some discrimination in the upper ranks of the leadership.  I wish it were not<br>
so.  Women are as capable or even more so in some things compared with men but<br>
this is not true for all areas.  I believe the Bible supports the idea of men in<br>
leadership roles.<br>
<p>
But you speak as if there is a large number of women clammering to get it but<br>
being denied this access.  I can believe there are some but not large numbers.<br>
 If you can substantiate these claims with even a statement that you know or<br>
have heard of x number of women that have been denied, I'd like to know about<br>
it.  I don't think the seminary denies a disproportionate number of women to<br>
men.  I am not saying that it doesn't happen...i just would be surprised.<br>
<p>
I really think that society as a whole still feels more comfortable with male<br>
leadership than female.  This goes back to Biblical days.  How many women<br>
prophets were there compared to men prophets?  How about disciples?  How about<br>
most of the stories of patriarchs and other heroric leaders.  Most were men.<br>
 Does this make it right or wrong...I don't know but I can say that when society<br>
as a whole desires to have more women in roles they before haven't been in<br>
before, then so be it.  But please stop flaming the SDA church because it<br>
doesn't fall in line with your goals or desires.  We are part of a society that<br>
traditionally likes men in leadership roles.  That's da facts, mam! (IMHO)<br>
<p>
By the way, how does the LDS church stack up to equivalent questions?<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
