<title>Feb_1993: women`s ordination</title>
<h1>women`s ordination</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Feb 93 11:15:46 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#166">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#166">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#166">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#166">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0167.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0165.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
We have heard much already on the issue of women's ordination.  I get the <br>
impression that most of the contributors to this discussion accept as an <br>
established fact that the Pauline passages such as "I do not allow a woman<br>
to teach" and "An elder must be the husband of one wife" do not apply (at <br>
least in this form) today.  Is this the consensus?  <br>
<p>
I am not convinced that we are being truthful in our hermeneutics.  What <br>
principle is Paul establishing in such passages?  I feel the Net is bypassing<br>
an important aspect of this topic.  Here are some questions we need to answer:<br>
<p>
     1.  Does scripture have anything to say to this the issue of women's <br>
         ordination, given that North American society offers women increasing<br>
         rights and privileges as compared with the Middle East centuries ago?<br>
<p>
     2.  If it does (as I believe) have something to say regarding this issue,<br>
         what is it?  (This really gets at a larger issue -- namely that of<br>
         the relative importance of considering the culture of the times when<br>
         extracting biblical principles and applying them today.)<br>
<p>
Must the discussion descend into numerous accusations of men being unloving and <br>
unChristlike because they refuse to give women their "rights?"  It is not at<br>
all clear to me that this is merely an issue of justice.  We need more<br>
thorough scriptural discussion on this issue.<br>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0167.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0165.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
</DOC>
