</DOCHDR>
<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Tue, 16 Feb 1993 11:48:20 -0500 (EST)" -->
<!-- name="Harvey Brenneise" -->
<!-- email="brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Women and the SDA Church" -->
<!-- id="9302161648.AA28420@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Feb_1993: Women and the SDA Church</title>
<h1>Women and the SDA Church</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Feb 1993 11:48:20 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#167">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#167">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#167">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#167">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0168.html">Steven Timm: "More Women's Issues"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0166.html">Tim Swensen: "women`s ordination"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0160.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It's interesting to me how a comment on another subject (thinking in the<br>
church) which was careless in its gender-inclusiveness (thinking<br>
_man's_ church) started a discussion on the role of women in the church.<br>
It is well for all of us to be gender inclusive in our language, not<br>
because it's PC, but because it's right.  I do not believe the orginal<br>
remark, however, was meant to be deliberately offensive.  However, along<br>
with Cheryl, I also was offended by the remarks quoted in her posting of<br>
15 Feb.  I also do not believe women who are "called" (whatever that is)<br>
should have to go outside the church to minister.  As to pay, that<br>
raises other interesting issues.  I've seen surveys that show that SDA<br>
pastors are paid at or above the average of other clergy (nor sure<br>
whether that includes Catholic priests or not, but certainly would<br>
include the fundamentalist type).  At any rate, pay rates would<br>
certainly vary from denomination to denomination, and even church to<br>
church (my local Lutheran friends think the Adventist system is better<br>
than their own on the latter point).  However, the determination of SDA<br>
clergy (at least some of them) to make sure that their pay is higher<br>
than any other denominational worker (other than medical, and there are<br>
some who wonder if they are really denominational workers at all!) is<br>
oppressive.  It certainly makes it difficult to hire professionals in<br>
many areas, including lawyers, college faculty, accountants, etc.  But<br>
that's a different topic.<br>
<p>
Unfortunately, I would have to agree with Cheryl that women pastors are<br>
being actively and oppressively denied pastoral jobs in many<br>
(fortunately not all) locations.  I only have to look out my office<br>
window to see one such church--Pioneer Memorial Church, which should be<br>
an example to the world church.  We have had women elders (only after a<br>
huge fuss) for about 5 years now, but no sign that we will get any<br>
female pastors, even though this desire has been plainly made to the<br>
pastoral staff.  Unfortunately, the pastoral staff and the conference<br>
staff are, I believe, doing exactly what Cheryl charges them with.<br>
There has already been enough time for something to do done, and at<br>
least some members of that congregation (myself included) are angry that<br>
nothing has been done.  This is the example that the seminary students<br>
see.<br>
<p>
I agree that elders are not pastors (although an important step in the<br>
right direction).  I'm not sure at present, exactly what the differences<br>
are, in practical terms, between ordained and unordained ministers<br>
(other than the need to be ordained to be in certain positions).  Does<br>
someone else on the net know what differences there are in pay and<br>
pastoral duties?  It seems that baptizing has been seen as for ordained<br>
only, although in some places female pastors have baptized.  Regardless<br>
of the practical sameness or differentness, even if it is totally<br>
symbolic (which it isn't), symbolism is still important.  It is for this<br>
reason that I believe some ordained ministers have threatened to give up<br>
their ordination until women are ordained.<br>
<p>
However, I disagree with Cheryl about the desirability to set a quota<br>
for female pastors.  For one thing, this assumes that as many women as<br>
men _want_ to become pastors.  At present, this does not appear to be<br>
the case, though of course there could be many reasons for this (there<br>
are many disincentives, to be sure).  I am in favor of much greater<br>
support for and encouragement of women to make this choice (this will be<br>
hard until women can be ordained).  I don't believe in quotas in any<br>
case.  For example, just because the library field is between 70 and 80<br>
percent female, I don't accept it as a "female profession."  I don't<br>
demand that libraries hire 50% men (although I think society has tended<br>
not to value librarians, with adequate compensation among other things,<br>
because of the common misperception).  There are also interesting<br>
gender differences between academic and public libraries (with public<br>
libraries much more female [and lower pay], and academic libraries with<br>
more male librarians [though closer to half]).  Academic library pay is<br>
closely related to campus pay, and thus higher.  I have noticed in the<br>
professional literature, however, that public libraries have been<br>
encouraged to make sure that their collections appeal to men as well as<br>
to women (i.e. more non fiction).  Enough on that.<br>
<p>
Again, I can't speak for the seminary (though I can see it also out my<br>
window!), I think I should say a few things about it (Nancy Vymeister<br>
can correct me if I'm wrong).  First, the seminary practices open<br>
admission (or virtually so), except for the doctoral programs.  In fact,<br>
this outsider would say they virtually take any warm body that shows up,<br>
and has money to pay the fees (which are much more heavily<br>
church-subsidized than other campus programs).  I should think the<br>
seminary would accept many more women, but they've got to apply.  I do<br>
not believe that an institution, like Andrews University, that accepts<br>
government aid to students can adopt a deliberately discriminatory<br>
admission policy that is suggested (and I really don't think a dedicated<br>
feminist really wants to open up that bottle).  It should also be<br>
pointed out that admission to the seminary has little or no relationship<br>
to (and is certainly no guarantee for) landing a job with a conference.<br>
Lack of admission standards has been a sore point with the seminary<br>
faculty for years, and we have accepted many academically poor students<br>
over the years.  Many students don't really want to be here, and don't<br>
really want to learn anything.  Really, it's rather pathetic.  Those who<br>
want to become ministers are either self-selected or God-selected,<br>
depending on how you react to the idea of receiving "a call."  We've<br>
seen some pretty nutty people (not to mention some that aren't very<br>
intelligent) feel very strongly "called."  Perhaps we need to encourage<br>
more women to feel "called."  <br>
<p>
However, there is certainly one thing that the Seminary should be doing,<br>
and there's some evidence that they're beginning to see the need for<br>
this:  stopping the harrassment of female seminary students by male<br>
ones.  This topic was recently raised in the student newspaper here, and<br>
conversations with female seminary students over the years convince me<br>
that it is a real problem.  Sometimes it appears to me that seminary<br>
students are among the most out of touch with the times.  There are<br>
still many who consider the ministry to be a male club, and who resent<br>
any "intrusion" by women, and this includes female seminary students.  I<br>
don't know all the harrassment techniques used, but these types find<br>
many ways to make the female students feel unwelcome.  I don't have any<br>
direct evidence that faculty are part of the problem, but at the least<br>
those who allow this kind of behavior are as much a part of the problem<br>
as those (if there are any) who engage in such behavior themselves.<br>
<p>
Well, I do believe I've written enough today to get myself in trouble,<br>
so will quit.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
