<title>Feb_1993: More Women's Issues</title>
<h1>More Women's Issues</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Feb 1993 17:53:51 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#168">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#168">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#168">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#168">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0169.html">Lisa Parry: "Seminary"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0167.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
We are getting to the place where this issue is generating more heat<br>
than light.  The questions about women in the LDS church begged to be<br>
asked, <br>
but I am not sure I want to see them answered here.  SDAnet has no business<br>
discussing the problems of another denomination when we can't solve our own.<br>
<p>
The question of ordination in general and women's ordination in specific<br>
is a burning theological issue which for the most part is hidden by politics.<br>
Most of the hardship being inflicted on women in the church currently has <br>
not to do with the lack of ordination, but what the political consequences<br>
of ordination are in today's church.<br>
<p>
Immediately if not sooner, we should:<br>
1) Remove the pay differential between ordained and non-ordained ministers<br>
2) Remove ordination or lack thereof as a qualification for career<br>
advancement and continued employment<br>
3) Return to the initial SDA policy of not requiring conference officers<br>
to be ordained ministers<br>
4) Enforce the existing guidelines on sexual harassment in SDA schools <br>
and workplaces<br>
5) Create opportunities within the SDA ministry that will not force women to <br>
choose between their families and their career.  (#'s 4 and 5 also apply<br>
to the teaching profession.)<br>
<p>
You will find that those who oppose the ordination of women will most likely<br>
oppose all five of the above measures as well, even though they have nothing<br>
to do with the spiritual functions of a minister.  It's an unfortunate<br>
fact that the biggest blow struck for women's rights in the SDA church<br>
was a <br>
lawsuit, the Merikay Silver case (after which my mother's salary nearly<br>
doubled).  Will legal action be required again? I would hope not but it <br>
is probably already being considered by some. <br>
<p>
When ordination is stripped of the political plums that accompany it, <br>
then it will be easier to focus on the spiritual issues.  Such as:<br>
<p>
1) Is ordination a sacrament bestowed by the church or a recognition of <br>
an existing call by the Holy Spirit?<br>
<p>
2) What are the larger implications of Bible interpretation that <br>
construes 2 Tim 2:11,12 to allow the ordination of women?<br>
<p>
Too often we tend to cast the whole debates in terms of rights, namely<br>
that women demand the right to be ordained to the gospel ministry<br>
and men claim the right to exclude them.  If the men of the church had cared<br>
more about preserving the rights of women through the years, women would not<br>
now be in a situation where they have to speak up for themselves.  <br>
<p>
If we could return to a consensus model of church governance, where<br>
everyone is concerned with preserving the rights of others rather than<br>
demanding their own, the problems would still exist, but the noise level<br>
would be a lot lower.  It seems to me that proof by CAPS LOCK is not the<br>
way to build consensus.  If we want to argue about womens issues we can<br>
each go to <br>
our local churches and do that.  SDAnet is not for rehashing old arguments,<br>
but for sharing viewpoints and building consensus.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
