<title>Feb_1993: Quotas</title>
<h1>Quotas</h1>
Dan Gill (<i>dangle@netcom.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Feb 93 16:36:27 -0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#171">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#171">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#171">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#171">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0172.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Women on women  (whoops!)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0170.html">Steven Timm: "Question on Great Controversy in Mexico"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have heard many statements lately about the church being not a nice<br>
place until 50% of ministers are women.  Well, the church's job is to bring<br>
the message of Christ to the world.  In this we need the best people to<br>
do the job.  In this search for excellence, we pick whomever it may be<br>
that is best suited for the job to fill at hand.  If we are now being<br>
required to fill a quota, we are now being restricted on this search for<br>
excellence.  <br>
<p>
One of the lessons that we need to learn in this world is that it doesn't<br>
always _seem_ fair.   Fact is, there are times when it isn't fair.  And<br>
that creeps into the churh, surprizingly enough.  But that doesn't mean<br>
that we get to take our toys and go home.  This is stil the greatest<br>
church on earth.  Not because of who we are, or what we have, but because<br>
of who we know!<br>
<p>
One of the problems in this battle is you have the &lt;liberals&gt;, and <br>
&lt;conservatives&gt;, each on one side of a table, and neither wants to <br>
"lose".  Because when one special interest's agenda gets approved, another's<br>
gets disapproved.  Thus someone has to "lose".  We are just too proud<br>
and selfish to buckle down, study the _entire_ issue, speak frankly about<br>
why we feel/think the way we do, and move forward.  We are caught up<br>
in the political process.  We can't make a move that would alienate this<br>
group because we need their votes at the next constituency meeting.  We<br>
have to move cautiously to prevent that group from being offended.   I<br>
say let's get on with the process of discovering all of the issues and get<br>
on with the job at hand.  Which you'd all agree is delivering the message<br>
to the world.<br>
<p>
thanks for your attention<br>
<p>
dan<br>
