<title>Feb_1993: Re: Women on women  (whoops!)</title>
<h1>Re: Women on women  (whoops!)</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>17 Feb 1993 11:22:02 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#172">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#172">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#172">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#172">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0173.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "GC and ordination of women"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0171.html">Dan Gill: "Quotas"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Just in order to avoid being misunderstood (too late, I fear), let me explain<br>
what I was referring to in my reference to "women on women".<br>
<p>
A certain proportion of my lady friends say that although they have no<br>
objection to lady pastors as a concept, they simply prefer to hear a<br>
man's voice, as they generally find men's speech easier to understand,<br>
and often more pleasant. They hasten to add that they are not only<br>
referring to church, they also prefer male radio announcers and<br>
public speakers in general.<br>
<p>
As a strong supporter of women's ordination and other "women's issues", <br>
this frustrates me a little, as I feel that even if men are generally<br>
easier to understand (and this is not really the case), why let such<br>
a minor issue stand in the way of an important one?<br>
<p>
I am not of the opinion that everything is just fine regarding the<br>
equality of men and women, be it in the church or in the general<br>
community. I only have to look up and down the corridors of my<br>
own physics department to know that there is much to be done.<br>
<p>
At the same time, I know there are many in our church who are concerned<br>
about the issue, and who are trying their hardest to do something about<br>
it. Hence I don't like seeing the entire SDA church being accused wholesale<br>
of ignoring women and so on. <br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
--Boundary (ID ZYVO7mjFoPjOKsWYdqI4NA)--<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
