<title>Feb_1993: The thinking person's judgment -&gt; Judgment on the thinking person</title>
<h1>The thinking person's judgment -&gt; Judgment on the thinking person</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>17 Feb 1993 14:49:52 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#176">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#176">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#176">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#176">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0177.html">Malachi Robertson: "Women's ordination"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0175.html">Malachi Robertson: "Satan and Minds"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl asks:<br>
----&gt;<br>
First, what is the IJ?<br>
What occurs during IJ?<br>
What is reviewed during IJ?<br>
Who is reviewed?<br>
Why are they reviewed?<br>
What decision is made during IJ?<br>
<p>
Then, explain to me (as you understand it) how works fit into this (if it does)?<br>
The obvious dilemma:  if we are saved by grace through faith and works are<br>
irrelevant, why is there an investigative judgement?  If works matter in the<br>
sense of reflecting our commitment and relationship to Christ, what is the<br>
purpose of the IJ?  If works matter a great deal and have impact on whether<br>
we are saved (by your own theology), is the IJ important and why?<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
DaveB also said:<br>
----&gt;<br>
I have always thought of the SDA church as being the church for people<br>
who eagerly want to search out the church that comes the closest<br>
possible to teaching what the Bible teaches.  EGW certainly points us<br>
in that direction.  A people who are eager to follow the word of God<br>
regardless of the cost, to obey God rather than man, to do His<br>
commandments because we love Him.<br>
<p>
Perhaps, when Woody said "thinking man's church" he meant those who<br>
want to be serious students of the Bible and obedient to what they<br>
find rather than a church for intelectual theologians.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
<p>
One gentleman who may have some interesting comments to make on both<br>
of these issues is one Desmond Ford. He too thought of the SDA church<br>
as being the church for people who eagerly want to search for Biblical<br>
truth, for serious students of the Bible and for those who wish to<br>
be obedient to what they find. He too tried to come to terms with<br>
the obvious dilemma concerning the investigative judgment. Everyone<br>
agrees he went wrong somewhere.<br>
<p>
Given the history of this issue, I consider it extremely unlikely<br>
that there will be more than one stock-standard answer to these<br>
questions appearing in writing. Perhaps we can save some bandwidth<br>
(I'm always one for saving bandwidth :-&gt; ) by referring Cheryl<br>
to the relevant chapters of the Great Controversy, original edition,<br>
which together with the Bible (KJV of course) will provide<br>
excellent answers to them all.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
