<title>Feb_1993: Investigative Judgement</title>
<h1>Investigative Judgement</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 1993 01:47:34 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#180">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#180">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#180">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#180">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0181.html">Steven Timm: "Congregational Adventism (or Adventist Congregationalism)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0179.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Social Issues..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The SDA doctrine of the investigative judgment derives from three basic<br>
Biblical principles:  the prophesied cleansing of the sanctuary in Daniel <br>
8:14, the description of Christ as the high priest in Hebrews, and <br>
the descriptions of the days of atonement in Leviticus, considering<br>
the investigative judgment to be the antitype of the Biblical Yom Kippur.<br>
The focus of this day in biblical times, as it should be now, was on <br>
repentance and confession of sins, and the cleansing of personal and<br>
corporate guilt from the congregation.  The tabernacle was cleansed once <br>
a year by the high priest going into the Most Holy Place and making<br>
confessions for all the sins of Israel.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;First, what is the IJ?</i><br>
The process of selecting and cleansing a people that will reflect the<br>
character of God.<br>
<i>&gt;What occurs during IJ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;What is reviewed during IJ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Who is reviewed?</i><br>
All of "spiritual Israel", those who claim or have claimed Christ as Savior.<br>
<i>&gt;Why are they reviewed?</i><br>
To see if they have claimed Christ's forgiveness for their sins.<br>
<i>&gt;What decision is made during IJ?</i><br>
Those who have overcome are not blotted out of the book of life, the others<br>
presumably are.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Then, explain to me (as you understand it) how works fit into this (if</i><br>
it &gt;does)?<br>
<i>&gt;The obvious dilemma:  if we are saved by grace through faith and works are</i><br>
<i>&gt;irrelevant, why is there an investigative judgement?  If works matter in the</i><br>
<i>&gt;sense of reflecting our commitment and relationship to Christ, what is the</i><br>
<i>&gt;purpose of the IJ?  If works matter a great deal and have impact on whether</i><br>
<i>&gt;we are saved (by your own theology), is the IJ important and why?</i><br>
<p>
If we were saved by grace through faith and works were irrelevant, God <br>
could take us all to heaven the moment we were saved.  "Good works" come<br>
as a natural result of the power of God's forgiveness changing our lives.<br>
Too often we lose sight of the redemptive nature of forgiveness, focusing <br>
only on the bookkeeping aspects of it.  The goal of the Day of Atonement<br>
is to prepare a people for the final days that is free of sin.  For this<br>
God must apply judgement to see who are those who have allowed His<br>
forgiveness to work.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
