<title>Feb_1993: LDS women</title>
<h1>LDS women</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 1993 09:46:12 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#182">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#182">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#182">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#182">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0183.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0181.html">Steven Timm: "Congregational Adventism (or Adventist Congregationalism)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Cheryl Berthelsen  cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu]<br>
I was very hesitant to post about this subject because the moderator has<br>
told me that many on the net complain whenever nonSDA stuff appears.  But<br>
since many of you asked, I assume I have license to answer.<br>
<p>
[I'd like to thank Cheryl for submitting a nonconfrontational response<br>
to an almost-rhetorical question.  Those who asked the question obviously<br>
have some different information, otherwise they wouldn't have asked it.<br>
It's common knowledge that some women in the LDS church have not been<br>
quite as happy of campers as Cheryl appears to be  (i.e. Sonia Johnson).<br>
We could dispute that fact all day, I hope we won't.  I hope this marks<br>
the end of this thread.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
The status of women in the LDS Church is not an issue among LDS members.<br>
This is primarily because, unlike the SDA Church, the LDS Church has a<br>
theological basis for having a male-dominated church government.  However,<br>
the LDS Church has a well-established women's program called "The Relief<br>
Society" which places women in leadership positions.  There is also "The<br>
Young Womens Society" for the teens.  These were set up in the very beginning<br>
of the development of the church and offer opportunity for service, leadership<br>
and address women's issues.  The LDS Church has never ignored its women,<br>
ministering to their needs, speaking to their needs regularly and consistently.<br>
<p>
The LDS Church does not have paid clergy so all the Bishops and Elders<br>
have regular jobs and perform their duties for the ward they are assigned<br>
to on a VOLUNTEER basis.  How many SDA minister would minister to the church<br>
members without pay while maintaining a fulltime job to support their own<br>
families?  So as you can see, being an LDS Bishop requires great commitment<br>
and fortitude and does not carry ANY financial reward whatsoever.  It is the<br>
eternal reward that satisfies.  LDS missionaries are not paid during the<br>
two years they service the church.  In fact, their own families pay their<br>
son or daughter's expenses.  The church, a few years back, recognized that<br>
missions in some areas of the world were cheaper than others so the leaders<br>
standardized the amount that is paid to support each missionary.  Each<br>
family pays at the present time $425 per month.  If the missionary does not<br>
have a family willing to pay, the local ward where he/she is a member pays<br>
it.<br>
<p>
The most obvious difference between women in the SDA church and women in the<br>
LDS church is this:  LDS churches do not have professional paid ministers.<br>
Not even those who speak in Sunday services are professional or paid.  Rather,<br>
all local members are asked at some time during the year to present a talk<br>
(sermon if you will) for sacrament meeting.  I gave a talk just 3 weeks ago on<br>
the subject of gratitude.  Our topics are usually assigned within the framework<br>
of a general theme and there are usually 2-3 speakers each Sunday. <br>
Every member<br>
over 12 years old (male and female) is expected to contribute to the<br>
spirituality of the ward in this way.  It is quite unique, I believe, because<br>
we hear talks from new converts, from seasoned life-time members, and from the<br>
teens.  We occasionally have a special talk from someone for the stake high<br>
council but these are not professional clergy either.<br>
<p>
Women are revered and respected in the LDS Church for their spiritual duty<br>
to their homes and families.  The LDS Church still emphasizes that if a<br>
woman has children at home, she should not work outside the home.  The<br>
church supports many single parents (divorcees with kids) rather than have<br>
them resort to government welfare.<br>
<p>
The church visitation program in the form of home and visiting teachers<br>
provides leadership and service for all men and women.  Each member or family<br>
in the ward has a home teacher (man) who visits them in their home once a month<br>
to deliver a spiritual message and see if they have any needs.  Each woman in<br>
the ward has a visiting teacher (woman) who visits once a month to specifically<br>
minister to the woman's needs, both spiritual and physical.  I have a visiting<br>
teacher (a woman) and a home teacher (an elder) and I visit teach 2 other women<br>
in the ward each month.  Thus, the LDS church has a formal program to address<br>
our needs and allow us to minister one another.  If I am ill, I can call my<br>
home teacher to come over and pray and annoint me.  If I have a physical need,<br>
I can call my visiting teacher and she will bring food, money, or whatever.  If<br>
I am discouraged, I can call either one, day or night.  Obviously, if each<br>
home or visiting teacher is responsible for 1 or 2 families, to minister to<br>
any of their needs, there is no need for paid clergy to do this.  And we each<br>
in our own duties are ministering to other.<br>
<p>
So, as you can see, there is not any gross disparity or "discrimination" in<br>
the LDS system.  The role of "minister" in the LDS church is more of an<br>
administrator behind the scenes.  In the year and a half I've been a member,<br>
I have never heard a Bishop give a talk on Sunday.  And I've not heard a<br>
single women feel that they are being treated unfairly or being slighted in<br>
any way.<br>
<p>
Thanks for allowing me to share this on SDAnet.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
