[From Sue Harrington  sue@cuc.edu, edited by me to make the lines the <br>
right length and make more clear who is talking.  Indented remarks<br>
are by Bruce Holm.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I have to disagree with this last statement.  To say that unless a</i><br>
church &gt;has a<br>
<i>&gt;female minister, it is not fit for women consumption is taking it abit</i><br>
too &gt;far.,<br>
<p>
Why is that?  <br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;Women are welcome and should be welcome to call it their church regardless &gt;of</i><br>
<i>&gt;the sex or race of the ministor/pastor.  What difference should it make?</i><br>
<p>
Why would we want to call it our church when we are denied access.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I am talking about attendence here, not jobs.  Now as for jobs go, I</i><br>
don't &gt;see or hear of very many women actively going into the ministry. <br>
<p>
Why would you study computer science if you were denied a computer on<br>
which to practice what you had studied?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I still think that not very many women DESIRE to become ministers.  </i><br>
<p>
Why would any thinking woman want to be a minister in this church.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I don't see nearly as many women DESIRING to become ministers as I do men.</i><br>
<p>
Is that supposed to be an insight?<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;When will we have our first female president of the USA?</i><br>
<p>
Good question!!!<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Why did a majority of women still vote for a male president with a male</i><br>
vp &gt;instead of a president with a female vp?<br>
<p>
Is this a serious question?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I believe society as a whole (including women) still prefer a man to hold &gt;the</i><br>
<i>&gt;	position of leadership of this country.  Why would it be expected to be</i><br>
<i>&gt;	different in a subset of this culture called the SDA church?</i><br>
<p>
My, are we threatened or what?  Could we more accurately say that those<br>
in power prefer to remain in power?<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;I believe the Bible supports the idea of men in leadership roles.</i><br>
<p>
Is this an "appeal to authority"?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I don't think the seminary denies a disproportionate number of women to</i><br>
<i>&gt;men. </i><br>
<p>
You might find useful information on this topic by talking to women who<br>
have studied at the seminary.  What kind of a learning experience was it<br>
for them <br>
<p>
<i>&gt;But please stop flaming the SDA church because it doesn't fall in line</i><br>
with &gt;your goals or desires. <br>
<p>
Are you saying that when we question erroneous practices of the church<br>
we are flaming the church.  For a good example of this practice you<br>
could check out the Holy One who came to this earth.  Jesus had nothing<br>
positive to say about the church of his day.  I choose to take my<br>
example from the only example we have of divinity and to keep<br>
questioning, critiquing, and even harrassing our church until all people<br>
in this church are treated with respect.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;By the way, how does the LDS church stack up to equivalent questions?</i><br>
<p>
Is this meant as a slam for Cheryl?  <br>
<p>
Personally, I find the egocentrism in some of the postings attempting to<br>
justify the current situation revolting.  At least you inspire me to<br>
keep working toward a more equitable church.<br>
<p>
Sue Harrington<br>
