<title>Feb_1993: The World Church</title>
<h1>The World Church</h1>
Stan Macasieb (<i>macasib@rtsg.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 1993 10:30:44 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#186">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#186">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#186">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#186">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0187.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Melton's "Encyclopedia of American Religions""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0185.html">McCluskey G: "Re: Jesus and social issues"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yes, fellow netters, it's me again. Steve tells me that there was record<br>
amount of traffic while I was away. It's a good thing my node was off; it<br>
probably would've been beeping like an alarm clock.<br>
<p>
Let me detour a bit toward the reason for my absence. I had just taken a trip<br>
to my parents' homeland, the Philippines. As the bastion of Christianity<br>
and Catholocism in Asia, it comes as no surprise that many traditions and<br>
attitudes are formed by images of Jesus, the Virgin Mary, and the Rosary.<br>
<p>
It's not to say that Protestantism is not alive and well. Methodists and<br>
Presbys were the first major wave, followed by SDAs and Inglesia Ni Cristo,<br>
a variation on Catholocism and native religion. Now we see movements such <br>
as UCC, Assemblies of God, and LDS (which, BTW, has a beautiful modern<br>
structure and a great basketball court with clear backboards in my dad's<br>
hometown, Cheryl :) ) making major inroads. But the power of the papacy<br>
still holds sway.<br>
<p>
A report of the SDA church in the Philippines is in order. In talking<br>
to some of the churchworkers and laypersons in the central part of<br>
the area called the Central Philippine Union Mission (CPUM), the spreading<br>
of the gospel is alive and well. Churches are growing, and new churches<br>
are being formed from this growth. The vitality of the church lies in its<br>
youth and young adults, and I found such evidence at an annual youth<br>
sports day in a town outside Iloilo City. I can recall as many as seven<br>
area churches participating, with over 100 youth and young adults present<br>
in the town plaza playing volleyball and basketball. According to one of<br>
the youth leaders, this is one way that the church tries to keep its young<br>
people involved in the congregation instead of wandering to the city and<br>
getting involved in its evils.<br>
<p>
In Dumaguete, located southwest of Cebu, the church that began under a thatched<br>
roofed structure and dirt floors has become a cinderblock building with<br>
over 100 members. In talking to one of the literature evangelists who<br>
serves the area, he is very excited about the growth prospects in this area.<br>
With the increased activity in this relatively sleepy region due to the<br>
thermoelectric generator in this region, more people will migrate here, <br>
opening up a larger evangelistic field.<br>
<p>
In Manila, the Pasay City church and the adjoining Manila Sanitarium and<br>
Hospital now must compete against the massage parlours and bars with dancing<br>
hospitality girls that have moved out of Ermita and the areas where the<br>
American bases used to be. It is a great challenge, but one that the church<br>
there is prepared to encounter. <br>
<p>
There are signs of growth. I even noticed signs for a new SDA church <br>
between Las Pinas and Alabang, located south of Manila.  <br>
<p>
The RCC still is most dominant, though. This fact was hammered home many times.<br>
The parades, the celebrations of Maria, the messages. The most disturbing<br>
message came from a roadside sign. It said, "Better to die of old age than<br>
to die of AIDS." The RCC also opposes government efforts to distribute<br>
condoms in the fight against AIDS, claiming that it will only encourage<br>
promiscuity among the young and it opposes procreation. That in spite of<br>
the fact that people are now slowly waking up to the explosion of AIDS<br>
in Asia, including the Philippines. And the government so far has listened<br>
to RCC leaders.<br>
<p>
-----<br>
<p>
As far as the leisure side is concerned, I'd suggest Boracay. After you paid<br>
for an US$1100 round-trip ticket from Chicago to Manila and a roundtrip<br>
to Caticlan, where you take a small boat to the island, it's all white<br>
sand and clear water. Utterly beautiful. And a small cabin nearby the shore<br>
with varying degrees of amenities such as running water and electricity.<br>
Of course, you'll be fine if you don't mind the international aspect of the<br>
place, which includes all-night bars, souvenir booths, and, just recently,<br>
women sunbathing topless. I thought they weren't allowed to do that. Church<br>
thing, you know?<br>
<p>
--stan<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
