<title>Feb_1993: Melton's "Encyclopedia of American Religions"</title>
<h1>Melton's "Encyclopedia of American Religions"</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 1993 10:38:49 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#187">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#187">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#187">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#187">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0188.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0186.html">Stan Macasieb: "The World Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I believe the discussion of whether the Jehovah's Witnesses, Worldwide<br>
Church of God, Church of God (7th Day), etc. are offshoots of the<br>
Seventh-day Adventist Church grew out of a reference to J. Gordon<br>
Melton's "The Encyclopedia of American Religions," (3rd edition),<br>
Detroit: Gale Research, 1989.  As a reference librarian, I thought I<br>
could make some additional comments on the book and its contents.  Our<br>
library's copy is in the Seminary Reference collection.<br>
<p>
First of all, let me say that it's an impressive reference<br>
book--accurate, and extremely thorough (as befits a publication from<br>
what is probably America's most important publisher of reference<br>
titles).  Almost 1600 different groups are listed.  I have never tried<br>
to find a group and not find it listed here.  It would be great to have<br>
to time to just sit and read it (but at over 1,000 pages, not<br>
likely--contrary to what many people think, reading is about the last<br>
thing librarians have time to do!).<br>
<p>
Rather than simply giving an alphabetical listing, Melton has divided<br>
the churches into 22 "families" (of which the Adventist family is #11,<br>
and the LDS family 93).  There are 84 groups listed under the Adventist<br>
family.  Melton includes a historical essay on each family, then a more<br>
detailed description of each church (in the directory section).  Sources<br>
are given.  Essentially, the churches in this section emphazize<br>
apocalypticism and millennialism.  These families are further sudivided<br>
into smaller groups.  The following are listed as Seventh-day Adventist:<br>
Branch SDA's, Davidian SDA Association, General Assn. of Davidian SDAs,<br>
People's Christian Church, the Registry, SDA Church, SDA Church--Reform<br>
Movement, Seventh Day Christian Conference, Unification Association of<br>
Christian Sabbath Keepers.  I suppose an argument can be made that some,<br>
if not all, of the above are "offshoots" of the SDAs.  Incidentally, the<br>
presence of so many independent churches that use the name SDA may have<br>
helped persuade the judge to decide against the SDA Church in its recent<br>
attempt to make the name a trademark, and subsequent lawsuit against SDA<br>
Kinship.<br>
<p>
To call the 7th Day Church of God an SDA offshoot is not technically<br>
correct (I have many relatives who are members of that church, or at<br>
least one of those churches), although some SDA history books may<br>
portray it otherwise.  I believe that these books would label the<br>
Messenger Party and Snook and Brinkerhof as those who departed from what<br>
was becoming the SDA Church.  As I recall, the authority of Ellen White<br>
and the sanctuary doctrine were among what this group rejected.<br>
<p>
I was interested in the comment by my colleage in the next building, Dan<br>
Turk, and I find that to a great degree I must agree with him.  Many in<br>
the church (certainly in the church hierarchy and bureaucracy) seem to<br>
value conformity rather than those who question (witness the Ford<br>
debacle).  In fact, it still remains an unanswered question (as it was<br>
30 years ago) whether the SDA Church can really operate a university<br>
(but that's another topic entirely!).  However, I would say that the<br>
church tends to value right thinking (i.e. believing correct<br>
doctrine--the Truth) over right doing (perhaps more emphasized by<br>
churches in the pietist and other traditions).  Think about it--compare<br>
the number of sermons you hear on what to believe as compared with how<br>
to live a successful Christian life.  I think there's room for growth<br>
here.  <br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
Internet:  brneise@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
