Well, since I talked about women elders, I guess I will go on record as supporting<br>
ordination of women as ministers.  I've never seen a problem with it.  I DO<br>
have a problem when a qualified, dedicated pastor is never ordained, or skippied<br>
over as a friend of mine has been.  It seems that ordination is used as a gal<br>
glass ceiling for men AND women. This person has been a dedicated minister,<br>
with a MDIV from Andrews for the past 10 years, and at one time was promised<br>
ordination, but before that happened, the confrence president who promised<br>
it was transfered (the great "Advent movement") and he had a conflict with<br>
the new guy, and so seems to have been left hanging.  To the extent that he<br>
has been forced to take a teaching job outside of the denomination to supp-<br>
ort his wife and kids.  He is a talented pastor, and a dedicated Adventist.<br>
My point here is, that it seems like the church uses Ordination for purposes<br>
of "professional birth control", whether it be female or maile.  I call for<br>
this to cease.<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
