<!-- body="start" -->
Now _this_ is classic.  It probably has to do with the _way_ Jesus's life<br>
and ministry has been taught to us.  As a person with a "Social Work brain"<br>
it is clearly evident that Jesus had at least a two-fold ministry.  <br>
Luke 5:18-19<br>
*seems* to be talking about a gospel which is both spiritual and social.<br>
It goes along with loving "God with our whole hearts.... and our neighbors<br>
*as ourselves*."<br>
<p>
Too often I run through this text so fast, that I miss its power and potential.<br>
The call for me to love God supremely will not negate the call to love my<br>
neighbor.  In fact, Jesus's life appears to be showing that the two are <br>
married,<br>
or "joined together" in heaven.  How _does_ one love her/his neighbor<br>
as her/himself?  What exactly does it entail?  Is it in concrete, or does it<br>
change depending on my neighbor's needs?<br>
<p>
The gospel of Jesus is so powerful, and sweet.  As the revered rulers<br>
and teachers of old couldn't thwart its expanse, and ramifications, so it is<br>
today.  The writer of Isaiah 56:1-~8~ might be on to something... I'll have to<br>
study it more.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
