<title>Feb_1993: Re: Social Issues...</title>
<h1>Re: Social Issues...</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 93 10:51:43 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#191">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#191">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#191">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#191">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0192.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Great Controversy in Spanish"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0190.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Social Issues..."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0179.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Social Issues..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0194.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Social Issues..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: ruben@ee.uts.edu.au (Ruben Gonzalez)</i><br>
<i>&gt; Why is it that neither Jesus nor the disciples never addressed the current </i><br>
<i>&gt; social issues of their day (eg slavery, infringement of human rights etc). These</i><br>
<i>&gt; issues were not petty or irrelevant yet Jesus never addressed them. Instead</i><br>
<i>&gt; of addressing them (Jesus could have effectively addressed various of these)</i><br>
<i>&gt; He taught the people to live with them, and even consider them hidden blessings.</i><br>
<p>
I think that we might be in some trouble by trying to fit our own world<br>
view on top of *really* foreign cultures...which describes almost everything<br>
in existence in the far past.  It's bad enough trying to filter events and<br>
thought and writings of only a century past through our current filter.<br>
<p>
Notwithstanding our current views of slavery, etc., I don't believe that<br>
it was an issue for almost anyone during the first century.  Right or<br>
wrong (I'm voting for wrong), it was probably seen as something that<br>
just was.  Do something about it?<br>
<p>
Jesus dealt with problems that faced everyone, slave or free.  Issues that<br>
could be understood as important by many, if not all, of the people that he<br>
had contact with.<br>
<p>
Note that the inevitable (at least, we *assume* them to be inevitable) result<br>
of the changes in thinking that followed the issues that he addressed did<br>
eventually result in changes in these other problems.  These changes couldn't<br>
have come about (or, perhaps, not without much greater social upheaval and<br>
shedding of blood) without the changes in world-view brought about by what<br>
Jesus *did* teach.<br>
<p>
If you've grown up in a culture where up to 90% of the total population is<br>
slave, in fact even if not in name, you're going to have to stretch quite a<br>
ways to see that things should change.  It's probably even harder if the<br>
slaves in question are made up of the same racial and ethnic composition as<br>
the non-slave population.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
