<title>Feb_1993: Great Controversy in Spanish</title>
<h1>Great Controversy in Spanish</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 1993 13:17:37 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#192">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#192">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#192">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#192">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0193.html">Fred Christiansen: "LDS practices"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0191.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Social Issues..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0196.html">patricio d navia: "Re: Great Controversy in Spanish"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I will try to summarize information on the deletions in some editions of<br>
the "Great Controversy" as found on pp. 28-29 of "Issues:  the<br>
Seventh-day Adventist Church and Certain Private Ministries."  I'm not<br>
sure I want to re-open that discussion, but shortly after it died down<br>
on this list, what should show up in my mailbox but a free copy of this<br>
almost 500 page book (apparently provided free to church employees in<br>
North America).  I know there was quite a stack for the library--I can<br>
only imagine the size truck it took just to deliver the Berrien Springs<br>
copies!  I would not have personally purchased the book (though of<br>
course the library would have gotten it), but since I had one, I have so<br>
far read part of it.  Actually, it seems quite balanced.  If anything,<br>
they provided more information than necessary (although as a librarian<br>
and historian I appreciate having copies of all the supporting<br>
documentation).  Without defending all decisions made by church bodies,<br>
it must be frustrating to have individuals and groups feel free to run<br>
around and make all kinds of (often exaggerated and/or unsubstantiated)<br>
tales without knowing how to respond without adding to the divisiveness<br>
or adding to their credibility.  I would also say that when I visit the<br>
GC, I also often note a certain defensiveness in the attitudes there,<br>
which I find unfortunate.  I don't want to get sidetracked on that.<br>
<p>
The issue of the deletions was raised by John Osborne (Prophecy<br>
Countdown) in one of his infamous videotapes (in this case, "The New Age<br>
Adventism") in which he correctly reports that some statements have been<br>
deleted in a Spanish version of the GC.  The NAD reply is that some<br>
years ago an antidefamatory law, which prohibited anti-Catholic<br>
publications, was passed in Argentina.  Church leaders there asked for<br>
an abridged version that could be sold in that country only until the<br>
ban was lifted.  After that an unauthorized reprinting of this (using<br>
the Pacific Press logo) was printed in the Caribbean (nothing is said<br>
about Mexico, which country, incidentally since their revolution has had<br>
very poor relations with the Catholic Church only recently being<br>
somewhat healed).  As is common with Osborne's pronouncements (and we at<br>
Andrews have had some first-hand experience with his statements), he<br>
makes this situation into a conspiracy.<br>
<p>
The NAD ends its defense in this case with a notation that during Ellen<br>
White's life, and with her permission, changes were made to GC to make<br>
it more appropriate for its intended public audience (specifically with<br>
reference to the first German edition).  They conclude, "Material that<br>
might be offensive to some in the foreign language can be deleted.  The<br>
Spanish edition discussed by Prophecy Countdown falls well within the<br>
accepted guidelines for editing English and foreigh language editions.<br>
These guidelines were established during Ellen White's lifetime and have<br>
been used ever since."<br>
<p>
I hope this sheds at least some light on the question.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(Internet:  brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
