<title>Feb_1993: LDS practices</title>
<h1>LDS practices</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 93 10:55:05 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#193">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#193">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#193">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#193">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0194.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Social Issues..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0192.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Great Controversy in Spanish"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I respect Cheryl for her gracious answers to what could have been viewed<br>
as needling questions.  ...  While my understanding of Scriptures leads<br>
me to be an SDA rather than LDS, my contacts with LDS over the years<br>
leads me to appreciate many of their practices.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; [From Cheryl Berthelsen  cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu]</i><br>
<i>&gt; The LDS Church does not have paid clergy so all the Bishops and Elders</i><br>
<i>&gt; have regular jobs and perform their duties for the ward they are assigned</i><br>
<i>&gt; to on a VOLUNTEER basis.  How many SDA minister would minister to the church</i><br>
<i>&gt; members without pay while maintaining a fulltime job to support their own</i><br>
<i>&gt; families?</i><br>
<p>
The LDS church would seem unique in this policy; it perhaps bears mentioning<br>
that many evangelical and some denominational congregations are unable to pay<br>
their pastors sufficiently and so they must work additional jobs (and still<br>
carry a pastoral load; as Harvey B pointed out, many find this difficult and<br>
would prefer the SDA approach).  Next, it bears mentioning that our pioneers<br>
worked in this fashion (and some churches still do; the Buckeye, AZ, SDA<br>
church is served w/o pay by Chaplain Coleman, USAF).  Finally, in a related<br>
tho't, IMHO, "tent-maker" missionary work is a new opportunity that the SDA<br>
church appears to be tentatively exploring (e.g., ESL teachers in China) and<br>
which are other churches (e.g., Christian &amp; Missionary Alliance) are developing.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; LDS missionaries are not paid during the</i><br>
<i>&gt; two years they serve the church.  In fact, their own families pay their</i><br>
<i>&gt; son or daughter's expenses.</i><br>
<p>
At some sacrifice, I imagine, which is a worthy attitude, praised by God.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Every member over 12 years old (male and female) is expected to contribute</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the spirituality of the ward in this way [talks].  It is quite unique, I</i><br>
<i>&gt; believe, because we hear talks from new converts, from seasoned life-time</i><br>
<i>&gt; members, and from the teens.</i><br>
<p>
My readings in Scripture and SoP so far indicate that members are to be far<br>
more involved in instruction, exhortation, and counseling, and pastors far less<br>
(so that they can address evangelism) than current practice (e.g., anecdotal<br>
evidence in EGW's Early Writings is remarkable in this regard).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; church supports many single parents (divorcees with kids) rather than have</i><br>
<i>&gt; them resort to government welfare. [my LDS friends tell me it's actually</i><br>
any member family. -FGC]<br>
<p>
Government welfare, esp members on welfare, is a stunning rebuke to Christian<br>
churches for failing to follow the apostolic model.  Thankfully, I am aware<br>
of many instances where SDA members provided for the needs of families in<br>
distress; and, alas!, some when they didn't.  My personal experience is that<br>
materialism leads many of us Christians into debt deep enough so that we do<br>
not have the extra $$ to help out when we see needs (re debt, see Rom 13:8,<br>
Deut 15:6, 28:12), a circumstance which we purposed to change 3 years ago.<br>
<p>
The two LDS friends who did the plumbing on my house are involved in a<br>
ministry to members, esp widows, wherein they do home repairs for free for<br>
anyone in need.  I have read of similar organized ministries in evangelical<br>
churches.  Perhaps there are SDA congregations who have similar.  And of<br>
course Maranatha Intl, et al, address keeping down the costs of church building.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The church visitation program in the form of home and visiting teachers</i><br>
<i>&gt; provides leadership and service for all men and women.  Each member or family</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the ward has a home teacher (man) who visits them in their home once/month</i><br>
<i>&gt; to deliver a spiritual message and see if they have any needs.  Each woman in</i><br>
<i>&gt; the ward has a visiting teacher (woman) who visits once/month to specifically</i><br>
<i>&gt; minister to the woman's needs, both spiritual and physical.</i><br>
<p>
Ex-LDS friends found some of these teacher visits unacceptably intrusive<br>
into their financial and marital privacy.  Nevertheless, a well ordered<br>
visitation program has great merit.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
