<title>Feb_1993: Re: Social Issues...</title>
<h1>Re: Social Issues...</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 93 12:16:24 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#194">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#194">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#194">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#194">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0195.html">Steven Timm: "Building consensus"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0193.html">Fred Christiansen: "LDS practices"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0179.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Social Issues..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Ruben Gonzalez writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Why is it that neither Jesus nor the disciples never addressed the current </i><br>
<i>&gt; social issues of their day (eg slavery, infringement of human rights etc). These</i><br>
<i>&gt; issues were not petty or irrelevant yet Jesus never addressed them. Instead</i><br>
<i>&gt; of addressing them (Jesus could have effectively addressed various of these)</i><br>
<p>
Several possibilities, my tho't being the last one:<br>
1)  God really doesn't care ... but I think we can dismiss this one, based<br>
    upon the evidence in Scripture.<br>
<p>
2)  God does care, but doesn't address the issues in revelation ... again,<br>
    I believe we can dismiss by examining the revelation in Scripture.<br>
<p>
3)  God does care, does address the issues in Scripture, but didn't while<br>
    Jesus was on earth.  I'll deal with the last part next and just<br>
    address Scripture here.<br>
<p>
    First, we tend to read Scripture with preconceived ideas of what<br>
    "addressing an issue" consists of, based upon contemporary methods.<br>
    This is risky, given Isa 55:8,9.  Second, we tend to want God to<br>
    straighten up others summarily, forgetting that God is as patient<br>
    with them as He is with us.  Therefore, don't expect God to impose<br>
    any social revolutions.<br>
<p>
	Sow an emphasis upon rights and you will reap rebellion (cf ISam 15:23).<br>
	Sow an emphasis upon responsibilites and you will reap reformation.<br>
<p>
    My readings of history (e.g., Code of Hammurabi, Canaanite practices)<br>
    and Scripture indicate God called Israel to high standards of sexual<br>
    morality, to vastly improved conditions for indentured servants<br>
    (called slaves, but our denotation involves property) as well as slaves<br>
    (Ex 21; Deut 15), to honoring one's wife and raising godly, Spirit-filled<br>
    children, to the compassionate treatment of widows and the fatherless.<br>
    The differences are signal.  God calls us ever onward to Christ-likeness.<br>
<p>
    One source of confusion to a great many is when Scripture tells us<br>
    what ought (God's best) vs what people actually did (the latter part<br>
    of Judges being an extreme example, summarized at the end "every<br>
    man did that which was right in his own eyes") vs what God permitted<br>
    given who He had (and still has) to work with (e.g., Mt 19:8).<br>
    Let us not assume that what God permitted is also His best.  More so,<br>
    let us not assume that what people did was always OK with God (a common<br>
    stumbling block to skeptic readers).<br>
<p>
4)  God does care, does address the issues in Scripture, and did touch<br>
    on them while Jesus was on earth; however His mission goals were of<br>
    such paramount nature that there was time only for fundamentals;<br>
    moreover, his audience was not Spiritually mature enough (Jn 16:12).<br>
<p>
Let me again emphasize the dangers of approaching Scripture from the basis of<br>
our contemporary ideas of "what ought" lest we misconstrue (2 Pet 1:20)<br>
or try to force conformance (Rom 12:2).  Rather, we start from Scripture,<br>
learn basic principles under the tutelage of the Holy Spirit, spiritually<br>
discern contemporary applications, and judge our culture thereby.<br>
<p>
Man seeks to make change my imposing from the outside (and does not always<br>
do so wisely).  God creates change from the inside out (Ps 51:10; Jer 31:33;<br>
Prov 3:3) within those who are willing (Ps 51:17).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; He taught the people to live with them, and even consider them hidden blessings.</i><br>
The testimony of a humble and gracious spirit, esp when personally wronged,<br>
is a powerful influence (Mt 11:29; Luke 23:34; 1 Pet 3:1-12; 1 Cor 6:7;<br>
1 Pet 2:18-23).<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
