<title>Feb_1993: Building consensus</title>
<h1>Building consensus</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 1993 23:00:31 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#195">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#195">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#195">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#195">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0196.html">patricio d navia: "Re: Great Controversy in Spanish"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0194.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Social Issues..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It was in a Software Engineering class at Andrews University that the<br>
benefits of consensus-building rather than majority vote were first<br>
stressed to me.  (The teacher of that class shall remain nameless but<br>
she knows who she is).  The goal to work on our class software project<br>
through consensus<br>
rather than majority vote was a difficult one, and a new experience for lots <br>
of hard-nosed programmers.  Consensus-building effectively requires <br>
nonstandard management techniques to bring it about.  It leads to an<br>
organization described not in terms of hierarchical charts, but in terms<br>
of network topologies.<br>
<p>
It would seem that consensus is even more important in the church than in <br>
software engineering.  But in the church we are slipping down the slippery <br>
slope away from the consensus on the basic beliefs that forms the only ground<br>
of unity for Seventh-day Adventists.  We have now set a precedent by voting<br>
on something which both sides claim to be an issue of Biblical truth, namely<br>
the ordination of women.  I reject the idea that truth can or should be <br>
decided by majority vote.<br>
<p>
But even if anyone wanted to build consensus (and I believe the General<br>
Conference leadership does), where could they start?  In a company where <br>
one person is holding up the consensus, you can fire him or her.  A church<br>
can't fire its members, and besides, it's not just one person, it's all<br>
thirteen sides in the dispute, each claiming their way is right and all the <br>
others are extremist bigots and sexists and what have you.<br>
<p>
I despise the tactics of confrontation, sound bites, and all the other<br>
tools of the mediocracy which rules both our country and our church. <br>
Yet, if <br>
I attack those who are critical, I am being critical myself.  Also, I should<br>
be prepared to supply them a better way, and unfortunately history has shown <br>
that the church will not listen unless the dollar sign is involved.<br>
<p>
So what about it?  How do we make consensus when all the parties are saying<br>
"We can have consensus if everyone agrees with me"?  Is there a middle<br>
ground that isn't a morally bankrupt compromise like the current<br>
"scorched-earth" policy on ordination?  As long as we are at least still <br>
shouting at each other, there's hope.  Perhaps if the protagonists on both <br>
sides of this debate were all sent to Somalia as missionaries for three<br>
years, and had to learn to work together or die, we would have a chance<br>
of consensus building.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
