<title>Feb_1993: Re: Great Controversy in Spanish</title>
<h1>Re: Great Controversy in Spanish</h1>
patricio d navia (<i>pdnavia@midway.uchicago.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 93 22:09:53 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#196">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#196">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#196">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#196">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0197.html">Drew Corrigan: "WCoG and SDAs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0195.html">Steven Timm: "Building consensus"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0192.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Great Controversy in Spanish"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
With regard to the Great Controversy (Spanish Version), I believe that <br>
only in specific cases has it been 'edited' to meet anti-difamatory<br>
laws in a few Latin American countries.<br>
<p>
Mexico certainly has not be the case. Since the 1910 Revolution, Mexico<br>
has maintained a strict separation on church and state.  ONly during the<br>
current presidency of Salinas de Gortari, Mexico has formally exchanged<br>
representatives with the Vatican and the Catholic Church has been <br>
recognized by the government.<br>
<p>
The position to deffednd human rights and indigenous rights adopted by<br>
the church --which sadly enough was nevver shared by the SDA-- and its<br>
keen criticisms of the ruling PRI party policies have prevented the<br>
church-state relations from reaching the levvel that most Latin American<br>
countries enjoy.<br>
<p>
At any rate, the anti-Catholic discourse is seldomly used by the <br>
SDA church in Latin America officially (although many people use it<br>
indivvidually) andMrs. White's references to the Pope are usually<br>
kept from 'potential' SDA members until they are 'trained' into<br>
most other aspects of the doctrine.<br>
<p>
Indeed, one could argue that a rejection of thee papacy represents<br>
a formal and necessary step for belivers who are ready to baptize (that's<br>
is only an idea and don't quote me on it--please).<br>
<p>
BUt,no.  EGW's writings could hardly be censored in Mexico since many<br>
government's official publications were more critical ofthe Catholic<br>
Church than MRs. White herself.<br>
<p>
Patricio Navia<br>
POlitical Science<br>
University of Chicago.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
