<title>Feb_1993: WCoG and SDAs</title>
<h1>WCoG and SDAs</h1>
Drew Corrigan (<i>Drew.Corrigan@cs.anu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Feb 1993 15:22:46 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#197">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#197">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#197">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#197">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0198.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Social issues"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0196.html">patricio d navia: "Re: Great Controversy in Spanish"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Drew Corrigan]<br>
<p>
Steve Timm asked: <br>
<i>&gt; [Some SDA folklore I have heard indicates that Armstrong's wife was a </i><br>
<i>&gt;  at one time.  Any truth to this?  SCT]</i><br>
<p>
I looked up the material I have on the history of the WCoG last night. The <br>
short answer to your question is "no". Mr Armstrong was raised a Quaker;<br>
Mrs Armstrong (nee Dillon) a Methodist. When they married they both <br>
attended the Methodist church. During a stay in Chicago they were quite<br>
involved in the social aspects of the "Forest Methodist Church". Mrs<br>
Armstrong had a strong interest in the Bible but Mr Armstrong never really <br>
had time for it.<br>
<p>
When they moved to Oregon their attendance became sporadic. Mrs Armstrong's<br>
interest in the Bible was reawakened by an elderly neighbour lady, Mrs Ora<br>
Runcorn. Mrs Runcorn took her through a study of the Sabbath and from that<br>
Mrs Armstrong was convinced to keep it. Mr Armstrong vigorously resisted this<br>
and endevoured to show his wife she was wrong. Between 6 to 12 months later, <br>
after independently researching it for himself, he came to agree with her and<br>
came to repentance. Mrs Runcorn and her husband were members of the Stanberry<br>
MO, congregation of the Church of God and the Armstrongs began to attend that<br>
Church with them.<br>
<p>
So, neither Mr or Mrs had any direct involvement with the SDA church. However, <br>
I would add that in those days ministers of the CoG7D cooperated to one <br>
degree or another with ministers from other Churches - Mr Armstrong made use<br>
of the SDA baptistry for example. Sometimes ministers from other Churches <br>
(not necessarily SDA) would join in CoG7D evangelical campaigns. So, there <br>
was some interaction going on at that time (late 1920's through 1930's).<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
