<title>Feb_1993: ordained vs not ordained duties</title>
<h1>ordained vs not ordained duties</h1>
<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>17 Feb 1993 19:53:48 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#199">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#199">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#199">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#199">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0200.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Des Ford"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0198.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Social issues"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm not sure about the pay, but I don't believe the duties of ordained<br>
and non-ordained pastors differ anymore.  Our pastor is not ordained<br>
(although he has an ordination interview scheduled) and he baptizes<br>
right along with the rest because he is _licensed_.  The IRS got into<br>
this awhile back and said that unordained pastors couldn't receive the<br>
ministerial perks if they somehow were not fulfilling all the functions<br>
of a minister: baptizing, marrying, etc.  This is how the female pastors<br>
get what little recognition they have -- they are licensed ministers,<br>
but not ordained.  Just as a point of interest -- why do people go to<br>
the seminary at all if they have no interest in it?  Our pastor does<br>
not even have a college degree and the administration is considering<br>
him as a candidate for ordination....  Come to Kentucky -- we can use<br>
you, even sans seminary training!<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
