<title>Feb_1993: Re: Women and the SDA Church</title>
<h1>Re: Women and the SDA Church</h1>
Dave Thomas (<i>umsfdtho@deimos.oscs.montana.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Feb 93 22:18:19 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#202">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#202">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#202">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#202">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0203.html">HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0201.html">Edgar Vega: "Jesus and social issues"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0167.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Women and the SDA Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0203.html">HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU: "Re: Women and the SDA Church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
With regard to Sue Harrington's response to Bruce Holm...<br>
<p>
Right on Sue!  Tradition can bind us together.  That's its chief<br>
value and function.  Unfortunately, many traditions that are really<br>
rooted in our sociology and culture are treated as if they were<br>
absolute and timeless rather than relative and temporal.  When<br>
someone with a "love it or leave it" attitude insists on defending<br>
such traditions, I insist on disagreeing.  The current limitations<br>
on the role of women in the church are a good example of such<br>
blind devotion to a culturally determined tradition.<br>
<p>
Listen, I've seen enough 25 watt men in 100 watt leadership positions<br>
to know that the church needs all the help and talent it can muster.<br>
One of the reasons we can't solve some of our problems is that we<br>
can't agree on who gets to help.  I'm a male university professor at<br>
Montana State University.  Other than my doctoral dissertation I've<br>
published 4 books and have two more in progress.  I've an international<br>
reputation that has led to academic visits to Australia, Singapore, <br>
and Russia.  But guess what.  As far as I can tell, every SDA with<br>
a copy of Education considers himself/herself my equal when it comes<br>
to questions of educational philosophy and practice.  In fact, most<br>
Adventists believe that right decisions follow immediately from right<br>
philosophy.  Anyone who knows anything about the nature of expertise<br>
knows that that single belief can overrule the most articulate and<br>
well supported argument if it is permitted to function unchallenged.<br>
So, that's my "job" in the church, to challenge silly and bogus<br>
thinking whenever I see or hear it.  I'm staying, too ... and I'm<br>
going to give some people headaches who otherwise might blunder<br>
through entire careers without being called to account.<br>
<p>
Personally, I'd rather see a clear thinking woman on a committee<br>
anyday than some muddle-headed patriarch.<br>
<p>
Dave Thomas<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
