<title>Feb_1993: ordained vs not ordained duties</title>
<h1>ordained vs not ordained duties</h1>
David E. Johnson (<i>71172.2044@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>20 Feb 93 23:18:04 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#210">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#210">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#210">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#210">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Steven Timm: "Thinking big"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0209.html">Ademir P. Soares: "More Women and SDA Church..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0216.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  ordained vs not ordained duties"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In addition to those who correctly point out that there is NO functional <br>
difference between ordained and non-ordained (licenced) ministers.  They <br>
baptize, perform weddings, conduct funerals, etc. with equal <br>
responsibilities. It is my understanding that this may only apply to the <br>
North American Division. (say, wasn't there some argument about all of us <br>
working in lockstep, er, "unity", or is this applied selectively????)<br>
<p>
In Southeastern California, and perhaps in other progressive conferences, <br>
it is both policy and practice to pay women who have qualified for <br>
ordination the same rate as if she had been ordained. There are, therefore, <br>
no functional or pay distinctions. All that is left is the imprimateur of <br>
the official church. I hope we overcome this one soon.<br>
<p>
Well, I am on "vacation" and am paying a 1-800 surcharge for this.... <br>
Perhaps, Steve, we need to talk about the summary?!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
