<title>Feb_1993: Thinking big</title>
<h1>Thinking big</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 21 Feb 1993 16:17:52 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#211">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#211">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#211">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#211">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0212.html">bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk: "Michael Card Songs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0210.html">David E. Johnson: "ordained vs not ordained duties"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0215.html">Lisa Parry: "Re: Thinking big"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Whenever I visit the Willow Creek Community Church in S. Barrington, IL,<br>
I have thoughts about thinking big.  This non-denominational church<br>
began in a theater in the 1970's with the goal of reaching the unchurched<br>
and the unsaved.  Along the way they have churched 12000 people,<br>
and have 3 full services, one on Saturday night and two on Sunday morning,<br>
filling their 4500-seat auditorium for each.<br>
<p>
The conventional church in N. America, Adventist or otherwise, begins with <br>
a small group of very excited people, builds a new church, grows to fill it,<br>
and then holds or declines from that membership on downwards.  There are <br>
many states in which you see a pattern of one church in each county. <br>
"Quality and not quantity" is only a slogan in those areas where the<br>
church<br>
thinks it can't get quantity.<br>
<p>
I'm glad our local church leadership here in Illinois is trying to think big.<br>
Currently we are airing the "Discover Jesus" series on local TV in<br>
preparation for the 5-day "Discover Jesus" seminar to be given by Mark<br>
Finley, followed up by a large series from a local pastor.  This series <br>
will differ both in scope and substance from what has gone before.<br>
<p>
I would like to see SDAnet join in thinking big, not only for the growth <br>
of SDAnet, but for the growth of the church at large.  I propose that <br>
we develop a list of "Problems we would like to have."<br>
<p>
First problem: People are lining up outside the church before we ever open <br>
the doors so they can get a seat.  <br>
<p>
Second problem:  Our 5000-car parking lot isn't big enough.  We have to start<br>
up a shuttle bus.<br>
<p>
Third problem:  More people want to be involved than we have jobs to<br>
give them.  We have to keep starting new ministries.<br>
<p>
Can others think of more?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
