To Dave Johnson,<br>
<p>
I'm very curious about your statement that in SE CALIF Conf the female<br>
ministers are paid the same as male whether ordained or not.  Do these<br>
same unordained ministers received the GC perks such as retirement pension,<br>
25% of home mortgage, etc?  I doubt they do because the retirement system<br>
is sponsored by GC and since they have refused to recognize unordained<br>
women as ministers, I don't think they could legally either.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<p>
[I don't understand--GC pensions are available to other GC employees <br>
including teachers.  Also I have never heard of them paying 25% of anybody's<br>
home mortgage.  "Refused to recognize unordained women as ministers"<br>
is also incorrect.  The GC action of 1990 permits any licensed minister<br>
to conduct all activities of the ministry except organize a new church or <br>
ordain another minister.  (Perhaps with the restrictions mentioned by <br>
Warren Trenchard in his post.) Although the changes in the past few years<br>
may not be enough, they are nevertheless important.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
