<title>Feb_1993: female licensed ministers and perks</title>
<h1>female licensed ministers and perks</h1>
<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>22 Feb 1993 07:46:00 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#217">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#217">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#217">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#217">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0218.html">Steven Timm: "The "Sharing Scripture" SS lesson"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0216.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  ordained vs not ordained duties"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yes, yes, yes, the female licensed ministers employed by the SDA<br>
denomination HAVE to get the same perks as do the male licensed<br>
ministers -- this is an IRS requirement.  The IRS does not recognize<br>
ordination as anything special, so if the church has to treat ordained<br>
and non-ordained men the same and because we now hire women also, they<br>
are treated as the non-ordained men.  Did that get too convoluted?  If<br>
the women did not get the perks, then the church would be in very not<br>
(hot) water with the IRS.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
