<!-- body="start" -->
[from Drew Corrigan]<br>
<p>
Tony wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; SDAs do *not* officially see the food laws as still binding.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Our dietary practices have more to do with general health principles</i><br>
<i>&gt; than with staying kosher. That's the official line, anyway. Individual </i><br>
<i>&gt; SDAs may disagree.</i><br>
<p>
This seems to conflist with your Statement of Beliefs which Steve Timm sent<br>
me last year. One of the paragraphs reads:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;We are called to be a godly people who think, feel, and</i><br>
<i>&gt;act in harmony with the principles of heaven. [...]</i><br>
<i>&gt; It also means because our bodies are the temples</i><br>
<i>&gt;of the Holy Spirit, we are to care for them intelligently.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Along with adequate exercise and rest, we are to adopt the </i><br>
<i>&gt;most healthful diet possible and abstain from the unclean </i><br>
<i>&gt;foods identified in the Scriptures.  [...]</i><br>
<p>
Though my experience with SDAs is quite limited, those I know seem to<br>
regard the food laws as binding. [FYI, the WCoG also teaches that the<br>
food laws are binding, though it does not promote vegetarianism or prohibit<br>
the consumption of alcohol.]<br>
<p>
Perhaps someone could clarify this for me?<br>
<p>
Thanks and regards,<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<p>
<p>
[There are different food laws in the Old Testament.  SDA's view the<br>
prohibition against unclean meats (which was known to Noah in Genesis 9)<br>
as something which predated the Jewish people and therefore applicable<br>
to all.  But something like "You shall not seethe a kid in his mother's<br>
milk"<br>
which Kosher Jews still interpret today as forbidding the mixture of <br>
meat and milk, we do not consider binding since this was part of the <br>
Law of Moses.  What I have said above is the church position.  Whether<br>
there is such a dichotomy between Law of God and Law of Moses,<br>
and if the unclean meats still hold in the light of Genesis 9, is <br>
open for discussion.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
