<title>Feb_1993: OT Laws</title>
<h1>OT Laws</h1>
Malachi Robertson (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 24 Feb 93 1:45:26 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#230">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#230">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#230">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#230">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0231.html">Woody Baker: "Re: OT Laws -- Applicability"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0229.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Food laws"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0233.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: OT Laws"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was interested to see that I am not the only one who has been struggling<br>
with the question of how to deal with OT laws.<br>
 <br>
Something to note in the matter is this:  In Acts 15 the Jerusalem council<br>
met to discuss which OT laws should be bound upon the Gentiles.  At issue<br>
really was whether a Gentile could be saved as a Gentile or whether a<br>
Gentile could only be saved by first becoming a Jew.  The council<br>
basically supported the encouraging of the Gentiles to look to the<br>
principles found in Leviticus 17-18; these dealt with sacrifices to idols,<br>
blood in animals, and sexual immorality.  Well, this covers the Gentiles,<br>
but what about Jewish believers?  Hebrews points to the redundancy of the<br>
priesthood system now that Christ has entered the heavenly sanctuary.  So<br>
in some sense the laws dealing with the sanctuary and priesthood here on<br>
earth are no longer applicable.  But what of the other laws?  There are<br>
still some ceremonial laws, civil laws, and health laws left out of the<br>
picture.  I am not sure where to go from here.<br>
<p>
Ian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
