<title>Feb_1993: Re: OT Laws -- Applicability</title>
<h1>Re: OT Laws -- Applicability</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 23 Feb 1993 22:20:02 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#231">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#231">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#231">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#231">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0232.html">McCluskey G: "Re: Americans United"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0230.html">Malachi Robertson: "OT Laws"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0219.html">Tim Swensen: "OT Laws -- Applicability"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Well, I don't think that the health laws "..were not done away with.."<br>
The entire old-testament system met it's anti-type in Christ.  The<br>
foodlaws have a timeless health benefit.  The underlying prinicple that<br>
leads the Adventist Church to subscribe to them, is the fact that we are<br>
the temple of God, and as such, we need to keep ourselves as healthy as<br>
we can.  Part of good health, (as we now know it today) implies that one<br>
cut down on cholesterol, etc.  Certain classes of meats are considered<br>
unclean, not so much from the ceremonial aspect, as from the health<br>
aspect.  Looking at the animals that are "permitted" one finds that they<br>
are all vegetarian for the most part.  Some are insect eaters, but none<br>
are carion eaters.<br>
<p>
One has to look carefully at the laws, and try to separate cultural<br>
aspects, from religous (ceremonial) aspects and health aspects.<br>
<p>
For example "leprosy of a house"..deals with green marks in and on the<br>
walls.  Most likely this refers to mildew or other fungi which ARE detrimental<br>
to one's health.  The mixing of cloth types is more problematic, but one<br>
needs to understand that there were no synthetic fibers, and each natural<br>
fiber has diffrent and unique properties.  The laws dealing with women<br>
may or may not be based on health laws, more likely they are cerimonial in<br>
nature, because they deal with blood emissions, and blood had some very<br>
heavy symbology associated with it.  One practical side might be present<br>
however, and that is synchronous mensus.  Apparently when women live<br>
in close proximity to each other, such as in a dorm setting, there tends<br>
to be a syncing of menus cycles.  It would be rather detremental to<br>
a LARGE group of nomads to have the majority of thier women in mensus<br>
at the same time.  Isolating the women may have helped eliminate that<br>
although we don't know for sure.<br>
<p>
Obviously the injuctions against incest and homosexuality are based on rather<br>
sound principles, both geneticaly, and emotionaly.  Many of the leveitical<br>
laws can be understood in the light of general medical knowlege today, which<br>
knowlege was not present at the time that they were needed, and so God<br>
gave the laws in a manner that the people of the day could understand, couched<br>
in cerimonial symbolism.<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
