<title>Feb_1993: Re: Americans United</title>
<h1>Re: Americans United</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 24 Feb 93 11:04:37 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#232">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#232">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#232">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#232">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0233.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: OT Laws"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0231.html">Woody Baker: "Re: OT Laws -- Applicability"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; A few days ago, someone posted a derogatory statement against</i><br>
<i>&gt; American's United for Separation of Chuirch and state.  It seemed to</i><br>
<i>&gt; imply that they were a greater danger to Religious Liberty than Jerry</i><br>
<i>&gt; Falwell.  Also this post seemed to attack the principle of Separation</i><br>
<i>&gt; of Church and State.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; No one questioned him.  I must be completely out of touch for I am a</i><br>
<i>&gt; member of that organization and I do believe in the principle of</i><br>
<i>&gt; Separation.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I would like to hear other views.</i><br>
<p>
I'm in favor of separation too, but I also have trouble with this<br>
organization.  Several reasons:<br>
<p>
	1.  They focus on particular issues (like Sunday laws or being<br>
	forced to work on Sabbath), but totally ignore other religious<br>
	liberty issues like school choice, taxes, government control<br>
	of social policy, and so on.<br>
<p>
	2.  They don't address the issue of if and when public policy<br>
	should be based on religious principles.  If, for example, we<br>
	lived in a totally atheistic nation, to be consistent laws<br>
	would have to be based on the principle of "might makes right"<br>
	from evolutionary biology.  I'm not sure I would wish to live<br>
	in such a country.<br>
<p>
	3.  They seem to read too much into individual cases, e.g. the<br>
	peyote case in Oregon.  I think you can pick up on the trend<br>
	of religious liberty by looking at collections of cases over<br>
	time, but I don't think that any one decision implies that the<br>
	end is nigh.  If you cry wolf too often, eventually you lose<br>
	your effectiveness.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
