<title>Feb_1993: Re: Americans United</title>
<h1>Re: Americans United</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 24 Feb 93 17:54:14 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#234">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#234">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#234">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#234">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0235.html">Steven Timm: "The relationship between SDAnet and SDA-L"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0233.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: OT Laws"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
McCluskey G writes:<br>
<i>	&gt;I'm in favor of separation too, but I also have trouble with this</i><br>
<i>	&gt;organization.  Several reasons:</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	1.  They focus on particular issues (like Sunday laws or being</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	forced to work on Sabbath), but totally ignore other religious</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	liberty issues like school choice, taxes, government control</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	of social policy, and so on.</i><br>
<p>
First off, this is a fine line.   Religion has given the "world" a history,<br>
(something the world can put it's fingers on) of "misuse" (I'm being<br>
extremely kind) of power in the name of Christ.  This is terrifying,<br>
when the common person's mind can't imagine those things ever<br>
being thoughts in the mind of the Christ, Jesus seems to portray.<br>
The Church has even stomped over governments of the land in order<br>
to do what it wants.  We reap this heritage, and these iniquities are<br>
visited upon the religious children unto the third and forth generation.<br>
Now for me to forget, or worse, _ignore_ this, makes me more than a<br>
fool.  Now we have the opposite extreme, government with it's hand<br>
in the cookie jars and bowls, pots and pans.  Obviously there must<br>
be some governmental controls (especially when they uphold<br>
with the higher principles of God's law in how we are to relate to each<br>
other) if the Church fails to uphold them - - which is a SAD commentary<br>
for the Church.<br>
<p>
<i>	&gt;	2.  They don't address the issue of if and when public policy</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	should be based on religious principles.  If, for example, we</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	lived in a totally atheistic nation, to be consistent laws</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	would have to be based on the principle of "might makes right"</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	from evolutionary biology.  I'm not sure I would wish to live</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	in such a country.</i><br>
Now _this_ is an EXCELLENT issue you've brought up.  I hope we can discuss it<br>
before the Sunday Blue Laws and capital punishment are supported by law.<br>
<p>
<i>	&gt;	3.  They seem to read too much into individual cases, e.g. the</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	peyote case in Oregon.  I think you can pick up on the trend</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	of religious liberty by looking at collections of cases ove</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	time, but I don't think that any one decision implies that the</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	end is nigh.  If you cry wolf too often, eventually you lose</i><br>
<i>	&gt;	your effectiveness.	</i><br>
I think this is true.  Which affirms my suspicion that  this <br>
organization is human.<br>
Yet this is a sticker bush we're beating.  It can be said that, surely <br>
a small group<br>
(in comparison to the rest of the worlds religions) like Sabbath keepers who<br>
refuse to support our (moral majority) oppression of the "immoral" through<br>
political strong arming, are truly children of the devil and support <br>
his agenda.<br>
In this, I can see how if it were possible, even the elect (those "hand <br>
picked" for<br>
the kingdom) might be deceived.<br>
<p>
Good discussion!  Anymore thoughts?<br>
