<title>Feb_1993: The relationship between SDAnet and SDA-L</title>
<h1>The relationship between SDAnet and SDA-L</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 24 Feb 1993 23:14:09 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#235">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#235">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#235">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#235">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0236.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Food laws"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0234.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Americans United"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
(Or, why do all my replies to SDA-L messages bounce back to me?)<br>
<p>
This is one of the posts that I have prepared in the last while that is<br>
going to be part of our Frequently Wondered but Never Asked Questions.<br>
<p>
SDA-L is a LISTSERV list run out of LLUVM.Bitnet .  It was founded by <br>
Enoch Hwang (math faculty at then-Loma Linda now-La Sierra) and<br>
Christine Hwang (his sister, now an MD in Toronto, Canada). They started<br>
in late 1990, a few months after SDAnet.  Their goal was to make a list<br>
mainly for fellowship and discussion among SDA students and faculty <br>
at colleges.  They did not expect a large doctrinal component.  In early <br>
1991 the two nets had about the same membership, 40 each, with some overlap.<br>
<p>
I discovered SDA-L in January and proposed joint distribution of the <br>
messages of the two networks.  This began in March 1991 and lasted <br>
for two months.  The combination of two nets full of loudmouths<br>
and the lack of moderation made a record traffic month that stood for 18<br>
months.  Some on the SDA-L side didn't like it because of the volume<br>
(both number and intensity of messages), and the heated doctrinal<br>
discussions.  I didn't like it because nothing from the SDA-L side was <br>
moderated and a lot of people's feelings were getting hurt.  Plus<br>
my people couldn't respond directly to the messages from SDA-L because<br>
they weren't members.  So when the two-month trial ended, we agreed that<br>
joint distribution should be dropped, and the traffic on SDA-L, although<br>
unmoderated, should confine itself to the original goals of the list, <br>
at least for a while.  I issued an invitation to all the SDA-L loudmouths<br>
to come on over to SDAnet, which they did.  Immediately the SDA-L traffic<br>
dropped to almost zero and has stayed there to this day.<br>
<p>
In May of 1992 I was asked to replace Christine Hwang as listowner in <br>
charge of membership and subscriptions, and now I handle the day-to-day<br>
maintenance of that list as well.  Enoch Hwang remains the listowner<br>
in charge of relations with the systems people at LLUVM.   He has had <br>
plans to move the list to La Sierra's Internet node for quite some time<br>
now, but I have heard nothing recent about that in several months.<br>
<p>
We continue to echo all SDA-L messages to SDAnet.  They come to you,<br>
as to their other readers, without the intervention of a moderator.<br>
Since SDA-L tags itself as the sender of all SDA-L messages, your replies<br>
will go there if you specify "Reply to sender".  I try to tag all SDA-L<br>
messages in the subject line so people will notice that something actually<br>
does come from there once in a while.  If you are not a member of SDA-L,<br>
your posts to there will be rejected.  However, if you are a member of<br>
both SDA-L and SDAnet, you will get double copies of SDA-L messages<br>
(not that you should worry.)<br>
<p>
To become a member of SDA-L send the message to LISTSERV@LLUVM.Bitnet<br>
<p>
SUB SDA-L Your Name<br>
<p>
To sign off SDA-L send this message to LISTSERV@LLUVM.Bitnet<br>
<p>
SIGNOFF SDA-L<br>
<p>
To avoid receiving double copies of SDA-L messages send this message<br>
to LISTSERV@LLUVM.Bitnet<br>
<p>
SET SDA-L NOMAIL<br>
<p>
<p>
All SIGNOFF's and SET's are sent to me for processing since the list is <br>
set up that way.  And don't ask if we can merge the lists because when <br>
I became a listowner of SDA-L it was with the specific mandate not to merge<br>
the two lists, or change the nature of SDA-L.<br>
<p>
To summarize the differences between SDA-L and SDAnet<br>
<p>
SDA-L                         SDAnet<br>
45 subscribers + all SDAnet   135 subscribers<br>
<p>
Low traffic (1-10 per month)  high traffic (60-225 per month)<br>
<p>
Unmoderated                   Moderated<br>
<p>
LISTSERV list                 sent out by hand and kludges,<br>
                              run by a real person.<br>
<p>
SDA fellowship and support    Those issues plus anything else<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
