<title>Feb_1993: theological physics</title>
<h1>theological physics</h1>
Rich Hannon (<i>unislc.slc.unisys.com!rgh@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 25 Feb 93 10:52:12 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#237">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#237">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#237">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#237">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0238.html">Steven Timm: "FAQ?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0236.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Food laws"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have generally enjoyed reading sdanet postings, but I confess a growing<br>
disinterest in discussion that focuses on the kind of subjects that <br>
gets the John Osbornes of the world apoplectic. Sometimes the<br>
postings wander off into that territory. Historically Adventism<br>
began with a focus on those areas where we theologically differed<br>
from other Christians and in my church experience there has always<br>
been a segment of the church population that has been very concerned<br>
about topics that seem esoteric to most non-Adventist Christians,<br>
let alone pagans. Ironically, those most zealous seem to fall on<br>
that end of the spectrum, while those who see more grey than black &amp;<br>
white tend to be less so. I guess introspection can be incapacitating <br>
but it doesn't _have_ to.<br>
<p>
Enough reflection. To illustrate how wonderful :-) theological<br>
random walks can be when married to other disciplines I offer the<br>
following which I found in a list of quotations the other day:<br>
<p>
The temperature of Heaven can be rather accurately computed. Our authority<br>
is Isaiah 30:26, 'Moreover, the light of the Moon shall be as the light of<br>
the Sun and the light of the Sun shall be sevenfold, as the light of seven<br>
days.'  Thus Heaven receives from the Moon as much radiation as we do from<br>
the Sun, and in addition 7*7 (49) times as much as the Earth does from the<br>
Sun, or 50 times in all. The light we receive from the Moon is one 1/10,000<br>
of the light we receive from the Sun, so we can ignore that... The<br>
radiation falling on Heaven will heat it to the point where the heat lost<br>
by radiation is just equal to the heat received by radiation, i.e., Heaven<br>
loses 50 times as much heat as the Earth by radiation. Using the<br>
Stefan-Boltzmann law for radiation, (H/E)^4 = 50, where E is the absolute<br>
temperature of the earth (-300K), gives H as 798K (525C). The exact<br>
temperature of Hell cannot be computed... [However] Revelation 21:8 says<br>
'But the fearful, and unbelieving... shall have their part in the lake<br>
which burneth with fire and brimstone.' A lake of molten brimstone means<br>
that its temperature must be at or below the boiling point, 444.6C. We<br>
have, then, that Heaven, at 525C is hotter than Hell at 445C.<br>
<p>
Move over theologians, here come the physicists.<br>
<pre>
-- 
+---------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Rich Hannon, Unisys SLC, UT, rgh@unislc.slc.unisys.com (801)594-6628|
+---------------------------------------------------------------------+
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
