<!-- body="start" -->
Members of SDAnet who are interested in the relationship of OT dietary<br>
practices to NT Christianity will find some helpful insights in an article<br>
published in "Spectrum" a dozen years ago. Written by John C. Brunt, a NT<br>
ethicist who is currently vice president for academic administration at<br>
Walla Walla College, the article carried the title "Unclean or Unhealthful?<br>
An Adventist Perspective" and appeared in vol. 11, no. 3 (February 1981),<br>
pp. 17-23. It stirred up some discussion, and a couple of letters were<br>
published in vol. 12, no. 1 (September 1981), pp. 71-72, together with<br>
Brunt's response. Whether or not one agrees with Brunt, his contribution<br>
to the Adventist discussion of this topic should not be ignored.<br>
<p>
SDAnetters who are interested in SDA members of Congress will want to know<br>
of the two who identify themselves as Adventist. One is<br>
Represenatative Richard Stump, a relatively long-time member from Northern<br>
Arizona who is not, I believe, officially a member of any Adventist<br>
congregation but has family ties to the church and gives "Seventh-day<br>
Adventist" as his religious preference. He is, I understand, involved in<br>
ranching and real estate. The other is Roscoe Bartlett, a<br>
recently-elected representative from Maryland and a practicing Adventist.<br>
I believe he holds a Ph.D. in engineering and has been connected with<br>
Johns Hopkins University. (Since I am not personally acquainted with<br>
either of these congressmen, this information is second-hand and should be<br>
regarded as such.)<br>
<p>
Fritz Guy<br>
