[This is evidently a response by Beng Tang to a private E-mail<br>
from Scott.  In general one should be careful about posting someone <br>
else's E-mail to the net without their permission.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
Scott Bechtel writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;All this talk about laws I find interesting!  I am currently doing resurch</i><br>
<i>&gt;to write a 7 to 10 page paper on Romans 6:12-14.  The vs. 14 states that</i><br>
<i>&gt;we are no longer under law [at all] but under grace.  I have been stuck on</i><br>
<i>&gt;that more than any other part of the verses.  I'm not sure how to take</i><br>
<i>&gt;that.  Reference to Ex. 20? or all of the OT laws  or what?  (at all was</i><br>
<i>&gt;added for my emphases)</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I would really like to see your views!</i><br>
<p>
Dear Scott, here's how i understood it when i read the text in question:<br>
The power of sin is the law, says Paul, and this is true inasmuch as sin<br>
is the breaking of the law, the penalty of which is death. Since Jesus the<br>
righteous judge has paid the fine for us, the offenders, with His own life,<br>
we nolonger receive the penalty, the power of sin is gone, there is no more<br>
condemnation for us. Before, we were under the death sentance. Now that<br>
Jesus has taken our place, we have been set free from death.<br>
	I think you should not stop at verse 14 but read the rest of the<br>
chapter and even the next chapter too. It is all talking about us and the<br>
law. I do not think this can refer to any other than the absolute moral law<br>
of God, which is the expression of His character and which we call the 10<br>
commandments.<br>
	regards,<br>
		beng tang, singapore<br>
