<title>Feb_1993: Unordained women/GC perks</title>
<h1>Unordained women/GC perks</h1>
David E. Johnson (<i>71172.2044@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>25 Feb 93 20:35:31 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#244">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#244">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#244">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#244">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0245.html">bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk: "Re:theological physics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0243.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Under Law"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl asks (I paraphrase) "Do unordained women receive the same GC perks?"<br>
<p>
Regarding participation in the retirement plan, an unequivocal YES. There <br>
haven't been many women in ministry who have reached retirement age, but I <br>
know of at least one in this conference. The settlement amounts on <br>
retirement depend on a complex set of factors including years of service <br>
and highest pay level attained (even if reduced later, as a conference <br>
president returning to a full time pastorate), but the benefits are alike <br>
whether the retiree is male or female. Since Southeastern California pays <br>
unordained but otherwise qualified women at the identical rate as ordained <br>
men, a man or women with equal time of service would receive exactly the <br>
same settlement.<br>
<p>
I am not clear what is meant by "25% home mortgage."  If you mean the <br>
parsonage allowance, all women pastors (and unordained men) are entitled to <br>
claim it, and in SECC all have.<br>
<p>
Dave Johnson<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
