<title>Feb_1993: Re:theological physics</title>
<h1>Re:theological physics</h1>
<i>bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk</i><br>
<i>Fri, 26 Feb 1993 10:45:58 +0000 (GMT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#245">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#245">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#245">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#245">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0246.html">Malachi Robertson: "Romans 6"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0244.html">David E. Johnson: "Unordained women/GC perks"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Tim,<br>
	Please relay this to SDAnet.  I got the message returned to me from cmu's <br>
postmaster saying that my return path was not correct.  If you got the <br>
previous one then please ignore that and relay this as it has a few <br>
corrections.  Thanks:-)<br>
<p>
<p>
<i> &gt; The temperature of Heaven can be rather accurately computed. Our authority</i><br>
<i> &gt; is Isaiah 30:26, 'Moreover, the light of the Moon shall be as the light of</i><br>
<i> &gt; the Sun and the light of the Sun shall be sevenfold, as the light of seven</i><br>
<i> &gt; days.'  Thus Heaven receives from the Moon as much radiation as we do from</i><br>
<i> &gt; the Sun, and in addition 7*7 (49) times as much as the Earth does from the</i><br>
<i> &gt; Sun, or 50 times in all. The light we receive from the Moon is one 1/10,000</i><br>
<i> &gt; of the light we receive from the Sun, so we can ignore that... The</i><br>
<i> &gt; radiation falling on Heaven will heat it to the point where the heat lost</i><br>
<i> &gt; by radiation is just equal to the heat received by radiation, i.e., Heaven</i><br>
<i> &gt; loses 50 times as much heat as the Earth by radiation. Using the</i><br>
<i> &gt; Stefan-Boltzmann law for radiation, (H/E)^4 = 50, where E is the absolute</i><br>
<i> &gt; temperature of the earth (-300K), gives H as 798K (525C). The exact</i><br>
<i> &gt; temperature of Hell cannot be computed... [However] Revelation 21:8 says</i><br>
<i> &gt; 'But the fearful, and unbelieving... shall have their part in the lake</i><br>
<i> &gt; which burneth with fire and brimstone.' A lake of molten brimstone means</i><br>
<i> &gt; that its temperature must be at or below the boiling point, 444.6C. We</i><br>
<i> &gt; have, then, that Heaven, at 525C is hotter than Hell at 445C.</i><br>
<i> &gt; </i><br>
 <br>
 I deduce that your calculations are based on the assumption that the <br>
atmospheric content of Heaven is the same as that on Earth....which would <br>
logically follow from the hypothesis that the same content is needed to <br>
support our earthly frame.  Since we will have a different body. So in <br>
computer-speak your base case in the proof by induction is flawed, I must say <br>
that the logical conclusions are invalid.<br>
 <br>
<i> &gt; Move over theologians, here come the physicists.</i><br>
 <br>
 Move over physicists, here come the computer scientists :-) <br>
 <br>
 Ajay Busari (bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk<br>
 "Lead Me Not Into Temptation<br>
	    For I Shall Find It<br>
         Myself"<br>
 ----------------<br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
