<title>Nov_1992: God's love</title>
<h1>God's love</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 11 Nov 92 12:01:26 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#20">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#20">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#20">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#20">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: God's love"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Dan Blake: "Re:  Halloween or Reformation Day?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0021.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: God's love"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to Minna's query, I have also heard Adventists question<br>
whether the Lord really required the sacrifice of Christ.  I'm sure<br>
this question has been discussed in great depth over the centuries.<br>
One answer is that justice demands a punishment for sin.  I think a<br>
better and deeper answer is respect for free will.  Part of free<br>
will is that our choices have consequences.  If we could shoot a gun<br>
but the Lord stopped the bullet before it did any harm the our free<br>
will would be to some extent limited.  However, we don't always know<br>
exactly what the consequences of our actions will be.  Sin is a<br>
choice to rebel, and even to harm another.  In order to respect our<br>
free will, someone has to suffer when we sin.  The Lord transferred<br>
the suffering to Christ.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: God's love"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Dan Blake: "Re:  Halloween or Reformation Day?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0021.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: God's love"</a>
</ul>
