<title>Nov_1992: Alternatives to Halloween</title>
<h1>Alternatives to Halloween</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  1 Nov 1992 11:11:43 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#0">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#0">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#0">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#0">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Adam David: "Tithe / First-fruits of labour."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0002.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Alternatives to Halloween"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I grew up long enough ago in a conservative enough part of Michigan that <br>
the signals were mixed on Halloween.  My best friends family didn't <br>
celebrate Halloween, arranging to be gone from their house that night.<br>
My folks only dressed me up in costume once, as I recall, the year I was<br>
in public school kindergarten and all the kids came to school in costume,<br>
although I went for "trick or treat" several other times and we would <br>
always give something to those that came to our door.  One year we gave<br>
out Little Friends and Junior Guides.<br>
Of course, later on Halloween became associated with collecting cans for the<br>
poor and homeless once we got into Pathfinders.<br>
<p>
Two years ago at Elmhurst, IL we had a liturgically-minded social committee<br>
director who called for celebration of Halloween as All Hallow's Even,<br>
since indeed it was at one time a religious festival preceding the major<br>
celebration of All Saints Day.  (Never mind that many of the trappings<br>
we associate with it preceded Christianity of any form.)  Our social that <br>
year included a performance by a Christian magician who included several<br>
morals into his sleight-of-hand illusions.<br>
<p>
In a private E-mail from Paul Gates that was routed through me, he mentions<br>
that his daughter invited all the kids at a church evangelistic meeting <br>
to come dressed as a Bible character or animal.  (This is an interesting and<br>
fun activity, Halloween or no.)<br>
<p>
There have always been some within the SDA church who condemn Halloween, but<br>
in general SDA's are more likely to come up with a substitute for<br>
something rather than condemn it entirely.  This process is sometimes<br>
referred to <br>
as "vegetarianizing."  This will be another whole post.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
