<!-- name="Adam David" -->
<!-- email="adamd@rhi.hi.is" -->
<!-- subject="Tithe / First-fruits of labour." -->
<!-- id="9210312108.AA05062@hengill.rhi.hi.is" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Nov_1992: Tithe / First-fruits of labour.</title>
<h1>Tithe / First-fruits of labour.</h1>
Adam David (<i>adamd@rhi.hi.is</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 31 Oct 92 21:08:17 GMT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#1">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#1">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#1">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#1">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Alternatives to Halloween"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0000.html">Steven Timm: "Alternatives to Halloween"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
About tithe, I understand that tithe is meant to be the _first_ 10% of one's<br>
income. What does this actually mean? Does this mean different things for a<br>
waged employee or a self-employed contractor?<br>
<p>
1) An employee is probably at a disadvantage, because tax and all kinds of<br>
deductions have already been taken from his wages. How can he take the first<br>
10% to give as tithe when some has already been taken? Should tithe be<br>
calculated from gross wages or net wages? If gross, should he just accept<br>
that he has been overtaxed and overdeducted because tithe was not taken into<br>
consideration at the wage office? If net, how does he justify that government<br>
and other human institutions get priority over G*D.<br>
<p>
2) A contractor has the advantage that he can decide himself whether to play<br>
it safe with the worldly authorities, or whether to stand up for truth and<br>
right and regularly take the gross profits or income (which one?) and tithe<br>
them before dealing with the taxes and deductions based on the 90% remainder.<br>
If it was profits, there is the dilemma of which expenses should be classified<br>
as essential and deducted before tithe, and the whole ethical question of how<br>
any expense can have as high a priority. If it was income, then there is the<br>
problem that tithe has become like a tax on turnover, so there is a 10% loss<br>
on items bought and sold at cost (or for whatever reason just passing through).<br>
How can these opposing interests be reconciled?<br>
<p>
<pre>
--
Adam David. (adamd@rhi.hi.is)
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Alternatives to Halloween"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0000.html">Steven Timm: "Alternatives to Halloween"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
