<!-- inreplyto="Alternatives to Halloween" -->
<title>Nov_1992: Re: Alternatives to Halloween</title>
<h1>Re: Alternatives to Halloween</h1>
Drew Corrigan (<i>Drew.Corrigan@cs.anu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 2 Nov 1992 18:11:49 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#2">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#2">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#2">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#2">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Steven Timm: "Digest coming up beginning this week."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Adam David: "Tithe / First-fruits of labour."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0000.html">Steven Timm: "Alternatives to Halloween"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; There have always been some within the SDA church who condemn Halloween, but</i><br>
<i>&gt; in general SDA's are more likely to come up with a substitute for</i><br>
<i>&gt; something rather than condemn it entirely.  This process is sometimes</i><br>
<i>&gt; referred to </i><br>
<i>&gt; as "vegetarianizing."  This will be another whole post.</i><br>
<p>
As a non-SDA (I'm a member of the Worldwide Church of God) I am genuinely<br>
surprised at this approach the SDA church takes towards Halloween (not to<br>
mention other things which were discussed earlier: Easter and Christmas).<br>
<p>
Though it is not for me to tell you what you ought to be doing, I am<br>
surprised that your approach to things of dubious origins is to "substitute"<br>
rather than to declare such things as "wrong". As I read the Bible, it<br>
seems pretty clear that "light has no fellowship with darkness", and that<br>
Christians are commanded to "come out of [the world]". I will grant you<br>
that we should certainly serve in the world, and extend ourselves by doing<br>
good even as Jesus did, but where are we advised to share in the erroneous<br>
traditions of the world?<br>
<p>
I am surprised that you employ the term "vegetarianizing" to this substitut-<br>
ion process. Though I understand that there are many "meat substitutes"<br>
which vegetarians may enjoy, in its fuller sense, surely vegetarianizing<br>
involves restoring something to the way it once was at creation and getting<br>
rid of those things which are unhealthful (both spiritually and in the<br>
literal sense).<br>
<p>
[Background: my wife and I are recent "converts" to vegetarianism for<br>
health reasons. The WCoG does not teach vegetarianism (and probably many<br>
members would view it as an "aberration"), but it does teach keeping the<br>
health laws given in Leviticus 11 and elsewhere. We choose not to discuss<br>
our vegetarianism with fellow WCoG members in order to "keep the peace".]<br>
<p>
I suppose the bottom line of my surprise is that both the SDA Church and<br>
the WCoG have a number of teachings in common (Sabbath, no immortal soul,<br>
eternal death of the wicked). We both claim the same spiritual lineage<br>
of the apostles, Paulicians, Waldenesians, Bogamils, and early Sabbath<br>
keepers in the US. (Well I think we claim the same - I haven't read much<br>
of the SDA view of history of the true faith.) I have a book "Divine Rest<br>
for Human Restlessness" by a leading SDA scholar and have been impressed<br>
by his insights.<br>
<p>
And yet, when it comes to what I would term "compromising" with the princi-<br>
ples of the Bible (even allowing for the vastly different social and cultural<br>
settings in the Bible compared to the 20th century), to be honest I am<br>
disappointed with the attitudes many seem to hold on SDAnet. Please do not<br>
misunderstand: what the SDA Church teaches and practises is entirely its<br>
business. However, if I was someone initially searching for Truth (as I was<br>
about 15 years ago) I know I would be quite disappointed if this is what the<br>
SDA Church had to offer.<br>
<p>
<p>
Sincere and genuine regards,<br>
<p>
Drew Corrigan.<br>
<p>
PS  Please do not take this as a "my church is better than your church"<br>
    posting - it is not intended as such, and in my opinion any such <br>
    contention is pointless. The WCoG has its warts too.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
