<title>Nov_1992: Vegetarianizing</title>
<h1>Vegetarianizing</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  2 Nov 1992 21:19:51 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Alternatives to Halloween (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Steven Timm: "Digest coming up beginning this week."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Drew has already attacked this practice more eloquently than I can, but<br>
I will share the thoughts I was going to share about it anyway.<br>
<p>
Some of the first "meat analogs" were developed by Dr. J.H. Kellogg<br>
at the Battle Creek Sanitarium.  Later the Battle Creek food company<br>
was taken over by Worthington Foods, which for a time was part of<br>
Miles Laboratories, then bought itself back.  In Adventist colonies,<br>
food stores carry a wide variety of vege-meat.  (Actually, much of it <br>
can even be found in mainstream supermarkets in Pittsburgh today.)  This<br>
has been criticized for being quite artificial and using lots of sodium and<br>
MSG, but the companies are responding to this as well.  Also, long<br>
before decaffeinated teas and colas were in style, Worthington <br>
was putting them out as well.  The point is that <br>
we have a substitute for every (speakable) type of meat there is, including<br>
some substitutes for pork that we theoretically shouldn't even want.<br>
<p>
The practice of vegetarianizing goes well beyond food for SDA's, though.<br>
The holidays are a big example of this.  In this we take practical counsel<br>
from Ellen White, particularly Christmas, where she suggests that a Christmas<br>
tree be erected in churches for the purpose of decorating it with gifts<br>
of money for missions.  In other words, celebrate the holiday, but don't<br>
make <br>
it pagan.  This is in the spirit of Paul's counsel on eating food<br>
offered to idols--we can affirm that the tree is created of God, and use<br>
it for a good purpose despite what others may do.  Halloween has<br>
traditionally been used<br>
by our church school children and Pathfinders as a time of service.<br>
<p>
Other examples include replacing the traditional school "prom" with a <br>
banquet (due to swiftly-falling prohibitions against dancing).  Also <br>
playing Rook instead of Bridge (don't want to get mixed up with cards that<br>
are commonly used for gambling.)  Also rewriting the words of songs that <br>
speak of lifting up of the hands.  <br>
<p>
Though I have been and am currently involved in youth evangelism efforts<br>
which attempt to some extent to compete with the world's entertainment,<br>
I don't think this is the best way.  We don't need to make our church like<br>
the world to make it attractive.  Or:  Why do we think people will come <br>
to the wave pool when the beach is free?<br>
<p>
I'd appreciate others' thoughts on this matter.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
