<!-- name="Raylene" -->
<!-- email="CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Halloween" -->
<!-- id="01GQPQOPTD6A8WYPJC@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Halloween" -->
<title>Nov_1992: Re: Halloween</title>
<h1>Re: Halloween</h1>
Raylene (<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>03 Nov 1992 12:20:35 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#9">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#9">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#9">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#9">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Steven Timm: "For better or worse, election almost over"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Pam Harris: "Halloween"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0008.html">Pam Harris: "Halloween"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Steve Timm writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; in general SDA's are more likely to come up with a substitute for</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; something rather than condemn it entirely.</i><br>
<p>
Drew Corrigan writes:<br>
<i>&gt;I am</i><br>
<i>&gt;surprised that your approach to things of dubious origins is to "substitute"</i><br>
<i>&gt;rather than to declare such things as "wrong".</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;And yet, when it comes to what I would term "compromising" with the princi-</i><br>
<i>&gt;ples of the Bible (even allowing for the vastly different social and cultural</i><br>
<i>&gt;settings in the Bible compared to the 20th century), to be honest I am</i><br>
<i>&gt;disappointed with the attitudes many seem to hold on SDAnet. Please do not</i><br>
<i>&gt;misunderstand: what the SDA Church teaches and practises is entirely its</i><br>
<i>&gt;business. However, if I was someone initially searching for Truth (as I was</i><br>
<i>&gt;about 15 years ago) I know I would be quite disappointed if this is what the</i><br>
<i>&gt;SDA Church had to offer.</i><br>
<p>
Thankfully to date Australians have been able to avoid such Americanisms as <br>
Halloween, though I was distressed to find a timid bunch of kids running<br>
around our street last Friday and Saturday nights wearing wierd hats.<br>
<p>
It really does seem to me that accepting such traditions freely (though I am <br>
not familiar with the origin of Halloween) *is* compromising our standards<br>
somewhat. (Though much, it seems, is not by "decree" from the church but <br>
decided largely by the individuals that make up the church.) <br>
<p>
As for Christmas and Easter, I largely speak for myself. Easter has never been<br>
a big deal (no deal at all actually) for me or anyone I know. The only thing<br>
good about easter is there are public holidays at that time, so you get the<br>
chance for a bit of a holiday during the year.<br>
<p>
As I grew up, my family usually celebrated Christmas. Well, no big drama.<br>
Usually a strange sort of Christmas tree cut down from the bush the day before<br>
and decorated with a few bits of tinsel &amp; so forth (nothing like the Christmas<br>
depicted in American movies eg. Home Alone! and anyway - no snow). We didn't <br>
actually make a big deal of the birth of Christ story but did exchange <br>
presents - once again, not of the hugely expensive variety. <br>
<p>
These days I'm sickened by the crass commercialism of Christmas in the shops<br>
at the beginning of October, but that may just be me.<br>
<p>
I don't think of myself as a major spoilsport or wet blanket, and am largely<br>
happy to see other people having a good, clean, fun time. And anyway, isn't<br>
it a bit of a risk these days to let children wander the streets receiving<br>
food? Just think of all the nasty people out there who might spike the food<br>
or steal the kids!?!<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
---*---<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
