<title>Nov_1992: Foot Washing, Husband/Wife</title>
<h1>Foot Washing, Husband/Wife</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 11 Nov 92 09:56:54 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Foot Washing, Husband/Wife"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Earvin "Magic" Johnson"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0024.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Foot Washing, Husband/Wife"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Received a phone call from one of the new elders at our church.<br>
<p>
He was at church board meeting last night and the topic came up<br>
about married couples foot washing.  Some churches don't do it<br>
at all, some churches offer this option each time.  At our church<br>
its been once a year.  The idea is that the men go one way, the<br>
women go to another set of rooms and one room is set asside for<br>
married couples who wish to choose thier spouce as partner.<br>
<p>
My friend said he had asked if this was something appropriate,<br>
was there any basis for it . . . .  Some members pointed out<br>
that those recently divorced or widowed might feel offended.<br>
A single woman said she would move to another church if it was<br>
to be done regularly.  The church board ended up<br>
delegating him to go off and study the whole thing out.  He asked<br>
me if I had studied the topic, if I chose to study it, could I<br>
pass on to him anything that I came across.  So I'm tossing it<br>
out to you for your input.<br>
<p>
EGW points out that there are no Bible examples of men washing<br>
womens feet.  There is the example of Mary washing Jesus' feet<br>
with her teers.  So, she basically rules out the idea of men<br>
washing womens feet in the context of the Ordinances of Humility,<br>
saying its ok for women to wash a man's feet based on Biblical<br>
precedent.  Is this relevent to the question of husbands &amp; wives?<br>
<p>
I think we have to ask what its all about.  And a story comes<br>
to mind from a mission story book I was reading to my boys several<br>
years ago.  Back in them canibal days the chief would commission<br>
the building of a village war canoe from time to time.  It was<br>
standard practice that several warriors would be selected at<br>
the time of the launching to lay like role logs to expedite<br>
the launching of the canoe.  This had a tendency to do serious<br>
damage, even to kill some of the human skids.  Many years later<br>
we come to the scene at the new church for the first occassion<br>
of foot washing.  One of the members had been seriously mamed<br>
years before.  The chief insisted on washing this former warriors<br>
feet.  He jumped up and was quite adament, that while it might<br>
be ok for him to wash the chiefs feet, that it was not at all<br>
proper for the chief to wash his feet.  In the end the chief was<br>
able to convince him that in Christianity it was indeed the<br>
right thing to do and that in Christ they were all equal anyway.<br>
Quite a moving story.  And illustrative of what Jesus had in<br>
mind when He said -- "This do in remembrance of me?"  And so,<br>
instead of trying to choose a close friend I prefer to choose<br>
an overlooked stranger or somebody who looks like they need<br>
a friend that day, or somebody who . . . . . . .<br>
<p>
Anyway, what does this ordinance mean to you?  From the Bible?<br>
 From EGW?  What about in the context of husband and wife?<br>
An option each time?  Once a year?  Never?<br>
<p>
Thanks for your feedback which I'll pass on to my friend.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
