<title>Nov_1992: Re: Foot Washing, Husband/Wife</title>
<h1>Re: Foot Washing, Husband/Wife</h1>
Drew Corrigan (<i>Drew.Corrigan@cs.anu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Nov 1992 14:25:26 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#24">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#24">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#24">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#24">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Pam Harris: "Foot washing musings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Dave Buxton: "Foot Washing, Husband/Wife"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0023.html">Dave Buxton: "Foot Washing, Husband/Wife"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Dave,<br>
<p>
For what its worth ...<br>
<p>
The WCoG practices the ceremony of foot washing once a year during the<br>
Passover service. Men go to one room and women to another. However, in<br>
cases where couples cannot attend the Passover for whatever reason (eg<br>
great distance) we have instructions for them on how to observe it at<br>
home. In this situation, husbands and wives wash each others feet.<br>
<p>
We would not see any problems with this. Christ washes the Church with<br>
the water of the Word, and he is our example of humility and service.<br>
<p>
The foot washing service teaches us not only that we must be genuinely<br>
humble and service minded towards others (and indeed that we rededicate<br>
ourselves to service each Passover) but also that we are prepared to <br>
let ourselves be "washed" by the Great Servant himself - Jesus. When I<br>
wash anothers feet I think of how I must serve and mentally rededicate<br>
myself to that. As I am washed, I mentally ask God to wash me of the <br>
"travel stains" (ie sins) I have acquired since the previous Passover.<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
