<title>Nov_1992: Foot washing musings</title>
<h1>Foot washing musings</h1>
Pam Harris (<i>HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU</i>)<br>
<i>12 Nov 1992 00:13:51 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#25">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#25">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#25">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#25">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Foot Washing, Husband/Wife"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Foot Washing, Husband/Wife"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Several observations about washing one another's feet.<br>
<p>
1. What is the underlying motivation and purpose? Humility, right? Feet were filthy in those days and a gracious host made his guest comfortable by washing<br>
feet, dirty feet. A stinky, yucky job. But somebody did it. This principle<br>
of humility rules out the idea that a man could never wash a woman's feet.<br>
We are all one family, brothers and sisters. Why shouldn't we be glad to<br>
make one another more comfortable? This is not a sexual act. <br>
<p>
2. Having written the last sentence, I can remember not too long ago<br>
when women did not wear panty hose, but stockings which clipped onto<br>
very private underwear. They removed these stockings for footwashing<br>
and it was considered modest for men and women to be separated. Some<br>
older women still wear these stockings and the woman who is uncomfortable<br>
may be in this situation. <br>
<p>
3. When I was in college, the older women were appalled that we college<br>
girls would wear those new panty hose and not remove them for footwashing.<br>
It probably seemed un-humble (?), brash, hurried and just downright<br>
untraditional. I remember hearing loud carrying on about it during the<br>
footwashing, sort of wrecking any reflections about the ordinance.<br>
<p>
4. If you really want to know what humility is all about, go to the<br>
library and find Richard Selzer's book, "Letters to a Young Surgeon."<br>
Read the chapter entitled "Toenails." This is a powerful true story<br>
about a physician engaged in an ordinance of humility of clipping the<br>
long, curling under toenails of the homeless people who live in<br>
the public library during cold winters. When I heard James Dobson read<br>
this story on his radio program one day, I drove right to the public<br>
library, checked out the book, made copies and read the story to all<br>
my family. I agree with Dobson. It makes the ordinance of humility<br>
get some perspective. <br>
<p>
5. If you cannot find the above book, I'll be glad to mail anyone a<br>
copy of this short story. E-mail me at PHARRIS@UTKVX.UTK.EDU with your<br>
snail-mail address. <br>
<p>
6. I'm wary of anyone who threatens to go to another church should the<br>
church try something new. On the other hand, being sensitive to others<br>
is what Christianity is all about. Surely there is middle ground here.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
