<title>Nov_1992: Re:  Footwashing</title>
<h1>Re:  Footwashing</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Nov 1992 08:01:27 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#27">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#27">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#27">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#27">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Dave Buxton: "The Church Will Go Through"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Foot Washing, Husband/Wife"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0034.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Footwashing"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0029.html">Dan Blake: "Re:  Footwashing"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In backwoods northern Michigan, our church tried the idea of husbands<br>
and wives being able to wash each other's feet once.  My folks enjoyed<br>
the <br>
procedure and thought it was a neat idea, and there doesn't seem to have<br>
been much hue and cry about it.  In other churches where I currently <br>
attend, it's clear the process would cause enough problems that even<br>
mentioning doing it would be unspeakable.  I have also heard of places<br>
where there are small rooms where a whole family may be together <br>
for the foot-washing.<br>
<p>
In footwashing, we follow the Lord's command and example by washing the <br>
feet of others, and we show our humility not by washing, but by <br>
allowing our feet to be washed.<br>
<p>
I think also that it is dangerous to argue from silence in the Bible,<br>
just saying that since it was never recorded that a man washed a woman's<br>
feet, it should never be done.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
