<title>Nov_1992: The Church Will Go Through</title>
<h1>The Church Will Go Through</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Nov 92 13:01:46 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#28">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#28">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#28">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#28">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Dan Blake: "Re:  Footwashing"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Footwashing"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0032.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The Church Will Go Through"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ellen White has given us the assurance that the Church will go through.<br>
We need to be careful in how we interpret this.<br>
<p>
* Consider that Jesus made a similar prophecy that His church would go<br>
  through and not even Hades would prevail against it.  The RCC has<br>
  taken ahold of this scripture and made the the keys in Peter's hands.<br>
  They claim to be the church that will go through, but we know that it<br>
  was the church driven into the wilderness that survives the Apostles.<br>
<p>
* Think of it as a Covenant that God has made, through His prophet EGW.<br>
  A covenant that this last day church will go through.  At Sinaii God<br>
  covenanted that he would place His law within their hearts.  But they<br>
  insisted on taking things into their own hands and so Israel turned<br>
  God's covenant into the "Old Covenant".  The Covenant was re-instated<br>
  in the New Covenant.  Paul illustrates this Old/New Covenant problem<br>
  with the story of Ishmael and Isaac.  It was not God's covenant that<br>
  was faulty, simply that Ishamael was the son of Abraham's lack of<br>
  faith and Isaac was the son of promise, the result of the selfsame<br>
  promise on God's part.<br>
<p>
Consider Ellen White's warning that our church would do much as Judaism<br>
did at the time when Jesus arrived on the scene.  There is much we can<br>
learn in order not to repeat their mistakes.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
