<title>Nov_1992: Re:  Footwashing</title>
<h1>Re:  Footwashing</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Nov 92 12:06:10 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#29">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#29">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#29">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#29">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Dave Buxton: "Footwashing -- History"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Dave Buxton: "The Church Will Go Through"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0027.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Footwashing"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; In footwashing, we follow the Lord's command and example by washing the </i><br>
<i>&gt; feet of others, and we show our humility not by washing, but by </i><br>
<i>&gt; allowing our feet to be washed.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
------------<br>
<p>
You seem to have a strange concept of humility.  Let us set the<br>
stage.  In the normal situation, the aristocrat is getting his<br>
feet washed, and the slave is the one doing the washing.  To <br>
wash someone's feet is to assume the position of a slave and to<br>
honor the person whose feet are washed.<br>
<p>
Those who recognize Jesus as the Christ are naturally taken back<br>
by his role as a servant.  Notice John the Baptist's response<br>
when Jesus came forward for a water baptism unto repentance.<br>
Peter's response was similar when Jesus wanted to wash his feet.<br>
Those who recognize Jesus as the Christ also hear his voice and<br>
follow his intruction.  John did baptise Jesus; Peter did have<br>
his feet washed.<br>
<p>
Dan Blake<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
