<title>Nov_1992: Footwashing -- History</title>
<h1>Footwashing -- History</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Nov 1992 22:53:13 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Dan Blake: "Re: God's love"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Dan Blake: "Re:  Footwashing"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0037.html">Dan Hamstra: "Re: Footwashing -- History"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi friends, thanks for your postings on the topic.<br>
<p>
One question I forgot to ask, does anybody know any of the history<br>
of foot washing.  I know of not text in the Bible that would suggest<br>
the disciples took up the practice in the context of early Christianity.<br>
Of course foot washing was an ongoing thing in the context of their<br>
dusty setting where people did a lot of walking on dusty roads.<br>
Anything in the "early fathers"?  What about Luther and other<br>
reformers.  What is the earliest indication of foot washing?<br>
<p>
Could somebody volunteer to do some historical research?<br>
<p>
I have heard that during early SDA church history the churches that did<br>
foot washing did it mixed and some of the men used to get all charged up<br>
on picking out a young maiden for a partner so as to remove her stockings<br>
and wash her feet.  I don't see that as a problem in the husband/wife<br>
context.  But if this is real history, then I can understand why<br>
it came time to separate the men to one room and the women to another.<br>
<p>
Does anyone know what churches other than SDA and WWCoG do foot washing,<br>
historically and today?  Baptists?  Seventh Day Baptists, Etc.  As far<br>
as I know the RCC does not and never did.  But hey, I don't know that.<br>
<p>
Thanks,<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<p>
[In fact the Pope every year on Maundy Thursday washes the feet of <br>
twelve selected people as a re-enactment of the first footwashing.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
