<title>Nov_1992: Re: God's love</title>
<h1>Re: God's love</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Nov 92 19:26:52 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#31">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#31">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#31">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#31">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The Church Will Go Through"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Dave Buxton: "Footwashing -- History"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0017.html">Minna K Puustelli: "God's love"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; One of my teachers at the university said that she doesn't accept</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christian believes because she can't understand how God could ...</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; What would you say to this educated woman who does believe in supernatural,</i><br>
<i>&gt; in some "greater power" or "universal love" but not in "our" God ??</i><br>
<i>&gt; I wasn't able to give her a good answer and I'd really like to know </i><br>
<i>&gt; what you would have said!</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Minna</i><br>
---------<br>
Hello Minna,<br>
<p>
When one is trying to respond to another's dilemma, the best<br>
approach is to discover the root problem.  Above, I deleted<br>
your teacher's specific point because that is not the problem.<br>
The first two lines give us the root problem.  Her problem is<br>
that she will not accept a God she cannot understand.  She will<br>
believe only if she is allowed to define God.<br>
<p>
What would I say to this educated woman?  Hear the words of<br>
Paul from I Corinthians:<br>
<p>
  17 For Christ sent me not to baptize, but to preach the<br>
gospel: not with wisdom of words, lest the cross of Christ<br>
should be made of none effect.<br>
  18 For the preaching of the cross is to them that perish<br>
foolishness; but unto us which are saved it is the power of<br>
God.<br>
<p>
  21 For after that in the wisdom of God the world by wisdom<br>
knew not God, it pleased God by the foolishness of preaching to<br>
save them that believe.<br>
  22 For the Jews require a sign, and the Greeks seek after<br>
wisdom:<br>
  23 But we preach Christ crucified, unto the Jews a<br>
stumblingblock, and unto the Greeks foolishness;<br>
  24 But unto them which are called, both Jews and Greeks,<br>
Christ the power of God, and the wisdom of God.<br>
<p>
She needs to hear the word of God and pray that he would open<br>
her understanding to its truth, which is a spiritual revelation.<br>
You keep preaching the crucified Lamb of God.  Personally, I<br>
find reading about the sacrifices in the Old Testament (Genesis<br>
and Exodus) very rewarding.<br>
<p>
May God bless your labors,<br>
<p>
Dan Blake<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
