<title>Nov_1992: Re: The Church Will Go Through</title>
<h1>Re: The Church Will Go Through</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Nov 1992 23:07:51 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#32">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#32">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#32">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#32">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Drew: "Re: The Church Will Go Through"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Dan Blake: "Re: God's love"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0028.html">Dave Buxton: "The Church Will Go Through"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0040.html">malcolm butler: "Warning -- pedant alert (was: The Church Will Go Through)"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave repeats some timely warnings about the possibility of the church <br>
going through.  I think we can trace back the theology that endangers <br>
churches, and it's theology that is not unheard of in SDA churches:<br>
<p>
The Catholic view in ancient times and today is that the church is the<br>
prime if not only dispenser of God's grace, which is conveyed through<br>
sacraments. (Baptism, Marriage, Absolution, Ordination, etc.)<br>
With the notion that such a group has a monopoly on God, it follows<br>
that they will never think they are wrong.<br>
<p>
Other churches which follow this lead will find their organizations <br>
also becoming like this.  A ministry turns into a priesthood.  <br>
Appeals to reason are replaced with appeals to "traditional Adventism"<br>
whatever that may be.  ("Adventism" itself is a word I would like to <br>
excise from the language.  We do not refer to the religion of Baptists<br>
as "Baptism", do we?)  <br>
<p>
The trend in SDA leadership recently is away from the imperialistic <br>
attitude, and this is good.  But it will take more than enlightened <br>
leadership for the survival and growth of the church.  It will take<br>
a people who are servants of God and of each other, not people who <br>
play "dodgeball" with the inspired writings.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
