<title>Nov_1992: Footwashing</title>
<h1>Footwashing</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Nov 92 23:26:30 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#34">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#34">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#34">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#34">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The Church Will Go Through"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Drew: "Re: The Church Will Go Through"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0027.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Footwashing"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The washing of feet was practiced regularly in the 1830s-1840s by various<br>
Baptist sects--the Original Free-Will Baptists, Six-Principles Baptists,<br>
Seventh-Day Baptists, United Baptists, and Dunkers.  In fact, Joseph Smith,<br>
the prophet of Mormon Church also instituted a footwashing ceremony in 1836<br>
at the time of the dedication of the first Mormon Temple in Kirtland, Ohio.<br>
Footwashing was also practiced in the Mormon "School of the Prophets" which<br>
was started in 1832.  When the first 12 apostles of the LDS Church were<br>
called, the President of the Church, Joseph Smith, wash the feet of these<br>
twelve men in 1835.  Footwashing is now part of the endowment ceremonies<br>
performed in modern LDS Temples.<br>
<p>
Seventh-Day Adventists obviously "inherited" or "borrowed" this ceremony<br>
from the Baptists who were already doing this even before 1844.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The Church Will Go Through"</a>
