<title>Nov_1992: Footwashing, why?</title>
<h1>Footwashing, why?</h1>
Cam Litvin (<i>CLLITVIN@bluemoon.profs.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 13 Nov 92 08:12:08 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#39">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#39">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#39">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#39">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0040.html">malcolm butler: "Warning -- pedant alert (was: The Church Will Go Through)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Marcus Stringer: "The Church Will Go Through/Dodgeball"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am a lifetime SDA.  I stopped participating in footwashing regularly<br>
several years ago.  The reason for me is that it appears to be a meaning-<br>
less tradition.  A large percentage of the individuals participating<br>
are just going through the motions.  They wash the feet while talking<br>
about all sorts of secular activities.  I've found that staying in the<br>
sanctuary, listening to the music, reading my bible and meditating on<br>
the word of God much more spiritually uplifting.<br>
<p>
I've enjoyed the comments on footwashing.  The views some have expressed<br>
regarding reasons for footwashing have been refreshing.  I look forward<br>
to seeing some more.<br>
<p>
--Cam Litvin  PROFS Support  CLLITVIN<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
