<title>Nov_1992: The Church Will Go Through</title>
<h1>The Church Will Go Through</h1>
Malachi Robertson (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 13 Nov 92 17:00:08 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Paul Gates: "First Digest"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">malcolm butler: "Warning -- pedant alert (was: The Church Will Go Through)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0033.html">Drew: "Re: The Church Will Go Through"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am unsure if this is related to what Steve was talking about, but my<br>
fear is that we will become stagnate in some sense.  What I mean by this<br>
is that we don't have any fresh looks at the old fundamentals, but just a<br>
constant rehashing.  I find it is good sometimes to question oneself to<br>
see that the path taken has been the correct one.  After being an<br>
Adventist for abou a year I began to become more questioning in regards to<br>
the evidences for certain belief the Church holds.  It was in some sense<br>
my time to really start being a good Berean.  At times I was disappointed<br>
when I took another look at passages that had been brought up almost in a<br>
proof text fashion to support certain views, but at the same time the<br>
texts that were not disappointing and other texts I found supported the<br>
general belief.  Other items I am still struggling with and I hope that<br>
through further reflection and study a solution might be found.  My<br>
problems are mostly in the area of interpretations of Revelation (which is<br>
ironic since that is what got me to go to meetings conducted by the church<br>
in the first place).  I guess my point is that we should not be afraid to<br>
question things as long as we are humbly submissive to God and willing to<br>
learn the truth.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Ian.<br>
