<title>Nov_1992: Hermeneutics</title>
<h1>Hermeneutics</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 15 Nov 92 10:15:54 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "More footwashing"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Paul Gates: "First Digest"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hermeneutics is a big word.  It is also a big topic.  And, to some extent a<br>
misunderstood concept.  Basically it means translating an idea across time and<br>
space.  Hence, what we have to do with the Bible any time we read it.<br>
<p>
I'm working on a project on hermeneutics as practiced by lay people.  In <br>
simple words, I want to know what kind of rules or parameters people apply to<br>
their Bible study when they really want to find out something.<br>
<p>
Please let me know what "rules" for Bible investigation you think are most<br>
important.  I'm not giving examples, since I don't want to prejudice anyone. <br>
<p>
I'd like to hear from any and all.  Obviously, there will be different<br>
approaches.  Different people will ask different questions of the text.<br>
<p>
Thanks for your help.<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
