<title>Nov_1992: Re:  Hermeneutics</title>
<h1>Re:  Hermeneutics</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 17 Nov 1992 09:48:36 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#47">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#47">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#47">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#47">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Hermeneutics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0046.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Hermeneutics"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0048.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Hermeneutics"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In recent years I have tried in interpretation of the Bible to discard<br>
as many external postulates as I can.  My first rule would be:<br>
<p>
1)  Don't claim for the Bible what it doesn't claim for itself.<br>
2)  Areas in which it does claim inspiration "Doctrine, Reproof,<br>
Correction, and instruction in righteousness" should be our major goals<br>
for using the Bible.  But even this claim should not be taken at face<br>
value--rather we have the opportunity to *prove* that this claim is <br>
true by applying the Bible to our lives in the ways described above.<br>
<p>
3)  Ignore extrabiblical concepts which either limit (God can't force...)<br>
or overextend the reach of God.  <br>
<p>
4)  View apparent contradictions as potential paradoxes to be resolved,<br>
resulting in a deeper understanding, but don't be upset when one can't<br>
be resolved directly.<br>
<p>
5)  Realize that the Bible is infallible, but not necessarily my<br>
interpretation of it.<br>
<p>
6)  If apparent conflicts develop between the Bible and science, realize<br>
that we have much more to learn about both and keep an open mind.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
