<title>Nov_1992: Hermeneutics</title>
<h1>Hermeneutics</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 17 Nov 92 8:20:21 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#48">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#48">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#48">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#48">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0049.html">Gilbert Bailey: "re:Hermeneutics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Hermeneutics"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0046.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Hermeneutics"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here is Cheryl's list of hermeneutical rules:<br>
1. Ask for guidance from the Holy Spirit.<br>
2. Don't be afraid to challenge what you've been taught in the past.<br>
3. Try to understand the context of what is being said and then figure out<br>
   whether this is an "eternal truth" or something for that time and place.<br>
4. Don't accept a solitary verse as the basis for a belief.  Rather use all<br>
   of Scripture and adopt a global view.<br>
5. Try to be consistent.  If you adopt a literal interpretation in one <br>
   instance, don't use a symbolic view of related verses.<br>
6. Use the original Greek or Hebrew words to link related uses of these<br>
   words rather than accepting the English words as being the same.<br>
7. The Holy Bible is not the literal word of God.  So look for the principles<br>
   being applied but don't expect perfect agreement even for the same author.<br>
8. Don't discount a verse or scripture just because there are no collaborative<br>
   of supportive scripture.  A single verse conveying an idea or doctrine is<br>
   certainly possible.<br>
9. Take great care in interpreting prophecies.  Don't rely on past interpreta-<br>
   tions.  Don't force a literal interpretation on verses that appear to be<br>
   symbolic.<br>
10.Be careful of contamination by personal motives.  For example, if I want to<br>
   go skiing on Sabbath I might rationalize "doing thine own pleasure" as<br>
   business dealings only.<br>
<p>
I'd like to hear reactions.<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
