<title>Nov_1992: re:Hermeneutics</title>
<h1>re:Hermeneutics</h1>
Gilbert Bailey (<i>gilbertb@lsid.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 16 Nov 92 7:10:27 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#49">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#49">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#49">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#49">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0050.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Ham radio operators on SDAnet"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Hermeneutics"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nancy Vyhmeister writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I'm working on a project on hermeneutics as practiced by lay people.  In </i><br>
<i>&gt;simple words, I want to know what kind of rules or parameters people apply to</i><br>
<i>&gt;their Bible study when they really want to find out something.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Please let me know what "rules" for Bible investigation you think are most</i><br>
<i>&gt;important.  I'm not giving examples, since I don't want to prejudice anyone. </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
OK, here is the way I like to approach Bible study :       <br>
<p>
  1- Determine the author  ( I usually use the SDA Bible Commentary )<br>
  <br>
  2- Determine the audience ( SDA Bible Commentary, again )<br>
 <br>
  3- Become familiar with the historical setting<br>
  <br>
  4- Try to understand the issues addressed in the passage<br>
<p>
  5- Try to discover the principle(s) applied<br>
<p>
  6- Refer to other passages on the same topic<br>
<p>
  7- Read the relevant Spirit of Prophecy references<br>
<p>
  8- Look for confirmation of interpretation from other Christians<br>
<p>
  9- Use several Bible versions       <br>
<p>
 10- Pray for the Holy Spirit's guidence (MOST IMPORTANT)<br>
<p>
<p>
The above list is not exhaustive by any means, and are most likely not in<br>
the correct sequence.  I'll be waiting for other posts, knowing I'll be able<br>
to add to my list.<br>
<p>
-Gilbert<br>
<p>
