<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Thanks for the postings on hermeneutics.  A question for all: Do you</i><br>
<i>&gt; think the principles and procedures of hermeneutics need to be taught</i><br>
<i>&gt; to lay persons?  Can we expect all church members to "interpret"</i><br>
<i>&gt; scripture accurately?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Nancy</i><br>
<p>
Well, I've seen a number of acquaintances of mine who have gone off<br>
the deep end on Biblical prophecy.  One of them convinced himself that<br>
the world would end in 1992 due to the "jubilee of jubilees" occurring<br>
then.<br>
<p>
Graham Maxwell has told the story of the Loma Linda dentist who, when<br>
Maxwell tried to make an appointment a few months ahead on some<br>
business matter, informed him that this could not be done because by<br>
then the dentist would no longer be on the earth (he would be raptured<br>
or something).<br>
<p>
I think many people would be better off simply practicing<br>
nuts-and-bolts Christianity and staying completely out of theology.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
