<title>Nov_1992: Last Night's 48 hours (CBS) program.</title>
<h1>Last Night's 48 hours (CBS) program.</h1>
patricio d navia (<i>pdnavia@midway.uchicago.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 19 Nov 92 11:46:50 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#56">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#56">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#56">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#56">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Cam Litvin: "Last Night's 48 hours (CBS) program."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Raylene: "Hermeneutics &amp; theology for everyperson"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Last night I wathced the program 48 Hours on CBS (a news special program in the<br>
U.S.)<br>
<p>
The topic was pornography.  The program seemed interesting and informative, at least<br>
the part I had the opportunity to watch.<br>
<p>
However, what really caugth my attention was a interview they conducted to a<br>
pronographyic movie actress.  She was an African American from Fresno, California and<br>
they said she had been raised in a Seventh Day Adventist Church.  They interviewed<br>
also her mother (who chose not to be shown in film). <br>
<p>
The actress said she did not want to do those types of movies for more than<br>
1 year and her goal was to become a 'real' movie director.<br>
<p>
She says that nobody would have thought she'd end up doing that, nor even herself.<br>
<p>
It's is rather uncomforting to hear those types of references to the church, I think.<br>
<p>
Well, that's my contribution, just a thought.<br>
<p>
Patricio navia<br>
Political Science<br>
University of Chicago.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
