<title>Nov_1992: Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity</title>
<h1>Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 20 Nov 1992 10:03:49 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#58">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#58">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#58">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#58">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Fred Christiansen: "CofE and the Papacy"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Cam Litvin: "Last Night's 48 hours (CBS) program."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0063.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am troubled by when people suggest that we shouldn't worry about <br>
theology and just concentrate on day-to-day Christianity.<br>
It seems to me that hermeneutics (which is a ten-dollar word for <br>
how one interprets the Bible) is closely tied in with everyday life.<br>
So, for that matter, should be all other aspects of whatever theology<br>
and doctrine we have.<br>
<p>
What we believe is important, especially for Seventh-day Adventists, because<br>
often that is the only thing we as Adventists have in common.  In particular<br>
since the subculture has disintegrated, the common ground in doctrine stands<br>
alone instead of alongside common ground in behavior.  The doctrinal <br>
pillars of our church can and must be used to build interpersonal unity<br>
and consensus in other areas of church life.<br>
<p>
Without the Advent message, the Adventist church would have no common <br>
purpose to exist.  Those who suppose that the distinctive doctrines of <br>
Adventism can somehow be separated from "basic Christianity" or<br>
"personal relationship with God" are mistaken.  All our doctrine and<br>
theology<br>
should lead us to a better relationship with God and our fellow man.<br>
We have a ways to go to prove that they in fact do--this is why we have<br>
not yet seen the world beating a path to our door.  But I am convinced<br>
that they can.  If someone feels that there is one of the 27 fundamental <br>
beliefs which does not directly help relationship to God or man, I encourage<br>
them to explain on the net why they think this is so.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
