<title>Nov_1992: Theology vs Theologians</title>
<h1>Theology vs Theologians</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 20 Nov 92 16:34:04 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#61">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#61">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#61">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#61">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0062.html">Malachi Robertson: "Hermenutics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Hermeneutics &amp; theology for everyperson"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I may be putting words into Glen's mouth but methinks his comments<br>
about theology may come from experiences with theologians .. you know,<br>
the academicians that teach Bible and Theology classes at colleges and<br>
seminaries.<br>
<p>
I attended Andrews Univeristy and Seminaire Adventiste du Saleve.  I had<br>
some good teachers, some questionable; some who brooked no discussion<br>
on interpretation and those who seemed swayed by "higher criticism" perhaps.<br>
For example, was it really the Red Sea that the children of Israel<br>
crossed or was Yam Suph (Sea of Reeds) just one of the Bitter Lakes?<br>
Yet again, Moses' history of Creation week may be "too simplistic".<br>
<p>
 From my experience, theologians run the risk of their Christianity<br>
becoming pedestrian, work-a-day, or on the other hand, esoteric (Acts 26:24b).<br>
They can become too full of themselves, of their own erudition (Pro 21:2),<br>
or too accepting of their peers and professors.  For example, most<br>
SDA theologians got their PhDs from non-SDA schools.  There have been<br>
problems with strange beliefs creeping in (e.g., Brinsmead, Desmond Ford).<br>
Mind you, it only takes a couple like this to give the whole crew a bad rap,<br>
to make common folk wary.<br>
<p>
A contemporary example, IMHO, is a recent Pacific Union Recorder where<br>
two theologians/ethicists from LaSierra, I believe, gave opinions pro/con on<br>
California's Right-to-Die proposition.  Two things concerned me here:<br>
1) The con opinion was really a pro opinion but recommending con for<br>
now, "let's wait and see how things turn out in Holland".  2) Both made<br>
vague references to Adventist tradition, views on human life, but totally<br>
without any Scripture references (or, gasp!, EGW quotes).  So help me!<br>
Have they really abandoned Scripture as having anything relevant to say?<br>
<p>
Theologian/teacher or layfolk, but especially them because of the role they<br>
have, need to understand the importance of a humble and teachable spirit<br>
and a servant's heart:<br>
  PSA 25:9 The meek will he guide in judgment: and the meek will he teach<br>
    his way.<br>
  JOH 3:30 He must increase, but I must decrease.<br>
  JAM 4:6 But he giveth more grace. Wherefore he saith, God resisteth the<br>
    proud, but giveth grace unto the humble.  (also 1 Pet 5:5,6)<br>
  PHI 2:8 And being found in fashion as a man, he humbled himself [..]<br>
  MAT 23:11 But he that is greatest among you shall be your servant.<br>
  JOH 12:26 If any man serve me, let him follow me; and where I am, there<br>
    shall also my servant be: IF ANY MAN SERVE ME, HIM WILL MY FATHER HONOUR.<br>
  GAL 1:10 For do I now persuade men, or God? or do I seek to please men?<br>
    for if I yet pleased men, I should not be the servant of Christ.<br>
<p>
Moses was mighty in Spirit because of his attitude:<br>
  EXO 33:13 Now therefore, I pray thee, if I have found grace in thy sight,<br>
    SHEW ME NOW THY WAY, THAT I MAY KNOW THEE, that I may find grace in thy<br>
    sight: and consider that this nation is thy people.  (emph suppl)<br>
  EXO 33:14 And he said, My presence shall go with thee, and I will give<br>
    thee rest.<br>
<p>
Solomon was blessed at Gibeon because of his attitude:<br>
  1 KI 3:7 And now, O LORD my God, thou hast made thy servant king instead of<br>
    David my father: and I AM BUT A LITTLE CHILD: I KNOW NOT HOW TO GO OUT OR<br>
    COME IN.<br>
  1 KI 3:9 GIVE THEREFORE THY SERVANT AN UNDERSTANDING HEART to judge thy<br>
    people, that I may discern between good and bad: for who is able to judge<br>
    this thy so great a people?<br>
  1 KI 3:10 And the speech pleased the LORD, that Solomon had asked this thing.<br>
<p>
Too often we approach Bible study just wanting knowledge for an assignment<br>
or to rebut someone on SDAnet 8-) or whatever.  I found these passages<br>
instructive:<br>
  EXO 31:3 And I have filled him with the spirit of God, in wisdom, and in<br>
    understanding, and in knowledge, and in all manner of workmanship,<br>
Notice that being mighty in Spirit, obtaining Godly wisdom, and<br>
understanding God's perspective come before knowledge and applied skill.<br>
There is another instructive passage on Christian growth:<br>
  2 PE 1:5-8 And beside this, giving all diligence, add to your faith virtue;<br>
    and to virtue knowledge; And to knowledge temperance; and to temperance<br>
    patience; and to patience godliness; And to godliness brotherly kindness;<br>
    and to brotherly kindness charity .  For if these things be in you, and<br>
    abound, they make you that ye shall neither be barren nor unfruitful in<br>
    the knowledge of our Lord Jesus Christ.<br>
<p>
Peace to you all in the Lord.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
