<title>Nov_1992: Hermenutics</title>
<h1>Hermenutics</h1>
Malachi Robertson (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 22 Nov 92 0:57:46 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Fred Christiansen: "Theology vs Theologians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Please forgive my spelling if I happened to mess up on that subject line.<br>
<p>
In reaction to Cheryl's rules of interpretation, I will first of all say<br>
that most of them I can generally agree with.  I have some problems<br>
though. With number 2 on questioning past teaching, I feel there is a<br>
right and wrong way on this.  You can do it humbly or arrogantly.  I guess<br>
that is just a qualification I would add.  With number 5 on consistency, I<br>
should have mentioned that myself.  If I had I would have added that<br>
sometimes inconsistencies are only on the surface and that there is some<br>
justification for the apparent inconsistency.  For example, I see a<br>
justified one in saying the woman was clothed with the sun and the sun<br>
being a symbol of the Light of God, while later when John says of the<br>
heavenly city, it had no sun, to say that that should mean the literal<br>
sun.  As for number 7 on the literal word of God, I am usure what is meant<br>
by the literal word of God and I am not comfortable with the statement<br>
about the authors.  With number 9, one should be cautious in not relying<br>
on past interpretations.  Sure let them be scrutinzed, but don't throw<br>
them out the window right off from the start.  I guess my probems are more<br>
qualifications I would make and a question or two.<br>
<p>
Ian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
