<title>Nov_1992: Song of Solomon</title>
<h1>Song of Solomon</h1>
Dan Hamstra (<i>hamstra@peter.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 23 Nov 1992 08:54:40 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Raylene: "Theology"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0072.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Song of Solomon"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Since this quarter's Sabbath School lessons are on Song of Solomon (Song of<br>
Songs), I'm looking for various opinions as to what this book of the Bible<br>
means.  I'm particularly interested in what you think this book's message<br>
is portraying.  Is it "love poetry?"  Does it represent Christ' love for<br>
the church?  Something else?<br>
<p>
While discussing this with some friends recently, I became aware that I<br>
could think of no place in the Bible where there are more words attributed<br>
to one woman than in this book.  I haven't checked out Ruth and Esther<br>
recently but I don't recall that they are quoted very much.  I suppose this<br>
may be considered trivial if you don't think of the Shulamite in Song of<br>
Solomon as being a literal person, but as a character in a story,  However,<br>
I still thought this "trivia" was interesting.<br>
<p>
dan hamstra<br>
hamstra@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
