<title>Nov_1992: Theology</title>
<h1>Theology</h1>
Raylene (<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>23 Nov 1992 16:59:34 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Dan Hamstra: "Song of Solomon"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Fred Christiansen</i><br>
<i>&gt;I may be putting words into Glen's mouth but methinks his comments</i><br>
<i>&gt;about theology may come from experiences with theologians ...</i><br>
<p>
<i> &gt;From my experience, theologians run the risk of their Christianity</i><br>
<i>&gt;becoming pedestrian, work-a-day, or on the other hand, esoteric (Acts 26:24b).</i><br>
<i>&gt;They can become too full of themselves, of their own erudition (Pro 21:2),</i><br>
<i>&gt;or too accepting of their peers and professors...</i><br>
<p>
Our judgement of certain groups of people is always coloured by those of that<br>
category that we have had dealings with. It was with this in mind that I<br>
noticed the above comments with interest. I don't know who it was that Glen<br>
thought should be having less theology and more Christianity but from my<br>
experience I wouldn't have thought of the theologians. I lived at Avondale<br>
College for 6 years while growing up, then for 4 years while doing a teaching<br>
degree, thus completing a number of Bible subjects. I have a great respect <br>
for those theologians in whose classes I sat. They seemed to be able to make<br>
the Bible come alive, put things into proper perspectives, present varying<br>
points of view. I didn't think of theology as being a dangerous or over-used<br>
thing in their hands.<br>
<p>
On the other hand, those non-theologians who may be retired, may be ex-<br>
evangelists, or who may on the other hand be preferring "lawlessness" seem to<br>
me to be the dangerous ones. It is these fringe-dwellers or trouble-makers I<br>
would have considered theology to be a deadly tool for rather than the<br>
theologians. But I would still have to defend their right to the Bible and <br>
even their right to deceive people as they do, though I'd rather they not<br>
do it.<br>
<p>
So that was the picture I saw anyway!<br>
Raylene<br>
---*---<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
