<title>Nov_1992: Re: Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity</title>
<h1>Re: Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 23 Nov 1992 09:31:28 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#66">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#66">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#66">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#66">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Steven Timm: "Making the church safe for baby boomers and yuppies"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Raylene: "Theology"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0058.html">Steven Timm: "Theology and Nuts-bolts Christianity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;As an outsider looking in, what were the things that SDAs once had in common</i><br>
<i>&gt;as their "subculture"? When and why did it disintegrate?</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Thanks,</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Drew.</i><br>
<p>
There are some on this net who would not agree with me that the subculture<br>
has disintegrated.  I would say that the most drastic changes happened in <br>
the 70's to and through the early 80's.  It was in the 70's that the<br>
people of the righteousness-by-faith message started really being heard.<br>
Unfortunately the message was misunderstood, leading to people accepting<br>
the easy part about salvation by faith but ignoring the part about <br>
salvation from sin.  When people started hearing that salvation was by <br>
faith alone, many were (and still are) unable to comprehend why the <br>
various components of the Adventist lifestyle should be practiced at all.<br>
<p>
The changes have included liberalization in forms of entertainment,<br>
diet, and dress.  From time to time all these issues are discussed here<br>
at length.  I refer to the death of the subculture not because of these<br>
changes, but because what happens at the church's institutions is becoming<br>
increasingly more irrelevant to the local churches that are far away <br>
from them.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
