<title>Nov_1992: Re: hermeneutics</title>
<h1>Re: hermeneutics</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>71172.2044@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>22 Nov 92 20:44:15 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#68">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#68">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#68">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#68">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Paul Gates: "Amateur Radio"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Steven Timm: "Making the church safe for baby boomers and yuppies"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The Reformation is lost if hermenutics is not taught to "lay" members.<br>
Since I don't think we have the Catholic approach to scriptural<br>
interpretation (some may disagree!) then the logical extension is that we<br>
*must* teach hermenutics to as many "lay" members as possible.  The wild<br>
ideas circulated by many fringe religious groups are often the result of<br>
narrow, confused, and uninformed application of scripture. <br>
I think many leaders are afraid of "lay" members asking too many<br>
questions. (And aren't we back to the Reformation?!)<br>
A broadened perspective and deeper understanding of the bible and its<br>
context in culture, history, and language can only help to expand our<br>
understanding and proclimation of scriptural truth.  The tools to do this<br>
cannot, must not be kept by the few.<br>
<p>
<p>
Dave J.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
