<title>Nov_1992: Hermaneutics -- Homework Assignment -- Isa 4:1</title>
<h1>Hermaneutics -- Homework Assignment -- Isa 4:1</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 23 Nov 92 08:13:00 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#70">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#70">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#70">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#70">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0071.html">Bob Moynihan: "Making the church safe for baby boomers and yuppies"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Paul Gates: "Amateur Radio"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0073.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Hermaneutics -- Homework Assignment -- Isa 4:1"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
"And in that day seven women shall take hold of one man saying, "We will<br>
eat our own food and wear our own apparel; only let us be called by your<br>
name, to take away our reproach."" -- Isa 4:1 (NKJ)<br>
<p>
* Is this a prophecy?<br>
<p>
* Is it a coded/symbolic prophecy?<br>
<p>
If it is a coded prophecy, what does it mean:<br>
<p>
* "And in that day" -- what time period?<br>
<p>
* Woman means church, what about seven women?<br>
<p>
* "one man"<br>
<p>
* "our own food"<br>
<p>
* "Our own apparel"<br>
<p>
* "called by your name", whose name?<br>
<p>
Here is how the text "decodes" for me:<br>
<p>
  In the last days there will be many churches that will take hold of<br>
  Jesus name saying, "We will have our own traditions and assume our own<br>
  forms of righteousness; only let us be called Christians, in order that<br>
  our religion may be seen as legitimate.<br>
<p>
How does it read for you?<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
