<!-- id="Added.If4Eog_00UkTAR9U4a@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Nov_1992: Making the church safe for baby boomers and yuppies</title>
<h1>Making the church safe for baby boomers and yuppies</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 23 Nov 92 10:48:53 EST </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#71">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#71">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#71">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#71">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Song of Solomon"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0070.html">Dave Buxton: "Hermaneutics -- Homework Assignment -- Isa 4:1"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; "Joe" has visited our church semi-regularly for four years at least.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; Often he arrives late, only in time for pot luck.  When he does come in </i><br>
<i>&gt; time for church, he will sit in the back, not in the main sanctuary.</i><br>
<i>&gt; He's very self-conscious about personal cleanliness but that doesn't mean</i><br>
<i>&gt; he is always cleaned up.  He has been homeless for most of this time. </i><br>
<i>&gt; He is essentially harmless and wouldn't hurt a fly.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Evidently in the period in which I was gone from Pittsburgh, and still</i><br>
<i>&gt; continuing now, there have been some problems mostly concerning the</i><br>
<i>&gt; almost compulsive and lengthy routine he goes through in the church's </i><br>
<i>&gt; restroom.  People of authority in the church have been speaking recently </i><br>
<i>&gt; about asking him to leave and never come back, and when I heard their </i><br>
<i>&gt; side of the story I had to admit that there is really a problem which </i><br>
<i>&gt; does need to be addressed.  Knowing "Joe's" track record it's unlikely </i><br>
<i>&gt; that he could change his behavior enough to reassure the large number </i><br>
<i>&gt; of people who are uncomfortable with his presence for a number of good </i><br>
<i>&gt; reasons. </i><br>
<p>
Well, since you don't detail what those reasons may be, it's hard to give<br>
an informed opinion on "Joe", but I'll give it a shot.  If his restroom<br>
"routine" is the main source of concern, keep in mind that he may have <br>
little opportunity for fastidiousness outside the perceived friendly<br>
confines of the church.  My impression is that his presence is tolerated<br>
but not welcomed.  Personally, I think rather than being shown the door,<br>
he should be encouraged to participate more.  His spiritual well-being is<br>
far more important than the sensibilities of church members whose track<br>
record of black intolerance is shameful. <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Are the homeless the next group that we must learn to tolerate?  Will it </i><br>
<i>&gt; hurt the yuppies to learn to tolerate them any more than it hurt the </i><br>
<i>&gt; rednecks of a generation ago to tolerate integration? </i><br>
<p>
If there is a group of people that are "different" from me for some reason, <br>
and those people are seeking our Savior, and my feeling is that I must<br>
"tolerate" their presence, then I submit that I'm a -lot- further from the <br>
Savior then they are.  No matter our color or circumstances, we are all equal<br>
in the eyes of the Lord.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; And, as a city church, can we afford to ignore an important sector of </i><br>
<i>&gt; the population? </i><br>
<p>
No.<br>
<p>
===================================================================<br>
Bob Moynihan                         Go Ipswich Town!<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com             Never let the rocks cry out.<br>
