<!-- body="start" -->
Dan writes:<br>
<i>&gt; Since this quarter's Sabbath School lessons are on Song of Solomon (Song of</i><br>
<i>&gt; Songs), I'm looking for various opinions as to what this book of the Bible</i><br>
<i>&gt; means.  I'm particularly interested in what you think this book's message</i><br>
<i>&gt; is portraying.  Is it "love poetry?"  Does it represent Christ' love for</i><br>
<i>&gt; the church?  Something else?</i><br>
<p>
A work I have found useful is Joseph Dillow's "Solomon on Sex". The basic <br>
view is that SoS deals with married love, and the issues couples sometimes<br>
face. He goes through all the symbolism as it would have been viewed in <br>
that culture. IMO the SoS is included in the Bible because God wants us to<br>
have happy marriages.<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
