<title>Nov_1992: Re: Hermaneutics -- Homework Assignment -- Isa 4:1</title>
<h1>Re: Hermaneutics -- Homework Assignment -- Isa 4:1</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 23 Nov 1992 22:19:50 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#73">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#73">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#73">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#73">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Song of Solomon"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Song of Solomon"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0070.html">Dave Buxton: "Hermaneutics -- Homework Assignment -- Isa 4:1"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My interpretation of Isaiah 4:1  -- It is in context of the previous <br>
chapter talking about the overthrow of Israel as a proud and haughty woman.<br>
We see in the preceding verses the women being stripped of all their<br>
garments.  I think the prophecy is quite literal and not coded, with no<br>
particular reference to the church of today except:<br>
<p>
The idea of seven women taking hold of one man is encouraging to those of <br>
us males who are still bachelors.  For this class of people it is a <br>
great and wonderful promise of sorts.  If only it weren't in the context<br>
of reproached and humbled women grabbing on, it would be even more so.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
