<title>Nov_1992: Re: Song of Solomon</title>
<h1>Re: Song of Solomon</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 23 Nov 92 14:53:27 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#74">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#74">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#74">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#74">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Song of Solomon"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Hermaneutics -- Homework Assignment -- Isa 4:1"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0064.html">Dan Hamstra: "Song of Solomon"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0075.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Song of Solomon"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[hamstra@peter.cs.andrews.edu writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; I'm particularly interested in what you think this book's message</i><br>
<i>&gt; is portraying.  Is it "love poetry?"  Does it represent Christ' love for</i><br>
<i>&gt; the church?  Something else?</i><br>
<p>
Numerous well-known and not-so-well-known Christian authors have<br>
written at length, and very well so, regarding SofS as love poetry.<br>
I have also heard folk speak on SofS as representing Christ' love<br>
for the church.  And seeing how God uses the metaphor of husband-and-wife<br>
for Christ-and-the-church it does not take any stretching to see both.<br>
<p>
Something else?  Well, we have a video from the Quiet Hour wherein some<br>
guests use SofS as a metaphor/model for the church thru apostolic times,<br>
the Dark Ages, the Reformation and so on.  And it seems to make sense.  It<br>
would not surprise me that God is using Song of Solomon for all of the above.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
