<title>Nov_1992: re: Song of Solomon</title>
<h1>re: Song of Solomon</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 23 Nov 92 10:39:28 EST </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#76">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#76">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#76">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#76">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Making the church safe for baby boomers and yuppies"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Song of Solomon"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0064.html">Dan Hamstra: "Song of Solomon"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dan Hamstra writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I'm particularly interested in what you think this book's message</i><br>
<i>&gt; is portraying.  Is it "love poetry?"  Does it represent Christ' </i><br>
<i>&gt; love for the church?  Something else?</i><br>
<p>
Well, I've been partial to the belief that in some respects, it <br>
represents God's love for us.  Think of Solomon as Jesus, and <br>
Shulamith as "us".  I get the impression that she loves Solomon <br>
deeply, but feels unworthy of his love, wanting to know why he <br>
loves her.  He, in turn, tells her that if she doesn't know, then <br>
she should follow him and find out. (That's what I got from Chapter <br>
1.)<br>
<p>
Solomon had hundreds of wives and concubines.  Jesus has millions <br>
of followers.  Just as Shulamith needed reassurance of her <br>
uniqueness to Solomon, that she as an individual was special and <br>
loved for her own sake, we too wonder how Jesus could love each of <br>
us individually, worried that we may be lost in a sea of faces.<br>
<p>
Solomon's joy at his wedding is Jesus' joy at our choosing to be<br>
part of Him.  These sorts of parallels kind of jumped at me. <br>
<p>
Did anyone else get the same impression? <br>
<p>
