<title>Nov_1992: Re: Making the church safe for baby boomers and yuppies</title>
<h1>Re: Making the church safe for baby boomers and yuppies</h1>
Stan Macasieb (<i>macasib@degas.rtsg.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 23 Nov 1992 09:46:16 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#77">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#77">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#77">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#77">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Steven Timm: "Re: baby boomer tolerance"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0076.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: Song of Solomon"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i> &gt;From Steve Timm:</i><br>
Even with the clear-cut evidence in this case, it still makes me<br>
uncomfortable to hear the attitudes of those proposing his dismissal.<br>
Are we setting a precedent by throwing out those who don't fit?  Will<br>
this enhance the spirit of classism already prevalent in this church?<br>
Who will be next?  Is the throwing out of the homeless the price we must<br>
pay to make our stated targed group, yuppies and baby boomers, comfortable?<br>
Will Joe be willing to leave Abraham's bosom to drop water on our tongues<br>
when the fire gets hot?  (Echoes of the parable of the rich man and Lazarus).<br>
--------------<br>
<p>
My comments:<br>
<p>
A pretty scary thought. I guess there are people in this world who would<br>
exclude on the basis that they are not us. <br>
<p>
I made a small comment in the last church newsletter that, because new<br>
members from our recent evangelistic crusade will be joining our church<br>
in the coming weeks, we needed to be prepared to accept them, warts and<br>
all, because we would like them to treat us in the same way and it's<br>
the way God intended for us to act.<br>
<p>
Does the Pittsburgh church have a tremendous number of 2nd and 3rd Generation<br>
SDAs? Not as much an indictment than an observation, I've observed a<br>
mainstream approach to our faith when we've been in this church "for<br>
life". We're starting to look like our Methodist and Baptist friends socially.<br>
For better or worse, we need to take a good hard look at our response to<br>
our brothers and sisters and wonder if we're doing as God would want us<br>
to do. <br>
<p>
To throw out the homeless to keep the beautiful people? Methinks, Steve,<br>
that the issue is much deeper than that. Are Baby Boomers that shallow<br>
to believe that image is much more important than belief? And are we <br>
really disguising our own prejudices by defending someone else's supposed<br>
prejudices?<br>
<p>
