<!-- body="start" -->
It seems to me that we should take a different approach to this issue.  Rather <br>
than focusing on the baby boomers' attitudes, let's look at "Joe" and ask <br>
ourselves, "How would Jesus treat him?"  It seems obvious that Jesus would not <br>
turn Joe away.  Instead he would try to meet his needs.  I lack Jesus' <br>
omniscience, but it occurs to me that Joe's needs could be met in a way that <br>
would alleviate parents' fears.<br>
<p>
As one idea, what about assigning a deacon to pick Joe up early Sabbath morning, <br>
get him a good breakfast, give him a chance to take care of his personal <br>
hygiene, and then take Joe under his wing for the day.  This may allow Joe to <br>
get his needs met without offending others at the church, and it certainly is <br>
more in line with the duties of a deacon than just taking up the offering on <br>
Sabbath morning.  Joe may or may not ever be able to function appropriately on <br>
his own, but he can still give his life to the Savior, and it is the <br>
responsibility of the church to help the Holy Spirit work in his life.<br>
<p>
I heard an audio tape a couple years ago that was put out by Focus on the <br>
Family.  Entitled "A Man Called Norman", it is about how to treat others that <br>
are different from ourselves.  Norman has a lot in common with Joe.  I believe <br>
this story has been made into a movie.  Our church will be showing it for a <br>
Vespers program within a few weeks.  Maybe yours could do the same.<br>
<p>
Andy Arkusinski<br>
_______________________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<p>
[This is precisely the issue.  Although these fears are probably unfounded,<br>
they are real.  I didn't want to give more details of the situation than<br>
necessary.  He has done nothing that would be considered sexually<br>
inappropriate, but he has behaved in away that is sufficiently out of<br>
order<br>
to arouse the above fears.  Everyone (myself included) agrees that something<br>
should be done, the question is what should or can be done.  SCT]<br>
