<title>Nov_1992: Adventist Shamanism</title>
<h1>Adventist Shamanism</h1>
Pam Harris (<i>HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU</i>)<br>
<i>24 Nov 1992 10:35:16 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#81">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#81">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#81">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#81">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0082.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "ISA 4:10"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0080.html">ARKUSINSKI ANDY : "More on Compuserve Forum"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A recently published book by Harold Bloom, "The American Religion: The<br>
Emergence of the Post-Christian Nation" (Simon &amp; Schuster, 1992), has a<br>
thought-provoking chapter on Adventism. Bloom read extensively in<br>
White's writings in preparation for writing this book. Some of his<br>
observations include:<br>
	Adventism is a "formerly racist church"<br>
	No American faith, not even Jehovah's Witnesses, has a theology<br>
	so convoluted as that of SDAs. "I observe this in admiration<br>
	not in disrespect.:<br>
<p>
	Bloom puzzles about the "enigma of her (White's) authority for<br>
	followers down to the present time."<br>
<p>
	He calls Adventist an "American Religion of Health, crossed<br>
	by the postapocalyptic dream of an end time never to be."<br>
<p>
	In regard to the Investigative Judgment, he says:<br>
	"I cannot think of another American doctrine, even among<br>
	the Jehovah's Witnesses, that assigns so crucial a role to<br>
	Satan. Were that malign spirit to be blotted out prematurely,<br>
	then there could be no salvation for Seventh-day Adventists.<br>
	Ellen White's Jesus is more a defense attorney for mankind<br>
	than he is the bearer of the Atonement...we are given, in<br>
	effect...a Satanic Atonement. Perhaps that is the final ven-<br>
	geance of those who suffered the Millerite Great Disappointment<br>
	of 1844."<br>
<p>
	"Pragmatically, the vicarious nature of the Atonement has<br>
	passed from Christ to Satan, with some rather dark<br>
	psychological consequences in Adventist believers."<br>
<p>
	"If you teach children that failure to keep the Seventh-day<br>
	Sabbath will bring upon them the Mark of the Beast, then you are<br>
	in danger of scapegoating children."<br>
<p>
	He predicts Adventism will "dwindle away into a purely medical<br>
	sect if such 'doctrinal modification' goes much further<br>
	(the second coming becoming more distant, upper-class<br>
	materialistic values)...Either Adventism will return to her<br>
	vision of shamanism as a branch of the American Religion,<br>
	or it will vanish from among us except as a vast medical<br>
	legacy."<br>
<p>
These are among the many interesting observations Bloom makes.<br>
<p>
There are chapters on Mormonism, Christian Science, Southern Baptist,<br>
Jehovah's Witnesses, Pentecostalism, The New Age, and others as well.<br>
<p>
Pam Harris<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
