<title>Nov_1992: ISA 4:10</title>
<h1>ISA 4:10</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 25 Nov 92 14:00:58 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#82">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#82">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#82">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#82">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0083.html">David Plaisted: "principles of interpretation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Pam Harris: "Adventist Shamanism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Indeed, here is a good opportunity to see the importance of correct hermeneuticsIf one's rules call for taking the simplest, straight forward meaning of a text<br>
within its context, we have one result.  If we go first to a prophetic or figur-<br>
ative sense, we get another idea.<br>
<p>
If we look for the simplest meaning, nearest to the context, we have Israel<br>
decimated by the invaders, the men killed off in battle.  The women who are<br>
left want husbands, not necessarily support.  Why would women want husbands?<br>
The historical social context of Israel in OT times indicates that a woman was<br>
fulfilled only if she had children.  Obviously, this is a prophecy, but unless<br>
we find it applied by another Bible writer to a later period, the primary <br>
application is the most normal.<br>
<p>
So would a rule that the normal, simple, literal interpretation is to be pre-<br>
ferred unless there is clear evidence of something else be valid?<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
