<title>Nov_1992: Copyright on EGW CD-Rom</title>
<h1>Copyright on EGW CD-Rom</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 30 Nov 1992 16:12:10 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: S.O.P. texts"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Beng Tang actually sent me the first chapter of "Steps To Christ"<br>
as a demonstration of what the software could do.  I didn't post it <br>
for the twin reason that it's awfully big and clearly in the US<br>
we would be violating some copyright.  I don't know if those copyright<br>
laws apply to him in Singapore or not, but one should be careful <br>
about doing much with it in the US of A.<br>
<p>
How much on-line stuff is possible would depend on whether or not the <br>
text is compressed on the CD-ROM.  When I was a student at Andrews University<br>
I worked on a project where we compressed the entire Bible and its<br>
concordance into less space than the uncompressed Bible would take up.  <br>
This created "The Lamp", a project which was technically ahead of its time<br>
but was hopelessly outmarketed and undersupported.  (I believe this project<br>
is now defunct at AU.)  When it came time to do the EGW project, <br>
they went with an outside contractor to do the software (smart).  With <br>
the storage space available on CD, probably compression is not necessary.<br>
Does anyone know how well the CD is indexed and cross-referenced? e.g.<br>
is every search a sequential search through the whole volume or are <br>
there some keys, or better yet, a full on-disk concordance?<br>
<p>
If the CD is in the format I think it is in, a Unix link would be <br>
technically trivial and legally a nightmare.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: S.O.P. texts"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
