<title>May_1992: Waldenses</title>
<h1>Waldenses</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 13 May 92 13:56:17 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: 1 Tim 4"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A recent message stated:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;"Waldensian SDA's"</i><br>
<i>&gt;seems like quite a contradiction in terms because the Waldenses are known</i><br>
<i>&gt;not to have kept the Sabbath.</i><br>
<p>
There is historical evidence that the Waldenses observed the Sabbath on<br>
Saturday during the middle ages, though some may also have observed<br>
Sunday.  For a discussion of this, see History of the Sabbath by<br>
J.N. Andrews or Truth Triumphant by Wilkinson.  They give the<br>
historical evidence.  I think they are available from Leaves of<br>
Autumn Press in Arizona, or Hartland Institute in Virginia.<br>
<p>
These books also contain evidence that the Waldenses originated in<br>
the days of the apostles or their immediate descendents, contrary<br>
to some history books today that say they originated about 1200.<br>
Thus the Waldenses represent a continuous descent from the early<br>
Christian Church, independent of the Roman Catholic church.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: 1 Tim 4"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
