<title>May_1992: Re: 1 Tim 4</title>
<h1>Re: 1 Tim 4</h1>
Scott Mattes (<i>COTRSSM@sea04vm.navsea.navy.mil</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 13 May 92 21:24:48 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#27">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#27">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#27">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#27">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0028.html">David Plaisted: "addresses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0026.html">David Plaisted: "Waldenses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Wed, 13 May 1992 11:40:37 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I am not sure where the "food animals" appear in the text.  Perhaps I need to</i><br>
<i>&gt;be shown what phrase they are hiding in.</i><br>
<p>
  See 1 Tim 4:3 and 4<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Other questions about diet:</i><br>
<i>&gt;Original diet= Gen 1:29--seeds and fruits</i><br>
<i>&gt;Post-sin diet= Gen 3:18--plants are added.  Maybe spinach and broccoli!</i><br>
<i>&gt;Post flood diet=Gen 9:3,4--meat but not the blood.  The fact that more of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;clean animals were in the ark suggests that these were the ones for food.</i><br>
<p>
  The last, post flood, is interesting, because God says in 3 that<br>
'Every moving thing that liveth shall be meat for you; even as the green<br>
herb have I given you all things.'<br>
<p>
  That sounds like clean and unclean.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Vegetarianism is not an article of faith.   Knowing what we know today about</i><br>
<i>&gt;cholesterol, fat, infections, calories, and cleanliness, it may be a matter</i><br>
<i>&gt;of wisdom.  What I do to my body--where God desires to dwell through the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Holy Spirit--has spiritual implications.  Since what affects my body also</i><br>
<i>&gt;affects my nervous system, and the only way God has to communicate with me is</i><br>
<i>&gt;through my brain and nerves, I feel strongly that I need to keep in good</i><br>
<i>&gt;condition.  The health responsibility includes much more than no meat.  I</i><br>
<i>&gt;must include other aspects of diet, exercise, rest, fresh air, cleanliness,</i><br>
<i>&gt;and trust in the divine physician.</i><br>
<p>
  Like I said, I don't disagree with these ideas.<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
