<title>May_1992: Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?</title>
<h1>Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 13 May 92 07:29:20 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#25">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#25">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#25">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#25">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0026.html">David Plaisted: "Waldenses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: 1 Tim 4"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0013.html">Dave Buxton: "Is the SDA church Ecumenical?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; The Waldensian church survived the persecution of the Middle Ages and</i><br>
<i>&gt; is still active, but small, today.  It is responsible for one of the </i><br>
<i>&gt; only Protestant translations of the Bible into Italian.  "Waldensian SDA's"</i><br>
<i>&gt; seems like quite a contradiction in terms because the Waldenses are known </i><br>
<i>&gt; not to have kept the Sabbath.</i><br>
<p>
There are several quotes I could dig up that indicate that at least some<br>
if not all of the Waldenses were pursued to their deaths because they<br>
were Sabbatarians.  It is possible that originally they were, as a<br>
church body, Sabbatarian.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
