<title>May_1992: dietary info</title>
<h1>dietary info</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 4 May 92 10:01:08 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#5">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#5">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#5">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#5">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">James Dunn: "Re: Free speech"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Eric Snyder: "dietary info"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I would say the position is to treat your body with as much care and<br>
reverence as you would God's temple, for indeed the Holy Spirit dwells in<br>
the believer who invites His presence.  Therefore, as part of presenting<br>
your body as a "living sacrifice" (i.e., what I do to my body is in as<br>
much subjection to God's will as my thoughts are to be) I will choose what<br>
I find in Scripture as God's best for my body (EGW elaborates extensively,<br>
but the basis is found in Scripture).  By noting that God's original diet<br>
for man involved fruits, grains, nuts, and vegetables, one concludes that<br>
this is the best.  However, SDAs who do choose to include meat in their<br>
diet (e.g., my father used to pastor a church in the Canadian Maritimes<br>
wherein most of the members were deep sea fishermen; I know folk here in<br>
Arizona who raise beef cattle) should remember to observe the restrictions<br>
which God lays out in Leviticus.  See also Gen ch.9 which outlines what<br>
we might today call "kosher" prep (altho there are various forms of Jewish<br>
kosher, some of which are difficult to understand; many are probably<br>
well founded, tho, IMHO).  These rules for what constitutes "clean" meat<br>
and how to prepare were not arbitrary on God's part.  HE has our best good<br>
in mind.  The challenge to the believer then is:  Do I want God's best<br>
for my life?<br>
<p>
There ought to be Scripture references for the half dozen or so verses I am<br>
roughly quoting above.  I'm just gonna have to get a Unix-based Bible search<br>
program; my DOS-based one is at home.<br>
<p>
For recipe books:  there are many.  Any SDA bookstore (Adventist Book Center,<br>
check local Yellow Pages) will have a glut of these.  Our family has<br>
concluded it is best to avoid free fats/oils and sugar (note also recent<br>
USDA suggestions).  Therefore I have found the books put out by Weimar<br>
Institute and Dr. Agatha Trash to be among the best (there are others<br>
equally good, but I forget their names).  One can also find others that<br>
do not share our position, i.e., include added oils, sugar.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola TSD (DW278), 2900 S. Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ  85282
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For I know the thoughts that I have toward you, says the Lord, thoughts of
    peace and not evil, to give you hope and a future (Jer 29:11).
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
