<title>May_1992: Re: Free speech</title>
<h1>Re: Free speech</h1>
James Dunn (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  6 May 1992 11:08:02 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Scott Mattes: "What does the SDA church about this?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Fred Christiansen: "dietary info"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I think SDA-L should remain unmoderated.  Abuse of this network just hasn't</i><br>
<i>&gt; been a problem.  As long as SDA-L stays away from heavy doctrinal</i><br>
<i>&gt; discussion and discussion of touchy issues within the church, we'll be fine.</i><br>
 <br>
I never post things which are better left unsaid, but the above "could" be<br>
read as a bit confusing.  First you state that the SDA-L should remain<br>
unmoderated, but then you stipulate "what" the people should or should not<br>
discuss.  I am both a new member as well as a member who has never posted,<br>
but in the name of free will, free choice, free speech, and our God given<br>
right of life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness, I would suggest not<br>
changing the status of SDA-L or it's membership may decline.<br>
 <br>
:)  Just my $.02 worth.<br>
[This message is going only to SDAnet, so it seems a little incongruous<br>
to say this here, but it's worthwhile to recap the history of the two nets<br>
for our new readers.<br>
SDAnet started in June of 1990, SDA-L a few months later, independently<br>
of each other.  SDAnet was moderated from the first, SDA-L never was.<br>
In March and April of 1991, we tried joint distribution of all messages<br>
jointly.  Nobody really liked this situation, in particular many on the <br>
SDA-L side expressed their dislike of heavy doctrinal discussions, and <br>
on the SDAnet side I was uncomfortable with all the flames from their echo<br>
that I couldn't control.  It was decided that the SDAnet posts would<br>
no longer be echoed to SDA-L, and that SDA-L would be primarily for<br>
fellowship among students and faculty at various campuses.  Unfortunately,<br>
such a topic generates almost no traffic, and SDA-L has been almost dead<br>
for the last year.<br>
<p>
I am in the final stages of arranging to become one of their listowners<br>
to replace Christine Hwang, at Christine's request.  The goal is to generate<br>
enough traffic on that list so that people will know it is there, but many <br>
of their subscribers don't like the heavy traffic of SDAnet.  So my <br>
message of free speech is actually intended to expand the traffic on that<br>
net, and the policy of refraining from doctrinal discussion has been a rule<br>
followed on that list for almost a year.<br>
<p>
In the case that SDA-L traffic does pick up, those who are not members of <br>
that list won't be able to respond to posts that come from there directly.<br>
There is a way to be a member of that list and this one without receiving<br>
double copies, but right now that requires intervention of the SDA-L <br>
listowner.  We are negotiating the technical details to make this work<br>
easier. SCT]<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; SDAnet members, if you receive two copies of this message send me mail</i><br>
<i>&gt; and I can tell you how to avoid that.</i><br>
 <br>
Yes, I did.  Why?  Am I on TWO membership lists?<br>
[I sent that message twice by accident.  Sorry.  SCT] <br>
<p>
<p>
