<title>May_1992: More on Soul/Spirit</title>
<h1>More on Soul/Spirit</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 7 May 92 21:45 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#9">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#9">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#9">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#9">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "1 Tim 4"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Scott Mattes: "Did I miss something?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
    Dave Plaisted writes:<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; 1       When the Christian dies, he or she sleeps till Jesus</i><br>
<i>&gt; 2   comes.  The next thing he or she knows is Jesus coming.</i><br>
<i>&gt; 3   So, for us, death is immediately followed by Christ's</i><br>
<i>&gt; 4   return and the heavenly reward, even though many years may</i><br>
<i>&gt; 5   intervene.</i><br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; 6       I think many Christians would echo Paul's desire to be</i><br>
<i>&gt; 7   absent from the body and present with the Lord.  When Jesus</i><br>
<i>&gt; 8   returns we will receive a new body, without the sinful</i><br>
<i>&gt; 9   tendencies and desires of the present body.  Just think of</i><br>
<i>&gt; 10  it -- no more constant struggle with the old man, always</i><br>
<i>&gt; 11  trying to regain control!</i><br>
 <br>
     Dave, when I examine your above paragraph, I note a contradiction.<br>
     On line 6, you mention that many Christians echo Paul's desire<br>
     to be "absent from the body" and be with the Lord.  Then in<br>
     line 8, you state that "we will receive a new body" when Jesus<br>
     comes.  If when we die, we go out of existence until Jesus returns<br>
     and then we receive a new body,  we never were "absent from the<br>
     body", thus, there would be no reason to be "absent from the body"<br>
     Let me restate what I see as an inconsistency in your logic:<br>
 <br>
     "If there is never a case where we could be absent from the body,<br>
     why would we echo Paul's desire to be absent from the body"<br>
 <br>
       In english, the word absent is about as straight-forward as it<br>
     gets.  If I am absent from work, I still exist, I just exist apart<br>
     from work.  If the SDA position on soul-sleep is correct, wouldn't<br>
     Paul have said "I prefer to be in my new body and at home with the<br>
     the Lord" or something like that?  It takes as much work to explain<br>
     the phrase "absent from the body" for the person who holds to "soul<br>
     sleep" as does the phase "those asleep in Jesus" for those who hold<br>
     the "soul/spirit survives death postion".<br>
 <br>
       Another verse that I believe needs to be looked at is 2 Cor 12:2<br>
     and 3. Paul is writing about his experience of being caught up into<br>
     Paradise.  Verse 2 reads:<br>
 <br>
        I know a man in Christ who fourteen years ago-whether in the<br>
     body I do not know, or out of the body I do not know, God knows-<br>
     such a man was caught up to the third heaven.<br>
                                         II Cor. 12:2    NASB.<br>
 <br>
        I want to make a few comments.  First, yes, I believe that new-<br>
     age philosophies are running rampant in our country.  Yes, there<br>
     are some new-agers who claim to have OBE (Out of body experiences).<br>
     Should Bible-believing Christians be involved or attempt to have<br>
     OBE?  Definitely NOT.  Should we who claim to be Christians and<br>
     believe the Scriptures for our rule for life participate in any<br>
     kind of new age activites....Absolutely NOT.  Ok, now that thats<br>
     out of the way, lets look honestly at what Paul's saying here.<br>
     He had an experience and he states as clearly as it could be said.<br>
     "whether in the body I do not know, or out of the body, I do<br>
     not know".  Paul is admitting that he doesn't know whether he was<br>
     in his body or out of his body when this happened.  He obviously<br>
     considered both a possibility, otherwise he wouldn't have said it<br>
     in verse 2, then repeated himself in verse 3.  If Paul didn't<br>
     consider it possibly to be out of his body, then, he "would have<br>
     known".  If Paul was out of his body, then what part of him was<br>
     out of his body?  What ever was out of his body was certainly<br>
     conscience ( he heard things which are unspeakable ).  If one<br>
     would conclude that he was "in the body", would they then also<br>
     conclude that his body was in Paradise....the third heaven ?<br>
 <br>
     Have a great weekend<br>
     Eric Snyder<br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
