<title>May_1992: 1 Tim 4</title>
<h1>1 Tim 4</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 11 May 92 8:32:31 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#10">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#10">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#10">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#10">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0011.html">David Plaisted: "absent from the body"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Eric Snyder: "More on Soul/Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1 Tim 4:1-5 describes what Christians could expect in the future.  Evil persons,deceived by demons, would try to teach another gospel than what Paul had<br>
preached.  They would condemn marriage and foods which God had created to be<br>
enjoyed by humans.  --One must be careful to leave together those elements that<br>
appear together in a verse--.  These good things--marriage and food--were given<br>
by God as gifts to the believers. And everything God makes is good--did not God<br>
himself say so at creation?<br>
<p>
Paul's prophecy did not take long to be fulfilled.  The Gnostics of the second<br>
century developed rules to put down the body, since it was matter and matter<br>
was not good.  Severe fasting, sexual abstinence in marriage, etc. were de-<br>
signed to keep the body--which was evil, because it was matter.  Some of these<br>
same ideas were later taken over by the monks who deprived themselves of food,<br>
clothes, and sleep, in order to perfect themselves.  <br>
<p>
The word broma in Greek means food in general.  Meat is not mentioned in the<br>
text.  <br>
<p>
Everything that God created is good: food and sex included.  However, nothing<br>
in the text gives permission to use God's good gifts for the wrong purpose.<br>
Clearly God gave Adam and Eve an ideal diet: fruits, grains, nuts.  He also<br>
set up the ideal sex life: marriage.  <br>
<p>
Let's thank our wonderful Creator for his good gifts and use them wisely!<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
