<title>May_1992: absent from the body</title>
<h1>absent from the body</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 10 May 92 13:54:47 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#11">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#11">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#11">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#11">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steven Timm: "More news on the transition"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "1 Tim 4"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I interpret Paul's statement ``absent from the body'' to mean<br>
``absent from this body.''  He wants to be present with the Lord.<br>
When, according to the Bible, are we present with the Lord?  According<br>
to John 14:1-3 it is when Jesus returns.  According to 1 Thess. 4:<br>
15 - 18 we are with the Lord when he returns.  According to<br>
Titus 2:13 the blessed hope is the return of Jesus, not to go to<br>
heaven at death.<br>
<p>
Why would Paul want to be absent from the body?  There is nothing<br>
evil about having a body;  Adam and Eve had a body before they<br>
sinned.  We will have a body when Jesus returns.  I think Paul<br>
mainly wants to be free from the sinful desires of the flesh.<br>
<p>
In vision, we might seem to be in heaven while our body is really<br>
here.  How the Lord accomplishes that I don't know.<br>
<p>
I appreciate your honest questions.  Please continue to discuss<br>
this if you are not satisfied.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
