<title>May_1992: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?</title>
<h1>Is the SDA church Ecumenical?</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 12 May 92 07:23:07 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Steven Timm: "Re: 1 Tim 4"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steven Timm: "More news on the transition"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0018.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A few months ago I was reading in Adventists Affirm about the three<br>
waves of the Pentecostal movement.<br>
<p>
More revently I was looking at some of the glossy bound publications<br>
of the World Council of Churches.  These publications prominently<br>
display three wavy lines.  The three wavy lines seem to have become<br>
one of the symbols of Ecumenical.  In these documents, right along<br>
side the RCC, are statements indicating that the SDA church endorses<br>
the motions and proceedings published within the documents.  The<br>
response from the GC has been that those SDA professors who have<br>
chosen to be members on these councils are there for their own personal<br>
reasons and are not delegates of the GC.  BUT, I was looking at<br>
the Review &amp; Herald I received in the mail yesterday.  On the cover<br>
and throughout the paper (one exception I think) I see that the three<br>
angels have been replaced with the three wavy lines.  Has our church<br>
decided to replace our symbols of identity with the symbols of ecumenical?<br>
The three angels are symbol of "come out of Babylon [Ecumenical]"<br>
While the three wavy lines are symbol of -- lets join up with<br>
Ecumenical [Babylon].  How can our church continue to deny an<br>
aloofness from Ecumenical when we are adopting the symbols?<br>
<p>
Is our church becoming Ecumenical?<br>
<p>
Is Ecumenical something our church should be embracing?<br>
<p>
What should be our church's position on the Ecumenical movement?<br>
<p>
What about our church's endorsements in the World Council of Churches?<br>
<p>
Oh, BTW, one of the few church's objecting to the proceedings of the<br>
WCC was the Waldensian church.  Somehow I thought they had been<br>
exterminated by the time of the Protestant Reformation.  Then more<br>
recently I heard about a summer camp meeting this summer to be<br>
sponsored by the "Waldensian SDAs".  Who are they?  Has anyone heard<br>
of them before?<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
