<title>May_1992: Re: is the SDA church ecumenical (actually just addressing Waldenses)</title>
<h1>Re: is the SDA church ecumenical (actually just addressing Waldenses)</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 12 May 92 12:09:26 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: 1 Tim 4"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Steven Timm: "Re: 1 Tim 4"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm not in a position to address the thrust of the article, but ...<br>
<p>
[davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Oh, BTW, one of the few church's objecting to the proceedings of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; WCC was the Waldensian church.  Somehow I thought they had been</i><br>
<i>&gt; exterminated by the time of the Protestant Reformation.</i><br>
<p>
If my recall of Wylie's History of the Reformation is correct, persecution<br>
of the Waldenses continued thru near the end of the 19th century.  As<br>
recently as 1962, when my family and I visited Torre Pelice, the Waldensian<br>
church was still alive.  I believe that there are some SDAs amongst the<br>
Waldensians (but this is trying to remember 30 years ago, when I was 8).<br>
My wife visited Waldensian churches during pre Youth Congress tour, 1969.<br>
<p>
For Reformation history fans:  We got the complete Wylie history of<br>
the Reformation thru Great Christian Books (ask 800-555-1212 for their 800<br>
number).  We tracked D'Aubigne's book thru the publisher, Baker Book House.<br>
<p>
As a side note on the Waldensian church ... my wife distinctly recalls<br>
reading a Review &amp; Herald article from the late 50's or 60's in which<br>
an interview with a Waldensian pastor was published.  He indicated that<br>
the church was dying because the youth were leaving.  This is what happened:<br>
The youth were allured by the dazzle of wordly pleasures and pasttimes.<br>
To try to keep their youth, the Waldensian church set up a dance hall in<br>
their mountain community so that the youth would not need to go to the cities,<br>
beyond the chaperonage of their parents.  This appeared to work .. but not<br>
for long.  Rather, the worldliness increased and spirituality declined;<br>
the youth left the church anyway.<br>
<p>
No matter how praiseworthy the goal, the tools of darkness are incompatible<br>
with God's work; they result in confusion.  "... God is light, and in Him<br>
is no darkness at all. (1Jn1:5)"  "... let us cast off the works of darkness,<br>
and let us put on the armour of light. (Rm13:12)"  "... for what fellowship<br>
hath righteousness with unrighteousness?  and what communion hath light<br>
with darkness? (2Co6:14)"  "Who can bring a clean thing out of an unclean?<br>
not one. (Job14:4)"  See also Eze 22:26, 44:23; Hag 2:11-13.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola TSD (DW278), 2900 S. Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ  85282
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For I know the thoughts that I have toward you, says the Lord, thoughts of
    peace and not evil, to give you hope and a future (Jer 29:11).
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
