On Mon, 11 May 1992 10:13:13 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<i>&gt;1 Tim 4:1-5 describes what Christians could expect in the future.  Evil</i><br>
<i>&gt;persons,deceived by demons, would try to teach another gospel than what Paul</i><br>
<i>&gt;had</i><br>
<i>&gt;preached.  They would condemn marriage and foods which God had created to be</i><br>
<i>&gt;enjoyed by humans.  --One must be careful to leave together those elements that</i><br>
<i>&gt;appear together in a verse--.  These good things--marriage and food--were given</i><br>
<i>&gt;by God as gifts to the believers. And everything God makes is good--did not God</i><br>
<i>&gt;himself say so at creation?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;...... some deleted ............</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;The word broma in Greek means food in general.  Meat is not mentioned in the</i><br>
<i>&gt;text.</i><br>
<p>
         From The New Strong's Exhaustive Concordance of the<br>
         Bible<br>
<p>
         Broma, bro-mah; food (lit. or fig.). espec. (cer.)<br>
         articles allowed or forbidden by the Jewish law<br>
         :- meat, victuals.       &lt;---- how the word is translated in KJV<br>
<p>
  You are right that 'meat' is not spoken by word, but, being careful to<br>
keep things together, the following verse makes clear that Paul is<br>
talking about food animals.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Everything that God created is good: food and sex included.  However, nothing</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the text gives permission to use God's good gifts for the wrong purpose.</i><br>
<p>
  True, how we use something counts for/against us as much as what we<br>
use.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Clearly God gave Adam and Eve an ideal diet: fruits, grains, nuts.  He also</i><br>
<i>&gt;set up the ideal sex life: marriage.</i><br>
<p>
  While I agree that the vegge diet is healthier, here are some things<br>
that struck me while thinking on this;<br>
<p>
1) when Adam and Eve were ushered out of Eden, the first thing God does<br>
   is kill an animal to clothe them.  I wonder if he didn't also show<br>
   them how to prepare venison at the same time.<br>
<p>
2) Abel kept flocks, wonder what for.<br>
<p>
3) Noah was told to eat animals<br>
<p>
4) God, in the OT, demanded animal sacrifices.  As part of their wages<br>
   God stated that part of those sacrifices (and those of non-animal<br>
   type) were for the Levites to eat.<br>
<p>
5) Jesus at fish, at least.<br>
<p>
6) Paul says animals were given for our eating.<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
