<title>May_1992: Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?</title>
<h1>Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 12 May 1992 15:21:25 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#18">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#18">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#18">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#18">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Jerome Grimmer: "The list and subscribers not unsubscribing"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0013.html">Dave Buxton: "Is the SDA church Ecumenical?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0020.html">Ruben: "Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave asks three questions:  The first one, "Is the SDA church becoming<br>
ecumenical" is certainly yes.  I think no one can deny that we are much <br>
less a peculiar people than we were even twenty years ago.  Just the fact<br>
that there is no real persecution right now should tell us something.<br>
<p>
Should our church be more ecumenical?  I think here we have both<br>
responsibilities and cautions to be aware of.  If we are the logical and<br>
natural extension of the Protestant reformation as we claim, then <br>
we have a responsibility to share the truth we know with our fellow <br>
Protestant denominations.  We should not shun contact with<br>
interdenominational assemblies if it is clear that we can proclaim the<br>
truth.<br>
<p>
At the same time, we should be very wary about language where unity is <br>
achieved at the expense of abandoning doctrine or say that "what you believe <br>
about this really isn't important" or some such.  While I have found it <br>
helpful to join Christian friends of other denominations in prayer circles,<br>
nevertheless the tension comes through if one is planning any kind of<br>
a teaching ministry.  <br>
<p>
The Waldensian church survived the persecution of the Middle Ages and<br>
is still active, but small, today.  It is responsible for one of the <br>
only Protestant translations of the Bible into Italian.  "Waldensian SDA's"<br>
seems like quite a contradiction in terms because the Waldenses are known <br>
not to have kept the Sabbath.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
