<title>May_1992: Re: 1 Tim 4</title>
<h1>Re: 1 Tim 4</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 13 May 92 11:27:18 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#24">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#24">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#24">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#24">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Is the SDA church Ecumenical?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Dave Buxton: "Freedoms in the USA"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0022.html">Steven Timm: "New SDA-L / SDAnet directory"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yes, Strong does admit that broma is translated "meat" and "victuals" in the<br>
KJV.  Those translations reflect 17th century usage and not Greek meaning.<br>
Bauer-Arndt-Gingrich, standard Greek-English lexicon clearly states the<br>
meaning as food, either literal or figurative.  The word appears in the NT 16<br>
times, meaning food in general.  <br>
<p>
I am not sure where the "food animals" appear in the text.  Perhaps I need to<br>
be shown what phrase they are hiding in.<br>
<p>
Other questions about diet:<br>
Original diet= Gen 1:29--seeds and fruits<br>
Post-sin diet= Gen 3:18--plants are added.  Maybe spinach and broccoli!<br>
Post flood diet=Gen 9:3,4--meat but not the blood.  The fact that more of the<br>
clean animals were in the ark suggests that these were the ones for food.<br>
<p>
Vegetarianism is not an article of faith.   Knowing what we know today about<br>
cholesterol, fat, infections, calories, and cleanliness, it may be a matter<br>
of wisdom.  What I do to my body--where God desires to dwell through the<br>
Holy Spirit--has spiritual implications.  Since what affects my body also<br>
affects my nervous system, and the only way God has to communicate with me is<br>
through my brain and nerves, I feel strongly that I need to keep in good<br>
condition.  The health responsibility includes much more than no meat.  I <br>
must include other aspects of diet, exercise, rest, fresh air, cleanliness,<br>
and trust in the divine physician.<br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
