<title>May_1992: Re: Interpretation of Hosea 2:11</title>
<h1>Re: Interpretation of Hosea 2:11</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 14 May 92 08:15:19 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "1 Tim 4"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Interpretation of Hosea 2:11"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0040.html">Dave Buxton: "Interpretation of Hosea 2:11"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I'm curious about how you interpret Hosea 2:11.  Hosea is clearly symbolic</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the way the Lord relates to his fallen church.  This verse says, "I will</i><br>
<i>&gt; also cause all her mirth to cease, her feast days, and her new moons, and</i><br>
<i>&gt; her sabbaths, and all her solemn feasts."  If Sabbath celebration was to</i><br>
<i>&gt; . . . . .</i><br>
<p>
This passage is symbol of what happens when God's people rebel.  They<br>
were taken into captivity where they were slaves 7 days of the week.<br>
In Jeremiah we read of God's promise of a New Covenant, to forgive and<br>
to forgive and to restore His law to their hearts.  And indeed those<br>
who chose to were able to return to Jerusalem and to rebuild.  Then<br>
we see Paul re-applying these Covenants of the exhile to Christianity<br>
and this side of the cross.<br>
<p>
The theme of New Covenants is found throughout the OT.  God had a<br>
Covenant with Abraham, but Abraham died.  So a New Covenant with<br>
Isaac, and . . . . . .  At the time of Sinaii we see yet another<br>
New Covenant, now called the Old Covenant.  In the context of that<br>
Old Covenant we see that it was God's plan to place His law within<br>
their hearts.  But they rebelled and insisted on doing things their<br>
own way.  So their freedom to keep God's law was taken from them<br>
in captivity because of their rebellion.  But God promised yet another<br>
New Covenant . . . . . .<br>
<p>
I see Hosea 2:11 as symbol of rebellion and its consequences.  Those<br>
who rebell will loose their freedoms, even the freedom to keep God's<br>
law.  But even then God will strive to restore a people unto Himself,<br>
He will restore His promises in New Covenanants that are not all that<br>
new, simply restorations of old promises.<br>
<p>
<p>
