<title>May_1992: 1 Tim 4</title>
<h1>1 Tim 4</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 14 May 92 9:07:52 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#31">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#31">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#31">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#31">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Eric Snyder: "Death Afterlife"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Interpretation of Hosea 2:11"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ah!  The animals are in the KJV!  The Greek uses the word ktisma, which<br>
means "created being" or "created thing."  Humans and celestial beings<br>
are called ktisma.  A good translation is: "everything that God created."<br>
<p>
An important principle of Bible interpretation is to draw conclusions on<br>
the basis of the whole Bible.  That means that any one text in isolation<br>
is not a good basis for doctrine.  One needs to look for everything the<br>
Bible says about the topic.  If I tell someone to turn on the TV and do<br>
not mention that first he should plug it in, am I saying that the TV can<br>
work without being plugged in?  That information is somewhere else--and<br>
quite probably in the mind of the one who is asked to turn on the TV.  The<br>
matter of clean and unclean is something like that.  If people know that<br>
clean animals are the ones to eat, speaking of all animals automatically<br>
<p>
triggers the "clean" idea in the mind.  But anyway, even if there is no<br>
reference to "clean animals" in Gen 9, it comes clearly in other passages.<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
