<title>May_1992: Death Afterlife</title>
<h1>Death Afterlife</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 14 May 92 13:05 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#32">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#32">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#32">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#32">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Fred Christiansen: "materials by the late James Arrabito:  how get a hold of?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "1 Tim 4"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0034.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Death Afterlife"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
          I would like to make additional comments regarding the Luke<br>
      16 parable.  (Lazurus and the rich man), but first I wanted to<br>
      say that I have read several commentators regarding the John 14<br>
      v3 passage.  It certainly seems to say that when Jesus comes<br>
      again (second coming) that at that point he will receive us<br>
      to Himself.  This passage does pose a problem for the "soul/spirit<br>
      survives death" position.  I will look further into it.<br>
 <br>
   Steve Timm writes:<br>
<i>&gt; My thoughts on the parable of the Rich Man and Lazarus</i><br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; Let's suppose for a second that this parable is literally true.</i><br>
<i>&gt; "The beggar died and was carried by the angels into Abraham's bosom."</i><br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; This doesn't mean that the beggar went straight to heaven.</i><br>
 <br>
   True, but it would seem to indicate that immediately after his death<br>
   he experienced some kind of consiousness.  Not necessarily heaven<br>
   but his was in a better position than the Rich Man.  It could not<br>
   likely be after the Resurrection for two reasons :<br>
 <br>
    1. There is nothing stating that after we are resurrected, that<br>
       we will be carried somewhere by angles.<br>
 <br>
    2. The Rich Man wants to return to tell his "still living brothers"<br>
       about the place of torment.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;"The rich man died, and was buried.  And in hell he lift up his eyes...</i><br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; Nor does it say that the rich man went to hell immediately</i><br>
 <br>
   If we can conclude that Lazurus' experience was after his death,<br>
   yet, prior to the resurrection, and his experience was taking place<br>
   the same time as the Rich Man, would we not conclude that the Rich<br>
   man's experience was immediatley after his death also ?<br>
   When the rich man wanted to return to tell his brothers so they<br>
   could avoid this place, Abraham, states that if they would not listen<br>
   to Moses and the prophets, they wouldn't listen to someone from the<br>
   dead.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;The communication which happens between Father Abraham and the rich man</i><br>
<i>&gt; is not impossible in hell as we know it, because Abraham stresses</i><br>
<i>&gt; There is a great gulf fixed.</i><br>
 <br>
   Without going into a detailed explanation of hell and hades, I<br>
   believe many would hold to an after death state and a final state.<br>
   I do not believe that the place where the Rich Man is, is the lake<br>
   of fire, referred to in Revelation.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; Finally, nothing says that the rich man doesn't eventually burn up.</i><br>
 <br>
    True, but at the same time, it never states that he will.  If you<br>
    read this text, do you honestly get the impression that the rich<br>
    man will burn up ?<br>
 <br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;So I think SDA's really have nothing to fear from this parable or a</i><br>
<i>&gt; need to explain it away.</i><br>
 <br>
    I would like to comment on this further, but lunch is over.<br>
 <br>
     Eric Snyder<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
