<title>May_1992: Re: Death Afterlife</title>
<h1>Re: Death Afterlife</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 14 May 92 18:02:25 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#34">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#34">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#34">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#34">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Dead don't go to heaven"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Fred Christiansen: "materials by the late James Arrabito:  how get a hold of?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0032.html">Eric Snyder: "Death Afterlife"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0039.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Death Afterlife"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu writes:]<br>
<i>&gt;     2. The Rich Man wants to return to tell his "still living brothers"</i><br>
<i>&gt;        about the place of torment.</i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;"The rich man died, and was buried.  And in hell he lift up his eyes...</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Nor does it say that the rich man went to hell immediately</i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<i>&gt;    If we can conclude that Lazurus' experience was after his death,</i><br>
<i>&gt;    yet, prior to the resurrection, and his experience was taking place</i><br>
<i>&gt;    the same time as the Rich Man, would we not conclude that the Rich</i><br>
<i>&gt;    man's experience was immediatley after his death also ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;    When the rich man wanted to return to tell his brothers so they</i><br>
<i>&gt;    could avoid this place, Abraham, states that if they would not listen</i><br>
<i>&gt;    to Moses and the prophets, they wouldn't listen to someone from the</i><br>
<i>&gt;    dead.</i><br>
<p>
If we accept that the Rich Man has somehow ended up in a place where he<br>
is conscious and that the time is before the resurrection and that he<br>
wants to talk to his living brothers (and Abraham thinks this is<br>
possible), then we must accept that this occurs to all (whether righteous<br>
or unrighteous) and that any one could do the same.  That would mean<br>
that the dead can indeed come and visit us and communicate with us.<br>
Scripture refers to these as "familiar spirits".  I leave it as an<br>
excercise for the reader to discover what the Scripture has to say about<br>
familiar spirits.  I Samuel 28 and I Chronicles 10:13 are just two of<br>
numerous references.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola TSD (DW278), 2900 S. Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ  85282
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For I know the thoughts that I have toward you, says the Lord, thoughts of
    peace and not evil, to give you hope and a future (Jer 29:11).
</pre>
