<title>May_1992: Dead don't go to heaven</title>
<h1>Dead don't go to heaven</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 15 May 1992 00:23 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#35">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#35">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#35">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#35">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Re:  Hosea 2:11"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Death Afterlife"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think we have significant evidence that the dead do not go immediately<br>
to heaven when we examine the account of the resurrection of Jesus.  John<br>
20:17 Jesus said to Mary Magdalene, "Touch me not; for I am not ascended to<br>
my Father:  but go to my brethren, and say unto them, I ascend unto my<br>
Father, and you Father, and to my God, and your God."  If Jesus had been<br>
in heaven with God the Father during his 3 days of physical death, he<br>
would not have said he had not been to his Father's yet.  Following this,<br>
Mary went and told His disciples that he had risen from the grave and<br>
He lated appeared to them in the upper room.  When Thomas disbelieved,<br>
Jesus told him to touch His wounds and thrust his finger into His side.<br>
Obviously something must have transpired between appearance to Mary and<br>
appearance to Thomas.  Mary was forbidden to touch him.  Thomas was<br>
encouraged to do so.  So where was the spirit of Jesus while he was in<br>
the tomb?  Obviously not with God the Father (i.e., in heaven).<br>
<p>
Yet, Jesus was not of normal human body after the resurrection for he<br>
was perceived as a spirit and could appear out of nowhere and then<br>
disappear into nowhere.  He did not do this before his crucifixion.  But<br>
he did have a physical body that could be touched.  There was obviously<br>
a transformation of some type at the resurrection.<br>
<p>
It's unfortunate that the Gospels do not specify what Lazarus, the brother<br>
of Mary and Martha, said after he was resurrected by Jesus.  However, it<br>
appears that the resurrection of Lazarus (and Jarius' daughter, and son<br>
of the widow of Nain) were of a different type than that of Jesus.  For<br>
they were not raised in an immortal body and in fact, did suffer death<br>
again.  Too bad the scriptures don't tell us anything about whether they<br>
were conscious during their state of lifelessness.  Paul tells us that<br>
the fact of Jesus' resurrection is proof that He has conquered death.<br>
The resurrections of Lazarus and others were clearly NOT a conquering of<br>
death but a mere reuniting of the spirit with body.  They were not<br>
resurrected as transformed beings as Christ was.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
