<title>May_1992: Re:  Hosea 2:11</title>
<h1>Re:  Hosea 2:11</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 15 May 1992 00:04 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#36">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#36">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#36">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#36">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Hosea 2:11"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Dead don't go to heaven"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0037.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Hosea 2:11"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave's interpretation of this verse certainly sounds plausible. However, I<br>
have one problem with it.  Other verses in the Bible which use the same<br>
Hebrew word clearly indicate that "to cease" is permanent rather than<br>
temporary.  Examples:<br>
<p>
Daniel 9:26,27 - And after threescore and two weeks shall Messiah be cut off,<br>
but not for himself, and the people of the prince that shall come shall<br>
destroy the city and the sanctuary; and the end thereof shall be with a<br>
flood, and unto the end of the war desolatiions are determined.  And he shall<br>
confirm the convenant with many for one week:  and in the midst of the week<br>
he shall cause the sacrifice and the oblation to cease.<br>
<p>
Hosea 1:4 - And the Lord said unto him, Call his name Jezreel; for yet a<br>
little while, and I will avenge the blood of Jezreel upon the house of Jehu,<br>
and will cause to cease the kinghom of the house of Israel.<br>
<p>
Deuteronomy 32:26 - I said, I would scatter them into corners, I would make<br>
the remembrance of them to cease from among men.<br>
<p>
Genesis 9:22 - While the earth remaineth, seedtime and harvest, and cold and<br>
heat, and summer and winter, and day and night shall NOT cease.<br>
<p>
Clearly, all these verses signify a permanent cessation, not something<br>
temporary.  Thus, if the verse in Hosea 2 which says he will cause her<br>
sabbaths to cease, would this not signify a permanent cessation of the<br>
observance of Sabbath?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
