<title>May_1992: Re: Hosea 2:11</title>
<h1>Re: Hosea 2:11</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 15 May 1992 09:00:24 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#37">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#37">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#37">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#37">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: materials by the late James Arrabito: how get a hold of?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Re:  Hosea 2:11"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0036.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Re:  Hosea 2:11"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
When interpreting the book of Hosea, we need to view it in the historical<br>
contest of God's dealings with the northern kingdom of Israel.  Shortly<br>
after the book of Hosea was written, Israel was taken into captivity<br>
by Assyria. The new moons, sabbaths, and feast days did in fact cease.<br>
The Sabbath continued, only Israel lost its opportunity to observe it<br>
because they were unfaithful.  God speaks of taking these blessings <br>
away from Israel because Israel did not recognize that they had their<br>
source in God.  As far as we know, most of the northern kingdom never<br>
returned from captivity.<br>
<p>
This text is to be contrasted with such passages as Isaiah 66:23,<br>
"From one new moon to another, and from one sabbath to another,<br>
shall all flesh come to worship before me, saith the Lord."<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
