<title>May_1992: Good News is No News?</title>
<h1>Good News is No News?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 17 May 1992 12:00:13 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "The Second Annual SDAnet contest"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Dave Buxton: "Interpretation of Hosea 2:11"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0045.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Good News is No News?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As I reflect back on last month, where I posted two or three articles in the <br>
"Good News And Happy Things" thread, a couple things stick out.<br>
<p>
1)  I was still backhanded and critical enough to cause controversy with <br>
a couple of those posts.<br>
<p>
2)  Nobody gave a positive response or posted any good news of their own.<br>
In fact, we were strictly admonished "Woe unto you when all men shall speak<br>
well of you."  <br>
<p>
How much greater is the woe when NO man, not even among ourselves, can say <br>
a good word for God, for the church, for the list, for the neighbors,<br>
nothing.  Is anyone out there happy?  Do you know the joy of the Lord?<br>
When was the last time you just woke up in the morning and sang a song of <br>
praise to God?  Has God been working mightily in your life?  If so, don't <br>
be afraid to let the net know.<br>
<p>
Perhaps this is an uphill battle, because the main function of SDA-L is for <br>
this, and of the ten messages it has had so far this year, five are from me.<br>
It seems a little cynical to think that the reason SDAnet has traffic is that<br>
we SDA's thrive on controversy and dispute.  Do we have a macabre<br>
satisfaction in focusing only on the problems in the church?  Do we<br>
think that the incredible ways that God is working in the world are<br>
somehow not newsworthy.<br>
<p>
Let the controversy go on.  Keep on debating.  I like it as much as<br>
anyone else.  But please, let's not forget to say a good word for God on<br>
occasion.<br>
One area of the list that I am happy to see is the number of posts<br>
relating to doctrinal discussion.  It's up remarkably over the last<br>
couple months,<br>
and I hope it stays that way.  Also, SDAnet will soon pass the 100-reader<br>
mark  (the combined readership of the two nets stands at 127).  <br>
<p>
I just praise God that He sees fit to use this list in whatever way is<br>
needed, I pray it will continue.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
