<title>May_1992: The Second Annual SDAnet contest</title>
<h1>The Second Annual SDAnet contest</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 17 May 1992 12:15:37 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#42">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#42">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#42">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#42">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0041.html">Steven Timm: "Good News is No News?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The SDAnet Drama Writing contest is open in two categories, puppet shows<br>
and short skits.  <br>
<p>
Puppet shows:<br>
Should be cast with no more than three puppets on stage at once, <br>
no more than five total.<br>
Should be written at a reading level that is performable and<br>
understandable by elementary school children.<br>
Scripts may be in English or Spanish.<br>
Should require a minimum of props.<br>
Should be true to life, no fantasy or superhero characters.<br>
Acceptable themes are Bible stories, mission stories, health and fitness,<br>
SDA heritage.<br>
Length of 3-7 minutes.<br>
May include music.<br>
<p>
Short Skits:<br>
Skits casting a predominance of young ladies are preferred (due to<br>
available cast of actors)<br>
Skits should use 2-5 characters, and should be performable by jr. high<br>
and high school students with an audience of jr. high to college.<br>
Should be 3-12 minutes in length.<br>
Scripts in English only.<br>
Acceptable themes:  Human relations of all sorts, mission stories,<br>
personal religion and outreach.<br>
Should not include music.<br>
<p>
Deadline for contest:  September 1, 1992<br>
<p>
First prize:  Twenty dollars.<br>
<p>
All entries (if any) will be judged by an independent judging panel, and <br>
become the property of Elmhurst Puppet Ministry.<br>
<p>
Last year nobody entered this contest.  This year maybe the recession<br>
will spur more interest.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
