<!-- body="start" -->
David, And here I thought you would appreciate the story of the apple tree<br>
and now you are taking issue with it!! &lt;smile!&gt;<br>
<p>
In my ministry I have observed the ones who think the Lord will give them<br>
the victory in due time or someday are the ones practicing Salvation by<br>
works only.<br>
<p>
A person who accepts Christ by faith has the asurrance. IJohn 5 makes that<br>
very clear. And I might say, he has the asurrance of victory in his life.<br>
Good works will be produced in the life -- a life of obedience -- but it<br>
has nothing to do with salvation. Some SDAs through the years have become<br>
so obsessed with the law and salvation by works only, that as EGW says,<br>
they have become as dry as the hill of Gilboa.<br>
<p>
I believe that the the apple tree illustration gives the message a<br>
certain sound -- a good sound. Applying to life it simple says that we do<br>
good works because we are saved not because we are trying to be saved.<br>
Venden is right on target!<br>
<p>
Matthew 9:14-17 has a tremendous message for us. It is time for us to<br>
start putting the new wine into new winebags. Some talk about the new<br>
theology! It was Jesus himself that had new theology -- and that is why<br>
he blew the socks off of the church leaders. We need to in my opinion<br>
leave the old ways and learn the ways of Jesus.<br>
<p>
I did not intend to have such a lengthy message David, I guess I felt a<br>
sermon coming on!! &lt;&lt;Grin!&gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
God bless,<br>
<p>
Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
