<title>May_1992: Commitment and Finances</title>
<h1>Commitment and Finances</h1>
Stan Macasieb (<i>Stan_Macasieb@isu.comm.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 1992 10:51:04 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#48">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#48">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#48">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#48">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0049.html">Bob Moynihan: "re:Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0047.html">John Wical: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0055.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Commitment and Finances"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am sure that this issue has come up from time to time, but<br>
now that I am confronting this issue at my own church, I need<br>
to find some answers.<br>
<p>
Should the eligibility of a member to the church board be<br>
dependent on the level of financial commitment he/she makes<br>
to his/her local church?<br>
<p>
Some background: the church is in a state of flux, with the <br>
older members having to accept the involvement of newer<br>
members. The older members would like to step down and let<br>
the younger ones take over, but there are some who are unhappy<br>
with the types of people who are taking over, that the church<br>
is sliding away from its fundamentalist groundwork. They<br>
feel a need to _take back_ their church and bring it back<br>
to the way things used to be. <br>
<p>
Thus, that faction has begun to question the latest round of<br>
nominations to the church board, and have used the tithe issue<br>
as a litmus test of commitment to the church. They reason that,<br>
because the church has been steadily losing money due to eroding<br>
attendance on a weekly basis and the church's inability to keep<br>
pace with escalating maintenance costs, they need to make sure<br>
that its higher-ups make a dual commitment, spiritually and<br>
financially, to its church. <br>
<p>
Is this a reasonable prereq? I had always thought that your <br>
relationship with God is a private matter, and the level of<br>
financial commitment, tithes and offerings, is something that<br>
should not be discussed outside of the boardroom. <br>
<p>
I hope I don't ruin a good thread out there. I've enjoyed your<br>
discussions over the last few weeks and am thankful to hear<br>
that such a group exists for SDA thoughts. Thanks and God bless<br>
you for your help in advance.<br>
<p>
--Stan Macasieb, Chicago (stanm@comm.mot.com)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
