<title>May_1992: re:Saved or Not Saved</title>
<h1>re:Saved or Not Saved</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 92 10:42:04 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#49">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#49">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#49">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#49">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Eric Snyder: "Death/Afterlife"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Stan Macasieb: "Commitment and Finances"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Which do you think it would be more correct to say; when one is converted</i><br>
<i>&gt; one is saved (full stop) OR one is on the path of salvation ?</i><br>
<p>
I'd say the latter.  Coverting to follow Jesus sets you on the path.  If you <br>
should die while on the path, then you are saved.  If you are on the path <br>
when Jesus returns, then you are saved.  Should you lose faith and stray<br>
from the path, then you are not.  <br>
<p>
I suppose one could say that unless you are perfect, then you are not truly<br>
converted, but in my opinion, that's a cynical view of things.  Even the <br>
apostles, who walked in Jesus' footsteps, had their failings and doubts.  I<br>
find it hard to believe that more would be expected from us who live 2000<br>
years after those footsteps left the Earth than was expected from those first<br>
disciples.<br>
<p>
Trust in the Lord to do with you that which is just.  In the form I have now,<br>
physical and spiritual, I do not deserve to be in His prescence.  All I can<br>
do is pray that whatever His will is for me, then let it be done, and that<br>
He change me to be what He wants me to be.  If that 'future me' is unrecognizable<br>
to the 'present me', then praise God, for the 'present me' is unworthy.<br>
<p>
May the Lord bless you all...<br>
<p>
Bob Moynihan                         Disclaimer: I speak only for myself, not for<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com                         the SDA Church, nor for Hewlett-<br>
                                                 Packard Company.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
