<!-- body="start" -->
   Fred Christiansen writes :<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;       If we accept that the Rich Man has somehow ended up in a</i><br>
<i>&gt;   place where he is conscious and that the time is before the</i><br>
<i>&gt;   resurrection and that he wants to talk to his living brothers</i><br>
<i>&gt;   (and Abraham thinks this is possible), then we must accept</i><br>
<i>&gt;   that this occurs to all (whether righteous or unrighteous)</i><br>
<i>&gt;   and that any one could do the same.  That would mean that the</i><br>
<i>&gt;   dead can indeed come and visit us and communicate with us.</i><br>
 <br>
      I have to disagree with Fred's reasoning.  After reading this<br>
    parable, its obvious that the rich man "cannot" return to warn<br>
    his brothers.  Otherwise, he most certainly would have.  The only<br>
    point that I believe Abraham is making is that even if he could,<br>
    and we conclude that he can't, that his brothers hearts are probably<br>
    so hardened, that even if someone did come back from the dead, they<br>
    still wouldn't repent.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;   Scripture refers to these as "familiar spirits".  I leave it</i><br>
<i>&gt;   as an excercise for the reader to discover what the Scripture</i><br>
<i>&gt;   has to say about familiar spirits.  I Samuel 28 and I</i><br>
<i>&gt;   Chronicles 10:13 are just two of numerous references.</i><br>
 <br>
    I am in 100% agreement with Fred, that any attempt to contact the<br>
    dead is an abomination to the Lord and strongly advised against.<br>
 <br>
    Eric Snyder<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
