<title>May_1992: Sabbath or sabbaths?</title>
<h1>Sabbath or sabbaths?</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 92 10:48:24 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#51">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#51">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#51">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#51">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Eric Snyder: "Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Eric Snyder: "Death/Afterlife"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0089.html">Rhonda Gaines: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In reading the discussion over Hosea's warning about the end of the<br>
new moons celebrations, feast days, and sabbaths, I haven't seen it<br>
brought up as to the possibility that this is not talking about THE<br>
WEEKLY Sabbath...<br>
 <br>
Weren't some of those feast days, etc. also called sabbaths, even though<br>
they were not WEEKLY Sabbaths?  I've always assumed that this text<br>
talked about the end of the celebration of the feasts, but not the Sabbath<br>
that came every week.  Although, as has been pointed out, those who went<br>
into captivity couldn't celebrate either kind.<br>
 <br>
I'd be happy to hear along these lines from someone who knows more than<br>
I do about it!<br>
 <br>
Lola Aagaard<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
