<title>May_1992: Jesus' Spirit after His death...</title>
<h1>Jesus' Spirit after His death...</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 92 12:45 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#52">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#52">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#52">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#52">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0051.html">Lola: "Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0054.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
  Cheryl writes:<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;  .....    So where was the spirit of Jesus while he was in</i><br>
<i>&gt;    Obviously not with God the Father (i.e., in heaven).</i><br>
 <br>
      If we look at the last words Jesus uttered from his lips,<br>
    we will find where His spirit went.  In Luke 23:46, He says<br>
    "Father, into Thy hands I commit my spirit".<br>
 <br>
      This is echoed by Stephen just before his death in Acts 7:59<br>
    He says "Lord Jesus, receive my spirit".<br>
 <br>
       Many have proposed that during Jesus death, he descended into<br>
    Hades and released the "spirits in prison". Or at least made<br>
    a proclamation of some sort.  They use the 1 Peter 3:19 as a proof<br>
    text.  After much research regarding 1 Pet. 3:19, I do not believe<br>
    that this passage refers to Jesus during His 3-day period after<br>
    the Crucifixion and before His Resurrection.  Wayne Grudem has a<br>
    commentary on 1 Peter and it contains a lengthy appendix dedicated<br>
    soley to 1 Peter 3:19.  It is the best reading on this passage I've<br>
    come across.  What I believe 1 Peter says in a paraphrase is this:<br>
 <br>
      Jesus was made alive (resurrected) in the spirit.  The very same<br>
    spirit that He also preached through Noah back during the time the<br>
    the Ark was built.  The preaching was to disobedient humans, who<br>
    had long since passed away and were now spirits in prison.<br>
    The preaching took place thru Noah, back when the Ark was being<br>
    built.<br>
 <br>
      You may disagree with this position, but I have read many<br>
    possible interpretations of this verse and the above is what I<br>
    personally believe is the most accurate.  In Wayne Grudem's appendix<br>
    he systematically deals with all the possible interpretations and<br>
    and gives solid reasons for his position.<br>
 <br>
      Back to the original question.  Where was Jesus between His<br>
    Crucifixion and Resuurection ?  I'm not certain there is enough<br>
    biblical evidence to form any concluding answer.   But, like stated<br>
    before, He gave His spirit into His Father's hands right before<br>
    He died.  It is quite possible that His spirit was with His Father<br>
    during that time until His Resurrection, at which time His trans-<br>
    formed physical body was made alive and once again His spirit was<br>
    present in His body.<br>
 <br>
    Good question Cheryl.....ok I'd love to here from Steve Timm<br>
    and Scott Mattes on this one.  (smile guys)...<br>
 <br>
    Eric Snyder...<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
