<title>May_1992: Re: Saved or Not Saved</title>
<h1>Re: Saved or Not Saved</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 92 09:38:02 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#53">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#53">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#53">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#53">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Eric Snyder: "Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0061.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A favorite illustration I get from those espousing once-saved-always-saved<br>
is that being 'saved' means adopted into the family.  Once a son or<br>
daughter, God is not going to throw us out of the household.<br>
<p>
Now lets imagine you are the parents of an adopted son.  You take him to<br>
the doctor because he is very ill.  The doctor takes you asside and<br>
whispers in your ear -- "the reason your son is near unto death is that<br>
he no longer wants to be your son".   You can be a son and member of<br>
the family, yet sick unto death because of sin.<br>
<p>
I have offered the parable of the prodigal son to illustrate that you<br>
can be a son, dis-own your sonship, and return again.  But they insist<br>
the son was not 'saved' into the family until he returned from the hogs.<br>
He did not really become a 'son' until after he threw his sonship<br>
asside.  Somehow I cannot buy that line of reasoning that says you<br>
cannot be 'saved' until you have rejected God for a spell.  But then<br>
you are saved such that nothing you do can un-save you.<br>
<p>
I recently received a book by Jack Sequeira.  Leafing through the<br>
book I found a table of over a page in length.  The left hand column<br>
illustrates Justification and offers texts.  The right hand column<br>
illustrates the related points of Sanctification and offers texts.<br>
Those who wish to insist that we are Justified (full stop period)<br>
for salvation are insisting on ignoring the abundance of texts that<br>
talk about sanctification.  We are not the ones who sanctify ourselves.<br>
It is by the power of God and the blood and example of Jesus Christ.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
