<title>May_1992: Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death...</title>
<h1>Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death...</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 1992 14:08:17 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Commitment and Finances"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0052.html">Eric Snyder: "Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Eric Snyder is trying to make the point that Christ's Spirit returned to <br>
God at his death.  This is a point on which Adventists agree.  The spirits<br>
of everyone return to God at death (Eccl 12:7).  What we disagree on <br>
is the question of what the spirit comprises.  In particular, does the <br>
post-death spirit form a conscious intelligent entity outside of or <br>
apart from the body?  To answer these questions we must turn to the large <br>
volume of texts, including the words of Christ referring to death as a sleep.<br>
These indicate that while the spirit may be with God, it is not conscious.<br>
<p>
The spirit could well be described as the backup tape of the character<br>
of an individual.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
