<title>May_1992: Re: Commitment and Finances</title>
<h1>Re: Commitment and Finances</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 92 10:03:57 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#55">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#55">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#55">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#55">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0056.html">McCluskey G: "Re: tithe and committment"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0048.html">Stan Macasieb: "Commitment and Finances"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0057.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: Commitment and Finances"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; nominations to the church board, and have used the tithe issue</i><br>
<i>&gt; as a litmus test of commitment to the church. They reason that,</i><br>
<p>
Here in the Oregon Conference the Conference President has basically<br>
declared war on independent ministries.  Less than full tithing support<br>
of the Conference can cost you your offices in the church -- I happen<br>
to be on a church nominating committee this year.<br>
<p>
Here is my finding after reading available EGW material and the Bible:<br>
<p>
 * We should send our tithe through the proper channels.<br>
<p>
 * If the proper channels are miss appropriating the tithes we should<br>
   protest to those in charge.<br>
<p>
 * If that does not remedy the problem we are accountable for what<br>
   happens to God's money from our income.  That may mean sending<br>
   our tithe to God's work outside of the established channels.  For<br>
   example EGWs 1905 dated letter to a conference president -- She<br>
   said she was sending her money to black pastors in the south<br>
   who were not being properly supported.  She accepted other peoples<br>
   tithe to forward to certain projects and gave a detailed accounting.<br>
<p>
 * Sometimes her tithing outside of proper channels was less a<br>
   protest of missappropriation but rather sending tithe to tithe<br>
   appropriate projects that the proper channels were unresponsive<br>
   to, or the committee process would have taken too long.<br>
<p>
 * If we are not happy with how our tithe is being spent we should<br>
   not withold our tithe.<br>
<p>
 * Not even conference presidents have any business trying to dictate<br>
   your conscience on tithing.  I should not condemn you for sending<br>
   your tithe to the conference.  I should not condemn you for not<br>
   sending your tithe to the conference.  Nor should the conference<br>
   president, the church pastor or the nominating committee.<br>
<p>
 * It is no light matter to decide to send your tithe outside of<br>
   the established channels and to decide where to send it.  Much<br>
   careful study and prayer must go into establishing personal<br>
   criteria.<br>
<p>
 * Tithe money should never be spent on ones own personal ministry.<br>
   For example a youth pastor who spent his tithe for gas money for<br>
   the Youth Van, costumes for an upcoming play he was writing,<br>
   . . . . . .<br>
<p>
Perhaps I should type up the relevant quotes, letters and texts and<br>
post them to SDAnet?  Tithing is simply too important to rest with<br>
my stated observations about what I have read.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
