<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Thus, that faction has begun to question the latest round of</i><br>
<i>&gt; nominations to the church board, and have used the tithe issue</i><br>
<i>&gt; as a litmus test of commitment to the church. They reason that,</i><br>
<i>&gt; because the church has been steadily losing money due to eroding</i><br>
<i>&gt; attendance on a weekly basis and the church's inability to keep</i><br>
<i>&gt; pace with escalating maintenance costs, they need to make sure</i><br>
<i>&gt; that its higher-ups make a dual commitment, spiritually and</i><br>
<i>&gt; financially, to its church. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Is this a reasonable prereq? I had always thought that your </i><br>
<i>&gt; relationship with God is a private matter, and the level of</i><br>
<i>&gt; financial commitment, tithes and offerings, is something that</i><br>
<i>&gt; should not be discussed outside of the boardroom. </i><br>
<p>
This church sounds pretty sick.  Isn't tithe information supposed to<br>
be secret in the first place?<br>
<p>
Even if it's public, judging people on such a basis smacks of<br>
salvation by works.<br>
<p>
Even if you consider judging on the basis of tithe to be OK, you would<br>
need information on the person's salary to do it fairly, else a<br>
plastic surgeon making $200K would wipe out a ditch digger making<br>
$20K.  Is the plastic surgeon more valuable to the church (probably<br>
LESS valuable in reality).<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
