<title>May_1992: re: Commitment and Finances</title>
<h1>re: Commitment and Finances</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 92 14:13:33 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#57">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#57">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#57">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#57">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0058.html">Fred Christiansen: "Good News (Chariots a-Comin')"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0056.html">McCluskey G: "Re: tithe and committment"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0048.html">Stan Macasieb: "Commitment and Finances"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0060.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Commitment and Finances"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Stand Macasieb writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Should the eligibility of a member to the church board be</i><br>
<i>&gt; dependent on the level of financial commitment he/she makes</i><br>
<i>&gt; to his/her local church?</i><br>
<p>
It depends on how the "litmus test" is used.  It is reasonable<br>
for board members to be expected to fulfill the obligation of<br>
returning a "faithful tithe" to the church.  After all, board<br>
members are (or should be) examples for the congregation.<br>
<p>
However, a faithful tithe is, by definition, 10%.  If a church<br>
member makes $1000 a month, his/her tithe is $100.  If he/she<br>
is indeed contributing that, then no one can say that he/she<br>
is not living up to a financial commitment just because he/she<br>
is not one of the churches highest contributors.  Indeed, that <br>
person could be rightly said to have done more than the person<br>
making $10,000 a month that contributes $1000, as the latter <br>
will still have far more means to live on than the former, and<br>
will have made much less of a sacrifice, relatively speaking.<br>
<p>
Churches should take care in saying that board members must be<br>
the greatest contributors of funds, as that makes for a board <br>
that is comprised solely by the wealthiest members.<br>
<p>
Bob Moynihan              Disclaimer: I speak only for myself, not<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com              for the SDA Church, and not<br>
                                      Hewlett-Packard Co.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
