<title>May_1992: Good News (Chariots a-Comin')</title>
<h1>Good News (Chariots a-Comin')</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 92 13:05:50 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#58">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#58">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#58">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#58">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: Commitment and Finances"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve was encouraging some good news.  All right!  The May 7 Adventist Review<br>
had an encouraging article on Revelation seminars in Romania, so if you have<br>
not read it, I urge you to do so.<br>
<p>
And now, here's some news from Richard Wilcox, GC Euro-Asia Affairs dept.<br>
We receive this newsletter since we have been supporting various projects.<br>
Typos are mine.  [Bracketted comments mine.]<br>
<p>
April, 1992<br>
<p>
I have been back from my last trip to the former Soviet Union<br>
now for about three days, so I must get this report<br>
off to you.  There are many thrilling items to share with you,<br>
how God's hand is over our brothers and sisters in the Commonwealth of<br>
Independent States.  The Gospel is going forward speedily in this<br>
vast land.  You dear people who are giving so generously and<br>
sacrificially of your means, as well as your prayers, are making<br>
this possible.<br>
<p>
As I write this report, Elder Mark Finley has finished his<br>
evangelistic campaign in the Kremlin--yes the Kremlin.  Just think,<br>
less than four months ago we were watching the unfolding [??] of the<br>
coup leaders in the great hall of the Kremlin in Moscow.  Now from<br>
that same platform Mark has been sharing the love of Jesus Christ<br>
with from ten to twelve thousand people every day.  The auditorium<br>
will only seat 6,000 opeople so he has gone to two meetings a day<br>
right from the very start.  By God's grace we have baptized over<br>
1400 precious souls as a result of these meetings.  From these<br>
meetings we will be forming at least three new churches.<br>
<p>
We also have two other evangelistic programs going on.  One in<br>
Chernovtsy, which is in the southwest corner of the Ukraine and one<br>
in Vladivostok which is in the far southeastern corner [still pretty far north]<br>
of the Russian Replublic, right up above Japan.  With all of the programs<br>
being help by outside evangelists [e.g., Quiet Hour] and the local follow-up<br>
meetings, we are projecting over 150 evangelistic campaigns in the<br>
Commonwealth of the Independent Sates in 1992.<br>
<p>
Elder Folkenberg is now on his trip to this vast country.  We<br>
have dedicated the medical clinic in Moscow, the publishing house<br>
in Zaokski, and part of the new dormitory and chapel at the<br>
seminary.  We will only have limited operations at the publishing<br>
house with everything else coming on-line a little later in<br>
the summer.  When everything is finished at the Medical Center in<br>
Moscow, we will be offering dental, physical rehabilitation, and<br>
health education.  Dr Carter is our first dentist.  He arrived<br>
April 20, and the health education and physical medicine [staff?] will<br>
follow soon.<br>
<p>
ADRA is in the midst of a tremendous program with the US<br>
Department of Agriculture to provide food and humanitarian help<br>
to eight cities out in the Urals, which is in the south central part<br>
of the Russian Republic.  They will have two convoys of 400 trucks<br>
each that will be bringing food in from a port in Germany.<br>
Altogether they will be providing 12,000 tons of food to these dear<br>
people for that area.  If this goes well, which [sic] we are confident<br>
that it will, the US government has indicated there will be many<br>
more projects of this type.<br>
<p>
Our construction moves slowly but by God's grace it moves<br>
ahead.  With the central government gone, approval to build<br>
comes very slow.  We also find it very hard to get the materials to build<br>
in many areas.  We presently have over 127 churches either under<br>
construction; or in some cases, we are purchasing and renovating<br>
established buildings.  We also have quite a few church buildings<br>
that are finishing up now that started as far back as two years<br>
ago.  We are still very hopeful that Maranatha will be able to<br>
be involved with us and take on some projects there, so that we can<br>
get churches finished much faster.  I will be visiting southern<br>
California to meet with an architectural firm that has developed a<br>
very light and inexpensive building material that can expedite the<br>
way we build.<br>
<p>
We have a business man, Peter Koolik, who is a general contractor<br>
from Australia and he has moved his family to Russia for one<br>
to two years.  He will be heading up all of the construction in<br>
the Zaokski and Moscow areas.  We know this will be a major break-<br>
through to help really get this phase of our work underway.<br>
<p>
I know I run the risk of leaving someone out when I do this<br>
but, I want to give special recognition to all of the employees of<br>
the Chesapeake Conference.  They wanted a special project at<br>
Christmas time so they decided to give their Christmas bonuses [??]<br>
to put stained glass windows in the the new chapel at the seminary.  I<br>
know this will be a lasting memorial to their desire to help these<br>
dear people.<br>
<p>
The need for Bibles, both adult and children's, along with<br>
other literature continues to be very pressing.  As we dedicate the<br>
publishing house in late April, we will then be able on a limited<br>
basis, to begin providing this help in a more timely way;  but the<br>
cost to do this goes up every day.  Our paper and supplies will be<br>
many times more costly than they were even a few months ago.<br>
However, with your continued support, I know God will help us to<br>
meet the needs of our church in this great country.<br>
<p>
I stood outside the church in Moscow and watched the young<br>
people going in carrying their Bibles under their arms.  I realized<br>
how proud they are to have their own Bible.  We ordered 25,000 of<br>
the Children's Bible in mid-1991 and distributed them to every<br>
Adventist home in the entire Division that has young people ages 2<br>
to 15.  However, the supply of books is exhausted, so we need to<br>
order more.<br>
<p>
None of the work from many of the evangelistic campaigns and<br>
building churches to providing Bibles and literature by the<br>
thousands would be possible without the dedication and sacrificial <br>
giving of each and every one of you.  We at the Euro-Asia Affairs<br>
office, as we are now called, want you to know how much we<br>
appreciate your support.<br>
<p>
May the love, peace, and grace of our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ<br>
be with you one and all.<br>
<p>
Your servants at the General Conference,<br>
(signed)<br>
Richard N. Wilcox<br>
Special Assistant to the President for Euro-Asia Affairs<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola TSD (DW278), 2900 S. Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ  85282
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For I know the thoughts that I have toward you, says the Lord, thoughts of
    peace and not evil, to give you hope and a future (Jer 29:11).
</pre>
