<title>May_1992: Re: Saved or Not Saved</title>
<h1>Re: Saved or Not Saved</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 19 May 1992 23:13:29 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#59">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#59">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#59">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#59">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Commitment and Finances"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0058.html">Fred Christiansen: "Good News (Chariots a-Comin')"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0061.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0062.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Most of what I see in the Bible implies that the only prequisite to<br>
salvation is asking for it.  I think we get into trouble, however, if we<br>
assume that once the assurance of salvation is ours, that there is<br>
nothing else to do <br>
in the Christian life.<br>
<p>
Even if there were no heaven, and we knew with certainty that good and<br>
bad alike were all going to burn in hell, God's way is still the best<br>
way to live<br>
here and now.  And it is only as we live the life with a disinterest in our<br>
own salvation and a large interest in loving God and others that we are truly<br>
living unselfishly.<br>
<p>
To summarize<br>
1)  God gives us ample assurance of salvation so we don't need to spend<br>
our lives worrying about it.<br>
<p>
2)  Salvation is the beginning, not the end result of the Christian<br>
experience.  A life lived just to get oneself into heaven is by<br>
definition <br>
selfish.  The selfless Christian will not be concerned with his own<br>
salvation, focusing rather on the needs of others.  (Witness Moses'<br>
willingness to have his name blotted out of the book of life.)<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
