<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all<br>
<p>
	Ok I hear you all loud and clear. I was not really refering<br>
to the once-saved-always-saved issue. I am rather trying to solidify<br>
in my own mind exactly how salvation works in this respect.<br>
<p>
	When we experience conversion I know that salvation is awarded us<br>
immediately, but we don't receive it in its fullness at that moment. <br>
Salvation in all its glorious fullness is really received only at the <br>
2nd coming ( ie savation from both sin and evil ). Isa (?) and EGW tell us <br>
that on conversion we start a journey along the path of righteousness<br>
a steep, narrow and perilous path which ultimately leads us to the New<br>
Jerusalem. "The path of the just is as a shining light that shineth more<br>
and more unto the perfect day" This journey can end for us at the very door<br>
of the New Jerusalem or by death (or by choice, however this cancels the <br>
salvation). <br>
So in this sense salvation is not received until that day in the New Jerusalem. <br>
<p>
So I suppose the question comes down to this does salvation mean the<br>
end or the beginning of the journey. Steve thinks its the latter. <br>
Some of EGW's statements regarding this make me feel the prior my be true.<br>
( again: we get to the end of the journey by sticking to it until we either<br>
die or Jesus comes. This has nothing to do with legalism)<br>
<p>
Do we have any consensus about which definition is more appropriate ?<br>
<p>
Ruben<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
