<i>&gt;The Church Manual, 1990 edition, p. 133, reads:  "Conference workers</i><br>
<i>&gt;and church elders and other officers and institutional leaders are to</i><br>
<i>&gt;recognize that as a principle of leadership in God's work, that a good</i><br>
<i>&gt;example is to be set in the matter of returning tithe.  No one shall be</i><br>
<i>&gt;continued as either a church officer or conference worker who does not</i><br>
<i>&gt;conform to this standard of leadership."</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;This may shed light on the problem.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Nancy V.</i><br>
<p>
Yesterday I received a letter from Don Jacobson, President of the Oregon<br>
Conference.  He was writing to answer the questions I had asked him.<br>
Regarding the policy of witholding offices to those who send any of<br>
their tithes outside the conference -- He said it its Church Manual policy<br>
and his own personal oppinion is not what matters.  I had heard that<br>
Joe Crews was no longer welcome in the Oregon Conference.  Don Jacobson<br>
wrote to me that Joe Crews is still welcome in the Oregon Conference<br>
because he continues to return all tithes sent to him.  He happens to<br>
be a bit out of date.  But thats the policy.  Any independent ministry<br>
they know of that accepts tithe is verboten.  Tye (sp?) Gibson was<br>
an example of an independent ministry determined to be not acceptable.<br>
He recently published a letter announcing that he will no longer accept<br>
tithes.  Soon after that we started receiving meeting notices that he<br>
is to be speaking at several churches in the Oregon Conference.<br>
<p>
Someone I know well, whom I'll not identify, has been for years a head<br>
elder, SS teacher etc.  But some of his tithe goes other than to the<br>
Oregon Conference.  He is on the nominating committee this year at his<br>
church.  The policy was stated by the pastor at the beginning of the<br>
nominating.  So he asked the pastor if he should turn down all his<br>
offices and nominations.  The pastor's reply was YES!<br>
<p>
I guess its not Conference Policy but the church manual from which<br>
these actions spring.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
