<title>May_1992: Re: finances and service to the church</title>
<h1>Re: finances and service to the church</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 20 May 92 10:29:15 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Steven Timm: "Tithe and salvation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Commitment and Finances"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[David Buxton writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Someone I know well, whom I'll not identify, has been for years a head</i><br>
<i>&gt; elder, SS teacher etc.  But some of his tithe goes other than to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Oregon Conference.  He is on the nominating committee this year at his</i><br>
<i>&gt; church.  The policy was stated by the pastor at the beginning of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; nominating.  So he asked the pastor if he should turn down all his</i><br>
<i>&gt; offices and nominations.  The pastor's reply was YES!</i><br>
<p>
If the pastor's reply was as abrupt as that, his handling of the situation<br>
was not wise.  While Mat 18:15 and Gal 6:1 speak of slightly different<br>
situations, the pastor would have been wise to apply to himself the underlying<br>
principles of these verses re a proper, Godly attitude and spirit.<br>
<p>
As for the person, God promises to "dump a semi load" of grace (Jam 4:6,<br>
1Pet 5:5) into that situation so that he can respond in a Christlike way<br>
(as in 1Pet 2:20:<br>
    For what glory is it, if, when ye be buffeted for your faults, ye shall<br>
    take it patiently? but if, when ye do well, and suffer for it, ye take<br>
    it patiently, this is acceptable with God.)<br>
<pre>
-- 
