<title>May_1992: Tithe and salvation</title>
<h1>Tithe and salvation</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 20 May 1992 14:27:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Eric Snyder: "What is the spirit ?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: finances and service to the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
First, a disclaimer:<br>
<p>
It is the policy of the editorship of SDAnet to encourage tithes to be<br>
paid through the appropriate channels.  SDAnet does not now, nor has it<br>
ever,<br>
called for tithes to be paid to itself or any other independent ministry.<br>
<p>
Now that the legal hassle is out of the way:<br>
<p>
For years tithing was enforced by making it sound like one of the many<br>
things required for salvation.  Also it has been encouraged by stories<br>
of people who pay their tithe and the rain came and fell only on their<br>
farm, etc.<br>
(I always wondered why we never heard stories of those who gave their tithe<br>
but still died in the drought, maybe because these people never live to<br>
tell about it.)  Now there is a renewed emphasis on what has long been<br>
church policy perhaps because the other two arguments have become less<br>
effective.<br>
Tithing came as truth to SDA's fairly late in the game, mid-1870's to<br>
late 1880's.  <br>
<p>
When the Illinois conference officers came to my church for a town<br>
meeting, they spent 90 minutes of their two hours talking about the<br>
conference <br>
financial woes.  Now I am a member of the Illinois Conference and they<br>
get my tithe of $100 a month and the conference is in worse financial<br>
shape than before.<br>
<p>
The tithe information is not confidential, at least not for church<br>
employees.  Conferences are known to check up on their employees to see<br>
if they are being faithful.<br>
<p>
I would be interested to see a church where there was 100% member<br>
involvement and no money at all.  Somehow I think we would be in better<br>
shape.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
