<title>May_1992: What is the spirit ?</title>
<h1>What is the spirit ?</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 20 May 92 14:51 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#66">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#66">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#66">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#66">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Steven Timm: "Tithe and salvation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
        I'm trying to clarify in my mind the SDA definition of the<br>
    "spirit".  I received one response that seemed to indicate that<br>
    when Jesus said "Father, into Thy hands I commit my spirit"<br>
    He was simply quoting Psalm 31:6.  The author of the post "I think"<br>
    was saying that at Jesus' death, nothing really went into the<br>
    Father's hands.  Jesus was simply quoting a Psalm.  When I compare<br>
    that with Steve Timm's reponse, it seems that Steve is stating that<br>
    something did indeed return to the Father at Jesus' death.  What<br>
    Steve Timm refers to as a "backup".<br>
 <br>
    Question:  Are you saying that between Jesus' Crucifixion and His<br>
    Resurrection, the eternal Son of God ceased to exist ? ?<br>
 <br>
    In the SDA formulation of the Trinity, is one of the Son's<br>
    attributes, His eternity?  I.E. No beginning, no end ? ?<br>
 <br>
 <br>
    In Hebrews 12:22,23 it says :<br>
 <br>
        But ye are come unto mount Sion, and unto the city of the<br>
    living God, the heavenly Jerusalem, and to an innumerable<br>
    company of angels,<br>
        To the general assembly and church of the firstborn which are<br>
    written in heaven, and to God the Judge of all, and to the spirits<br>
    of just men made perfect......        KJV<br>
 <br>
        Are you then saying that this could be reworded and the<br>
    "backup copies" of men made perfect ?<br>
 <br>
     What about the spirits of wicked men, not made perfect ?<br>
     It would appear that they would not be in the heavenly Jerusalem.<br>
 <br>
     Would you eqate Steve Timm's idea of a back-up with the term<br>
     soul in  either Genesis 35:18, or Matthew 10:28 ?  Or is that<br>
     that something else ?<br>
 <br>
     Eric Snyder<br>
