<title>May_1992: The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew</title>
<h1>The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 21 May 92 12:06:38 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#69">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#69">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#69">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#69">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0070.html">McCluskey G: "Re: The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Steven Timm: "More news on transition"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0070.html">McCluskey G: "Re: The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One of the things we often speak of in Adventism is the Reformation and<br>
how forgotten truth was rediscovered.  We trace Huss, Wycliffe, Luther,<br>
Calvin, Zwingli, Farel, then on to Wesley, et al, finally talking about<br>
the contributions to rediscovered truths that we believe we SDA's have made.<br>
<p>
One of the observations we make is that often (re)discoveries were made in<br>
parallel and that reformers often learned from their predecessors,<br>
building upon that foundation.<br>
<p>
Another observation is that the churches started by the reformers almost<br>
invariably did not progress and accept the newly rediscovered truthes<br>
found by subsequent reformers.  Indeed, one could argue that today many<br>
of those churches are in declension from the teachings they were originally<br>
established upon.  So, what happened?<br>
<p>
My wife has been reading a biography of Katherine von Bora, the wife of<br>
Martin Luther.  In some ways, it is also an excellent biography of<br>
Luther himself.  Many passages are direct from his writings, her writings,<br>
and the notes and writings of those who were close.  In one passage that<br>
my wife was reading Martin is grieving over converts to the Reform faith.<br>
Many of them, it seems, were once zealous in saying their Hail Marys,<br>
attending Mass, taking communion, going to the confessional, etc.  But<br>
now, having accepted the Reformed faith, they are becoming slothful and<br>
lukewarm.  They attend church, pay their tithes and offerings, send their<br>
kids to church school .. but they are not growing spiritually!  (The<br>
comfortable pew syndrome?)<br>
<p>
Sutherland, in his book on principles of Christian Education, indicates that<br>
Luther and Melancthon established a school system as diametrically opposite<br>
to the Catholic system as they could.  Within scant years, all of Germany<br>
as well as other areas, had converted to the Reformed faith.  One could<br>
not find a Catholic.  Shortly after the death of these two, however,<br>
school and church leaders started to push for certain "reforms", ostensibly<br>
to achieve academic excellence.  These "reforms" slowly returned the schools<br>
to the methods of the Catholic schools; spiritual excellence declined as<br>
a direct consequence.<br>
<p>
Sutherland observes that folk had failed to establish themselves in<br>
Scripture and its principles (Col 2:7, Acts 17:11) independent of<br>
what they heard by word of mouth from Luther and Melancthon.  Secondly,<br>
Protestantism (SDA's included .. and this was written a long, long time ago)<br>
failed to (re)reform the school system.  {Reading Sutherland absolutely<br>
blows me away!  It is mind boggling what we accept.}<br>
<p>
So, here we sit, at the end of a long line of reformers.  Have "we" not<br>
made strides in spiritual truth beyond those reformers?  Is not God's<br>
blessing upon "our" church in a special and unique way?  Have we not the<br>
world's largest Protestant denominational school system?  And medical system?<br>
It should be a shoe-in! Ah, but are we really in any better shape spiritually<br>
than those other churches?  ... There's no such thing as cultural memory.<br>
You don't inherit salvation because your parents are church members.<br>
No one rides in on anyone else's coattail.  Each must work out his own<br>
salvation (Phi2:12).  Each must grow in grace and in the Scripture (2Pet3:18).<br>
<p>
In our Sabbath school classes do you see folk eagerly pouring over the<br>
Scripture discovering its doctrinal truths *and* principles for daily<br>
life, claiming specific Bible promises for specific answers, encouraging one<br>
another with memorized verses of hope and comfort?  Or are they sitting<br>
silently, with the talkative few saying "I think" this or "it seems to me"<br>
that or occasionally "doesn't Sister White say ..." (they really aren't sure)<br>
or "haven't I read somewhere ..." such-and-such?  Is Rev 3:15,16 not apt?<br>
<p>
OK.  Enough preaching to the choir.  Let's hear what Scripture says<br>
about the spiritual disciplines.  What produces a people redeemed from<br>
all iniquity (doing things my way), purified and peculiar (unique,<br>
outstanding, standing in bold relief), zealous of good works?  (cf Titus 2:14)<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola TSD (DW278), 2900 S. Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ  85282
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For I know the thoughts that I have toward you, says the Lord, thoughts of
    peace and not evil, to give you hope and a future (Jer 29:11).
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
