<title>May_1992: Re: The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew</title>
<h1>Re: The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 22 May 92 08:32:33 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#70">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#70">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#70">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#70">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0071.html">Gross: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Fred Christiansen: "The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0069.html">Fred Christiansen: "The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; In our Sabbath school classes do you see folk eagerly pouring over the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Scripture discovering its doctrinal truths *and* principles for daily</i><br>
<i>&gt; life, claiming specific Bible promises for specific answers,</i><br>
<i>&gt; encouraging one another with memorized verses of hope and comfort?  Or</i><br>
<i>&gt; are they sitting silently, with the talkative few saying "I think"</i><br>
<i>&gt; this or "it seems to me" that or occasionally "doesn't Sister White</i><br>
<i>&gt; say ..." (they really aren't sure) or "haven't I read somewhere ..."</i><br>
<i>&gt; such-and-such?  Is Rev 3:15,16 not apt?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; OK.  Enough preaching to the choir.  Let's hear what Scripture says</i><br>
<i>&gt; about the spiritual disciplines.  What produces a people redeemed from</i><br>
<i>&gt; all iniquity (doing things my way), purified and peculiar (unique,</i><br>
<i>&gt; outstanding, standing in bold relief), zealous of good works?  (cf</i><br>
<i>&gt; Titus 2:14)</i><br>
<p>
One mundane but it seems to me important aspect of this question has<br>
to do with our old friend "human nature".  The humans I know simply<br>
aren't equipped to continually be challenged on points of "truth".<br>
That does not mean they are not sincere, but it simply means they are<br>
human and fallen.<br>
<p>
You see this in various ways.  For example, the SDA church teaches<br>
that we should go out and "convert the world".  Yet how many of us<br>
would seriously consider allowing some other religion to convert us to<br>
THEIR faith?  If we are not willing to do so, why should we expect<br>
others to convert to OUR faith?<br>
<p>
The point is not that all religions are equally valid, but that most<br>
people including SDAs (and including me) inhabit a comfort zone from<br>
which it is difficult to dislodge them.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
