<title>May_1992: Re: Saved or Not Saved</title>
<h1>Re: Saved or Not Saved</h1>
Gross (<i>grossg@dg-rtp.dg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 22 May 92 10:09:41 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#71">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#71">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#71">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#71">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Fred Christiansen: "The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew (follow-up)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0070.html">McCluskey G: "Re: The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0062.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0067.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Ruben:<br>
<p>
The Bible talks about salvation in three tenses:<br>
<p>
1.  You are saved -- an accomplished fact.<br>
2.  You are being saved -- an on-going work of God in us.<br>
3.  You will be saved -- the final act in our salvation at the 2nd<br>
    Coming.<br>
<p>
My notes on this are at home so I have not noted chapter and verse.<br>
If you would like, I can present the proof texts in another message.<br>
Just let me know so I'll remember to bring my notes in.<br>
<p>
The main point that must be dealt with is that salvation is the work<br>
of God and not man.  And I trust that what God does is perfect,<br>
lacking nothing.  Dave Buxton and I have discussed this before, but my<br>
definition of salvation is not the one you'd expect to hear.  Based on<br>
a study of the words pistis and pisteuo, I find that what Jesus talks<br>
about and what Paul, under inspiration, talks about is not mere mental<br>
movement when they talked of faith and belief.  The Greek words imply<br>
far more than that.  They imply, tacitly, a full, 100 percent, nothing<br>
lacking commitment to Jesus Christ.  So when you read John 3:16, the<br>
word "believe" means precisely this: a full commitment to Jesus<br>
Christ, nothing wavering, nothing withheld, of everything that you<br>
are, or ever will be, and of everything you have, or ever will have.<br>
<p>
This then is the faith of salvation.  And, frankly, I do not find that<br>
to be a natural faith in humans.  This is why Paul writes under<br>
inspiration -- for by grace are you saved through faith, and that [the<br>
faith] not of yourselves, but it is a gift of God ....<br>
<p>
I have heard so many people talk about their faith, and some even have<br>
good works to show, but when faced with a serious event that would<br>
take their life or cause them severe loss (like losing their jobs),<br>
these same people compromise.  What Jesus calls us to is faith that<br>
will not compromise, faith that will stand all the tests that come to<br>
us.  Therein is salvation, and the outworking of our salvation.<br>
<p>
Gotta run for now.<br>
<p>
En Agape tou Iesous,<br>
<p>
Gene Gross <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
