[I wrote:]<br>
<i>&gt; In our Sabbath school classes do you see folk eagerly pouring over the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Scripture discovering its doctrinal truths *and* principles for daily</i><br>
<i>&gt; life, claiming specific Bible promises for specific answers, encouraging one</i><br>
<i>&gt; another with memorized verses of hope and comfort?</i><br>
<p>
I was pleasantly surprised, upon going home for the day, to find that<br>
the latest Adventist Review (May 21) has an AnchorPoints article by<br>
Alden Thompson encouraging, exhorting us to study the Bible.  On the<br>
second page, middle column, middle of the column are some interesting<br>
EGW quotes on the consequences of not studying Scripture for yourself<br>
but depending upon others.  The article, w/ quotes, also addresses the use<br>
of one's intellect and reasoning (read the article to find out).<br>
<p>
For the life of me, I cannot figure out, tho, why the layout people<br>
accompanied the article with a picture of someone who appears to be<br>
a stereotype of the proverbial hellfire-and-brimstone, Bible-thumping<br>
preacher.  Major cognitive dissonance.<br>
<pre>
