<title>May_1992: "The Universal Publishing Association" and the Church Manual</title>
<h1>"The Universal Publishing Association" and the Church Manual</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 25 May 1992 18:26:47 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#73">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#73">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#73">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#73">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Steven Timm: "Adventists and Fundamentalism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Fred Christiansen: "The Reformation and The Comfortable Pew (follow-up)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0076.html">Jim Dunn: "Re: "The Universal Publishing Association" and the Church Manual"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
After a visit to my parents over the weekend, I found a tract had been sent <br>
to me called "The unerring eye that reads the Church Manual."  It is<br>
published by an organization which claims to call itself the "Universal<br>
Publishing Association."  The alleged address is Bashan Hill, Exeter,<br>
Missouri, 65647.<br>
<p>
The tract consists of a series of Ellen White quotes plus a set of<br>
quotes from various General Conference bulletins which may or may not be<br>
attributable to her.  These are arranged in the usual arrogant,<br>
point-scoring, repugnant style which characterizes so many of these<br>
compiliations.  Bible verses are nowhere to be seen.  Try as they might,<br>
they<br>
at least don't attempt to reproduce nonexistent Ellen White quotes against a <br>
church manual.  But they do use ample brackets for explanation of quotes<br>
which have little to do with the subject.<br>
<p>
Has anyone else heard of "The Universal Publishing Association"?  If no<br>
one else has, then I apologize for giving them this unwarranted publicity.<br>
I assure you you haven't missed a thing by not reading this tract.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
