<title>May_1992: Adventists and Fundamentalism</title>
<h1>Adventists and Fundamentalism</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 25 May 1992 18:42:55 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#74">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#74">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#74">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#74">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Steven Timm: ""The Universal Publishing Association" and the Church Manual"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The following two questions have entered my mind recently:<br>
<p>
1)  Are Adventists fundamentalists?<br>
<p>
2)  Should we be?<br>
<p>
Let me begin the discussion by saying that there is a broad definition of the <br>
word, and also a pejorative one.  The broad definition relates to a group <br>
of Protestant theologians in the early 1900's that made a stand against <br>
liberalism and affirmed basic values about the Bible.  They held to <br>
traditionally conservative interpretations in the face of arguments from<br>
communism, evolution, and what have you.  This movement was at its peak<br>
about the time of the death of Ellen G. White in 1915, and it is not<br>
surprising <br>
that the SDA church also followed many of the same theological trends at <br>
that time.<br>
<p>
The pejorative definition is used by the media against those<br>
fundamentalists who have developed a well-formed social agenda. <br>
Fundamentalists are active <br>
in the pro-life movement, the school prayer movement, the anti-pornography <br>
movement and many others.  Some of these social causes I feel are worthwhile,<br>
but I wonder about the methods that are used.  Has God's word in the hand<br>
of fundamentalists changed from the two-edged sword that cuts preacher<br>
as well as listener to a blunt club that is used to beat others into<br>
submission?<br>
I am afraid so.  We see the concept of creeping inspiration where the<br>
manner of presentation implies that not only the Word but also the<br>
interpretation is infallible.<br>
<p>
Now, I realize that in saying this I am questioning belief #1 of the <br>
Statement of Fundamental Beliefs.  (The postulate of the inspiration of<br>
the Bible).  But are we justified to claim for the <br>
Bible (or, for that matter, Ellen G. White) what those writings do not claim <br>
for themselves?  And, even were those writings to claim infallibility, which <br>
they do not, is that excuse to use them as a club against all those who<br>
disagree?<br>
<p>
I hope some careful discussion can be generated about this in the near future.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
