<title>May_1992: Re: Saved or Not Saved</title>
<h1>Re: Saved or Not Saved</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 25 May 92 11:47:19 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#75">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#75">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#75">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#75">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0076.html">Jim Dunn: "Re: "The Universal Publishing Association" and the Church Manual"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Steven Timm: "Adventists and Fundamentalism"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0093.html">Gross: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
Gene writes :<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;The Bible talks about salvation in three tenses:</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;1.  You are saved -- an accomplished fact.</i><br>
<i>&gt;2.  You are being saved -- an on-going work of God in us.</i><br>
<i>&gt;3.  You will be saved -- the final act in our salvation at the 2nd</i><br>
<i>&gt;   Coming.</i><br>
<p>
I have no problem with this, in fact I agree 100%. The way point 1 is expressed<br>
about however I am a little dubious. I would say our salvation has already been <br>
perfectly worked out for us, I would not say that my salvation in its totality<br>
an accomplised fact.  <br>
<p>
Do you support the opinion that Salvation is like a path that <br>
one travels ? As soon as you step on the path you are saved, and remain<br>
so while you progress along this path ? <br>
<p>
Is it like a race that we enter knowing we will win the prize because <br>
Jesus has promised us the victory, but we only really receive the prize<br>
at the end of the race ?<br>
<p>
We speak about perfection being progressive, ie non-static. It is not<br>
a stage one reaches but a phase one enters of perpetual advancement.<br>
<p>
Can the same be said of salvation ? Is it not a stage one attains but<br>
a process of continual and more complete salvation. Let me see, how could I <br>
exemplify this statement :<br>
<p>
When one is converted he is perfectly saved from his/her past, and ample<br>
salvation for the present is supplied. As one cherishes this present salvation,<br>
power is given us to save us from present/future evil/sin. Finally we shall <br>
be saved from the very presense of sin. The past salvation is from our guilt,<br>
the present salvation is from sin and the future salvation is from morality.<br>
<p>
I suppose one could say this sounds like a bit of a discussion of whether<br>
sanctification and (glorification )is part of salvation, but I don't think <br>
that is really what I am getting at. I accept 100% that without santification <br>
there is no justification, and vice versa (ie you need both for salvation to be <br>
effective) I really wish to understand the correct usage of the term salvation.<br>
<p>
Do we conclude that the term Salvation has multiple meanings each distinct<br>
and separate ? If so then every time we speak of salvation we must quantify<br>
exactly to which salvation it is that we mean.<br>
<p>
Or do we conclude that salvation is a process and that while one is on the <br>
path his salvation is progressively more perfect?<br>
<p>
Regards,<br>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
