<title>May_1992: Spirit and Soul</title>
<h1>Spirit and Soul</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 25 May 1992 19:38:54 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#77">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#77">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#77">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#77">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Steven Timm: "Anti-religionism?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0076.html">Jim Dunn: "Re: "The Universal Publishing Association" and the Church Manual"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0080.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Spirit and Soul"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Eric Snyder raises several questions about the spirit and by extension <br>
the soul.  In particular, is the spirit the same as the soul.  As defined <br>
in Genesis 35:18, the answer is no.  As to Matthew 10:28, it's more <br>
difficult to say.  Perhaps someone with a Strong's can tell us what <br>
Greek word is translated "soul" in that verse:  "Fear not them which kill<br>
the body, but are not able to kill the soul, but rather fear him which is <br>
able to destroy both soul and body in hell."<br>
<p>
Eric is referring to two verses here which suggest that in addition to <br>
being a soul, we also have a soul.  There are several others.  I have an <br>
explanation for this but would like to hear what other netters have to say<br>
about these and other verses.<br>
<p>
As to the question Eric puts forth "Did the Son of God cease to exist <br>
over the Passion Weekend?"  I will not claim to know what happened to <br>
the divine nature of Christ over this time (maybe others can shed light<br>
on this) but as far as is observable to human eyes his death was not <br>
physically different than any of ours.  <br>
<p>
Perhaps the best way to describe the spirit is the character of a person.<br>
We need to discuss this more and really look at answering the questions about <br>
this doctrine that people are asking now. <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
