<title>May_1992: Anti-religionism?</title>
<h1>Anti-religionism?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 25 May 1992 19:57:41 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#78">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#78">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#78">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#78">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Steven Timm: "More on Soul and Spirit in the NT."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Steven Timm: "Spirit and Soul"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Over the weekend of May 16, most of the Adventist Review staff visited<br>
the Hinsdale, IL area.  I attended the forum that they held in the afternoon.<br>
As might be expected, Associate Editor Roy Adams proved to be the<br>
lightning rod for the afternoon, with a large part of the discussion<br>
centered on his<br>
editorials espousing unconventional views on church-state relations.<br>
<p>
(For background--Roy Adams has suggested in his editorials that it <br>
might be appropriate for those SDA parents who send their children to <br>
parochial schools to receive some refund of the property tax they pay to <br>
support the public schools.)<br>
<p>
He made the following point in response to questions:  Sometimes when <br>
the SDA church stands against organized prayer in public schools, and <br>
other similar issues, we appear to be anti-religion.<br>
<p>
(He made his point much better than I just did.  My apologies.)<br>
<p>
Other side issues:  William Johnsson responded to the issue of the change<br>
of three angels to three wavy lines:  "The three wavy lines in the "A"<br>
of Adventist Review are three stylized angels."  No lie.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
