<title>May_1992: More on Soul and Spirit in the NT.</title>
<h1>More on Soul and Spirit in the NT.</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 26 May 1992 09:55:16 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#79">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#79">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#79">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#79">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0080.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Spirit and Soul"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Steven Timm: "Anti-religionism?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
All the references in the NT translated as "soul" by the KJV trace back to <br>
the same Greek word "psuche".  Strong's Concordance gives the primary meaning<br>
of this word as "spirit".  In the NT it is almost always referred to in the <br>
possessive, in other words as something one has rather than something one is.<br>
This is what would be expected when you view the whole person as a <br>
composite of body and spirit, frequently referred to , as in Matt 10:28,<br>
as "body and soul."<br>
<p>
This is distinct from the Greek word "pneuma", usually translated "spirit"<br>
which is used interchangeably to refer to the Holy Spirit, evil spirits,<br>
or the human spirit.<br>
<p>
More later.  I've got to get to work.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
