<title>May_1992: Re: Spirit and Soul</title>
<h1>Re: Spirit and Soul</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 26 May 92 07:23:12 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#80">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#80">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#80">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#80">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Dave Buxton: "Three Wavy Lines"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Steven Timm: "More on Soul and Spirit in the NT."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0077.html">Steven Timm: "Spirit and Soul"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Perhaps a good way to respond to Steve's &amp; Eric's posts is to point<br>
out that:<br>
<p>
 * The OT is especially clear that body, soul, spirit were all seen<br>
   to be parts of man's inseparable WHOLENESS.<br>
<p>
 * The Greeks taught that these were parts of man's SEPARATENESS that<br>
   came together temporarily during a man's lifetime.<br>
<p>
Greek is the language of the NT.  It can be clearly established which<br>
words from the Hebrew were used in the Greek to mean soul and spirit.<br>
Do we use the Hebrew meanings that can be clearly established with<br>
a careful Hebrew and/or Concordance study?  From such a study it<br>
becomes clear that these are parts of man's wholeness.  Or do we use<br>
the Greek meanings?  Augustine is an example of an early church "father"<br>
who did much to popularize the views of Plato's Helenism (Greek Culture)<br>
on the separableness of man.  The earliest of the "church father's"<br>
were not yet into this sort of theology.  But over the years the<br>
philosophy of the Greeks became more and more accepted church theology.<br>
<p>
We know that the Pharisees absorbed a lot of Greek culture, even<br>
believing in the separableness of man.  I sometimes ponder to what<br>
extent Paul was influenced by his Pharisaical up bringing.  There are<br>
times when Paul speaks very clearly that, for example, our reward comes<br>
not at death but at the ressurection.  But when Paul seems a bit<br>
ambiguous is it his former training in Greek culture leaking through?<br>
<p>
That raises a question.  Does our model of what makes a prophet and/or<br>
a Bible writer allow that some heresies might glint here and there<br>
because of a Bible writer's former upbringing?  I think that to be<br>
on the safe side we had better define our terms from the Old Testament<br>
as much as possible and avoid tainting our terms from Greek Philosophy.<br>
<p>
Some theologians actually teach that the OT folks were somewhat ignorant<br>
of all the truth on the matter of the after life, that God exposed them<br>
to Helenism to bring them to an understanding of the true nature of<br>
the soul and spirit of man.  That is their objection to the clear<br>
position of the OT on the inseparableness of man.  I cannot buy that.<br>
What comes to mind is the sermons of Paul speaking out against the<br>
philosophy of the Greeks.  They are were not inspired of God as were<br>
the writers of the OT.  And so it is that I define my terms from the OT.<br>
That defines for me the inseprable nature of man.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
