<!-- body="start" -->
On Tue, 19 May 1992 14:09:28 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;.......... stuff deleted ........</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; Is this a reasonable prereq? I had always thought that your</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; relationship with God is a private matter, and the level of</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; financial commitment, tithes and offerings, is something that</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; should not be discussed outside of the boardroom.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;This church sounds pretty sick.  Isn't tithe information supposed to</i><br>
<i>&gt;be secret in the first place?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Even if it's public, judging people on such a basis smacks of</i><br>
<i>&gt;salvation by works.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Even if you consider judging on the basis of tithe to be OK, you would</i><br>
<i>&gt;need information on the person's salary to do it fairly, else a</i><br>
<i>&gt;plastic surgeon making $200K would wipe out a ditch digger making</i><br>
<i>&gt;$20K.  Is the plastic surgeon more valuable to the church (probably</i><br>
<i>&gt;LESS valuable in reality).</i><br>
<p>
  In the LDS church tithing is a prereq for certain things.  You are<br>
interviewed, ususally by the bishop (local congregation minister, but<br>
not really) and asked certain standard questions.  One is 'are you a<br>
faithful full tither'.  You answer yes/no.  But you are really talking<br>
to the Lord and even if you lie to the bishop it will come out in the<br>
wash.  We have even won a court case about using tithing as a prereq for<br>
a church job (some non-religious, but paying job).<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
