<!-- body="start" -->
I see that my post has created quite a stir in this group. <br>
<p>
The general consensus is that, despite the possibility of church<br>
leaders meddling with the tithe, its symbol as a commitment to<br>
God is much stronger. This also means that the church CAN use<br>
lack of financial support to the church as a reason for denial of<br>
church office. For how can you demonstrate commitment to others<br>
if you can't exhibit a basic commitment to God through your 10%?<br>
<p>
What I wonder now is if a church can enforce a level of tithing.<br>
That is, does the church have the right to know how much you<br>
earn in a year and, armed with that knowledge, use that information<br>
to make sure that you return that much tithe on a consistent basis?<br>
<p>
I understand the major spiritual ramnifications of this discussion.<br>
And I don't want to feel that I'm shortchanging God in any way,<br>
especially on such an important topic.<br>
<p>
But I also feel a sense of legalism in such a question. Are we <br>
starting to debate nits like how much tithe we give, instead of <br>
concentrating on whether we give at all? Whether we are returning<br>
because we have to, or because we want to? Thank God we are able<br>
to give at all!<br>
<p>
Thanks again.<br>
<p>
--Stan Macasieb (stanm@comm.mot.com)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
