[The words of Rhonda Gaines]<br>
After replying by private mail to Lola, she suggested that I post<br>
this reply to the group.  Here goes... Hope it doesn't start a war<br>
:-)).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;In reading the discussion over Hosea's warning about the end of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;new moons celebrations, feast days, and sabbaths, I haven't seen it</i><br>
<i>&gt;brought up as to the possibility that this is not talking about THE</i><br>
<i>&gt;WEEKLY Sabbath...</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Weren't some of those feast days, etc. also called sabbaths, even though</i><br>
<i>&gt;they were not WEEKLY Sabbaths?  I've always assumed that this text</i><br>
<i>&gt;talked about the end of the celebration of the feasts, but not the Sabbath</i><br>
<i>&gt;that came every week.  Although, as has been pointed out, those who went</i><br>
<i>&gt;into captivity couldn't celebrate either kind.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Lola Aagaard</i><br>
<i>&gt;Aagaard@Morekypr</i><br>
<p>
Having not read the particular passage of scripture you're referring<br>
to, I can definitely tell you that when the scripture refers to a<br>
sabbath, it isn't always referring to the seventh day sabbath.<br>
That's how many errors in the dating of the feasts have come about,<br>
from the incorrect assumption that sabbath always equals 7th day<br>
sabbath especially when taken out of context.  For example, the<br>
crucifixion has established "Good Friday" because the jews removed<br>
Christ's body from the cross before the beginning of the high<br>
sabbath.  Many, catholics, baptist, etc., assume that this means the<br>
7th day sabbath, when actually it means the feast of unleaven bread<br>
sabbath which is a high sabbath.  They don't take the time to<br>
reference it back to the corroborating (sp?) scriptures in the old<br>
testament or even the new testament for that matter.  In the example<br>
above, the old testament scripture clearly states that the messiah<br>
shall be cut off in the midst of the week.  How the midst (middle)<br>
of the week ever got to be friday, I'll never know :-).  Hope this<br>
provides some favorable enlightenment and that it doesn't<br>
sound...mean.  That's not the word I'm looking for but it's the best<br>
I can do right now :-).<br>
<p>
 -rhonda<br>
 <br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Rhonda Gaines              INTERNET: rrg@fibercom.com
FiberCom, Inc.             UUCP: ...!uunet!fibercom!rrg   
P.O. Box 11966             PHONE: 703-342-6700 or 800-423-1183 x291
Roanoke, VA  24022-1966    FAX:   703-342-5961
<p>
[Note that Rhonda is not presenting an SDA viewpoint here.  Rhonda refers 
to "the midst of the week" from Daniel 9:26, I presume.  When viewed
in the context of the seventy weeks prophecy interpreted according to the 
year-day principle, the week refers to the last 7 years of time alloted 
the Jews, beginning in 27 AD with the baptism of Christ.  Christ was cut 
off in the midst of the week, 31 AD.  Other more persuasive arguments
can be made both for and against a Wednesday crucifixion, we will deal 
with those if we need to.  All that being said, Rhonda's point of 
not all sabbaths being the 7th day Sabbath is, I believe, a valid one.  SCT]
</pre>
