<title>May_1992: Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?</h1>
Leslie Robert Lait (<i>lrlait@ertel.gsfc.nasa.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 27 May 92 19:38:14 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#90">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#90">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#90">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#90">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0091.html">McCluskey G: "Re: tithing"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Rhonda Gaines: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0051.html">Lola: "Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0092.html">McCluskey G: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Recent posts have raised questions about confidentiality of members'<br>
giving records, culminating in our moderator's comment:<br>
<i>&gt;  The tithe information is not confidential, at least not for church</i><br>
<i>&gt;  employees.  Conferences are known to check up on their employees to see</i><br>
<i>&gt;  if they are being faithful.</i><br>
<p>
This is true up to a point, but I think perhaps a little clarification<br>
is needed so our non-SDA friends don't get the wrong impression.  I am<br>
an assistant treasurer in Silver Spring, and I asked our treasurer (who<br>
also works part-time at the General Conference) about this.<br>
<p>
Within the local congregation, only the treasurer (plus any assistants)<br>
has regular access to the records of individual members' giving, tithe<br>
or otherwise. (Yes, I know that tithe is "returned," not "given"--I'm<br>
just using a single, generic term to cover tithes and offerings.)<br>
<p>
The pastor has access upon request.  Some pastors never ask; some do.<br>
<p>
As far as the local congregation is concerned, this information is not<br>
supposed to be released to anybody else for any reason.  The finance<br>
committee chairman does not see it; the stewardship director does not<br>
see it; the nominating committee does not see it.  (In that last case,<br>
the pastor is supposed to see to it that nominated officers are regular<br>
tithepayers, but nobody brings out a list of who-gives-what for<br>
inspection by the committee.)<br>
<p>
What about the conference (the next level up from the local church)?<br>
The conference treasurer's office gets the information with the local<br>
church's financial reports.  Again, there are supposed to be clearly<br>
drawn channels about who has access to this information (I specifically<br>
asked about whether anyone there would be trolling for big donors or for<br>
names for mailing lists and was told that would be considered very<br>
inappropriate).<br>
<p>
Church employment is conditioned on tithe payment (as someone quoted<br>
from the _Church_Manual_ recently), but interpretation and enforcement<br>
of this rule apparently varies from place to place.<br>
<p>
No donation information with names attached is supposed to rise above<br>
the conference level.  That is, the unions and the General Conference<br>
get financial reports from below, but nothing with donors' names<br>
listed.<br>
<p>
The basic principle is that tithe and offering information is supposed<br>
to be tightly controlled up through the conference level and is not<br>
propagated beyond.<br>
<p>
About enforcement on non-church-employees and non-church-officers,<br>
the _Church_Manual_ states:<br>
<i>|     Although the returning of the tithe is not held as a test of</i><br>
                                             ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ <br>
<i>|     fellowship, it is recognized as a scriptural obligation that every</i><br>
      ^^^^^^^^^^<br>
<i>|     believer owes to God and as one of the spiritual exercises in</i><br>
<i>|     which he should have part in claiming by faith the fulness of </i><br>
<i>|     blessing in Christian life and experience</i><br>
<p>
No one is going to force a member to disclose his or her income (note<br>
that the conference already knows how much its employees are making).<br>
Furthermore, there is some question about just what constitutes an<br>
"honest" tithe: do you tithe on your gross income? net? before taxes?<br>
"increase?" Does a retiree who spent his working life tithing his gross<br>
income pay a tithe on his Social Security check, or some part of it?<br>
It's like Sabbathkeeping: some things are clearly in bounds, and some<br>
are clearly out of bounds, but the church has not drawn up a long set<br>
of official rules detailing exactly what goes and doesn't go.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Leslie Robert Lait                           | <br>
lrlait@ertel.gsfc.nasa.gov                   |  "...Now hit any key.<br>
My opinions are my own, not NASA's.          |   WAIT! NO! Not *that* key!"<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
