<title>May_1992: Re: tithing</title>
<h1>Re: tithing</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 May 92 09:15:38 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#91">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#91">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#91">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#91">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0092.html">McCluskey G: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0090.html">Leslie Robert Lait: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; ... This also means that the church CAN use lack of financial support</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the church as a reason for denial of church office. For how can you</i><br>
<i>&gt; demonstrate commitment to others if you can't exhibit a basic</i><br>
<i>&gt; commitment to God through your 10%?</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What I wonder now is if a church can enforce a level of tithing.  That</i><br>
<i>&gt; is, does the church have the right to know how much you earn in a year</i><br>
<i>&gt; and, armed with that knowledge, use that information to make sure that</i><br>
<i>&gt; you return that much tithe on a consistent basis?</i><br>
<p>
This is an interesting issue.  Most of us would agree that there has<br>
to be some discrimination for church office, but how do you decide?<br>
For example, I think a person who is grossly overweight (temperance)<br>
but pays tithe is no more qualified for church office than someone of<br>
normal weight who doesn't pay tithe.  However, if the church started<br>
REALLY enforcing this kind of rule, there would be an uproar.<br>
<p>
Perhaps one key to this is to note that the judgement of the church is<br>
not the judgement of God.  Billy Graham would be deemed unsuitable for<br>
SDA church office (he worships on the wrong day of the week), but who<br>
can deny he is a man of God?<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
