<!-- name="Gross" -->
<!-- email="grossg@dg-rtp.dg.com" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Saved or Not Saved" -->
<!-- id="9205281520.AA02425@patriot" -->
<!-- inreplyto="9205250147.AA01475@europa.ee.uts.edu.au" -->
<title>May_1992: Re: Saved or Not Saved</title>
<h1>Re: Saved or Not Saved</h1>
Gross (<i>grossg@dg-rtp.dg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 May 92 11:20:05 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#93">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#93">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#93">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#93">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0092.html">McCluskey G: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0075.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0101.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I wrote:<br>
# <br>
# &gt;The Bible talks about salvation in three tenses:<br>
# &gt;<br>
# &gt;1.  You are saved -- an accomplished fact.<br>
# &gt;2.  You are being saved -- an on-going work of God in us.<br>
# &gt;3.  You will be saved -- the final act in our salvation at the 2nd<br>
# &gt;   Coming.<br>
<p>
Ruben responds: <br>
# I have no problem with this, in fact I agree 100%. The way point 1 is <br>
# expressed about however I am a little dubious. I would say our salvation <br>
# has already been perfectly worked out for us, I would not say that <br>
# my salvation in its totality an accomplised fact.  <br>
<p>
First, does God ever give us an imperfect gift!?  And if we agree that<br>
salvation is a gift (Eph. 2:8, 9), then what would be lacking or<br>
incomplete about it?  Would it not be salvation to the uttermost, for<br>
all eternity?<br>
<p>
Second, the oft quoted verse of John 3:16 states that if we believe<br>
(pistis) we have (present tense, an accomplished fact) eternal life<br>
(or salvation).<br>
<p>
The problem is that while we come alive spiritually we still have a<br>
physical body that is unregenerated.  Our flesh is still subject to<br>
the lusts thereof.  So, the path you talk about, Brother Ruben, is<br>
indeed a path -- we are working out our salvation in fear and<br>
trembling.  Each day we must appropriate anew the power of our<br>
glorious Savior to defeat our own flesh and sinful tendencies, and to<br>
come against an implaccable, though defeated, foe.  Were it not for<br>
the fact of our salvation, which we took possession of at the moment<br>
we believed (pistis, again), we would be powerless to make this<br>
journey on the path of God's salvation.<br>
<p>
But we must never think that it is our works that earn us the<br>
salvation.  The salvation is a gift, given freely by God because of<br>
His grace and not our own merit.  Our works are part of the discipline<br>
(in the instructional sense of that word) that we take on as God works<br>
in our lives to conform us to the image of His Son (Rom. 8:29).<br>
<p>
Too often, some render works to the background of Christian living.<br>
Others seem to place all the stress on works and little on the grace<br>
of God that brought us the gift of salvation.  The balance and the<br>
truth of this matter is not in the extremes.  It is in realising what<br>
the works are for and that they come after the person's salvation.<br>
The works will not come without first being born-again.  This is not<br>
to say that some don't have works without salvation, but they do not<br>
stand for long in the presence of the Eternal Creator God who will<br>
judge all things.  And in fact, I think we are beginning to see some<br>
of those works being judged now -- for God always starts houseclening<br>
in His own house first.<br>
<p>
Hope this helps to better explain my own understanding of salvation<br>
and works.  And before someone asks, yes, I do believe that a person<br>
who is saved is saved for eternity.  However, I would point you back<br>
to my previous article on what I believe is meant by the Greek words<br>
pistis and pisteuo, which we translate believe and faith.  I don't<br>
accpet the notion that what is being talked about is some mere mental<br>
exercise.  Something more profound is going on, something that takes<br>
the person from here to eternity spiritually, which results in such in<br>
all-consuming change of that person's life and thoughts that they<br>
really have become a "new creature" in Christ.  I recall knowing that<br>
I could do nothing without Christ and because of Him I would do<br>
anything and everything that He asked.  There was never a doubt, and<br>
there still isn't.  Am I perfect -- NOPE!  I still stumble around and<br>
fail -- my knees are getting very sore as I get older. ;-)  But I know<br>
that my salvation is sure and assured because of the surety of God --<br>
the Holy Spirit -- and because God has never given an gift that was<br>
lacking in anything, nor one that was dependent upon me.<br>
<p>
Gotta run.  Later, friends.<br>
<p>
En Agape,<br>
<p>
Gene Gross <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
