<title>May_1992: What is Love (Agape)</title>
<h1>What is Love (Agape)</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 May 92 10:23:41 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#95">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#95">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#95">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#95">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To SDAnet,<br>
<p>
In our church there are those who protest that this person or that<br>
person is not a loving person because they protest certain things,<br>
such as celebration themes.  Or they say the protests have not been<br>
done in a "loving" way.  But there are those who get mighty abrasive<br>
at times in their promotion of (for example again) celebration themes.<br>
And nobody says they are unloving.  It would seem that any protest is<br>
inherantly unloving.  And that you are pretty safe of the love scale<br>
if you aggressively promote most anything.<br>
<p>
This leads me to ponder if the "love" litmus is popularity?  If someone<br>
is popular they are more likely to be sited as 'loving' examples.<br>
<p>
Also, for example in Sabbath School class, when ever the discussion<br>
gets into some of the weightier matters of the Torah there are those<br>
who pipe up with -- but love is the only thing that matters.  They<br>
would just as soon not participate in . . . . . . because its not<br>
on their list of subtitles under the topic of 'love'.  I might think<br>
it is, but according to their criteria its not a relevant discussion<br>
considering that "love is the only thing that matters".<br>
<p>
Please, I don't want to be starting a 'celebration' thread here.  I<br>
don't want to be starting a liberals vs conservatives pitched battle.<br>
I do want some serious comments about what really is the 'love' that<br>
the Bible calls for.<br>
<p>
Ellen White talks a lot about "lovesick sentimentalism" being mistaken<br>
for love, being mistake for the gospel.  Is it is the dangerous<br>
theology she makes it out to be?<br>
<p>
One discussion I was reading a few days ago mentioned that the Greeks<br>
objected to the Bible writers using the word Agape.  To the Greeks<br>
agape was an obscure, unatainable theoretical sort of love.  Heavenly<br>
eros was to the Greeks the ultimate in love.  So, some of the early<br>
'fathers' started using eros in place of agape.  This created quite<br>
an uproar from some quarters.  So, Augustine solved the problem by<br>
synthesizing the word critos (I'm sure I have it spelled wrong).  This<br>
is a latin word and was meant to be the synthesis of eros and agape.<br>
This was seen to be both the form of love that God exhibits and the<br>
form of love that man is capable of.  It meant that God had to be<br>
met half way in order to be saved.  The King James, for example,<br>
translates it "cherity".  I looked up cherity in my Youngs Concordance<br>
and sure enough, every single instance of cherity comes from agape.<br>
The greatest of these is "AGAPE", not eros/agape.   But is man capable<br>
of agape?  No!  Is God capable of implanting agape into a human? Yes!<br>
Does God meet us when we are at -100% ?  YES!  Even in the depths of<br>
hell on earth.<br>
<p>
We know that God alone is the judge of what is agape love.  We cannot<br>
fathom its depths and bredth.   But can we establish some criteria<br>
of what it is?  When God sent Jonah to Ninevah was God calling Jonah<br>
to demonstrate agape love while Jonah prefered eros -- hey these<br>
folks are going to . . . . . if I preach that kind of a sermon.<br>
Is Agape vs Eros even relevent when we talk about Jonah?<br>
When we read about the prophets of the OT who made some rather bold<br>
statements in the face of kings and priests, were they demonstrating<br>
agape, or did agape only show up after the cross?   Is it possible that<br>
our various litmus of Christian love is more tainted by Hollywood than<br>
by the Bible?<br>
<p>
And so I ask, what really is love [agape].  What texts can you offer<br>
to illuminate this question?   Or must we consult the overall fabric<br>
of the Bible record from cover to cover?<br>
<p>
Thanks,<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
