<title>May_1992: Re: tithing</title>
<h1>Re: tithing</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 May 1992 10:55 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#97">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#97">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#97">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#97">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Rhonda Gaines: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Glen posted:<br>
<p>
"This is an interesting issue.  Most of us would agree that there has<br>
to be some discrimination for church office, but how do you decide?<br>
For example, I think a person who is grossly overweight (temperance)<br>
but pays tithe is no more qualified for church office than someone of<br>
normal weight who doesn't pay tithe.  However, if the church started<br>
REALLY enforcing this kind of rule, there would be an uproar.<br>
"<br>
<p>
Glen is assuming that obesity is caused by intemperance.  This is not<br>
necessarily the case.  In fact, science is discovering that the genetic<br>
predisposition to obesity is very real and that many people struggle all<br>
their life with an image that they grossly indulge when this is not the<br>
case.  For many, obesity is something they struggle with all their life<br>
and there seems to be very little they can do about it.  Tithing on the<br>
other hand is just a choice and commitment.  There is not predisposition<br>
genetically to be a nontither.  I have been a member of the an SDA church<br>
in the past where the head elder regularly took his family skiing on<br>
Sabbath, other elders drank alcohol socially, and the wives wore furs and<br>
gaudy jewelry to church.  These items are more appropriate measures of<br>
"conformity to church standards" than obestiy.  However, whenever we start<br>
judging others based on outward appearances, we are not following God's<br>
way.  I think the SDA church organization which has members of the local<br>
church selecting individuals for church office will encourage the use of<br>
outward appearance and behavior patterns in the selection process.  The<br>
LDS church, on the other hand, offers "calls" for all church positions<br>
based on the decision of the bishopric (lay leaders) of the ward.  Sometimes<br>
individuals are given an assignment, not because they are "worthy" but<br>
rather to give them an opportunity for spiritual and personal growth.<br>
<p>
For example, I doubt the disciple known as Simon, later called Peter, would<br>
have been given an SDA church office.  Yet Jesus called him personally and<br>
through his association with Christ became a powerful church leader.<br>
<p>
Another issue in the nomination of church officers in the SDA church is<br>
that many times the nominating committee cannot find anyone "willing" to<br>
accept an appointment.  For example, the SDA church in Salt Lake City has<br>
always had trouble finding anyone willing to lead the Earliteen &amp; Junior<br>
divisions.  We also had several Sabbaths that the cradle roll and kindergarten<br>
teachers just didn't show.  I don't know how prevalent these kinds of<br>
problems are across the US, but how does the local church deal with these?<br>
<p>
Cheryl Berthelsen<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
