<title>May_1992: Life's A Beach</title>
<h1>Life's A Beach</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 May 1992 22:21:30 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#99">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#99">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#99">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#99">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0100.html">Rhonda Gaines: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Rhonda Gaines: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In the question about just when are we saved, I offer the following <br>
parable, adapted from ideas set forth in a book I once tried to write:<br>
<p>
We are born on the beach and live there most of the time.  There's nothing<br>
inherently wrong with being on the beach, but it is dangerous.  Hurricanes,<br>
tidal waves, and sharks come along from time to time.  A cliff rising<br>
directly up from the beach offers safety at its top but is difficult if<br>
not impossible to climb.<br>
<p>
Most people believe in the Great Lifeguard, even though they've never<br>
seen him.  But the theories are widely different.  Some say "The Great<br>
Lifeguard has done it all for you already.  You can just stay here on<br>
the beach and you'll be fine."  Others are taught at "cliff school" that<br>
it is their duty to try to climb the cliff.  "If you haven't made it to<br>
the top yet when the tidal wave comes, then the Great Lifeguard will<br>
pull you the rest of the way."<br>
<p>
I tried to climb the cliff, but found that I quickly slid back down to the<br>
base.  I saw the cliff-divers jump off the cliff and fall to the water below.<br>
I tried jumping up, but still fell back to the bottom.  I concluded that<br>
the law of gravity doomed me to existence at the bottom.  "As long as I<br>
stay pretty close to shore, I'll be all right."<br>
<p>
I didn't even see the tidal wave coming.  I turned around and only had time <br>
to call HELP!  Just as it seemed I would be smashed up against the rocks <br>
of the cliff, I felt the strong arms of the Great Lifeguard grab me,<br>
and a lifeline quickly pulled me up the cliff to safety. <br>
<p>
"I'm saved!"  I shouted, and rushed to join the line of cliff divers<br>
ready to jump off the cliff.<br>
<p>
---------<br>
<p>
Here ends the parable.  There are several things that can be said about<br>
salvation, the nature of Christ, and the nature of the law using this<br>
parable.   Please comment on what you think the parable is saying, as <br>
well as my comments below. <br>
<p>
The important things I draw from it are<br>
<p>
1)  The Great Lifeguard doesn't break the law of gravity when he takes<br>
someone to the top of the cliff.  Instead, at the top of the cliff the<br>
law of gravity works to your advantage.<br>
<p>
2)  The Great Lifeguard has something we don't, a direct lifeline to the <br>
top, yet he seeks to give the use of this lifeline to anyone who wants it.<br>
<p>
3)  When talking of being saved, it's important to remember what we are<br>
being saved from and why we need to be saved from it.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
