<title>May_1992: Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?</h1>
Rhonda Gaines (<i>rrg@fibercom.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 29 May 1992 09:09:50 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#100">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#100">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#100">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#100">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0101.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Saved or Not Saved"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Steven Timm: "Life's A Beach"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0051.html">Lola: "Sabbath or sabbaths?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i> &gt;From the keyboard of "Edward W. Fargusson" &lt;uunet!compuserve.com!72450.2430&gt;:</i><br>
<i>&gt;I believe the use of "High Sabbath" refers to when a ceremonial sabbath falls </i><br>
<i>&gt;on the seventh-day sabbath. Whenever two sabbaths fell on the same day it was </i><br>
<i>&gt;referred to as a "High Sabbath." This might refer to the beginning of the </i><br>
<i>&gt;feast of unleavened bread falling on the seventh-day sabbath.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Ed Fargusson @ Compuserve: 72450,2430</i><br>
<p>
But then you negate the OT prophecy that the messiah would be cut<br>
off in the the midst of the week and the NT prophecy that the<br>
messiah would be in the heart of the earth 3 days and 3 nights.  <br>
In our denomination (gee I hate to use that<br>
word...it's not about denomination, but salvation) we refer to what<br>
you're calling a "High Sabbath" as a "Double Sabbath".  I'll post what I<br>
consider a high sabbath after I've had a chance to get some<br>
scriptures together.  For now, here's how I *firmly* believe the<br>
crucifixion is timed.  <br>
<p>
1.  Wednesday - Jesus crucified on passover (Body removed from<br>
    the cross and buried before sundown so it would not be hanging<br>
    on the cross on the high sabbath (beginning of the feast of unleaven <br>
    bread)<br>
2.  Thursday - High sabbath (feast of unleaven bread)<br>
3.  Friday - preparation day for the 7th day sabbath<br>
4.  Saturday - 7th day sabbath<br>
<p>
Therefore Jesus was in the grave 3 days and 3 nights (Wednesday,<br>
Thursday, and Friday nights; Thursday, Friday, and Saturday days)<br>
with him being risen at the end of the 7th day Sabbath.<br>
<p>
My conclusion is that if these prophecies were not fulfilled then<br>
Jesus could not have been the messiah.  But since the prophecies<br>
were fulfilled then he is the messiah, not that there is any<br>
question in this forum over that.<br>
<p>
Please try to disprove this theory with scriptural reference.  I<br>
appreciate the opportunity to be challenged to force me to dig<br>
deeper into the scriptures.  I do not say this in an argumentative<br>
sense nor do I take my beliefs lightly, but from my studies this is <br>
what I have found to be true and if I am in error I want to know the <br>
truth.<br>
<p>
 -rhonda<br>
<p>
