Hi All,<br>
<p>
<p>
Gene writes :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;First, does God ever give us an imperfect gift!?  And if we agree that</i><br>
<i>&gt;salvation is a gift (Eph. 2:8, 9), then what would be lacking or</i><br>
<i>&gt;incomplete about it?  Would it not be salvation to the uttermost, for</i><br>
<i>&gt;all eternity?</i><br>
<p>
I agree with this, but God does not always give us everything at once<br>
sometimes He gradually imparts things to us as we are able to bear them.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;  [....]</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;But we must never think that it is our works that earn us the</i><br>
<i>&gt;salvation.  The salvation is a gift, given freely by God because of</i><br>
<i>&gt;His grace and not our own merit.  Our works are part of the discipline</i><br>
<i>&gt;(in the instructional sense of that word) that we take on as God works</i><br>
<i>&gt;in our lives to conform us to the image of His Son (Rom. 8:29).</i><br>
<p>
Of cause not there is nothing we can do to of ourselves redeem ourselves <br>
from our lost condition. Christ is the only one who can redeem us.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; [.,...]</i><br>
<i>&gt;Hope this helps to better explain my own understanding of salvation</i><br>
<i>&gt;and works.  And before someone asks, yes, I do believe that a person</i><br>
<i>&gt;who is saved is saved for eternity.</i><br>
<p>
Yep it does. However it raises one question. If when one is saved <br>
he/she is saved for eternity, then what happens when one falls from grace ?<br>
Being saved for eternity means never falling from grace. Do you believe<br>
one can never fall from grace ? There are examples in the scriptures<br>
where people did fall from grace.<br>
<p>
If as you say one is saved for eternity then all of his guilt has also been<br>
dealt with for eternity. But the scriptures say that even though our sins are<br>
forgiven they are not blotted out from the records in heaven untill the last <br>
day. How do you understand this ? How do you understand our salvation from <br>
the presence of sin and mortality ? Or are these things not actually<br>
part of "salvation" as such but need to be referred to by different vernacular ?<br>
<p>
Do you see savlation as something which we are completely awarded but not <br>
actually handed over in its entireity all at once ?<br>
<p>
Let me see, I think this is how I can best sum up my present understanding<br>
of what I mean by salvation, tell me if you agree.<br>
<p>
I don't think salvation is something that one gets all at once, however<br>
one is awarded and guaranteed complete and perfect salvation at conversion<br>
but that salvation is not completely fullfilled at the time of conversion.<br>
Part of it is, salvation from guilt and past sin and salvation from present<br>
sin (if the person wishes). The remaining part of salvation is progressively<br>
imparted to the person as it is required and the person is able to bear it,<br>
such as salvation from mortality. Yes he was awared the salvation from mortality<br>
at conversion but he does not actually receive this until the last day.<br>
So I see it as a path, while one is on the path the end result is guaranteed<br>
if one leaves the path, the final reward is forfitted. (note: I am not refering<br>
here to works or sanctification or anything like that even though it could<br>
be applied to the analogy). <br>
<p>
It becomes a bit like an interlocutory judgement (in legalease). Full rights<br>
to complete and perfect salvation is awarded to you now, it becomes yours. <br>
However you do not appropriate all of it at all at once, but it is apropriated<br>
at the specified time (for example immortality at 2nd coming).<br>
<p>
How does that sound ? any comments ?<br>
<p>
Regards,<br>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
