<title>May_1992: Pathfinders:  An Investment in Pride?</title>
<h1>Pathfinders:  An Investment in Pride?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 29 May 1992 10:47:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#103">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#103">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#103">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#103">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0104.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Jesus' Spirit after His death..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0102.html">Steven Timm: "Utilizing or Wishing"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0114.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Pathfinders:  An Investment in Pride?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I know the title sounds cynical.  Let me assure you before you read farther<br>
that I believe the Pathfinder clubs, our church's group for boys and<br>
girls ages 10-15 is a wonderful program that does a world of good for<br>
the kids.  I have been a Pathfinder and Pathfinder leader myself. <br>
Though I will describe an abuse of the system below, I personally told<br>
this leader that she was doing a great job.<br>
<p>
Over the past weekend I visited the small country church that is the<br>
home church of my parents and was my home church for five years.  On<br>
this particular Sabbath the Pathfinders had just returned from the<br>
Pathfinder fair.  The club from our church had been awarded the First<br>
Prize overall at the fair.  The fact that we have a club of fifteen<br>
Pathfinders in this town at all is amazing.  More amazing is that they<br>
are so well-organized and <br>
disciplined.  They showed a large panel of the various ribbons they had won,<br>
most of them first prizes.  Several pictures were snapped, various<br>
medals were awarded to some of the Pathfinders, and the Pathfinder<br>
leader spent several minutes telling us how proud we should be of our<br>
Pathfinders.<br>
<p>
Now, as long as parents are going to be proud of something, we can be glad<br>
that they have a good Pathfinder club to be proud of.  But I can't help<br>
but wonder if the desire to feed parental ego is one of the reasons the<br>
Pathfinder program has lasted these 50 years now.  Some parents stake so<br>
much of their own well-being in their kids that it can be emotionally<br>
damaging<br>
to both parent and child.  Perhaps if parents didn't feel the need to<br>
store so much pride in their kids, we wouldn't have so many emotionally<br>
damaged kids who are the ones that need the Pathfinder program the most.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
