<title>May_1992: Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?  (Wed Crucifixion)</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?  (Wed Crucifixion)</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 29 May 92 06:46:21 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#106">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#106">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#106">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#106">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0107.html">Joanne_Figueiredo@vos.stratus.com: "Appearances"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0105.html">Dave Buxton: "Dear Net Friends"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Steve, I would appreciate hearing the arguments against a Wednesday</i><br>
<i>&gt; crucifixion.  I have none and would like to be enlightened on the</i><br>
<i>&gt; SDA view of this.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;  -rhonda</i><br>
<p>
We have a couple of people in our church, one couple are Seventh-Day-Church<br>
of God, who subscribe to the Wednesday theory.  The S-D-C-G members<br>
find their own church too far away for regular attendance and so attend<br>
our church.<br>
<p>
Their main point of argument seems to be that when the Bible says a day<br>
it means a day and that day is 24 hours long.  And so they have Jesus<br>
dying Wednesday afternoon and rising Sabbath afternoon, precisely<br>
72 hours later.  They offer texts from the story of Jonah to try and<br>
prove their 72 hour theory.  The main answer to their 72 hour theory<br>
is the Jewish system that says any part of a day is a day.  So, do we<br>
take the Bible literaly in todays modern terms or do we try to understand<br>
the times and culture?<br>
<p>
I have a "Harmony of the Gospels" compiled by a Baptist theology<br>
professor in which he offers a foot note that argues from the Greek and<br>
Jewish culture that Jesus really arose very soon after sundown at the<br>
end of the Sabbath on the 1st day of the week.  In other words, early<br>
on the 1st day was early after sundown after the Sabbath ended.  Today<br>
we are in the habit of thinking of early the 1st day being early in<br>
the wee hours of the day.  At sunrise +/- a few hours.  It is clear<br>
as the King James reads it that Jesus was alive before the sun came<br>
up.  But you have to understand Jewish reconing and the Greek to see<br>
that He could have been alive quite soon after sundown, which would<br>
be Saturday night in todays vernacular.  The women were constrained<br>
in what they could do with His body during the Sabbath hours.  Right<br>
after sundown they would be free to light up their lamps and rush to<br>
the tomb, to find the tomb already empty.<br>
<p>
If you accept Jewish reconing, which I have confirmed with modern<br>
Jewish friends, then Friday afternoon was the 1st day, the Sabbath<br>
the 2nd day and the early hours of Sunday the 3'd day.  And even if<br>
that totaled, lets say, 26 hours = 1 + 24 + 1 hours, then that<br>
would still be three days of Jewish reconing.<br>
<p>
True, I have over simplified the whole question from their point of<br>
view.  But I think I've covered the may objection.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
