<title>May_1992: Appearances</title>
<h1>Appearances</h1>
<i>Joanne_Figueiredo@vos.stratus.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 29 May 92 11:02 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#107">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#107">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#107">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#107">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0108.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: High Sabbaths"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0106.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?  (Wed Crucifixion)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I've never written before so before I start I'd like to introduce<br>
myself. My name is Joanne Figueiredo and I'm a senior Education/Psychology<br>
major at Atlantic Union College in Massachusetts. I'm working full time<br>
this summer at Stratus Computer in MA. I've really enjoyed reading all<br>
the messages sent in to this net. <br>
<p>
Cheryl says:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; .......................................... There is not predisposition</i><br>
<i>&gt;genetically to be a nontither.  I have been a member of the an SDA church</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the past where the head elder regularly took his family skiing on</i><br>
<i>&gt;Sabbath, other elders drank alcohol socially, and the wives wore furs and</i><br>
<i>&gt;gaudy jewelry to church.  These items are more appropriate measures of</i><br>
<i>&gt;"conformity to church standards" than obestiy.  However, whenever we start</i><br>
<i>&gt;judging others based on outward appearances, we are not following God's way.</i><br>
<p>
I'm not sure what tithing has to do with the other things mentioned, but<br>
on the subject of judging others based on outward appearances, I totally<br>
agree. This subject has been one that I recently discussed with some close<br>
friends and I couldn't believe their thoughts on it. One of these friends<br>
is a "pastor's kid" and she is in total agreement that leaders of our church<br>
should be an example, therefore doing all the things like paying tithe, not<br>
going to movies, etc. And I disagree in a way. I think our leaders should be<br>
a good example but, if they are doing these things only to hold an example,<br>
but deep down they don't feel like they should, then they are not being <br>
honest. For example, I know a pastor who does not object to going and seeing<br>
a movie and because he was honest enough to say that, he was kept from a<br>
higher position (there were other factors as well). Now, I respect him <br>
because he wasn't going to hide the fact, in other words, he wasn't going<br>
to be two-faced. I am finding so much of this in the church (although, I'm<br>
sure other churches have similar problems so I'm not in any way turned off<br>
from the church). <br>
<p>
I guess what I'm trying to say is that I'm tired of people judging other<br>
people based on outward appearances. The example that Cheryl gave:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I doubt the disciple known as Simon, later called Peter, would have been</i><br>
<i>&gt;given an SDA church office. Yet Jesus called him personally and through</i><br>
<i>&gt;his association with Christ became a powerful church leader. </i><br>
<p>
I think this is an excellent example. Yes, leaders should be true followers<br>
of God, but how many humans do you know are perfect?? I think we have to<br>
stop putting so much stock behind maintaining appearances, and start looking<br>
within. If pastors (leaders) have problems, hey, thats o.k., they are human,<br>
but no one should go around, including them, acting as if everything is<br>
perfect. Now, we could start off on what sort of things should be allowed, <br>
and what shouldn't but I've found that when it comes right down to it, we<br>
all have different opinions, and thats o.k. But lets at least try to be more<br>
honest with ourselves. I want to end with one more example:<br>
<p>
This past weekend, as I mentioned before, I was with a few close friends. We<br>
had decided to spend the weekend together since her parents were out of<br>
town. We got together Friday night and had decided that on Sabbath we would<br>
go for a picnic at a state park. Now, we could have prepared everything before<br>
Friday night, but we didn't. So we went to the store on Friday night. Now,<br>
I had a problem with it in the sense that I felt uncomfortable breaking the<br>
sabbath that I believe in. My friend felt uncomfortable because she was afraid<br>
we would run into someone we knew and that would just be awful for her. So,<br>
what really is more important?? I didn't say anything to her about it because<br>
I knew she would make some excuse for it.<br>
<p>
Besides wanting more honesty, I'm also wanting consistency. I know I'm not<br>
always like that, but I can admit it and in times of uncertainty, I go to<br>
the Bible for answers or to people who I respect who have these qualities.  <br>
I think thats all we can do. But lets always remember that God loves <br>
EVERYONE and we cannot take his place in judging others. <br>
<p>
Thanks for listening!! Have a happy Sabbath!!<br>
     ~Joanne<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
