</DOCHDR>
<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Fri, 29 May 92 11:26 PDT" -->
<!-- name="Russell Grau" -->
<!-- email="reg@ctsx.celtech.com" -->
<!-- subject="good bye" -->
<!-- id="m0lrBf4-0000laC@ctsx.celtech.com" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>May_1992: good bye</title>
<h1>good bye</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctsx.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 29 May 92 11:26 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#110">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#110">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#110">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#110">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0111.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Sabbath or sabbaths?  (Wed Crucifixion)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0109.html">Christine: "good bye"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;Glen posted:</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;"This is an interesting issue.  Most of us would agree that there has</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;to be some discrimination for church office, but how do you decide?</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;For example, I think a person who is grossly overweight (temperance)</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;but pays tithe is no more qualified for church office than someone of</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;normal weight who doesn't pay tithe.  However, if the church started</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;REALLY enforcing this kind of rule, there would be an uproar.</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;"</i><br>
<p>
Cheryl replied:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Glen is assuming that obesity is caused by intemperance.  This is not</i><br>
<i>&gt;necessarily the case.  In fact, science is discovering that the genetic</i><br>
<i>&gt;predisposition to obesity is very real and that many people struggle all</i><br>
<i>&gt;their life with an image that they grossly indulge when this is not the</i><br>
<i>&gt;case.  For many, obesity is something they struggle with all their life</i><br>
<i>&gt;and there seems to be very little they can do about it.  Tithing on the</i><br>
<i>&gt;other hand is just a choice and commitment.  There is not predisposition</i><br>
<i>&gt;genetically to be a nontither.  I have been a member of the an SDA church</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the past where the head elder regularly took his family skiing on</i><br>
<i>&gt;Sabbath, other elders drank alcohol socially, and the wives wore furs and</i><br>
<i>&gt;gaudy jewelry to church.  These items are more appropriate measures of</i><br>
<i>&gt;"conformity to church standards" than obestiy.  However, whenever we start</i><br>
<i>&gt;judging others based on outward appearances, we are not following God's</i><br>
<i>&gt;way.  I think the SDA church organization which has members of the local</i><br>
<i>&gt;church selecting individuals for church office will encourage the use of</i><br>
<i>&gt;outward appearance and behavior patterns in the selection process.  The</i><br>
<i>&gt;LDS church, on the other hand, offers "calls" for all church positions</i><br>
<i>&gt;based on the decision of the bishopric (lay leaders) of the ward.  </i><br>
              ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
<p>
Sounds somewhat similar to a type of "nominating committee".  That is what<br>
our nominating committees are supposed to do.  At the church that I am now<br>
attending, forms were passed out for every member of the church to list <br>
their preferences/"callings" for specific positions within the church.  The<br>
nominating committee took these as suggestions for service and then prayerfully<br>
selected individuals to fill the posts.  Each of the posts was filled AFTER<br>
the person selected had been given an opportunity to accept or refuse the<br>
call.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Sometimes</i><br>
<i>&gt;individuals are given an assignment, not because they are "worthy" but</i><br>
<i>&gt;rather to give them an opportunity for spiritual and personal growth.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;For example, I doubt the disciple known as Simon, later called Peter, would</i><br>
<i>&gt;have been given an SDA church office.  Yet Jesus called him personally and</i><br>
<i>&gt;through his association with Christ became a powerful church leader.</i><br>
<p>
What is your reasoning here?  It is a moot point in any case.  We can <br>
speculate all that we want about what MIGHT have been our COULD have<br>
been.  We just won't KNOW what WOULD have BEEN had this had opportunity.<br>
To make such a blanket statement is also rather uncharitable.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Another issue in the nomination of church officers in the SDA church is</i><br>
<i>&gt;that many times the nominating committee cannot find anyone "willing" to</i><br>
<i>&gt;accept an appointment.  For example, the SDA church in Salt Lake City has</i><br>
<i>&gt;always had trouble finding anyone willing to lead the Earliteen &amp; Junior</i><br>
<i>&gt;divisions.  We also had several Sabbaths that the cradle roll and kindergarten</i><br>
<i>&gt;teachers just didn't show.  I don't know how prevalent these kinds of</i><br>
<i>&gt;problems are across the US, but how does the local church deal with these?</i><br>
<p>
As with any office that is left open, it becomes the responsibility of the <br>
local church to fill it.  When you have people who may be unprepared to accept<br>
the responsability of a position, forcing someone to take it is wrong.  Usually,<br>
a person will step forward who may have had some interest and will work into<br>
the position until a more suitable replacement can be found.<br>
<p>
As far as a person not showing up for the class or program.  It depends.  At <br>
a small church I used to attend, we had to deal with this as an ongoing <br>
problem.  Not that the teachers were negligent, but that with only a single<br>
person for some classes, it made it difficult to work with when the person was<br>
out of town or sick.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Cheryl Berthelsen</i><br>
<i>&gt;cberthel@cc.utah.edu</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
It does seem that people are making too much of the tithe issue and the <br>
nominating committee.  I served on two nominating committees during recent <br>
years.  The only question that was asked by the committee of the treasurer<br>
was if the person appeared to be faithful in their tithes and offerrings.<br>
<p>
This was settled with a simple yes or no.  There was no question to the<br>
amount of the tithe or offerrings.  It was just to ensure that the <br>
individual had some level of commitment to the church that they were being<br>
asked to serve.<br>
<p>
