<title>May_1992: Love is...</title>
<h1>Love is...</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 29 May 92 18:42:38 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#113">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#113">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#113">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#113">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Pathfinders:  An Investment in Pride?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Wil Clarke: "Re: good bye"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
And so I ask, what really is love [agape].  What texts can you offer<br>
to illuminate this question?   Or must we consult the overall fabric<br>
of the Bible record from cover to cover?<br>
<p>
Thanks,<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
-------<br>
<p>
Hi Dave,<br>
<p>
Very good questions.  May I answer the second one first?<br>
<p>
A2:  Yes, we must.  "On these two commandments [to love God and to<br>
love our neighbor] the whole law hangeth, and the prophets."  Mt22:40.<br>
If you want to understand the depths of God's love for his elect, and<br>
if you want to understand how to express your love to your God and to <br>
your neighbor, you must look to the whole of God's revelation.<br>
<p>
<p>
A1:  Having said that, I will offer a succinct answer to your first<br>
question.  It is found in Luke 10:25-37.  But he [a lawyer],<br>
desiring to justify himself, said unto Jesus, And who is my<br>
neighbor?  [Insert story of the good Samaritan.]  Bottom line:<br>
Which of these three, thinkest thou, proved neighbor unto him that<br>
fell among the robbers?  And he said, He that showed mercy on him.<br>
And Jesus said unto him, Go, and do thou likewise.<br>
<p>
There are, of course, many more biblical examples of what is love.<br>
Your question seemed to focus upon love among the brethren.<br>
<p>
God bless,<br>
Dan Blake<br>
dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
