<title>May_1992: Sabbath.</title>
<h1>Sabbath.</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 29 May 92 20:48:40 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#116">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#116">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#116">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#116">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0117.html">Steven Timm: "VIEW:  New magazine for SDA's 20 to 30"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0115.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Pathfinders"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Interestingly, the word translated as "day of preparation" in the stories<br>
of Christ's crucifixion means much more.  Paraskeue is the name for <br>
Friday.  This name was common among Jews and early Christians.  Friday<br>
was the "Day of Preparation" just as Sabbath was the "Day of Rest"--which<br>
is the meaning in Hebrew.<br>
<p>
As one reads the story in Mark 15:42-16:2 and in Luke 23:54-24:1, there is <br>
no possibility of reading Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Sabbath into the <br>
outline of days provided.  The whole context is important.<br>
<p>
Nancy V<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0117.html">Steven Timm: "VIEW:  New magazine for SDA's 20 to 30"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0115.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Pathfinders"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
