<title>May_1992: VIEW:  New magazine for SDA's 20 to 30</title>
<h1>VIEW:  New magazine for SDA's 20 to 30</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 30 May 1992 20:14:39 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#117">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#117">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#117">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#117">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pathfinders"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Sabbath."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have been asked to serve as part of a focus group to review the new <br>
magazine "View" which has just published a limited-distribution trial <br>
issue.  Their target audience is SDA's in their 20's no matter the<br>
background.  (This is a remarkable response seeing I just made a call<br>
for something for this group two days ago on SDAnet, but I digress.)<br>
<p>
The magazine is published by the Church ministries department of North<br>
American Division, edited by Celeste Ryan.  The first issue included a <br>
summary of the meeting of Folkenberg's Youth Cabinet, a list of resources,<br>
an article about AIDS, an interview with A.C. McClure, and an article<br>
by Patti Nash of Columbia Union College entitled "Why I Stay."<br>
<p>
This magazine is a large 8-page in broadside format, printed on hi-grade<br>
newsprint.  It uses 2-color technology.  The format is appealing, the<br>
articles are interesting, and I think this magazine may well enjoy a<br>
bright future.  I will give a favorable report to the focus group.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
