<title>May_1992: Re: Pathfinders</title>
<h1>Re: Pathfinders</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 30 May 1992 20:25:20 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#118">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#118">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#118">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#118">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0119.html">McCluskey G: "Re: pride and EGW"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0117.html">Steven Timm: "VIEW:  New magazine for SDA's 20 to 30"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0103.html">Steven Timm: "Pathfinders:  An Investment in Pride?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nancy Vyhmeister writes<br>
<i>&gt;Steve, you speak as one who has not yet experienced the legitimate pride of</i><br>
<i>&gt;parenthood!  </i><br>
<i>&gt;On the other side of the coin, there is the fantastic self-esteem that is</i><br>
<i>&gt;built into kinds who "can" and "do."  </i><br>
<p>
After an extensive search of my Bible and the writings of Ellen White,<br>
I fail to find record of any pride that is legitimate or any self-esteem<br>
that is fantastic.  (With the exception of boasting in the cross of Christ.)<br>
They are both sins by definition as far as I can tell.  I will be glad to <br>
consider any inspired quotes to the contrary.  Furthermore, people like<br>
Dr. Dobson try to tell us that self-esteem is good, but the scientific<br>
data just isn't there.  The California self-esteem study failed to find<br>
any correlation between level of self-esteem and success in life, and<br>
this was one of the most exhaustive studies that has ever been done.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Perhaps the worship service is not the best place to show off, but when our</i><br>
<i>&gt;kids are doing anything right and good, they need to hear about it.</i><br>
<p>
I agree that our kids need to hear that they have done a good job, but<br>
this is totally separate from self-esteem in any way (at least as I<br>
define it and <br>
as the dictionary defines it--"pride in oneself.")  Usually when I have<br>
this argument with people I find they are defining self-esteem in a<br>
different way which I would be more likely to call self-worth or<br>
self-concept (both of which are essential for emotionally healthy<br>
children and which I promote.)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
