<title>Jun_1993: Adventism Today</title>
<h1>Adventism Today</h1>
<i>Beng.Tang@f622.n600.z6.fidonet.org</i><br>
<i>02 Jun 1993 23:00:46 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#21">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#21">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#21">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#21">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re: Cognitive Dissonance"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Basis for discussion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dear Steve,<br>
     When i downloaded my latest mail packet from the BBS and read it, i was<br>
at first quite shocked and horrified at some of the things written therein<br>
(about homosexuality especially), because they seem to express views so<br>
different from what i would expect from SDAs. I was really quite aghast at it<br>
all, and i still am. But after i went over it again a couple of times i felt<br>
it so funny that i couldn't help laughing out loud, because of this:<br>
<p>
     I've been on SDAnet since November last year, when i first got in, i<br>
almost got in trouble with the trustees of the E G White Estate for offering<br>
to give out copies of Steps to Christ and other inspiring inspired writings,<br>
like autumn leaves, then someone called Admir was having a hard time from<br>
church elders for chewing gum in church and so we discussed that for a while,<br>
and since then we've had many hot discussions on everything from whether the<br>
NIV is of the antichrist to baptism and euthanasia; and while these are real<br>
issues, sometimes when i look back at us SDAnetters discussing them until we<br>
get all worked up over bizarre things and it looks laughable.<br>
<p>
     Also, i have acquired impressions about the characters and views of<br>
various regular SDAnetters, although i have never met them in person. As<br>
such, many of their responses and reactions have become predictable. I mean,<br>
if you throw up a question about, say prostitution or ecumenism, you can<br>
almost guess who will say what. Well, i tried to imagine all the various<br>
SDAnetters in the same congregation, and it looked like a most unlikely crowd<br>
indeed that was what made me laugh. What i am getting to is this: The<br>
Seventh-day Adventist Church today is not at all as homogeneous or united as<br>
i used to think it was. There is actually a very large variance of thought<br>
and practice within it. Now, the church should have variety and differences,<br>
just as the body has different organs for different functions, but they all<br>
need to work together and have certain basic things in common, a mutual goal<br>
and mission, certain shared a-priori principles to work by. The speaker at<br>
one of our youth praise and worship meetings last year, Del Johnson, gave a<br>
vivid illustration, which i think says it well: Our theme was unity in<br>
diversity, in the body of Christ, and he gave a presentation on that. He<br>
concocted an ice-cream dish on stage, getting a volunteer from the audience<br>
to help him add all the ingredients, various flavours of ice cream, nuts,<br>
chocolate syrup etc, until it (supposedly) looked really delicious with all<br>
the varieties of stuff on it, then he asked the volunteer if he'd like to eat<br>
it, and of course he responded in the affirmative. He then got a can of<br>
engine oil and poured it in, and asked the same question, which was now<br>
answered "no".<br>
<p>
     I think we as a church, really need to get our act together and decide<br>
what we believe etc. Please pray for the church. Most of all, we all need the<br>
love of God.<br>
<p>
     One of the great divides in the SDA church seems to be between the<br>
"liberals" and "conservatives". Though there are the extremists at both ends<br>
which are really far out, i think the vast majority  of these people actually<br>
agree with each other, it is just that their emphasis is different.<br>
     The conservatives see the influence of the world infiltrating the<br>
church, they see church standards and even basic bible doctrines being eroded<br>
and being treated with less and less importance. They therefore place great<br>
emphasis on behaviour and good works, church standards and correct doctrine,<br>
and calling sin by its right name. They believe in salvation by grace through<br>
faith, but are afraid to stress it lest it open the floodgates of iniquity.<br>
They fear that if people think that we are not saved by good works, they will<br>
become lawless and decadent.<br>
     The liberals, in part at least, are reacting to what they perceive as<br>
the teaching of salvation by works, from the conservatives. They stress the<br>
love and grace of God, and the freeness of the gift of salvation, that it is<br>
not at all by works, lest any man boast. While they do not emphasize the<br>
importance of church standards or correct behaviour, because they fear that<br>
that will give people the impression that we are saved by works, they do<br>
agree with it and support it.<br>
     Perhaps that is over-simplifying it but i think that's roughly how it<br>
is. I personally agree with both of these groups, but i feel that we need to<br>
get a balanced picture of what we believe, so that we don't confuse people.<br>
It is *not* however, a question of doing a "balancing act" or walking in the<br>
"middle of the road" or of "compromise" because there is nothing to<br>
compromise. Both of these viewpoints, though presented in a one-sided way,<br>
are equally valid and necessary. They are two sides of the same coin, or<br>
better, they are the two metals that make up the alloy of the coin. They are<br>
part and parcel of the same system of practical Christian truth. When viewed<br>
with the correct perspective, from the bible with the Holy Spirit as<br>
interpreter, there is no conflict at all, between free salvation by grace<br>
alone, and the importance of good works. It all makes perfect sense.<br>
<p>
     One thing i have realised is that we should never take for granted that<br>
even our fellow church members have the same understanding of Adventist truth<br>
that we do. Many SDAs, even some who have been in the church for years, do<br>
not have a clear understanding of even the very basics of Christian doctrine.<br>
In this year's youth commission survey for the Far Eastern Division, it was<br>
found that 88% of baptised, SDA youth in the FED answered "yes" to the<br>
question "in order for God to accept me, i must live a good life" while 64%<br>
said that the Adventist faith is a legalistic religion, and only 59% said<br>
that they knew that if Jesus were to return now, they would be saved. Now,<br>
what does this show about what these people have been taught to believe?<br>
Almost half of them have no assurance of salvation, and seem to believe in<br>
salvation by works!!!<br>
<p>
     Speaking about adventist behaviour, i have a friend who used to attend<br>
church, but left because she felt that she didn't measure up to being a<br>
Christian and somehow God could not accept her. Anyway, she went to the US<br>
recently for a holiday, and she tells me that she went to Las Vegas to see<br>
what all the hype about it was, with a friend who is a regular church-going<br>
SDA, and she found the city eerie and weird, because it seemed to her to run<br>
on gambling and sleeze and not much else, and she didn't like it there. But<br>
this is what perturbed me, her SDA friend who brought her there, went there<br>
to gamble! And she said that that puzzled her, because she used to believe<br>
that Christian people don't do certain things, and gambling was one of them.<br>
Well, i can't say that i'm surprised about it now, but i still wish that that<br>
SDA hadn't done that, because it has helped confuse my friend even more. Why<br>
am i writing about all this? I don't know, but i just want to say that we<br>
should always be conscious that people are looking to us and watching us,<br>
because they expect Christians to be Christlike, and by our behaviour we can<br>
sometimes be a stumbling block to others. I am not saying we should put up an<br>
act and pretend to be holy or something, but.... i don't know. I am just in<br>
a sort of identity crisis about the church i belong to -- the SDA church. I<br>
don't like to speak discouragement, but frankly, some of the things in the<br>
SDA church make me sick. God says it makes Him sick too:<br>
<p>
"So then because thou art lukewarm, and neither cold nor hot, I will spue<br>
thee out of my mouth." Rev 3:16<br>
<p>
The message continues:<br>
<p>
"17 Because thou sayest, I am rich, and increased with goods, and have need<br>
of nothing; and knowest not that thou art wretched, and miserable, and poor,<br>
and blind, and naked: 18 I counsel thee to buy of me gold tried in the fire,<br>
that thou mayest be rich; and white raiment, that thou mayest be clothed, and<br>
that the shame of thy nakedness do not appear; and anoint thine eyes with<br>
eyesalve, that thou mayest see. 19 As many as I love, I rebuke and chasten:<br>
be zealous therefore, and repent. 20 Behold, I stand at the door, and knock:<br>
if any man hear my voice, and open the door, I will come in to him, and will<br>
sup with him, and he with me. 21 To him that overcometh will I grant to sit<br>
with me in my throne, even as I also overcame, and am set down with my Father<br>
in his throne. 22 He that hath an ear, let him hear what the Spirit saith<br>
unto the churches."<br>
<p>
I am not in a position to speak like this; when i look at my own life, i see<br>
it full of sin and selfishness, and i am as much to blame as anybody else,<br>
for the condition of things, but i just wish that the church as a whole would<br>
"wake up its idea" and be more "on the ball", to borrow phrases they use in<br>
the Army here. If we don't get our act together, how do we expect to be able<br>
to reach people like those "atheists" in your post?<br>
<p>
About those atheists, most of their questions sound reasonable and valid, and<br>
i think i would ask them myself, if i were in their shoes, with very little<br>
knowledge of the truth. Some of them seem to be the result of the erroneous<br>
teachings of the babel of religious confusion, like the question about<br>
eternal torment in hell; and others seem to stem from a confused idea about<br>
salvation and justice, which disappears when one understands better the<br>
issues of the great controversy between Christ and Satan, and the nature of<br>
the sin problem and how we gain salvation. If those questions are all that's<br>
keeping them from becoming believers, i suggest we pray for them, and tell<br>
them the truth just as it is in Jesus. If they are honest in their search for<br>
truth, the Holy Spirit will be able to convict them of the truth. Truth can<br>
stand for itself, all we have to do is tell it to them. The gospel is so<br>
simple even a child can understand it. If they are willing to know the truth,<br>
they shall know it, and the truth will set them free, then they shall be free<br>
thinkers indeed.<br>
<p>
About the homosexual discussion, i needn't have started it in the first<br>
place. What happened was that the gay pastor who convinced my friend that it<br>
is right to be gay, according to the bible, sent him a sheaf of literature<br>
about it, and it said that the bible doesn't mention female homosexuality, so<br>
i searched for it in the concordance and couldn't find anything. That's why<br>
i sent a post out asking for scriptural support. When i read the rest of the<br>
articles however, i found that i needn't have bothered. The gay pastor had<br>
listed out conveniently, all the texts in the bible that have to do with<br>
homosexuality, so that he could explain them away, and the text i was looking<br>
for was there.<br>
<p>
-Beng Tang<br>
<p>
... email:    Beng.Tang@f622.n600.z6.fidonet.org<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
