<title>Jun_1993: Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost</title>
<h1>Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost</h1>
Dan Drazen (<i>drazen@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 1 Jun 1993 09:09:40 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#3">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#3">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#3">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#3">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: Cognitive Dissonance"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Tony Dyson: "Re: net.athiests"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 Steve:<br>
 As someone who was an Episcopalean before converting to Seventh-day<br>
 Adventism in my teen years, let me put my two cents in:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 1)  There's precious little difference between Episcopals and Catholics.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Still enough to make the Catholics call the Episcopals damnable heretics, </i><br>
<i>&gt; (Episcopals break the wafer of bread as they consecrate it) but not much </i><br>
<i>&gt; else.  I believe the word "Protestant" was struck from the title </i><br>
<i>&gt; "Protestant Episcopal" some time ago.  (check me on this?)</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
True enough; both are what are called "high churches" due to their<br>
liturgical style.  The differences between them, however, are a touch<br>
more serious.<br>
<p>
The Episcopal Church started as the Anglican Church, formed by Henry<br>
VIII pretty much because he felt that the sovreign of England should<br>
have more say in church matters than the bishop of Rome.  There have<br>
been attempts to reunite the two parties (Anglicans and Catholics) but<br>
recognizing the primacy of Rome has long been a sticking point.  And now<br>
that the Anglican Church has taken steps toward allowing the ordination<br>
of women (which the Vatican still rabidly opposes) the reconciliation<br>
may be delayed even longer.<br>
<p>
The problem with being an Anglican was that you recognized the<br>
King/Queen of England as head of the church and "Defender of the Faith"<br>
-- a rather untenable position in the year 1776.  The Episcopal Church<br>
was formed as a domestic product: the rites were retained but ties to<br>
the mother church in England were severed.<br>
<p>
(Just a thought: the system whereby the English sovereign becomes the<br>
"Defender of the Faith" is a good argument against the establishment of<br>
religion.  Can you picture Prince Charles having anything serious to say<br>
about religion, especially considering his relationship with Di?)<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; 2)  Both find ways to involve young people as integral parts of the service.</i><br>
<i>&gt; With all the crosses, candles, and whatnot to lug around, several acolytes</i><br>
<i>&gt; and crucifers are needed.  In the Episcopal tradition, acolytes can be girls</i><br>
<i>&gt; as well as boys, and a news item indicated that Catholics are thinking </i><br>
<i>&gt; about allowing this, too.  What would an SDA service look like with two</i><br>
<i>&gt; young people serving communion on either side of the pastor?  Couldn't hurt?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Or is it pagan by definition because the Catholics do it?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
I started in the Episcopal Church when I was about 8, singing in the<br>
choir on Sunday mornings.  It wasn't that I was religious -- I wanted an<br>
excuse to get out of the house in case my Dad woke up hung over.  But<br>
choir members were the low end of the food chain; acolytes let it be<br>
known that they outranked me.  Then again, maybe we just had some rotten<br>
kids as acolytes.  And in the early to mid-Sixties, girls were NOT<br>
allowed to be acolytes -- that was a later development.<br>
<p>
I've come across articles that deal with child participation in<br>
RECEIVING communion ("'Mommy, may I have a sip?'" by Carl Hartman,<br>
_Ministry_, Feb 1992, p. 19, and Letters in reply, _Ministry_, Oct<br>
1992), but this is the first I've heard anyone suggest kids assist in<br>
ADMINISTERING communion.  My guess is that local elders would 86 that<br>
proposal, and not necessarily because it could be considered a "Roman"<br>
practice.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 3)  You never have a first elder stumbling through an impromptu prayer</i><br>
<i>&gt; because the order of prayer is always predetermined.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 4)  On the con side, singing the same liturgy every week would get slightly</i><br>
<i>&gt; boring.  But you do have to be on your toes to follow it all at first.</i><br>
<i>&gt; There's no sitting back and sleeping for 40 minutes, participation is </i><br>
<i>&gt; required every step of the way except during the 10-15 minute sermon.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
You have to take both into consideration: the set liturgy eliminated the<br>
guesswork but it does make for a boring service.  Of course you do have<br>
the "Book of Common Prayer" to guide you through the order of worship.<br>
Trouble is, revising the worship service can cause major ideological<br>
battles (about the use of sexist language and whatnot).  And while the<br>
prayer may not be impromptu, there's no guarantee that the speaker will<br>
be up to the material.  I remember one priest who assisted at a church I<br>
attended, St. Paul's Episcopal back in Illinois.  He was a nice enough<br>
gentleman but his palsied readings could get on your nerves; it was<br>
something of a relief when he retired.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; So how did the SDA form of worship become mostly like the Baptist liturgy?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Baptists weren't prominent in the early SDA church, were they?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Both denominations are so-called "spiritual experience" denominations</i><br>
<i>&gt; which place large emphasis on preaching as opposed to corporate worship</i><br>
<i>&gt; (and expect their ministers to uphold high moral standard).  That's</i><br>
<i>&gt; all I can think.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
I'm no expert on Adventist liturgy (though I always thought they owed<br>
more to Methodism than to the Baptists).  And I'm not very nostalgic<br>
about high church form (although I must confess that I get a kick out<br>
of looking through church supply catalogs at the robes, vestments,<br>
copes, paraments, etc. -- even the names of the articles have a<br>
beautiful, exotic quality).<br>
<p>
Still, no matter how beautiful a form public worship can take, the<br>
danger is that it could slip into empty theatricality -- which is<br>
another way of saying that it assumes a form of godliness without the<br>
power thereof.  Besides, the doctrine of the priesthood of all believers<br>
is a good argument for a clergy that can't be distinguished by fancy<br>
vestments.<br>
<p>
Finally, let me just say that it all comes down to the people.  Father<br>
Duran, back at St. Michael and All Angels Church in Illinois, was simply<br>
a really great guy.  A faulty clergyman, in any denomination, can make<br>
the spiritual life difficult for his people.<br>
<p>
Of course some people in the congregation can be difficult themselves.<br>
I have somewhere in my files a clipping about a parish priest of a<br>
Catholic church in Wisconsin.  He was great at involving kids in the<br>
service, including girls, and the kids loved him for it.  One of the<br>
parishoners who didn't like the idea of girls being involved in public<br>
worship registered his complaint with the priest by killing him with a<br>
handgun.  But that's another topic on the bulletin board.<br>
<p>
Daniel J. Drazen<br>
Editor, SDA Periodical Index<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
