<!-- body="start" -->
---&gt;<br>
<i>&gt; 2) If god is so just, good, and loving, and if god wants to save us so bad, w</i><br>
<i>&gt;    doesn't he show himself to all the people in the world at once? That's </i><br>
<i>&gt;    the sure way to get everybody converted.</i><br>
<p>
Yea this is called Satans impersonation of Christ, and boy won't<br>
the whole world be converted. !<br>
&lt;---<br>
<p>
So why doesn't God get in first? Not that I have an answer, but I think the<br>
original question is a fair one.<br>
<p>
---&gt;<br>
I note that a sizeable proportion of these might be probs to a lot of <br>
evangelicals, but should be pno problem for SDAs.<br>
&lt;---<br>
<p>
Still worth thinking about though! It's amazing how many things a person<br>
can believe without having compelling reasons. Or, from another angle, many<br>
things which may be compelling to one are certainly not to another!<br>
<p>
Take the question "Why are you a Christian/Why do you believe in God?"<br>
<p>
For many of us, the *honest* answer is "Because I was born into a Christian<br>
family and brought up that way". Now I'm not saying that other reasons haven't<br>
come along for any of us. But I've often thought myself that if I was brought<br>
up an agnostic, and went to uni to do the study I've done and am doing, it is<br>
highly unlikely that I would have been converted to Christianity. Unless the<br>
Holy Spirit did a special job on me! <br>
<p>
The secondary answer to the question is "Because as a Christian my belief<br>
system allows me to make sense of the world". This is still not concrete by<br>
any means, because many would say that Christianity made no sense at all!<br>
<p>
There are two ways to answer many of the questions. The honest way and the<br>
evangelistic way. Both have their uses, and its worth thinking about the<br>
questions both ways.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
