<title>Jun_1993: Re: Cognitive Dissonance</title>
<h1>Re: Cognitive Dissonance</h1>
Darius A. Lecointe (<i>dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 1 Jun 1993 13:04:31 -0500 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Dan Drazen: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Or, the grass is always greener over the septic tank</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I don't remember the percentage of people that leave the SDA church over</i><br>
<i>&gt; some conflict with some person, but it is large.  I suspect that even </i><br>
<i>&gt; this figure is underreported, because some of the people who have left</i><br>
<i>&gt; over doctrinal disagreements have come to these disagreements during</i><br>
<i>&gt; conflict with people or organization of the church, which may have had</i><br>
<i>&gt; nothing to do with the doctrine.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
[deleted much about Catholic and LDS conversions]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What does this tell us?  It points out that if the written words of a</i><br>
<i>&gt; doctrine fail to match up to the practice of the doctrine, people notice.</i><br>
<i>&gt; This is a gut-level emotional reaction, which is the opposite of the </i><br>
<i>&gt; initial reaction that comes with conviction of truth.  There can be a </i><br>
<i>&gt; positive side for this, because it is frequently such a reaction that</i><br>
<i>&gt; leads people to search out the SDA church.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Thoughts?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I can speak from a unique perspective.<br>
<p>
We need to stop looking at ourselves as the true church and see outselves<br>
for what we really are: the repository of God's truth for these last days.<br>
 There has become a focus more on what SDA's believe than on what God<br>
teaches.  In a way we have lost our focus.  We are more interested in<br>
membership than in faith.  We are becoming more and more like our natural<br>
counterparts the Jews.<br>
<p>
As I noted in an earlier post, I am a SDA pastor on study leave.  In<br>
October of last year the church I attended forced me off the organ in the<br>
middle of the divine service and stopped me from instructing the Youth<br>
Sabbath class I was leading.  The only reason was because I was opposed to<br>
the pastor's advice to the church to seek legal injunctions to keep a<br>
Davidian college student from the church premises.<br>
<p>
That same month I wrote to the local conference, with copies to the<br>
Union and GC, asking them to look into this adoption of Babylonian behavior.  <br>
To this date I have not received so much as a note of acknowledgement.  Not <br>
only is this unprofessional and rude; if we are too busy balancing budgets<br>
and making policy to be concerned that one of our churches is going astray<br>
then we are really too busy.<br>
<p>
I still believe the message of the SDA church but I refuse to be<br>
held hostage by a church hierarchy which will do whatever it can get away<br>
with to keep our churches filled.  If we have the truth why are we so<br>
scared of dealing with those who violate church policy?  We act quickly<br>
when a young woman gets pregnant but excuse the more dangerous actions of<br>
those who lead.<br>
<p>
I don't ask for an apology from the church.  My salvation is from God. <br>
But a church which is too proud to admit when it has treated one of God's<br>
children does not have any authority discipline God's children. We have<br>
sacrificed our principles at the altar of membership and budgets.  That is<br>
not reflective of the God I serve.<br>
<p>
I never thought I would see the day when an Adventist church would lock<br>
its doors on Sabbath to keep people out, or call police on to the premises<br>
to take people away who were only interested in coming to worship.  If<br>
this is acceptable behavior then God must be dead.  I know He is not for<br>
He has done too much for me.<br>
<p>
I would prefer to fellowship with those who believe as I do.  But a church<br>
which is policed by civil authorities and drags me off their organ at the<br>
same time they pay a member of the local Baptist church to play the piano,<br>
with the explanation that this is a form of soul winning, shows no<br>
interest in my salvation and is not a place I desire to fellowship.  <br>
<p>
Sadly, both churches in town chose to use their own remedies and called<br>
the cops in.  I wonder, if this is how the church relates to one who has<br>
the pastoral gift, how are other members treated.  No wonder they leave. <br>
My only prayer is that soon this will be put right.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Darius Lecointe                        God is the answer to a question.
dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu
dlecoint@freenet.scri.fsu.edu
</pre>
