<title>Jun_1993: Basis for discussion</title>
<h1>Basis for discussion</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>01 Jun 1993 13:51:11 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#1">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#1">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#1">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#1">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Tony Dyson: "Re: net.athiests"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0000.html">Dan Drazen: "Re: Cognitive Dissonance"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
---&gt;<br>
If the audience does not accept the underlying hypotheses,<br>
why should we expect anyone to listen to the arguments?<br>
&lt;---<br>
<p>
Because you don't have to agree with someone to listen to them.<br>
<p>
Listening to a person explain what their hypotheses are, and how<br>
that relates to their opinion on something, can help us understand<br>
where they're coming from. It can show that a person's position<br>
is at least internally consistent, even if it is based on <br>
hypotheses another person may not accept.<br>
<p>
The fact that two parties may never agree does not mean that they<br>
can't listen and relate to one another. It often means they *won't*,<br>
but it doesn't have to. There is a difference between discussion<br>
and debate; I'm sure there is room for both on SDAnet, providing<br>
there is more of "my opinion is only my opinion", and less of "your<br>
opinion is only your opinion"!<br>
<p>
In my opinion, of course...!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
