<i>&gt;  What would an SDA service look like with two</i><br>
<i>&gt; young people serving communion on either side of the pastor?  Couldn't hurt?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Or is it pagan by definition because the Catholics do it?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
<p>
yep.	:^)<br>
<p>
Why don't you ask this question of someone who has "come out" of the<br>
RCC communion ?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 3)  You never have a first elder stumbling through an impromptu prayer</i><br>
<i>&gt; because the order of prayer is always predetermined.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
the words would be too, making it rather formalistic, and dry. Definitively<br>
not the fresh running waters from the fountain of God's spirit.<br>
<p>
Tell me how much space do they make for the Spirit to guide and work ?<br>
Or is the whole thing so manufactured and predetermined 100s of years<br>
in advance that the H.S. is left no space to work nor direct.<br>
Save us from formalism !<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 4)  On the con side, singing the same liturgy every week would get slightly</i><br>
<i>&gt; boring.  But you do have to be on your toes to follow it all at first.</i><br>
<i>&gt; There's no sitting back and sleeping for 40 minutes, participation is </i><br>
<i>&gt; required every step of the way except during the 10-15 minute sermon.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
even participation gets boring when it is ritualistic, and by defn. <br>
meaningless.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; So how did the SDA form of worship become mostly like the Baptist liturgy?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Baptists weren't prominent in the early SDA church, were they?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Both denominations are so-called "spiritual experience" denominations</i><br>
<i>&gt; which place large emphasis on preaching as opposed to corporate worship</i><br>
<i>&gt; (and expect their ministers to uphold high moral standard).  That's</i><br>
<i>&gt; all I can think.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Is the SDA church service today more devoted to conveying information</i><br>
<i>&gt; or to worship of God?  Are these mutually exclusive?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Is the RCC service more devoted to pomp and ritual works on an impersonal<br>
level than to seeking personal edification and conviction of sin through the <br>
direct promptings of God's Spirit ? <br>
<p>
<p>
It is interesting to observe the anti-typical appeal of the worship practices <br>
of the Midianites at Baal-peor for the Israelites. hmm, very interesting !<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
