<title>Jun_1993: Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost</title>
<h1>Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  1 Jun 1993 21:27:04 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Steven Timm: "Sacraments:"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0005.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In Ruben's post he complains that a liturgical service would be too<br>
formal and ritualistic.  While I do agree with this, I remind you that <br>
SDA churches in general are obsessed with ritual.  If you have any doubt<br>
of this, watch the deaconesses argue about the right way to unfold the <br>
communion cloth and fold it again.  In debates about the style of worship,<br>
both sides are adamant that it really matters in what way one worships God.<br>
Even the so-called "Celebration churches" have a very set ritual.  The music<br>
is newer, people may be happier, but it is ritual nevertheless.  The good<br>
ones operate to a TV schedule, even.  And perhaps the ritual, shorn of <br>
most of the trappings, has less intrinsic meaning and symbolism than <br>
the older ones.<br>
<p>
What does the SDA church have today to offer a visual learner, or a<br>
kinesthetic learner?  For years the church service has been something to <br>
hear, and not something to see.  Does this work differently among <br>
SDA churches in illiterate peoples?  (Or are there such:  Do we require<br>
that someone learn to read the Bible before we even baptize him/her?)<br>
<p>
I anticipate that fifty years from now in the nursing home, the pastor<br>
of our "celebration church wanna-be" in Pittsburgh will still be requesting<br>
the same popcorn choruses he is singing now.  "Let's sing that great old<br>
hymn "Majesty"".  And other people in that same church will still be saying<br>
that he never should have taken the wooden railing off the choir loft<br>
and removed the big pulpit, let alone greet others in the sanctuary (GASP!).<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
