<title>Jun_1993: Sacraments:</title>
<h1>Sacraments:</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  1 Jun 1993 21:40:08 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#7">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#7">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#7">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#7">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Ray Mialki: "Re:  Sacrements"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0016.html">Dan Drazen: "Re: Sacraments:"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I want to check my understanding of SDA theology on this one:<br>
<p>
The standard view of liturgical churches is that there are seven<br>
sacraments, which are the means of conveying God's grace to the members<br>
of the church.<br>
These are baptism, confirmation, marriage, confession, ordination, last<br>
rites, (and what's the other one...burial?) (or else communion)<br>
<p>
If I understand the SDA view correctly, we hold that there are no sacraments.<br>
We perform baptism but this is only a sign of the person's previous<br>
commitment to God and does not convey any magical graces to the person.<br>
Ordination is a recognition that God has called a person to the gospel <br>
ministry.  The place or form of a persons burial has no effect on his/her<br>
salvation, it's too late for that.  <br>
<p>
The one I am not sure of is ordination, which involves the laying on of <br>
hands.  This follows the Biblical formula of laying on of hands and praying.<br>
Is it in this act that a special portion of the Holy Spirit is to come <br>
on those who are ordained?  Acts 6 doesn't indicate one way or the other.<br>
<p>
In general I appreciate the idea of a God who is not a trained poodle<br>
and has to jump around with every ringing bell.  But I wonder if I <br>
might be missing something in my understanding of the sacraments.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
