<title>Jun_1993: Re:  Sacrements</title>
<h1>Re:  Sacrements</h1>
Ray Mialki (<i>rm1g+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  1 Jun 1993 21:55:54 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#8">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#8">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#8">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#8">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Steven Timm: "Sacraments:"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A little correction Steve.  Not all liturgical Churches hold to seven<br>
sacrements.  The Catholic Church does.  They are Baptism, Penance, Holy<br>
Eucharist, Confirmation, HOly Matrimony, Holy Orders, and Last Rites.<br>
<p>
Most Protestant Churches hold to only two:  Baptism and the Lord's<br>
Supper.  These are kept because they had been originally instituted by<br>
Christ.  The others, although they have their sacredness, were not<br>
instituted by Christ.<br>
<p>
Matrimony, or marraige, was actually instituted before the Fall.  In the<br>
RP Church, this is what is referred to as a "creation ordinance".  It is<br>
binding on all creation, not just the people of God.  The Sabbath is<br>
another creation ordinance.  <br>
<p>
Ray the kop<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
