<title>Jun_1993: Re: discrimination or morality?</title>
<h1>Re: discrimination or morality?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  1 Jun 1993 22:02:14 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#10">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#10">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#10">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#10">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Drew Corrigan: "Portions of the Spirit (was Re: Sacraments:)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Rick suggests that "homosexual" is one label that can easily be applied.<br>
It is indeed one of the most frequently applied labels in the habit<br>
of people to try to separate "us" from "them."  It is still one of the <br>
most persistent labels in a church and society that has given labels <br>
to many.<br>
<p>
The church tends to view sins that disrupt the traditional family cycle<br>
as the most severe.  Even heterosexual singles are looked upon with suspicion<br>
sometimes.  But divorced people and single parents also know what it is <br>
to be labeled, and sometimes sexually harassed, by members in their church.<br>
The situations of these people draw attention because they are obvious, <br>
and also frequently irreversible.  She who has a child out of wedlock has<br>
the child to follow her around for the rest of her life, as a continual<br>
reminder of the mistake.  <br>
<p>
Some would say that the church ought to pay more attention to these types<br>
of behavior because they are obvious and show flaws in what should be the <br>
loving families of the church.  In some cases, such as 1 Corinthians 5,<br>
there is biblical support for this, but this case involved someone who<br>
would not repent after the best rehabilitative efforts of the church.<br>
If there is not much likelihood that other people will repeat the mistake,<br>
then it does not pose a risk to the community and doesn't need to be <br>
met with either labelling or banishment.<br>
<p>
Besides, in 20 years, homosexuality will be as accepted in the church<br>
as divorce is today.  Look at the trends.  Every generation allows<br>
what their parents forbid, then proceeds to draw new lines which they<br>
defend furiously.  You can be sure that all necrophiliacs and<br>
sadomasochists will be rooted out of the church of 20 years from now,<br>
just like homosexuals are today.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
