<title>Jun_1993: A former Catholic speaks</title>
<h1>A former Catholic speaks</h1>
Ray Mialki (<i>rm1g+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  1 Jun 1993 22:18:18 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Steven Timm: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Since there has been discussion concerning the Episcopalian Church and<br>
the Catholic Church, I figured I could shed some unique insights, since<br>
I have been involved in both, as well as everywhere else in between.<br>
<p>
I was raised in the Roman Church.  Early in my schooling years, we went<br>
from the Latin mass to English.  I also served as an altar boy.  When<br>
our Church merged with another parish, and they tore down my old church<br>
building, I was able to obtain as souvenoirs one of the candlesticks,<br>
and the "Sacrementary", the book used by the priest to say mass from. <br>
My particular copy has both the English and the Latin Order of Mass, as<br>
well as for the various prayers.<br>
<p>
At age seventeen, I came to know Christ, and wound up worshipping in a<br>
Pentecostal Church while I finished HIgh School.  <br>
<p>
After I started college, I began to attend an Episcopalian Church.  I<br>
worshipped there for nearly four years, and even taught Sunday School. <br>
I quit going there, and resigned my position as Sunday School teacher,<br>
when I found out that the priest and the Director of Christian Education<br>
were both Universalists.  Their belief was that all people are going to<br>
heaven because Christ died for all men.  This was true whether you<br>
accepted Him or not.  Hell did not exist.<br>
<p>
I have found the Episcopalian Church to be quite an adventure.  Many<br>
denominations can be stereotyped.  I have heard it say that if you are<br>
away from ;home, and know nothing about the Churches in an area, it is<br>
safe to go to a Baptist Church, for you will always have the basics of<br>
the Gospel preached.  But the Episcopalian Church is quite different. <br>
They cover the whole spectrum.  Right here in Pittsburgh, you have an<br>
Episcopalian Church that has the Universalist as the pastor, another one<br>
which is headed by an openly homosexual priest, and then one that is<br>
truly Evangelical and true to the Scriptures, and many of the local<br>
college students who live committed to Christ attend.  All three of<br>
these Churches are within ten minutes of each other.<br>
<p>
I really liked the episcopalian Church I attended for so long.  But if<br>
there ever could be a mishap in a worship service, it would happen<br>
there.  Like when they caught the Advent Wreath on fire.  Or when the<br>
person swinging the incense burner clonked it into the Baptismal font. <br>
Or when the rope broke on the bell in the tower.  ETc.  But I digress.<br>
<p>
One striking difference between the Catholic Church and the Episcopalian<br>
Church is the focus of the mass.  Although much of the ceremony, ritual,<br>
and liturgy is similar, the Catholic mass is offered FOR THE DEAD.  The<br>
Catholic mass is a sacrifice so that the sins of those that have died<br>
can be forgiven.  The lEpiscopalian Church teaches no such thing.  The<br>
Episcopalian Church does not teach a Purgatory.  There are no<br>
indulgences to be earned in the Episcopalian Church.  <br>
<p>
I think that is even more significant difference than who is the head of<br>
the particular church.  <br>
<p>
Ray the kop<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
