<title>Jun_1993: Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost</title>
<h1>Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  1 Jun 1993 22:27:01 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#12">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#12">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#12">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#12">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0013.html">Ray Mialki: "A former Catholic speaks"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Drew Corrigan: "Portions of the Spirit (was Re: Sacraments:)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; What does the SDA church have today to offer a visual learner, or a</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; kinesthetic learner?  For years the church service has been something to </i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;NLP here we come ! doesn't the bible say that faith comes through</i><br>
<i>&gt;hearing of the word? For some reason I just can not picture Jesus, together</i><br>
<i>&gt;with Peter James and John acting out a little skit to illustrate a point</i><br>
<i>&gt;can you ?</i><br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;Ruben.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
This is rich.  I will just give some of the references I can find to <br>
Jesus teaching visually.<br>
Matthew 6:26,28<br>
Matthew 18:2-6<br>
Matthew 21:19-20<br>
Matthew 22:19<br>
Matthew 24:2<br>
Luke 7:44<br>
Luke 9:47<br>
Luke 21:1,2<br>
Luke 24:39<br>
John 8:6<br>
John 20:27<br>
<p>
In all these texts Jesus points to a visual example.  While I must admit<br>
Peter, James, and John never acted out a skit, there were powerful <br>
visual object lessons to be had.  And this doesn't even count the parables<br>
which were probably told based on things familiar and nearby,<br>
visible at the time to the disciples.  (I will check Christ's Object<br>
Lessons tonight).<br>
<p>
When was the last time you employed your sense of smell during <br>
a worship service (to good and edifying effect?)  What of touch?<br>
Does or should taste have a larger purpose than once a quarter during <br>
communion (ditto touch?)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
