<!-- body="start" -->
[Ruben Gonzalez writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Doesn't the bible say that faith comes through</i><br>
<i>&gt; hearing of the word?</i><br>
<p>
True.  But only by preaching?  Evidently predominantly so (1 Cor 1:21,<br>
Tit 1:3, Rom 10:14,15, 2 Tim 4:2).  But exclusively?  Let's look.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; For some reason I just can not picture Jesus, together</i><br>
<i>&gt; with Peter James and John acting out a little skit to illustrate a point</i><br>
<i>&gt; can you ?</i><br>
<p>
While the extreme rarity of acted-out drama in Scripture should suggest<br>
something to us as to how frequently to use it, there is, however, some<br>
definite use.  Beyond Steve's observations re illustrations Jesus used,<br>
consider the object lessons of:<br>
* Hosea's marrying the wayward prostitute Gomer (talk about drama in<br>
  real life!).<br>
* Jeremiah's underclothing (Jer 13, altho this appears to have been done in<br>
  private); Jeremiah's singleness (Jer 16); the potter's vessel (Jer 18);<br>
  the bonds and yokes (Jer 27, 28); the purchase of real estate (Jer 32);<br>
  the Rechabites and wine (Jer 35); stones in clay (Jer 43).<br>
<p>
It is worthy of observation that, on balance, Jeremiah did far more preaching;<br>
moreover, his dramas were simple, not great productions.  I am not aware of<br>
any public dramas in NT times (Agabus incident, Act 21, was rather private).<br>
There is the frequent use of metaphors, imagery in visions, etc, but this is<br>
distinct from theatrical drama.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
