<title>Jun_1993: Re: Sacraments:</title>
<h1>Re: Sacraments:</h1>
Dan Drazen (<i>drazen@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 2 Jun 1993 12:42:18 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#16">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#16">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#16">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#16">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: Cognitive Dissonance"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0015.html">Alan Fargusson: "Re: net.athiests"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0007.html">Steven Timm: "Sacraments:"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; If I understand the SDA view correctly, we hold that there are no sacraments.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Steve:<br>
<p>
As I have understood it, the traditional broad-spectrum Protestant<br>
belief was that there were only two sacraments that had any Scriptural<br>
basis and should be retained: baptism and communion.  Not that the two<br>
weren't altered to fit -- communion in the Protestant camp deliberately<br>
undercut the notion of transubstantiation (which is another word for<br>
"Trust me, even though these look and smell and feel and taste like<br>
bread and wine they're really really really the flesh and blood of<br>
Jesus.  Work with me on this one."<br>
<p>
So ordination in the Protestant view isn't exactly a sacrament.  In<br>
fact, Luther's writings contain the germ of the notion of "vocation" or<br>
calling -- the sense that one is doing precisely what God meant you to<br>
do (whether God meant for you to do this even before you were born<br>
depends on how you feel about predestination...but I digress).  My twin<br>
brother, on the other hand, claims that employment is based more on<br>
economic necessity on the part of the employer than on anything so<br>
mystical as a calling.  The fact that he's currently putting his<br>
Master's degree in Communication to use working in the word processing<br>
pool of an insurance company in Chicago may have something to do with<br>
it.  And it only just recently occurred to me where I'd heard that line<br>
of reasoning before: "Indeed, does Job serve you for nothing?..."<br>
<p>
Daniel J. Drazen<br>
Editor, SDA Periodical Index<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: Cognitive Dissonance"</a>
