<title>Jun_1993: Re: Cognitive Dissonance</title>
<h1>Re: Cognitive Dissonance</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 2 Jun 1993 14:47:14 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#22">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#22">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#22">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#22">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Dan Blake: "Re: net.athiests"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Beng.Tang@f622.n600.z6.fidonet.org: "Adventism Today"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steves comments on cognitive dissonance were quite pertinent. In spite<br>
of the protests of evangelists and theologians, people join the church<br>
because that is where their friends are. It takes more than church<br>
authority, doctrinal purity, moral rectitude and logic to convince<br>
people that the church is the right place to be. Human relationships<br>
are probably the most important single factor in influencing a person<br>
to join or stay with the church.<br>
<p>
The Bible emphasises this with statements like:<br>
<p>
"By this shall all men know you are my disciples, if you love one<br>
another.."<br>
<p>
"Ye are the salt of the earth..", etc<br>
<p>
Jesus ministry is most compelling when he is ministering at a personal<br>
level. eg The woman at the well, His conversations with Peter, His<br>
discussions with rabbis at night, His willingness to eat with tax<br>
collectors, His affirming the value of people who were prostitutes,<br>
publicans and sinners.<br>
<p>
Our church often has greater concern for doctrinal purity, Greek textual<br>
backgrounds, orders of service. I do not deny the necessity for these things,<br>
but I think that we must relate to real people.<br>
<p>
I think our attitudes are expressed in the sort of training we give to<br>
our ministers. More time is given to studying doctrine and academic theology<br>
while less time is spent on social issues. A minister in our society<br>
probably spends more time as a social worker than as a preacher, just as<br>
in Christ's own ministry. We owe it to them to prepare them thoroughly for<br>
this type of work.<br>
<p>
For the rest of us, computer scientists, physicists, accountants etc. we<br>
must live our Christianity by seeking opportunities to love those who<br>
need our love, both in and out of the church. The judgement scenes depicted<br>
in the parable of the sheep and the goats shows no commendation for<br>
doctrinal purity, knowledge of the 27 fundamentals, or the ability to recite<br>
proof texts. Cups of cold water, visting the sick, and imprisoned are<br>
given rich reward. To accept Jesus as saviour carries with it<br>
the responsibility of sharing love with people in need.<br>
<p>
Christian Regards<br>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Avondale College<br>
mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au<br>
   .-_|\<br>
  /     \<br>
  \.--._/<br>
       V<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
