<title>Jun_1993: Re: Cognitive Dissonance</title>
<h1>Re: Cognitive Dissonance</h1>
Darius A. Lecointe (<i>dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 2 Jun 1993 17:47:00 -0500 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#17">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#17">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#17">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#17">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0018.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Dan Drazen: "Re: Sacraments:"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I hope that your USENET ministry works out well.</i><br>
<i>&gt; I think that the church is better in some places than others.  It's</i><br>
<i>&gt; not all as bad as what you experienced.  We had an experience where</i><br>
<i>&gt; our pastor got out of line and the conference president came down</i><br>
<i>&gt; to explain to the congregation what had happened and how the pastor</i><br>
<i>&gt; had erred.  I was grateful for that.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I don't even require that.  There is no need to embarrass a pastor before<br>
his congregation.  But to totally ignore a matter, to not even acknowledge<br>
receipt is abrogation of responsibility.  Sometimes it is better to deal<br>
with the pastor and have him talk to the church about it.  It happened to<br>
me once.  In one of my sermons I made an innocent remark about a political<br>
figure the congregation supported.  Someone spoke to the president.  He<br>
knew me well, he had baptized me and called me to the ministry, and called<br>
me into his office.  After we had discussed it he understood the<br>
misunderstanding.  I  could have left it there.  The next time I preached<br>
at that church, I spoke to them first at their level.  (I long ago pledged<br>
to only deal with the word from the pulpit).  I told them I was sorry for<br>
the misunderstanding and explained what my remark had meant.  Doing that<br>
did not diminish me in any way. In fact I believe they respected me more<br>
as a result.  I would not have liked it if the president had paid a visit<br>
to the district.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Darius Lecointe                        God is the answer to a question.
dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu
dlecoint@freenet.scri.fsu.edu
</pre>
