<title>Jun_1993: Re: Historically Correct Meets Politically Correct</title>
<h1>Re: Historically Correct Meets Politically Correct</h1>
Darius A. Lecointe (<i>dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Jun 1993 01:10:25 -0500 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">lsusers: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0026.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Historically Correct Meets Politically Correct"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Some have regretted starting the discussion on homosexuality.  But look</i><br>
<i>&gt; at the big picture.  In SDAnet we were able to discuss it without resorting</i><br>
<i>&gt; to profanity, name-calling, or ad hominem attacks.  You should see what </i><br>
<i>&gt; happens on the big net (where, incidentally, several articles have appeared</i><br>
<i>&gt; recently on what Paul did mean by the Greek term "Arsenokoitai",</i><br>
<i>&gt; found only in that place in the Bible (Romans 1).)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; If anyone is ready to tackle the big issues and put out a post which does </i><br>
<i>&gt; not claim to be the word of the Lord, by all means continue.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I can't understand why there such a upshot over homosexuality.  If we were<br>
really concerned with sin I would understand.  But we encourage pride,<br>
excuse embezzlement.  We cannot be selective.  Do you for one moment think<br>
that a sermon on adultery breaks up the deacon's wife from the church<br>
elder?  I know that is simplistic and not quite complete.<br>
<p>
We cannot be true to scripture and accept homosexual behavior as<br>
appropriate.  Where I have difficulty is with those who argue against born<br>
homosexuals.  In my mind if sin has marred the creation it is only to be<br>
expected that it messed up the genes of some people.  When I pastored I<br>
had a few rumored homosexuals in my congregation.  I left it alone.  In my<br>
view just saying that something is fine does not make it fine in God's<br>
sight.  We have to ask God for guidance each day.  Sometimes He asks us to<br>
stop doing even things which are good.  Someone who earnestly seeks God's<br>
will will always have his prayer answered.  Why it should it be more<br>
sinful to keep on being homosexual (in behavior) than in refusing to give<br>
up pride.  The truth is only God knows who he is going to take into His<br>
heaven.  I cannot take you in by accepting your behavior or keep you out<br>
by rejecting it.  After all if you are faking God knows.  Our cleverness<br>
of argument does not impress Him at all.<br>
<p>
Intellectual debate is fine, but unless we are working towards towards<br>
building faith.  It is faith Jesus was concerned about finding on earth. <br>
People who only comply to church edits have not built faith.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Darius Lecointe                        God is the answer to a question.
dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu
dlecoint@freenet.scri.fsu.edu
</pre>
