<!-- body="start" -->
Dan quotes<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;   19 Thou wilt say then unto me, Why doth he still find fault?</i><br>
<i>&gt;   For who withstandeth his will?</i><br>
<i>&gt;   20 Nay but, O man, who art thou that repliest against God?</i><br>
<p>
and then writes<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;But for Tony (and other believers) I have another answer.  God has</i><br>
<i>&gt;shown himself to all the people in the world at once.  Not only</i><br>
<i>&gt;that, but at that time, all the people in the world were not</i><br>
<i>&gt;tainted by sin!  Yet, Mr. and Mrs. Adam rebelled against a revealed,</i><br>
<i>&gt;trice-holy God.  Their "conversion" was not the result of their</i><br>
<i>&gt;experience of seeing God, but due to the mercy and grace of God.</i><br>
<p>
Good points all, Dan. I think though that there is a difference between<br>
Adam &amp; Eve's situation and ours today. They didn't realize, but their<br>
situation could only get worse. Ours has a lot of room for improvement!<br>
Eve was deceived into thinking she was choosing a better option, just<br>
like people will be once again in the scenario Ruben mentioned.<br>
<p>
Having thought about the question "why doesn't God just show himself<br>
etc. etc.", I would agree with whoever said that people wouldn't believe<br>
him anyway. What would it take to convince a 20th century man that you<br>
were God? And even then, those who did believe would probably do so<br>
for the wrong reasons, like Judas apparently did.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
