<title>Jun_1993: Teaching aids</title>
<h1>Teaching aids</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>03 Jun 1993 15:16:57 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#36">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#36">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#36">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#36">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Re: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Tony Dyson: "Re: net.athiests"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0048.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: Teaching aids"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It sounds, Ruben, as though you would be happy with a narrated mime or<br>
skit, but not with other forms of drama.<br>
<p>
What I must admit I fail to understand, is why this problem is even a problem.<br>
<p>
Surely it is obvious to any communicating person that people have different<br>
ways of listening and learning. The division into auditory, visual and<br>
kinesthetic is just an arbitrary classification scheme that can help in<br>
understanding some of the different ways people "listen". Even within a narrow<br>
field of learning this is the case. Some physicists use diagrams for <br>
everything, others prefer equations. When studying for exams, some people<br>
remember the sound of a formula by reciting it to themselves, others remember<br>
how to write it down or what it looks like.<br>
<p>
So why not take these differences into account when communicating with<br>
people? Teachers certainly should. Why not preachers? It's not a case of<br>
NLP, hypnosis or mind control, just simple communication skills.<br>
<p>
By the way, how about all the prophets who were given visions, rather than<br>
hearing the voice of God? Some of them actually experienced physical<br>
sensations as well. You can't tell me that the scene with Isaiah and the<br>
burning coal wasn't some kind of dramatic presentation for his benefit!<br>
What about Jeremiah lying on his side for weeks on end, or Hosea's struggles<br>
with his wife? The allegorical form of communication has a long and<br>
distinguished history!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
---------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Anthony J. Dyson				_________<br>
Theoretical Surface Physics Group		_|__o__|_<br>
University of Newcastle				_|_(/)_|_<br>
Australia					   d-b<br>
<p>
		     "I'd rather be flying!"<br>
        		              Anonymous<br>
