<title>Jun_1993: acceptance in the Lord</title>
<h1>acceptance in the Lord</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Jun 93 16:17:14 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#29">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#29">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#29">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#29">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re:  Historically Correct Meets Politically Correct"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Sex changes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0050.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  acceptance in the Lord"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
		       What's a trick question?<br>
<p>
A recent message mentioned a survey taken in the Far Eastern Division<br>
in which the youth were asked a question like ``Do you have to live a<br>
good life in order to be accepted by God?''  A large majority said<br>
yes.  This was interpreted as evidence that the youth do not<br>
understand righteousness by faith.  I have some problems with this<br>
interpretation.  It is true that we do not earn salvation by our works<br>
and that we are justified by faith.  However, that is not exactly what<br>
the question said.  We will be judged on the basis of our works, as<br>
the Scriptures make abundantly clear.  These works are the fruit of<br>
faith working by love.  But if the works are not present then we do<br>
not have saving faith.  So in a sense it is true that we have to<br>
live a good life (as evidence of faith) in order to be accepted by<br>
God (on the judgment day).<br>
<p>
One might say that the Lord accepts us now because of the cross and<br>
all we have to do is accept the fact that He accepts us.  The Bible<br>
does say that we are ``accepted in the Beloved'' (Ephesians 1:6).<br>
However, if the Lord accepts us now regardless of our response, then<br>
why will He not accept us on the judgment day?  Why will He not accept<br>
us into heaven regardless of whether we accept Him, if He accepts us<br>
now regardless of whether we respond?  It seems to me that there is a<br>
valid sense in which one can say that the Lord does not really accept<br>
us now if we do not respond to Him in faith.  I would find it a<br>
strange kind of acceptance if the Lord fully accepted me all my life<br>
and then when judgment day comes I am rejected because I did not<br>
respond.  That would be like my boss being friendly to me every day<br>
and then suddenly firing me.<br>
<p>
So now I assume that the church leaders will take the responses to<br>
this questionnaire as evidence that the youth of the Far Eastern<br>
division do not understand righteousness by faith.  My impression is<br>
that the Far Eastern Division is probably a lot more alive than the<br>
North American Division where the answers to this question might be<br>
slightly more ``politically correct.''  Now the leaders will try to<br>
convince the youth that what you do isn't so important but who you<br>
believe.  Suppose instead that the leaders had asked the question,<br>
``Can you be saved if you continually and deliberately sin?''  Now,<br>
that may also be a trick question.  But I am sure that quite a number<br>
would reason, yes, we are all sinners, and we are saved by faith, so<br>
we can be saved if we continually sin.  But the leaders could say, the<br>
answer should be no, our faith should be revealed in a life of<br>
obedience and so we need to convince the youth of the importance of<br>
sanctification.  (Hebrews 10:26,27) I would not be completely happy<br>
with that decision, either.  I wonder if the kind of questions that<br>
are asked reveals more about the plans of the leadership than the<br>
responses do about the beliefs of the church members.<br>
<p>
My point is that you have to use more than a few responses to<br>
ambiguous questions in order to determine the state of one's<br>
spirituality or that of the youth of the church.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
