<title>Jun_1993: Re: Letter from Tang Beng Yong #1</title>
<h1>Re: Letter from Tang Beng Yong #1</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Jun 93 18:17:32 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#34">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#34">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#34">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#34">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Tony Dyson: "Re: net.athiests"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Notes on the day of Penteco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I read Beng's letter with some interest, there are some comments I would like <br>
to make, regarding some of what Beng said.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;      The conservatives see the influence of the world infiltrating the</i><br>
<i>&gt; church, they see church standards and even basic bible doctrines being eroded</i><br>
<i>&gt; and being treated with less and less importance. They therefore place great</i><br>
<i>&gt; emphasis on behaviour and good works, church standards and correct doctrine,</i><br>
<i>&gt; and calling sin by its right name. They believe in salvation by grace through</i><br>
<i>&gt; faith, but are afraid to stress it lest it open the floodgates of iniquity.</i><br>
<i>&gt; They fear that if people think that we are not saved by good works, they will</i><br>
<i>&gt; become lawless and decadent.</i><br>
<p>
I don't think conservatives have stopped stressing salvation by faith at all,<br>
that they consider santification an important aspect of salvation does<br>
not weaken their emphasis on justification, its just that the two go together<br>
or not at all. There is no continuing justification without an accompanying <br>
sanctification. I completely disagree that conservatives fear that without<br>
the people being deceived into believing salvation by works they will become<br>
lawless and decadent. If this is what you think conservatives are about<br>
then you are mistaken. This salvation by works issue is a staw man set up by<br>
some in order to get the unaffiliated on side. Was EGW a legalist ?<br>
did she want to deceive people into legalism ? Well the same applies<br>
to conservatives as applied to her. Of course I know some people will <br>
say that EGW was a legalist. But then that is only because we have a new <br>
definition of legalism. <br>
<p>
Legalism used to be defined as attempting to be saved by our own<br>
merits in doing works, nowdays legalism in some quaters has come to mean<br>
anybody who thinks works have any role in the Christian life. Well for those <br>
who think they don't, tell me one thing, how will you be judged ?<br>
<p>
Its especially true that any unbalanced understanding of the gospel leads <br>
to lawlessness and the salvation by works concept leads to just as much <br>
lawlessness as the anitnomian one.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;      The liberals, in part at least, are reacting to what they perceive as</i><br>
<i>&gt; the teaching of salvation by works, from the conservatives. They stress the</i><br>
<p>
<p>
A large component of the "confirmed" liberals  I know (note the qualification)<br>
are not reacting at all, rather they are pro-acting. (And I am not<br>
alluding to any SDAnet correspondents)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;      Perhaps that is over-simplifying it but i think that's roughly how it</i><br>
<i>&gt; is. I personally agree with both of these groups, but i feel that we need to</i><br>
<i>&gt; get a balanced picture of what we believe, so that we don't confuse people.</i><br>
<p>
I wish it was so simple, but unfortunately it isn't.<br>
<p>
Thats exactly the problem, what do we believe ? what we used to believe<br>
or what we are now told we are supposed to believe ? There are two gospels<br>
in the church today, we are not talking two viewpoints, we are talking<br>
two separate and distinct gospels.<br>
<p>
Those who have really studied the issues on both sides of the fence will<br>
tell you that there can be no compromise between both sides. There are two<br>
paths, and they both lead in separate directions. Of course very few have<br>
actually done a profound study on both sides of the issues and so<br>
will not appreciate that even though some things sound similar they lead<br>
down completely different paths.<br>
<p>
Should we change the pillars of our faith to be more accomodating for those <br>
who don't believe ? If so then where do we draw the line ?<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
