<!-- body="start" -->
Dear SDA Net:<br>
<p>
As a learning disabled student I have many times felt left out of church<br>
because of the lack of the ablility for the preacher to use the proper<br>
words and method of teaching that I learn in.  I am a very visual learner<br>
and learn the least through my ears.  I am easily distracted and when I<br>
was younger was hyperactive.  Now that I am in college sometimes my<br>
hyperactivity will sneek up on me, but I usaly can control it.  I am still<br>
learning disabled and get distracted a lot.  <br>
<p>
Then one Sabbath something new caught my eye.  Rather my brain, I suddenly<br>
realized that as I was learning sign language from Fred Christenson and<br>
others who I deeply miss, that I was understanding sermons for the first<br>
time in my life since I was able to fallow them the whole way through.  I<br>
learned that the sign will allow my mind to use sight as well as movement<br>
and space to learn.  Besides I am still using my ears.  You have no idea<br>
the joy I foudn in the Lord because of that.  Now that I go to church with<br>
out an interpriter, I often find myself falling asleep again and have no<br>
idea what is being said or how diffrent things relate.<br>
<p>
I'm not saying that every SDA should learn sign language (as much as I<br>
wish.... :)~  But I am saying that learning diffrences are not made up and<br>
people will learn only in the way their brain can function.  In Jesus day<br>
the comon people mostly spoke.  Lille did they write for pleasure becuase<br>
of how complex it was for writing and supplies.  The people were oral. <br>
Jesus used paribles then to paint a spoken mental picture or story of what<br>
he is trying to say and explain.  Now that people watch tv so much we are<br>
now a visual society.  We need the plays, skits, dramma, to tell us what<br>
used to be spoken to us.<br>
<p>
Us the tools God have given!  If you can teach more than one style than do<br>
it.  There is a phrase, "If 1/3 of your audience is youth then 1/3 of your<br>
sermon should be for them."  I say that holds true for others too.  <br>
(eg: use something physical you are holding such as a lemon to make a<br>
point, use body movments, use pictures, use music, use lighting, use more<br>
than one speaker, use diffrent communication skill of style of speaking. etc.)<br>
<p>
Scott Bechtel<br>
srbechte@nyx.cs.du.edu<br>
<p>
##############################################################################<br>
# Scott Bechte at Union College  #   srbechte  #  Ham: N0UJY  C$S: 71175,414 #<br>
##############################################################################<br>
