<title>Jun_1993: Re: When Big Brother comes after you</title>
<h1>Re: When Big Brother comes after you</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 04 Jun 1993 08:22:51 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Re: Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Ray Mialki: "A Christian Military Man"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0076.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Unfortunatly the constitution DOES NOT protect us.  An no, I am not an avocate<br>
of taking up arms to defend against the death decree.  However, the mere presence<br>
of an armed citizenry is enough to hold abuses in check generaly.  Once again<br>
I want to state that the concept of the free-hold estate and the armed free<br>
man is central to the twarting of tyranny.  Unfortunatly, our courts have<br>
gutted or nearly gutted most provisions of the constitution governing freedoms.<br>
The free excercise clause is now gone. (Hopefully the Freedom of Restoration<br>
Act will make it through, and Clinton will sign it).  Free speech is severelyt<br>
curtailed, rights of choice in other matters are curtailed, and protection<br>
against unlawful search and seizure has been gutted as well.  We are rapidly<br>
spinning toward a police state.  Of course, most SDA's have expected that<br>
to happen for a very long time, but folks it IS happening.<br>
<p>
For our international members, the U.S. constituion guarantees the right<br>
to freedom of religion.  The constitution forbids the government from<br>
making any laws that  interfere or promote religion i.e. they have to be<br>
neutral, and further prevents it from interfering with the "free excercise"<br>
of religious beliefs.  Now, up until a couple of years ago, the government<br>
had to prove a "compelling state interest" in order to interfere with any<br>
religious practice whatsoever, be it putting a road through the Native<br>
American holy spots, etc. etc.  Justice Antone Scalia is a rabid anti-religious<br>
freedom oriented judge.  A couple of years ago, Smith vs Oregon was decided<br>
in favor of Oregon.  Apparently Mr. Smith had a drug conviction on other grou<br>
grounds, and as part of his sentence, was required to work in a drug rehab<br>
center.  He was a member of the Native American church, which uses the drug<br>
peote to induce "spiritual visions"  It is a powerful hallucinogen.  He was<br>
fired for this, and applied for unemplyment benefits.  The state of Oregon<br>
denied them.  The case got appealed to the supreme court, which threw out<br>
the "compelling state interest" test, and substitued "facially neutral" for<br>
the test.  That is, if the law is a "facially neutral" law not aimed at any<br>
PARTICULAR religion (note it MAY be construed to mean that a general law<br>
could be aimed at ALL religions), then that is all that is required for the<br>
government to interfere.  It does not take a rocket scientist to see that this<br>
lays open a wide potential for abuse.  There is a town in Florida, that in<br>
order to stop animal sacrifices going on in a particular religion, has out<br>
lawed all animal sacrifices.  One of the relgious leaders points out that<br>
you can "kill a turkey, cook it, say prayer over it and eat it", but under<br>
the new law, if you "say prayer over the turkey, then kill, cook and eat it<br>
you can go to jail".  The city claims that it is a "facially neutral law"<br>
not aimed at any particular religion, but is aimed at animal sacrifices<br>
specifically.  Of course, there are no known cases of animal sacrifices outside<br>
of that particular religion, but that makes no diffrence.  Using the<br>
"compelling state intrest" test, this law would be overthrown.  Using the<br>
"facially neutral" law, and the ultra conservative Bush/Reagan stuffed court<br>
it may well be upheld.  <br>
<p>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
