<title>Jun_1993: Re: Sex changes (fwd)</title>
<h1>Re: Sex changes (fwd)</h1>
Darius A. Lecointe (<i>dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Jun 1993 11:43:37 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: &gt; Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: Sex changes (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0086.html">Dan Crowe: "Sexual Immorality"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Looks like my mailer is acting up again.  I copied the last message to<br>
myself and it appears in my mailbox complete with my post.  Fortunately I<br>
had saved the message in my home directory also.<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Darius,</i><br>
<i>&gt; you replied to a message but only included Marcus Stringer's text</i><br>
<i>&gt; and didn't say anything new.  Did you send too fast, or something?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I notice that the posts you send me have the original poster's address as<br>
the return path, not yours.  As a result when I reply in my mailer the<br>
response goes to the poster not you.  After I composed that reply I edited<br>
the headers and put your address in the To line.  That must be the reason<br>
for the blank message.  I deleted Marcus's message but I think I remember<br>
enough to recompose.  Here goes.<br>
<p>
Dealing with homosexuality in the church is not as huge a problem as we<br>
make.  It must be dealt with the same way as we deal with any other sin. <br>
Homosexual activity is no different from sexual activity between single<br>
Adventists.  It is foolish to assume that a pretty woman has a date and<br>
just as foolish to assume that one who looks or acts publicly as *gay* is<br>
engaged in sexual activity.  Surely we are not advocating camping under<br>
lovers' beds.  The church has never been given any authority to punish sin<br>
for God has reserved to Himself the right to decide to whom He will<br>
impute iniquity (Rom. 4:8).  If we really trust God we must trust Him<br>
enough to believe He will not allow sin into the kingdom.  The presence of<br>
sin on earth or in the church is no  indication of God's approval of it{<br>
<p>
Sex in the context of marriage cannot be wrong.  If homosexuals can be<br>
married in God's sight then sex between them cannot be wrong.  The<br>
question is Does God recognize homosexual marriages?  I see no evidence in<br>
the bible to support that.  The bible speaks of a man being joined to a<br>
wife.  It never speaks of marriage outside of the context of gender.  I<br>
cannot but conclude that same sex marriages, and therefore homosexual sex, is<br>
not accepted by God.<br>
<p>
This is where we have shot ourselves in the foot.  We teach that even if a<br>
marriage would not have been sanctioned by God He blesses it based on its<br>
civil legality.  That argument is often used to deny valid divorces to<br>
those who may have married for the wrong reasons.  What that argument does<br>
is force us to be duplicitous.  How do we relate to a homosexual marriage<br>
in a state where the civil laws allow it?<br>
<p>
Our problem comes from a practice I first observed here--TODOA: the open<br>
display of affection.  If we can justify this on the basis of cultural<br>
adjustments then how do we refuse it to those who those who may rightfully<br>
claim that their genes have been altered by the ravinging effects of sin? <br>
We must be consistent and not just show ourselves as only being interested<br>
in putting *others* in their place.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Darius Lecointe                        God is the answer to a question.
dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu
dlecoint@freenet.scri.fsu.edu
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
