<title>Jun_1993: Re: When Big Brother comes after you</title>
<h1>Re: When Big Brother comes after you</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Jun 93 13:51:07 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Notes on the day of Penteco"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0067.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: Steven Timm &lt;st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; As a lifelong flatlander, I've often wondered how I would get out to </i><br>
<i>&gt; any sort of mountain when the persecution started.  </i><br>
<p>
I *knew* there was a reason I preferred living on the West Coast... :}<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Besides this, to track me down electronically would be trivial.</i><br>
<p>
Perhaps this is another argument for us to give up worldly things<br>
that bind us. Half :}, come to think of it.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I suspect a hand will just come out</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the terminal, slap on the handcuffs, and that will be it.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Do those of you who say that guns are needed to protect us in America from </i><br>
<i>&gt; our own government intend to take up arms whenever the death-decree folks</i><br>
<i>&gt; come after you?</i><br>
<p>
My own feeling is that by that time it may well be too late to do anything.<br>
<p>
It's the period before that point that may permit us to some things that<br>
might either hold it off a bit, or reduce a little the severity.<br>
<p>
On the other hand, there is some history during the 20th century of "death<br>
decrees" having been enacted, with differing degrees of success, ranging<br>
from the mass killings of Stalinist and Nazi times on down.<br>
<p>
Perhaps we miss something in focusing totally on an apocalyptic, worldwide<br>
event to the exclusion of more-regional events.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Do you think it will do any good to shoot a few of them?</i><br>
<i>&gt; And if you don't think you would do it in the ultimate situation, why</i><br>
<i>&gt; in any other situation?  </i><br>
<p>
By this argument one should not resist criminal attacks such as rape or<br>
assaults on children.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; As long as we have the constitution to protect us from our own government,</i><br>
<i>&gt; we are fine.</i><br>
<p>
Then we're wasting time and money in contesting various First-Amendment-<br>
violating laws.  There's no point in publishing Listen magazine, either.<br>
<p>
I'm not serious.<br>
<p>
The constitutional guarantees did slave in the U.S. no good for a long time.<br>
<p>
Right now you can see evidence of government agents at various times and<br>
various places violating parts (or all) of the First, Second, Fourth, and<br>
Fifth amendments.  Just because the Bill of Rights guarantees a number of<br>
inherent, God-given rights doesn't mean that there might not be violations<br>
of those same rights. (The War on Drugs, among other faults, has been for<br>
some time a sort of justification for violating one or more of many persons'<br>
"inalienable right".)<br>
<p>
Who was it who said "put not your trust in princes"? (The concordance in<br>
the Bible here at work is *really* pitiful...) It's more true now than it<br>
was then, if for no other reason than current "princes" can do more damage<br>
that the ancients could.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If people ever mess with the constitution, they'll probably put</i><br>
<i>&gt; in gun control, too, so guns would not be available to do the job the</i><br>
<i>&gt; constitution could not.</i><br>
<p>
The Constitution is being messed with right now.  Has been for years.<br>
(And if you were to look at countries who currently ban civilian ownership<br>
of firearms, you'll find none that are completely-successful at it. In all<br>
cases, criminals still have access to, and use, firearms.)<br>
<p>
The main notion of the Second amendment was to provide one more check on<br>
the power of the State.  Also note that a militia could be called up for<br>
more than just defense against foreign invasion; the first police departments<br>
were set up with unarmed policemen who were to call out armed citizens at<br>
need to deal with criminals, both individuals and groups.<br>
<p>
Been a while since that's been done.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I think that at the time of the end the only thing</i><br>
<i>&gt; we will be able to trust to protect us from our government is the power</i><br>
<i>&gt; of God,  and that is no less true now than it will be then.</i><br>
<p>
Perhaps we should depend on prayer alone to deal with disease and injury.<br>
<p>
Perhaps we can go too far in either direction?  Where should the balance<br>
point stand? (We ought to eat/drink/exercise/etc. to avoid getting sick,<br>
but we often have to depend on physicians and surgeons when things still<br>
go wrong...and I don't know many who look on the medical work as some sort<br>
of abandonment of God's grace and power.  Over-reliance on the medical<br>
arm is something else again.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Of course, we could follow the example of the old Quaker farmer who said,</i><br>
<i>&gt; "Friend, I mean thee no harm but thou standest where I am about to shoot."</i><br>
<i>&gt; If I were to do that, I'd most probably shoot myself in the foot or something.</i><br>
<p>
While not everyone needs access to firearms, or even ought to have them, it<br>
doesn't seem right that all should be prohibited such access. In most cases,<br>
it should be up to the individual to choose.<br>
<p>
Even Jesus gave his disciples leave to arm themselves for self-defense...and<br>
it is equally clear that irresponsible use of them was not part of the package.<br>
<p>
Wouldn't it be nice if things were simple?  :{<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
