<title>Jun_1993: Re: Gun, Guns</title>
<h1>Re: Gun, Guns</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Jun 1993 18:36:10 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Steven Timm: "The Historically Correct visual aid"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Sex changes"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0037.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Re: Gun, Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Randall Helperman writes:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; So far I've stayed out of this gun ownership debate, but now I'm going</i><br>
<i>&gt; to spring in because I believe that SDA's should be aware of the end-time</i><br>
<i>&gt; significance of what's going on.  No, I don't mean that Koresh was the</i><br>
<i>&gt; antichrist or similar silliness, I just mean that the U.S. government</i><br>
<i>&gt; is drifting in a most disturbing direction and it is not hard to see </i><br>
<i>&gt; how Sunday Law legislation could be inflicted soon.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I'll start with some radical statements and then back them up with facts. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Radical statement:  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Americans need guns to protect themselves against their own government.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Facts:  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 1.  The people who wrote the constitution recognized this.  That is why it </i><br>
<i>&gt;     was written into the constitution.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;     Thomas Jefferson was the one who said that the right to keep and bear</i><br>
<i>&gt;     arms was for the citizens to protect themselves from the government.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
It's Friday afternoon, and I'm going to be foolish enough to jump into<br>
this again.  It is true that the Founding Fathers placed this in the<br>
constitution.  One must also remember that this was 200 years ago (and<br>
has been pointed out, but society and weapons technology were quite<br>
different), immediately after an armed rebellion against the government<br>
and in a society struggling to tame a wilderness.  No one can know for<br>
sure, but I would venture that if they were suddenly resurrected they<br>
might be shocked at how this has turned out.  Jefferson also recommended<br>
an armed rebellion every 30 years or so (we forget how radical he was).<br>
The one armed rebellion there was was a great national tragedy, as is<br>
the armed civil war going on in Yugoslavia today.  Little is recorded<br>
about what the "Founding Mothers" thought.  While it is true that many<br>
women own guns, they constitute a minority.  [Are guns a phallic symbol<br>
in our society?]  Seriously, I would like more female input in this<br>
discussion.<br>
<p>
I believe the discussion was begun by someone outside the US wondering<br>
why this was necessary in a democracy.  It's still a valid question.<br>
There are many functioning democracies in the world, and few of them<br>
have the level of gun-ownership that the U.S. does.  I'm wondering, for<br>
example, how things are in Australia?  I know in England the police<br>
often aren't even armed with firearms.  Perhaps Gandhi's ideals of<br>
non-violence would be a better model (as they are for the Mennonites).<br>
I believe Mao said power came out of the end of a gun.  For the moment<br>
in his country that may be true, but we've seen elsewhere the power of<br>
non-violent non-cooperation can have, and in the end will probably<br>
succeed in China as well.<br>
<p>
I'm wondering what evidence Mr. Helzerman has to back up his belief in<br>
an imminent Sunday law.  Some time ago, I sent a post on that subject.<br>
There was never any response.  I was surprised--either it was never sent<br>
or everyone must have agreed with me!  Even our church religious liberty<br>
people have had to admit that this is a non-issue in the U.S., and<br>
really hasn't been an issue since the turn of the century when<br>
conservative Protestants didn't like the loose Sunday habits of the<br>
Catholic immigrants.  Look around you.  More and more business is done<br>
on Sunday (including the first public library in Berrien County to open<br>
on Sunday so that our library is now not the only library in the county<br>
to be open on Sunday).  We live in a multi-cultural society (which not<br>
incidentally has a powerful Jewish lobby--check their influence on our<br>
foreign policy).  Much of the rest of the world is the same--secular<br>
and/or non-Christian or a liberal democracy.  The problem is that our<br>
eschatology (at least in that specific) is of the nineteenth century and<br>
is no longer "present truth," but we haven't the courage to admit it and<br>
find something more relevant to replace it (this is directly related to<br>
a problem of a literal reading of Ellen White).  I simply refuse to be<br>
paranoid about "last day events" and the need for a gun to protect my<br>
rights.  We need more of the love of Jesus.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<p>
That's probably enough to get me in trouble today.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
