<title>Jun_1993: The Historically Correct visual aid</title>
<h1>The Historically Correct visual aid</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri,  4 Jun 1993 19:00:44 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#55">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#55">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#55">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#55">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0056.html">Floyd Poenitz: "RE: Sex changes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Gun, Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Seventh-day Adventists have in one sense been at the forefront of the visual<br>
aid.  The various drawings of beasts and whatnot have given us a unique<br>
artform which has been used by many evangelists.  Many readers have probably<br>
seen the painting "The Way Of Life", later revised under commission from <br>
Ellen White under the title "Christ, the way of life".  <br>
<p>
SDA's have been on television with Faith For Today nearly as long as there <br>
has been television.  That's probably why television was never forbidden.<br>
Contemporary gospel music and emotional evangelistic appeals have also been<br>
around as long as there has been evangelism.  I think this is mostly a good <br>
thing.<br>
<p>
There is a danger involved with this, and that is that church members that <br>
are already grounded in the truth may grow to depend on the entertainment<br>
provided by these activities, and when the church activities do not provide<br>
enough, look elsewhere for the entertainment.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
