<title>Jun_1993: Re: When Big Brother comes after you</title>
<h1>Re: When Big Brother comes after you</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 5 Jun 93 15:54:18 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#76">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#76">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#76">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#76">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh? (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Rolaant.McKenzie@um.cc.umich.edu: "Re: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As a gun owning SDA, I have to admit that I have not come up with all the<br>
answers to Steve's questions.  I have been looking for and thinking about<br>
what is the correct answer to them from a Christian perspective.  I will share<br>
some of my thoughts developed upto this point in time.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Do those of you who say that guns are needed to protect us in America from </i><br>
<i>&gt; our own government intend to take up arms whenever the death-decree folks</i><br>
<i>&gt; come after you?  Do you think it will do any good to shoot a few of them?</i><br>
<i>&gt; And if you don't think you would do it in the ultimate situation, why</i><br>
<i>&gt; in any other situation?  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; As long as we have the constitution to protect us from our own government,</i><br>
<i>&gt; we are fine.  If people ever mess with the constitution, they'll probably put</i><br>
<i>&gt; in gun control, too, so guns would not be available to do the job the</i><br>
<i>&gt; constitution could not.  I think that at the time of the end the only thing</i><br>
<i>&gt; we will be able to trust to protect us from our government is the power</i><br>
<i>&gt; of God,  and that is no less true now than it will be then.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
<p>
First off, I am not a militarist.  I own guns but not for being ready for the<br>
day our govt goes off the deep end.  I fully support the right to bear arms by<br>
those who abide by the law (as we know it today).  When an individual breaks<br>
the law, particularly involving the use of a gun, I say they have forfeited <br>
this right.  The same for those who are found mentally unstable and/or on drugs.<br>
I stand behind this right because when this very basic right is removed, watch<br>
out..other basic rights are going to be removed.  I also believe there is <br>
nothing to be gained by removing the right to bear arms and much to be lost!<br>
<p>
You ask about the day of death-decrees, etc.  Well, I think of the time of the<br>
end as a prophesied event so-to-speak.  It has been fortold and will happen.  I<br>
can not change what is prophesied.  We are told we will be put in prison, <br>
hiding in caves, running for our lives, etc.  To me, having a gun may or may not<br>
be very helpful.  In fact it will likely be a detriment at giving your position<br>
away to the searchers.  And if you are caught, it likely would make your life<br>
a bit more uncomfortable.  So I doubt that I will be carrying a gun come the<br>
time of the end.<br>
<p>
But as for now, in this time prior to Sunday laws and the public out looking<br>
for us, I think that we are living in a time of evil people running around<br>
hurting alot of innocent other people.  I can think of situations that could<br>
easily warrent the use of a gun in defense of yourself and/or your family.  I<br>
do not think that a gun should be your first line of defense, and probably<br>
your last, given the serious consequences.  But this decision is a personal<br>
one.<br>
<p>
The difference is basically this:  When the Sunday law is passed and death<br>
decree goes out, probation will have closed.  God's protection is promised<br>
for His people from that point on.  But prior to this time, there is a limit <br>
to God's protection for us... there are times when God has to let evil run its <br>
ugly coarse because of the great controversy and for the benefit of letting <br>
others see the natural results of sin.  This means that in some cases, <br>
innocent Godly people have been and will be killed.  <br>
<p>
So I have to ask, if God is letting sin run its coarse in some situations, <br>
then why can I not get involved in this "coarse" and defend myself and my <br>
loved ones from the evil?  Why be an innocent bystander or victim, hoping <br>
God will get you out of a situation when this may be one of those times He <br>
choses not to prevent it.  Or maybe He knows you have a gun and because He <br>
has given us a brain and hands and feet, He expects us to use them.  Would <br>
that not be just as much a help from God as sending an angel to blind the <br>
other guy?  Why does help from God always expected to be miraculous?  Can<br>
not the help be simply impressing upon us the right course of action in a<br>
given situation and letting us do the acting?  We are told that we are His<br>
hands and feet... does this exclude situations where God wants to protect<br>
us?  Or do we stand back and let God do the protecting?<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
PS:  Just because they may someday put gun prohibition into the constitution<br>
does not mean that suddenly guns are going to dissappear from people's houses.<br>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
--
Bruce G. Holm               503-685-1350      email:  bruceh@wv.mentorg.com
Mentor Graphics Corp.       503-685-7000
8005 SW Boeckman Rd.
Wilsonville, OR 97070-7777     Disclaimer:  Opinions expressed are my own!
</pre>
