<title>Jun_1993: Sexual Immorality</title>
<h1>Sexual Immorality</h1>
Dan Crowe (<i>dcrowe@puc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 6 Jun 1993 10:28:36 -0700 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#86">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#86">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#86">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#86">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0087.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Beng's Letter"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Religious liberty dangers from the new left:"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: Sex changes (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0097.html">Fred Christiansen: "an extract from Steve &amp; Darius' exchange"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Fri, 4 Jun 1993, Darius A. Lecointe wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Dealing with homosexuality in the church is not as huge a problem as we</i><br>
<i>&gt; make.  It must be dealt with the same way as we deal with any other sin. </i><br>
<p>
Agreed.  We must love the sinner but hate the sin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The church has never been given any authority to punish sin</i><br>
<i>&gt; for God has reserved to Himself the right to decide to whom He will</i><br>
<i>&gt; impute iniquity (Rom. 4:8).</i><br>
<p>
The preceding statement is false.  Consider the following texts:<br>
<p>
	Exodus 21:12-36			1 Corinthians 5<br>
	Exodus 35:2			2 Thessalonians 3:6-15<br>
	Leviticus 18:22,29<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Sex in the context of marriage cannot be wrong.</i><br>
<p>
The Biblical passages refer only ambiguously to "sexual immorality", but<br>
the following Spirit of Prophecy quotes are quite clear that even within<br>
the context of marriage, sexual excess is sinful:<br>
<p>
	AH 121-8		2T 391, 472-3, 480<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; This is where we have shot ourselves in the foot.  We teach that even if a</i><br>
<i>&gt; marriage would not have been sanctioned by God He blesses it based on its</i><br>
<i>&gt; civil legality.  That argument is often used to deny valid divorces to</i><br>
<i>&gt; those who may have married for the wrong reasons.  What that argument does</i><br>
<i>&gt; is force us to be duplicitous.  How do we relate to a homosexual marriage</i><br>
<i>&gt; in a state where the civil laws allow it?</i><br>
<p>
Paul (not the Lord) says not to divorce an unbeliever if the unbeliever is<br>
willing to stay, but that the unbeliever should be allowed to initiate the<br>
divorce (1 Corinthians 7:12-6).  This position is tenable if the married<br>
couple does not engage in improper sexual activity (see EGW references<br>
above).  Since homosexual activity is improper, the application of this<br>
principle to homosexual marriages is inappropriate.<br>
<p>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
