<title>Jun_1993: Re: When Big Brother comes after you</title>
<h1>Re: When Big Brother comes after you</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 6 Jun 93 12:35:21 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#67">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#67">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#67">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#67">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Episcopal Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Re: Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0043.html">Steve Hix: "Re: When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0065.html">Woody Baker: "Re: When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Then we're wasting time and money in contesting various First-Amendment-</i><br>
<i>&gt; violating laws.  There's no point in publishing Listen magazine, either.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I'm not serious.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The constitutional guarantees did slave in the U.S. no good for a long time.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Right now you can see evidence of government agents at various times and</i><br>
<i>&gt; various places violating parts (or all) of the First, Second, Fourth, and</i><br>
<i>&gt; Fifth amendments.  Just because the Bill of Rights guarantees a number of</i><br>
<i>&gt; inherent, God-given rights doesn't mean that there might not be violations</i><br>
<i>&gt; of those same rights. (The War on Drugs, among other faults, has been for</i><br>
<i>&gt; some time a sort of justification for violating one or more of many persons'</i><br>
<i>&gt; "inalienable right".)</i><br>
<p>
This is a true statement.  Individuals have had their "constitutional rights<br>
taken from them from the beginning of the Country.  This may be hard for<br>
some of us to believe, but the documentation is not very hard to find.  I<br>
offered some in the past, I offer it again.`<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Who was it who said "put not your trust in princes"? (The concordance in</i><br>
<i>&gt; the Bible here at work is *really* pitiful...) It's more true now than it</i><br>
<i>&gt; was then, if for no other reason than current "princes" can do more damage</i><br>
<i>&gt; that the ancients could.</i><br>
<p>
Yes we cannot put our trust in Bill Clinton, George Bush, or the constitution.<br>
As was noted above, people have lost their rights at the whim of some leader<br>
throughout American history.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; If people ever mess with the constitution, they'll probably put</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; in gun control, too, so guns would not be available to do the job the</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; constitution could not.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The Constitution is being messed with right now.  Has been for years.</i><br>
<i>&gt; (And if you were to look at countries who currently ban civilian ownership</i><br>
<i>&gt; of firearms, you'll find none that are completely-successful at it. In all</i><br>
<i>&gt; cases, criminals still have access to, and use, firearms.)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The main notion of the Second amendment was to provide one more check on</i><br>
<i>&gt; the power of the State.  Also note that a militia could be called up for</i><br>
<i>&gt; more than just defense against foreign invasion; the first police departments</i><br>
<i>&gt; were set up with unarmed policemen who were to call out armed citizens at</i><br>
<i>&gt; need to deal with criminals, both individuals and groups.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Been a while since that's been done.</i><br>
<p>
And as was said, some groups have had this right taken from them.  They don't<br>
need to change the constitution.  They just have to disregard it.<br>
and this has been done.<br>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
"We must accept finite dissapointment,
 but we must never lose infinite hope."  --  Dr. King
<p>
Sherman H. Cox, II       scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu
