<title>Jun_1993: Episcopal Church</title>
<h1>Episcopal Church</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 6 Jun 1993 13:26:02 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#68">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#68">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#68">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#68">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Re: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: When Big Brother comes after you"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This is in response to Steve's posting some time ago.  The 1992<br>
_Yearbook of American and Canadian Churches_ gives the following<br>
information.  The church entered the colonies as the Church of England<br>
(Anglican Church), but changed its name to Protestant Episcopal in 1789<br>
in an attempt to distance itself from the British Crown (it had been the<br>
established church in several colonies).  Its name changed again in 1967<br>
to Episcopal Church.  Episcopal is a reference to the fact that the<br>
church has bishops (as does the Methodist Episcopal Church).  I believe<br>
members of this church are called Episcopalians rather than Episcopals.<br>
More US presidents have been Episcopalians (including George Bush) than<br>
any other church.  The National Cathedral (also called the Washington<br>
Cathedral or the Cathedral of Saint Peter and Saint Paul--guess they<br>
couldn't make up their minds!) is Episcopalian.  [I saw some cute books<br>
there about "Episcocats".]<br>
<p>
The yearbook also says this:  "The beliefs and practices of the<br>
Episcopal Church, like those of other Anglican churches, are both<br>
Catholic and Reformed, with bishops in the apostolic succession and the<br>
historic creeds of Christendom regarded as essential elements of faith<br>
and order, along with the primary authority of Holy Scripture and the<br>
two chief sacraments of Baptism and Eucharist."  Even though the<br>
original break with Rome was over power rather than theology it would be<br>
a mistake to conclude that England did not have a Reformation or that<br>
the Reformation had no theological impact on the Anglican Church.  They<br>
did retain, however, much of the liturgy of the Catholic Church,<br>
although in an English way (for example, music is much more important in<br>
the Anglican/Episcopal liturgy than it is in most Catholic churches).<br>
The reformation in England was an ongoing one.  Both the Puritan<br>
movement (to purify the Anglican Church) with the resultant<br>
Congregational Church (later United Church of Christ) and the Methodist<br>
Church came out of Anglicanism.  Like the English constitution, the<br>
English church has evolved.<br>
<p>
Most early Adventists did not come from the high church tradition, but<br>
from the working and lower classes which tended to go to churches with a<br>
simpler style of worship.  Ellen White, I believe, was Methodist and<br>
James White came from the Christian Connection.  It should not be<br>
surprising that our worship service follows this style (which is also<br>
similar to Baptist).  Adventists came out of a number of Protestant<br>
churches.  It is unfortunate that reverence in church is not an<br>
important element in the Adventist worship style (as it is in many of<br>
the liturgical churches, including Orthodox).  Worship services should<br>
try to combine meeting the congregation's informational needs as well as<br>
the need to worship God.  Getting the correct balance is not easy.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
