<title>Jun_1993: Re: Letter from Tang Beng Yong #1</title>
<h1>Re: Letter from Tang Beng Yong #1</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  6 Jun 1993 19:40:39 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#74">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#74">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#74">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#74">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Rolaant.McKenzie@um.cc.umich.edu: "Re: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Dan Crowe: "Re: acceptance in the Lord"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; sanctification. I completely disagree that conservatives fear that without</i><br>
<i>&gt; the people being deceived into believing salvation by works they will become</i><br>
<i>&gt; lawless and decadent. If this is what you think conservatives are about</i><br>
<i>&gt; then you are mistaken. This salvation by works issue is a staw man set up by</i><br>
<i>&gt; some in order to get the unaffiliated on side. Was EGW a legalist ?</i><br>
<i>&gt; did she want to deceive people into legalism ? Well the same applies</i><br>
<i>&gt; to conservatives as applied to her. Of course I know some people will </i><br>
<i>&gt; say that EGW was a legalist. But then that is only because we have a new </i><br>
<i>&gt; definition of legalism. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Legalism used to be defined as attempting to be saved by our own</i><br>
  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
<i>&gt; merits in doing works, nowdays legalism in some quaters has come to mean</i><br>
  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
<i>&gt; anybody who thinks works have any role in the Christian life. Well for those </i><br>
<i>&gt; who think they don't, tell me one thing, how will you be judged ?</i><br>
<p>
The underlined text is the correct definition.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Its especially true that any unbalanced understanding of the gospel leads </i><br>
<i>&gt; to lawlessness and the salvation by works concept leads to just as much </i><br>
<i>&gt; lawlessness as the anitnomian one.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
[Most of the text John Prosper included deleted.  What's left is from Ruben<br>
Gonzalez SCT]<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Thats exactly the problem, what do we believe ? what we used to believe</i><br>
<i>&gt; or what we are now told we are supposed to believe ? There are two gospels</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the church today, we are not talking two viewpoints, we are talking</i><br>
<i>&gt; two separate and distinct gospels.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Those who have really studied the issues on both sides of the fence will</i><br>
<i>&gt; tell you that there can be no compromise between both sides. There are two</i><br>
                ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
<i>&gt; paths, and they both lead in separate directions. Of course very few have</i><br>
<i>&gt; actually done a profound study on both sides of the issues and so</i><br>
<i>&gt; will not appreciate that even though some things sound similar they lead</i><br>
<i>&gt; down completely different paths.</i><br>
<p>
There is no compromise with Divine Truth.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Should we change the pillars of our faith to be more accomodating for those </i><br>
<i>&gt; who don't believe ? If so then where do we draw the line ?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I have passed through a number of different churches before I became a<br>
SDA-ist.  Wherever I have gone, the issue of legalism is always raised and<br>
discussed as though it is a difficult concept to grasp.  On one extreme there<br>
are those who argue that belief in the Grace imparted through Calvary is<br>
sufficient and that no good works are necessary.  The proponents of this<br>
thinking turn a deaf ear (and blind eye) to scripture -- "Faith without works<br>
is dead".  On the other extreme are those who preach and pursue the Law,<br>
paying meticulous attention to the letter of the Law and little or none to the<br>
spirit in which It was coded.<br>
<p>
Is the issue really so difficult to state clearly?<br>
<p>
The primary mistake with the former extreme seems to be the definition of<br>
'belief' in salvation.  Those who hold to this seem to constrain the term<br>
'belief' to a passive sense (i.e., the mere intellectual acceptance of an<br>
idea) rather than the active, dynamic tenor which the gospel implies.  To<br>
believe in Christ implies the complete acceptance of everything which is<br>
Christ's -- including good works.  (A mere passive belief makes us no<br>
better than Satan.)  Our works ARE necessary for salvation, but they are<br>
not sufficient!  The Salvation wrought by Christ is both necessary and<br>
sufficient (with the qualifier) for those who completely accepts Christ!<br>
-- this embraces the Law.<br>
<p>
Nevertheless, it is foolish to take this to the opposite extreme and begin to<br>
worship the Law.  We were created to be stewards of all that the Lord has<br>
given us.  Just as the earth is a part of the House of Heaven, the Law is the<br>
House Policy.  As good stewards we are expected to abide by that Policy.<br>
However, just as it is foolish to worship creation besides the Creator, it is<br>
likewise ridiculous to worship the Law besides the Law Giver.<br>
<p>
Legalism, then, is merely another manifestation of idolatry and a violation of<br>
the first two commandments.  I don't think EGW or any other prophet gave<br>
any impression of worshipping the Law and, hence, cannot be properly<br>
labelled as legalists.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
------------------------<br>
John A. Prosper<br>
prosper@cs.fsu.edu<br>
prosper@magnet.fsu.edu<br>
------------------------<br>
