<title>Jun_1993: Beng's Letter</title>
<h1>Beng's Letter</h1>
<i>ronswen@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 07 Jun 93 05:13:29 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#87">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#87">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#87">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#87">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Guns, guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0086.html">Dan Crowe: "Sexual Immorality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve:<br>
<p>
I read Beng's letter with great interest and to some extent sadness.  I too<br>
have grown up Adventist and have heard the term "lukewarm" applied to us as<br>
long as I can remember, even before celebration churches existed or before we<br>
seriously debated whether to accept into fellowship homosexual or transsexual<br>
individuals or before members felt it appropriate to go gambling or to the<br>
movies.  (Lest I sound too much like a grandpa, I am 34, but the church has<br>
changed a lot since the 1960's when I was growing up, much of it for the<br>
better.)  Behavior is different now but the underlying problem is still the<br>
same.  We need more personal Godliness.<br>
<p>
Beng quoted the passage from Revelation to the church in Laodicea and in it<br>
is a beautiful promise: "Behold I stand at the door and knock: if any man<br>
hear my voice, and open the door, I will come in to him and will sup with<br>
him, and he with me." Rev. 3:20.  My favorite example of Christ having supper<br>
with people is in Luke 24:13-35.  This story is life changing.  It tells the<br>
story of two men returning from Jerusalem devastated because Jesus had been<br>
crucified.  They said with downcast faces, "we had hoped that he was the one<br>
who was going to redeem Isreal" Luke 24:21.  Christ, unknown to the men,<br>
began to walk with them and to unfold the scriptural story.  He revealed how<br>
all of the events which the travellers had witnessed were fulfillments of<br>
prophecy.  He then joined them for supper and "When He was at the table with<br>
them he took bread, gave thanks, broke it and began to give it to them.  <br>
Then their eyes were opened and they recognized Him, and He disappeared from<br>
their sight."  Luke 24:30-31.  Their lives were changed!!!  They ran back to<br>
Jerusalem and became part of the group which testified of Jesus as the Risen<br>
Lord.  40 days later the Holy Spirit exploded upon Jerusalem in the "sound<br>
like the blowing of a violent wind" (Acts 2:2) and tongues of fire were seen<br>
over the heads of the believers.  Peter, speaking by inspiration of the Holy<br>
Spirit traced the story from the words of the prophet Joel and King David. <br>
Peter also repeated the call to "Repent and be baptised every one of you in<br>
the name of Jesus Christ for the forgiveness of your sins.  And you will<br>
receive the gift of the Holy Spirit."(Acts 2:38)  <br>
<p>
We are not the inheritors of a dead tradition but instead we are the<br>
spiritual children of a Living God.  When we are called to repent we are<br>
called out of ourselves into a better life of freedom in Christ.  We are<br>
promised power to deliver us from our sins.  If God calls homosexuality sin<br>
(1Cor.6:9-11), those of us who have this affliction are promised power to<br>
escape this sin.  If God calls adultery or fornication sin, those tempted are<br>
promised power to escape.  This is also true of gambling, backbiting, hatred,<br>
pride or any other disgusting human fraility.<br>
<p>
In saying this, I don't suggest that we should set ourselves up as spiritual<br>
"judge, jury and executioner".  Rather, let us follow the advice of 1Cor. 13<br>
and Colossians 3.  "Therefore, as God's chosen people, holy and dearly loved,<br>
clothe yourselves with compassion, kindness, humility, gentleness and<br>
patience.  Bear with each other and forgive whatever grievances you may have<br>
against one another.  Forgive as the Lord forgave you.  And over all these<br>
virtues put on love, which binds them all together in perfect unity." Col.<br>
3:12-14.  Those individuals who struggle with sin in all of its forms should<br>
be welcomed into fellowship and treated with love.  Anyone who sins be it<br>
adulterers, homosexuals, gossips, proud imperious "jerks" or whoever they may<br>
be are to be made welcome unless they refuse to follow Jesus.<br>
<p>
I am excited by what the Bible says.  It promises us power and hope.  Read<br>
some of these passages and see if you don't agree!!!<br>
<p>
<p>
Thanks for reading,<br>
Ron Swensen<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
