<title>Jun_1993: RE: Big brother</title>
<h1>RE: Big brother</h1>
Archau (<i>archau@wwc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 7 Jun 93 13:01</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#90">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#90">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#90">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#90">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Steven Timm: "The Two and the Ten"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "RE: Homosexuals and the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0108.html">Fred Christiansen: "RE: Big brother"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have read the various posts relating to guns with increasing degrees of <br>
alarm.  The idea that the constitutional provision with respect to the <br>
bearing of arms will in anyway help us in the day of persecution is so <br>
foreign to my understanding of last-day events as taught in Adventism that <br>
I truly wonder whether I belong to the same church that some of my fellow <br>
SDAnetters do. <br>
<p>
There seem to be two problems wrong with this notion.<br>
1.  There is no reference in the New Testament scripture of christians <br>
resisting persecution by "defending themselves."  On the contrary, the <br>
experience of Jesus and the apostles was always a humble, even joyful <br>
acceptance of persecution. There is also the example of Paul using the <br>
legal means at his disposal and appealing to Rome.  But never is there a <br>
hint of physical self-defence.   Indeed, one wouAnd one would expect no <br>
less of person's whose ethical charter is the Sermon on the Mount ... "love <br>
your enemies","pray for those who persecute you" etc. Would Hus, for <br>
example, have been better of arming himself against the Bohemian <br>
authorities?  Christ said "If my kingdom were of this world, then would my <br>
servants fight"<br>
<p>
2.  The emphasis, even reliance on the U. S. constitution as some kind of <br>
hedge during the time of trouble ignores the fact that in the very <br>
interpretation of end-time events that is being appealed to, this very <br>
constitution would be perverted (as EGW says) as a precursor to the end <br>
time persecution.  I personally have some concerns about the <br>
Americanization of our doctrinal positions, and would question how the <br>
Sunday Law would apply to muslim countries, for example.  But within the <br>
accepted interpretation, arming ourselves is an aberrant (and abhorrent as <br>
well)  position, both to the spirit of Christanity in general and to <br>
Adventism in particular.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
