<!-- received="Mon Jun 07 15:58:00 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Mon, 7 Jun 93 15:58:00 PDT" -->
<!-- name="Steve Hix" -->
<!-- email="fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Gun, Guns" -->
<!-- id="9306072258.AA23050@dobbs.Eng.Sun.COM" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Gun, Guns" -->
<title>Jun_1993: Re: Gun, Guns</title>
<h1>Re: Gun, Guns</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 7 Jun 93 15:58:00 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#96">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#96">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#96">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#96">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0097.html">Fred Christiansen: "an extract from Steve &amp; Darius' exchange"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0095.html">Steve Hix: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu (Harvey Brenneise)</i><br>
<i>&gt; Randall Helperman writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Radical statement:  </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Americans need guns to protect themselves against their own government.</i><br>
<p>
I'd amend that to read that we do need to protect ourselves (and<br>
others) from excesses of our own government.  There are a wide range<br>
of tools for doing so, guns being only one, and the last of all, at<br>
that.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt; 1.  The people who wrote the constitution recognized this.  That is why it </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;     was written into the constitution.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; It's Friday afternoon, and I'm going to be foolish enough to jump into</i><br>
<i>&gt; this again.  It is true that the Founding Fathers placed this in the</i><br>
<i>&gt; constitution.  One must also remember that this was 200 years ago (and</i><br>
<i>&gt; has been pointed out, but society and weapons technology were quite</i><br>
<i>&gt; different), immediately after an armed rebellion against the government</i><br>
<i>&gt; and in a society struggling to tame a wilderness.</i><br>
<p>
Puckle, and others, had described in patent applications and otherwise<br>
every workable method for fully-automatic firearms before the 1770's.<br>
Franklin, if not Jefferson, probably were aware of these technical<br>
explorations, and I doubt if they missed many of the most obvious<br>
implications of such weapons.  Still...  <br>
<p>
The Founding Fathers (FF's hereafter) could not have imagined radio,<br>
television, media marketing, laser printers, and the like either. The<br>
fact of the existence of such do not invalidate the utility of the<br>
First Amendment, while they might make its existence less comfortable<br>
than it was even then.<br>
<p>
While the overall shape of society is different now, the basic<br>
problems of acquiring needs, criminal threat, abuses of power by<br>
govenments and individuals was there then, and are still with us.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; While it is true that many women own guns, they constitute a minority.</i><br>
<p>
One of the most important purposes of our nation's construction (not<br>
forgetting all you non-USAnians here!) is the protection of the rights<br>
of minorities of all sorts who might deviate from majority practice or<br>
thought.  Toleration, at least.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  [Are guns a phallic symbol in our society?]</i><br>
<p>
Not according to a number of studies on the question.  The only ones I've<br>
met who seem to think so, also tend to not own or use guns.  But then, I<br>
don't deal with psych/sociology if I can help it. I can barely keep up<br>
with computers.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I know in England the police often aren't even armed with firearms.</i><br>
<p>
This is becoming less and less the case.  Metropolitan areas are beginning<br>
to use more special armed squads available for use in situations where<br>
the local unarmed police are outmatched.  Their violent-crime rate is rising<br>
quite a bit faster than the the U.S. rate, and the number of with-gun<br>
violent crimes is rising with it.  (Before the first of the modern gun-control<br>
laws was enacted in the early 1920's, England's rate was about 1.20th of<br>
the U.S. rate at the same time, now it's closer to about 1/4th.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Perhaps Gandhi's ideals of non-violence would be a better model (as</i><br>
<i>&gt; they are for the Mennonites).</i><br>
<p>
Gandhi's use of ahimsa would not have worked as well, perhaps at all, had<br>
India been part of someone else's empire.  The British were, on the whole,<br>
basically sympathetic to his goals.  If India had been part of, say, a<br>
1940's German empire...<br>
<p>
But his approach is certainly worth emulation, even as one should not<br>
underestimate the potential costs. (Remember what happened to Gandhi,<br>
both Mohandas and Indira, in the end. And what has gone on in India <br>
since then.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I simply refuse to be paranoid about "last day events" and the need</i><br>
<i>&gt; for a gun to protect my rights.</i><br>
<p>
You're probably right there.  The gun you don't want (and I wouldn't<br>
want to force anyone to take up arms if they don't want to, and would<br>
discourage anyone from taking them up otherwise) is *not* the only<br>
tool that (may) be needed for "protecting my rights". If used at all,<br>
it should be the very last resort.<br>
<p>
But one shouldn't think that *no* tools should be taken up for this<br>
sort of effort. Prayer first, other action to follow.<br>
<p>
While it looks as though secularization is proceeding inexorably in<br>
our society, don't forget that there have been (and likely will be)<br>
wild swings in public mood regarding such things.  There have been<br>
great swings in U.S. history, from religious to secular, from temperance<br>
to non.<br>
<p>
Imagine the possibility of the U.S. economy getting *really* wrecked.<br>
Imagine that a liberal administration were perceived as the cause of the<br>
trouble. A huge conservative backlash ("to return to the values and<br>
goals that made our country great") might follow, with the doers of evil<br>
being enthusiastically punished.  And if things didn't get better quickly,<br>
how likely that the label of "evildoer" might not spread out wider and<br>
wider, until anyone deviating from the "norm" might be swept into the<br>
net.<br>
<p>
Could czarist Russia have foreseen the Stalinist era back in 1893? Could<br>
any German have believed that Hitler and the Nazi's might arise from<br>
thirty or forty years before?<br>
<p>
The devil doesn't care if we're vigilant or not...he does what he can<br>
get away with.<br>
<p>
I hope I'm wrong.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; We need more of the love of Jesus.</i><br>
<p>
Now *that* has not, and will not, change.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; That's probably enough to get me in trouble today.</i><br>
<p>
Isn't that what email is for? :}<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
