<title>Jun_1993: Re: Guns, guns</title>
<h1>Re: Guns, guns</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 7 Jun 93 16:28:31 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "RE: Homosexuals and the church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Beng's Letter"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0058.html">lsusers: "Guns, guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: "lsusers"  &lt;LSARCHER@scifac.indstate.edu&gt;</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; As, it progressed,</i><br>
<i>&gt; we began to see more of what I consider ludicrous arguments about</i><br>
<i>&gt; defending ourselves against tyrannical governments, and end time</i><br>
<i>&gt; persecution.  </i><br>
<p>
The U.S. Army, while not specifically interested in end-time events,<br>
does concern itself with fighting against irregular forces.  In short,<br>
they don't like the idea...it's very expensive for the regulars.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Although this may seem to be a reasonable view to some,</i><br>
<i>&gt; are we really suggesting that as persecuted Christians we will defend</i><br>
<i>&gt; ourselves with automatic weapons or whatever weapons our laws allow?</i><br>
<p>
Not necessarily...there are other ways of doing the job.<br>
<p>
A lot of people don't realize that there are something between 600K<br>
and 1M with-gun defenses each year in the U.S. (Hart, 1981; Mauser, 1990;<br>
about six other studies of less usefulness, dealing with local populations.)<br>
The *vast* majority do not end with injury or death (or attacker or defender),<br>
most don't even involve firing the gun.  In most cases, once the agressor knows<br>
that the defender is armed, the attack is broken off.<br>
<p>
This sort of usage, btw, is more in line with the likeliest reason<br>
for citizens' weapon ownership being useful in restraining excesses<br>
of a government; it becomes less certain that said government might<br>
feel it could get away something shady.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Somalia is my example of gun ownership run amok; where the limitation</i><br>
<i>&gt; of weapons to the citizenry would help rather than hurt.</i><br>
<p>
The average Somali can't get weapons, while the warlord bands have no<br>
effective curb to their excesses. It might be useful if Somalia had a<br>
government to deal with the warlords...but as it is, some can exercise<br>
force, the majority have no way to counter them.<br>
<p>
I'm not saying, btw, that arming everyone will make things better...but<br>
*everyone* being armed is *not* what is causing the trouble in the<br>
country.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If our kingdom is of this world, then we should fight.</i><br>
<p>
Granted. (But then, there is fighting, and there is fighting.  Different<br>
opponents, different problems, different tools, different solutions.)<br>
<p>
In the story of Esther, the end result of Haman's machinations was that,<br>
since the law couldn't be changed, the Jews were permitted to take up<br>
arms in their own defense...and the expected slaughter didn't take place.<br>
<p>
Why did Jesus, in Luke 22: 35-36 say that the disciples acquire arms<br>
(a sword was the local equivalent of a handgun) for their personal<br>
defense?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Since it is</i><br>
<i>&gt; not,  I will never buy a gun, own a gun, or use a gun (and since I'm</i><br>
<i>&gt; a vegetarian, I don't plan to do any hunting).</i><br>
<p>
OK (but I think you're mixing more than one issue here).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I respect the</i><br>
<i>&gt; constitutional rights of everyone who under law desires to own</i><br>
<i>&gt; weapons, but I will retain the right to do without one.</i><br>
<p>
Excellent. I respect your choice.<br>
<p>
Some would coerce others to conform to their point of view, whichever <br>
side would do that would be wrong.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
