<!-- subject="Re: Radiation from Tobacco?" -->
<!-- id="9306161439.AA22348@ccu.UManitoba.CA" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Radiation from Tobacco?" -->
<title>Jun_1993: Re: Radiation from Tobacco?</title>
<h1>Re: Radiation from Tobacco?</h1>
Tino (<i>constant@gn.ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 7 Jun 93 20:57:37 GMT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#200">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#200">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#200">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#200">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0201.html">Dan Crowe: "Truth and Time"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0199.html">Tino: "Re: Radiation from Tobacco?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In article &lt;1v03a1INN3rr@gap.caltech.edu&gt; mason@cco.caltech.edu (Richard Mason) writes:<br>
<i>&gt;I have heard several times that smokers receive a (relatively) high</i><br>
<i>&gt;radiation dose because they inhale radioactives (radon daughters?)</i><br>
<i>&gt;which were in the tobacco.</i><br>
<i>&gt;However, I haven't heard, or don't recall, where the radon comes from.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Is there some good reason radon should be on tobacco leaves?  Why not</i><br>
<i>&gt;on &lt;other crop&gt;?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Email replies appreciated.</i><br>
<p>
I'm following up on the group because I think that this is an important<br>
topic. From Tino's embryonic nuclear faq:<br>
<p>
Average annual individual doses in mrems from natural and man-made         <br>
radiation sources:<br>
<p>
Source                   Exposed Group    Body Portion Exposed    Indiv. Dose<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Natural Radiation:<br>
  External sources:<br>
    Cosmic Rays          Total population      whole body              28<br>
    Terrestial gammas    Total population      whole body              26<br>
    Radon and daughters  Total population      bronchial epithelium  ~150<br>
<p>
Man-made Radiation:<br>
  Tobacco                Smokers (1.5 packs/d) bronchial epithelium  8000<br>
<p>
The tobacco leaf is rather large, and in the growing season, has the      <br>
opportunity to pick up a lot of Polonium-210, which, like radon, is a<br>
daughter product of natural uranium and thorium decay. According to LaMarsh <br>
(Intro. to Nuclear Eng.), Radon, a noble gas, can diffuse out of the ground<br>
into the atmosphere. When it decays down to Po-210, the dust or moisture<br>
that it has attached itself to can land on a leaf. When you smoke it, you<br>
trap that isotope in your lungs. It happily decays away, kicking off<br>
5.3 MeV alpha particles with a half-life of 138 days. Since alpha particles<br>
are the worst form of ionizing radiation to have trapped in your body, they<br>
do a fine job of destroying any lung tissue that surrounds them.<br>
<p>
The tobacco industry and the medical profession know this, and one group<br>
doesn't want to admit it. The reason other plants don't bother you is because<br>
alpha particles can get flushed out of your digestive system, but _not_ out<br>
of the lungs.<br>
<p>
If everyone knew just what the hell was going into their body (and not coming<br>
out), I suspect the human lifespan would increase noticeably...<br>
<p>
At your service,<br>
<p>
Tino<br>
<pre>
-- 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Hundreds of millions of people will soon perish in smog disasters in New York
 and Los Angeles...the oceans will die of DDT poisoning by 1979...the U.S. life
 expectancy will drop to 42 years by 1980 due to cancer epidemics."         
                       
                              - Paul Ehrlich, 1969
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
