<title>Jun_1993: Of guns and rights...</title>
<h1>Of guns and rights...</h1>
David Klein - EECS (<i>dklein@dribble.eecs.wsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 7 Jun 93 21:37:01 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#101">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#101">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#101">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#101">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0102.html">Marcus Stringer: "FW: Helpful Reading"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0100.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think guns &amp; gun control has been hashed out now to the point where<br>
we are beginning to repeat ourselves.  There have been good arguements<br>
on both sides of the story.  I saved this clipping of this letter to the<br>
editor from WSU's student newspaper, The Evergreen.  It appears that <br>
they were having an arguement much like ours.  Although the approach<br>
is simplistic, I think there is a little truth is what he says.<br>
<p>
GIVE PEACE A CHANCE, PLEASE<br>
<p>
Editor:<br>
  I would like to make a few comments about the apparent debate columns <br>
concerning the right bear arms published the 10th of February.<br>
  No one denies the fact that guns are able to take a human life.  Then<br>
again, so do cars, cancer and cheese burgers.  The question is, will<br>
removing the rights of the citizen to keep and bear arms reduce its death<br>
toll.<br>
  The answer is, it probably would.  But, at what cost to individual<br>
rights and liberties?<br>
  Let's suppose, for arguement's sake, that I wanted you dead and that all<br>
registered firearms were suddenly transmorgified into Petunias.  How<br>
would I get the job done?  Among others, I could reach into my closet and<br>
pull out my legally unregistered black powder, muzzle loading, Kentucky<br>
long rifle which I legally bought at age 15 without a waiting period.<br>
True, it is only a single shot, but I am pretty confident you would have<br>
at least a bad powder burn and some lost hearing.  The point is that <br>
owning a deadly weapon such as a gun, bow and arrow, baseball bat, pointy<br>
stick or catapult is not the activity a government should be regulating.<br>
The wanton taking of human life is the activity which needs to be<br>
addressed more closely.<br>
  However, there is a point to one of the anti-gun movement's arguements.<br>
The world would be a nicer place to live in if all guns were banned.  All<br>
guns, meaning yours, mine, Bosnia's, Somalia's, Iran's, Israel's, US<br>
military's, police, big guns, artillery, flying guns, floating guns, <br>
nuclear guns.  I wish I could see that day.<br>
<p>
  Andrew Peek<br>
<p>
All spelling errors and mistypes are mine.<br>
<p>
BTW: I own two guns.  Used to make pretty good money in South Dakota <br>
shooting rats at the dump.  Some old ladies got real mad at the city <br>
when their cats died from eating poisoned rats.  No, I don't hunt for<br>
food.  Yes, I do shoot feral dogs.  Particularly after they ate one of <br>
my cat's and attacked a little kid two miles down the road from my home <br>
in New Mexico.  Would I shoot a human?  No, although I have had a legal <br>
chance to.  Our house lives on a mesa close to a route that illegal <br>
mexicans like to take north.  Our neighbors, although close, can not see <br>
the house.  Thus, on occasion, attempts have been made to steal things from<br>
our yard or break into our house.  I will say this:  It was amazing how<br>
fast a person dropped its knife and disappeared when I let fly into the <br>
the ground several yards behind the window it was forcing.  However, I<br>
must warn you that this is not a way to encourage your trees to grow when<br>
you shoot with a .44 magnum.  And yes, I was praying pretty hard and not<br>
a litle scared.  Dad didn't like the hole in his tree (the second one I've<br>
managed to mangle) and my ears rang for a week.  But dad does like the<br>
knife the person left behind.<br>
Hmmm... the wild west is over, eh?<br>
<p>
Food for thought, no?<br>
<p>
Cheers!<br>
<p>
David<br>
<pre>
-- 
David J. Klein - dklein@eecs.wsu.edu
Electrical Engineering - Computer Science
Washington State University - Pullman
</pre>
