<title>Jun_1993: Re: sex changes, divorce</title>
<h1>Re: sex changes, divorce</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  7 Jun 1993 22:20:45 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#83">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#83">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#83">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#83">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0082.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: sex changes"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0082.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: sex changes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0112.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: sex changes, divorce"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Darius suggests that offering baptism to the transexual person would be the<br>
same as offering baptism to the remarried (improperly) person in a divorce.<br>
<p>
Such a statement assumes that there are still any teeth in the church's <br>
policy on divorce and remarriage.  Such is not the case.  It is not unheard<br>
of today for man and wife to divorce, both remarry, and both remain in <br>
the SDA ministry, not to mention membership.  Perhaps the policy was <br>
ill-advised from the start, but as far as I can tell it is now non-existent.<br>
I've not heard of anyone being under church discipline for divorce and <br>
remarriage for the last ten years.<br>
<p>
Perhaps this is why the homosexual argument now has more hearing than it <br>
once did.  If the church could say that it really treats all of what it terms<br>
adultery the same way, then there would not be so much accusation of <br>
singling one group out.  But divorce, even among the ministry, has become<br>
so common that the rationalizers have rationalized "the majority do it, <br>
so it must be OK."<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
