<title>Jun_1993: Re: Questions from the net.atheists</title>
<h1>Re: Questions from the net.atheists</h1>
David Klein - EECS (<i>dklein@dribble.eecs.wsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 7 Jun 93 22:41:14 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#105">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#105">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#105">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#105">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0106.html">LAINIE@delphi.com: "Re: Religious liberty dangers from the new left:"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0104.html">David P. Harris: "Re: Notes on the day of Penteco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>|I am a "recovering Catholic;"  that is to say, I have almost purged all of the</i><br>
<i>|detrimental teachings of that particular sect from my brain.  I spent a year</i><br>
<i>|in the seminary, on my way to becoming a priest (or so I thought).  I give you</i><br>
<i>|this background to let you know that my search for God (long since abandoned)</i><br>
<i>|is no fly by night, passing concern.  </i><br>
<i>|</i><br>
<i>|Here's the question that no Christian can answer.  How do you know God's will?</i><br>
<i>| Let's assume you need to make a very important decision, and in Christian</i><br>
<i>|fervor pray over the matter in order to discover God's will.  You pray, and</i><br>
<i>|some sign or another (which you of course interpret as a sign, using your</i><br>
<i>|mind) comes to you.  You then decide what to do.  Note those words *YOU*</i><br>
<i>|*Decide* what to do.  </i><br>
<i>|</i><br>
<i>|If one wants to pass off the responsibility for making a decision to what one</i><br>
<i>|perceives as God and his will, that is your right.  However, ultimately</i><br>
<i>|knowing what to do is up to the thinking individual, even *if* you deign to</i><br>
<i>|call the decision God's will.</i><br>
<p>
This one has bothered me for awhile too.  I've seen people pray and pray and<br>
never able to make a decision on their own without some "sign" from God, what<br>
ever that might be.  I've also seen people hide their own failings behind God.<br>
I've finally decided on the following method:<br>
<p>
1. I take a good look at the examples of decisions made by people in the Bible,<br>
what little history I know and comtemporary people I know and respect.  And I<br>
pray.<br>
<p>
2. Then I make a decision, and tell God what I've decided to do and ask for<br>
his input.  A basic "if this isn't right for me, close the door." kind of<br>
prayer.<br>
<p>
3. If whatever endevor I'm undertaking blows up or for some reason doesn't<br>
happen, I'm responsible.  And if it does work, I'm still responsible.  But it<br>
sure is nice when God supports you.  At least, I choose to interpret some<br>
things that have happened in my life as unexplainable except for God taking<br>
a hand.<br>
<p>
Perhaps it is not the most theologically stable method, but it means I can <br>
get things done without wearing out my knees and always wondering if what <br>
I'm hearing is God's "sign" to me.  However, I've walked out on a limb and <br>
cut it off behind me before.  It is interesting that God &amp; I generally managed <br>
to pick me up quicker when I tried to figure out what might have been better<br>
then just sitting there blaiming God.<br>
<p>
Yeah, it would be nice to have a god that would always clearly point out what<br>
he wants for us or what is best for us.  But that would take all the fun out<br>
of life.  Where would the challenge of being an individual be?  But I do think<br>
that if I take the time to look at all sides of the problem: past, present,<br>
future, and what God might have in mind, I make a much better decision.  <br>
<p>
Note:  By saying what God might have in mind, I mean what the picture of God<br>
I have in my head would have in mind.  And the real God has gone and proved<br>
my picture pretty flawed in the past.<br>
<p>
Cheers!<br>
<p>
David<br>
<pre>
-- 
David J. Klein - dklein@eecs.wsu.edu      | I have to live today by what truth
Electrical Engineering - Computer Science | I can get today, and be ready 
Washington State University - Pullman     | tomorrow to call it falsehood.
------------------------------------------|
These are my thoughts and plagarisms...   | (Adapted from William James.)
</pre>
