<title>Jun_1993: The Two and the Ten</title>
<h1>The Two and the Ten</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  7 Jun 1993 22:51:32 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#91">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#91">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#91">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#91">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0092.html">Randall A Helzerman: ""Arsenal" at Waco? (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0090.html">Archau: "RE: Big brother"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Marcus posted recently in reference to the Two and the Ten, <br>
being different representations but all part of the one Law of God.<br>
Though he didn't mention it specifically, this is one of the ideas <br>
found in Alden Thompson's book, "Inspiration".  It is also Alden Thompson<br>
who includes as prefaces to his book both the introduction to the Great<br>
Controversy and the several sections of Selected Messages to which Marcus<br>
is referring.  I own this book and have read it several times, and I think <br>
most of the ideas are good ideas that deserve much more hearing.<br>
<p>
Applying this principle to guns:<br>
"Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself" from the Two<br>
"Thou shalt not kill" from the Ten.<br>
<p>
Nevertheless we know of many situations in the Bible where God ordered<br>
others to kill.  Saul was punished for not killing the Amalekites.<br>
The children of Israel were supposed to totally destroy the various <br>
Canaanite tribes.  Then there are all the crimes in the law of Moses<br>
for which the death penalty was prescribed.  There are instructions<br>
in the Bible to "beat the plowshares into swords."  (and vice versa).<br>
Then there is the story of Elisha calling fire from heaven down on <br>
the companies of soldiers.  And we musn't forget the various plagues<br>
that the Lord sent first on the Egyptians, then on the children of Israel<br>
as they wandered in the wilderness.<br>
<p>
(There is another book by Alden Thompson called "Who's afraid of the <br>
Old Testament God", which I have not yet read.  I understand it speaks to<br>
these issues and more.)<br>
<p>
If we are to view the Bible as casebook and not codebook, what does this<br>
suggest as to how we are to handle the issues of violence.  We may safely<br>
say that those episodes are not only to boost the Bible's ratings.  <br>
Looking at what God and Jesus did is only the first step.  There are things<br>
that Jesus did that I couldn't do myself without it being a sin for me.<br>
(Driving the money-changers out of the temple with the cord, for instance).<br>
Through the guidance of the Holy Spirit I believe we can learn to know<br>
what actions we can undertake in the name of God while still possessing <br>
the spirit of God.<br>
<p>
One of the questions that is in the big list of questions from alt.atheism<br>
is <br>
<p>
"If your God told you to take a rifle and go out and start shooting people,<br>
would you do it?"  We can't say it doesn't happen because it did happen.<br>
<p>
How to answer?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
