<title>Jun_1993: FW: Helpful Reading</title>
<h1>FW: Helpful Reading</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  8 Jun 93 00:01:20 PST </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#102">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#102">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#102">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#102">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Homosexuals and the church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0101.html">David Klein - EECS: "Of guns and rights..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here are a few books on Spirituality in dealing with women/AIDS/sex roles<br>
and sexual orientation issues.<br>
<p>
None are SDA books, maybe there's already a FAQ listing them.<br>
I know Ron Springett from Southern College wrote a book a few years ago.<br>
I made this list about a year ago, and am pleased to say that since then,<br>
quite a bit more has been written about each subject.  I hope this helps<br>
people.<br>
=================<br>
1.   "The Example of Jesus"  by Michael Griffiths<br>
	Griffiths explores the meaning and significance of Jesus' example<br>
	for today's Christians.  A "Jesus Library" book.<br>
		204 pages, paperback, $8.95<br>
2.   "With Both Eyes Open"  by Patricia Johnson &amp; Janet Kalven<br>
	The human species... has been driving down the highway of life with<br>
	one eye (the female) held firmly closed, says Elizabeth Dobson Gray.<br>
	This book encourages a second look at patriarchal  Christian<br>
	theology from a more balanced perspective.<br>
		201 pages, paperback, $10.95<br>
3.   "AIDS and the Church"  by Earl Shelp/Ronald Sunderland<br>
	This book takes a sensitive look at how the church, clergy, and laity<br>
	should respond to 	the growing crisis of AIDS.  Also describes various<br>
	ways of ministering to those with AIDS and shows how the church<br>
	should set the example for all of society.<br>
		151 pages, paperback, $8.95<br>
4.   "Is the Homosexual my Neighbor?"  by Letha Scanzoni/Virginia Mollenkott<br>
	Blends painstaking Biblical and theological research with the best<br>
	recent psychological and sociological findings.  Offers guidelines and<br>
	invites Christians to develop a response to homosexuality that expresses<br>
	Christ's principles - not prejudices of the world.<br>
		159 pages, paperback, $9.95<br>
5.   "Women of Faith In Dialogue"  by Virginia R. Mollenkott<br>
	 In a unique dialogue project sponsored by the American Jewish<br>
	Committee, eighteen women of faith - Protestant, Catholic, Jewish, and<br>
	Muslim - discuss the challenges that confront women in the respective<br>
	communities of faith.<br>
		144 pages, paperback, $9.95<br>
6.   "Homosexuality and the Conservative Christian"  by L. Robert Arthur<br>
	A brief, concise explanation of each of the Biblical 'clobber passages'<br>
	written from the view of a conservative Christian.  Rev. Robert Arthur holds<br>
	a Masters of Arts degree in Bible from Bob Jones University in Greenville,<br>
	South Carolina.  Recommended reading for those struggling with what the<br>
	Bible says about the subject of homosexuality.<br>
		13 pages, paperback, $2.50<br>
7.   "A Directory of Women in Church History"  by Mary L. Hammack<br>
	Concise, factual, scholarly definitions make this work a valuable tool for<br>
	the student, pastor, or professional.  Nearly 1,000 entries drawn from the<br>
	first century to the present.<br>
		167 pages, hardback,$11.95<br>
8.   "AIDS, the Spiritual Dilemma"  by John E. Fortunado<br>
	This informative, sensitive book is exactly what's needed to answer the<br>
	witches' brew of ignorance, prejudice, half-truths, and whole lies evoked<br>
	by  the word AIDS.  Fortunado is a therapist to gay and straight, to those<br>
	dying of [living with] AIDS and those by the grace of God more fortunate.<br>
		156 pages, paperback, $8.95<br>
9.   "Living in Sin"  by Bishop John Shelby Spong<br>
	This book looks at the historical development of male-dominated society<br>
	and religion, new findings about the causes of homosexuality, and changes<br>
	in marriage practices among better educated and longer living people.<br>
	Also included are chapters on what Bishop Spong believes should be the<br>
	church's positive and pastoral response to the changing pattern of human<br>
	relationships.<br>
		253 pages, hardbound, $16.95<br>
10.  "Goodbye, I Love You"  by Carol Lynn Pearson<br>
	The story of a couple's struggle as a husband comes out and reconciles his<br>
	sexuality.  Later, the wife is by his side as he deals with AIDS.<br>
		227 pages, paperback, $3.95<br>
11.   "Daughters of the Church"  by Ruth A. Tucker/ Walter Liefeld<br>
	Rich in historic events and colorfully written, this fascinating account of<br>
	women in the Church spans nearly two thousand years of church history.<br>
	This volume is enriched by pictures, appendices, bibliography, and indexes.<br>
		552 pages, paperback, $15.95<br>
12.  "Christianity Social Tolerance &amp; Homosexuality"  by John Boswell<br>
	One of the most extensive treatments on the subject.  Challenges, received<br>
	opinion, and preconceptions about the Church's [Catholic] past relationship<br>
	to its gay members, among whom were priests, and even bishops and<br>
	canonized  saints.  Well researched.<br>
		424 pages, paperback, $12.95<br>
13.  "Dirt, Greed and Sex"  by L. William Countryman<br>
	A direct, simple, solid piece of scholarly work which can profitably inform<br>
	even the casual reader.  Much care is taken to 'unwrap' the New Testament<br>
	passages which form directly and indirectly how we think about issues of<br>
	human sexuality.<br>
		288 pages, hardbound, $19.95<br>
14.  "The Church and the Homosexual"  by John J. McNeill S.J.<br>
	Condemned by the Catholic Church for its message of spiritual fulfillment for<br>
	gays and lesbians, this classic book has recently been updated with new<br>
	material on AIDS, gay and lesbian sexuality, and McNeil's own struggle with<br>
	the Catholic Church.<br>
		280 pages, paperback, updated ed. $9.95<br>
15.  "Intimate Connections"  by James Nelson<br>
	This is not a book about so-called 'real men'; it is a book about<br>
	"whole men."  Nelson asserts that men and women seek something the<br>
	sexual revolution did not provide: an understanding of the true meaning of<br>
	love.  Topics include: the genitalization of sex to the neglect of <br>
intimacy and<br>
	sensuousness; a sense of separation that works against true intimacy; the<br>
	difficulties men have in establishing friends, particularly with other <br>
men, and<br>
	the need for friendship with God.<br>
		140 pp., paperback, $8.95<br>
16.  "Gay/Lesbian Liberation: A Biblical Perspective"  by George R. Edwards<br>
	This book shows, on Biblical grounds, that gay/lesbian liberation rightfully<br>
	belongs to the genre of liberation theology, that the homophobic rejection<br>
	of gay/lesbian persons by the churches and synagogue cannot claim<br>
	Biblical sanction.<br>
		153 pages, paperback, $9.95<br>
17. "Pastoral Ministry in the AIDS Era"  by Louis Kavar<br>
	Utilizing a developmental theory for living with chronic illness, Kavar<br>
	examines the experience of families living with AIDS.  Case studies <br>
illustrate<br>
	the role of pastoral intervention.  Family, in this work, includes <br>
both biological<br>
	and chosen relatedness.<br>
		61 pages, paperback, $7.95<br>
18.  "Beyond Sex Roles"  by Gilbert Bilezikian<br>
	A guide for study of female roles in the Bible.  This is a first-rate <br>
Biblical,<br>
	theological study by a committed evangelical teacher that affirms full<br>
	equality of the sexes in church and family.<br>
		300 pages, paperback, $12.95<br>
19.  "Women, Men &amp; The Bible"  by Virginia R. Mollenkott<br>
	The classic text supporting an attitude of 'mutual submission' between<br>
	persons.<br>
		144 pages, paperback, (updated/revised), $9.95<br>
20.  "Embracing the Exile: Healing Journeys of gay Christians"  by John <br>
E. Fortunado<br>
	Gay and Christian.  Cornerstones of who I am.  And, though it hasn't always<br>
	been so, 	I've come to believe that both are good.<br>
		137 pages, paperback, $8.95<br>
21.  "Embodiment, An Approach to Sexuality"  by James B. Nelson<br>
	A first-class study in theological ethics.  The comprehensive and<br>
	imaginative treatment sets both traditional and unconventional sexuality<br>
	issues within the context of God's fulfilling grace.<br>
		303 pages, paperback, $12.95<br>
22.  "Between Two Gardens"  by James Nelson<br>
	Continuation of "Embodiment,".<br>
		193 pages, paperback, $8.95<br>
23.  "The Ten Commandments For Today"  by William Barclay<br>
	Barklay's own presentation of the timeless meaning of the Ten<br>
	Commandments, and their relevance to today's moral and ethical<br>
	dilemmas.  He devotes a chapter to each commandment, blending<br>
	traditional wisdom and fresh insights.<br>
		205 pages, paperback, $8.95<br>
24.  "The New Testament &amp; Homosexuality"  by Robin Scruggs<br>
	This solid study constitutes one of the best resource books available on<br>
	the question of what the New Testament does or does not say about<br>
	homosexuality.<br>
		158 pages, paperback, $8.95<br>
25.  "Gays Under Grace"  by Maury Johnston<br>
	A Christian's response to the Moral Majority.  This book is meant to be an<br>
	aggressive attack upon the anti-gay ideology of "Falwellian"<br>
	fundamentalism as well as an objectively critical review of various<br>
	life-styles among some gay Christians which only tend to give more<br>
	credence to the extremist accusations that all gays are "immoral and<br>
	perverted."<br>
		202 pages, hardbound, $15.95<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
