<!-- body="start" -->
But Dan,<br>
<p>
Don't you see that these instances of judging are after we have<br>
trampled on the great law of love to God, and fellow human?<br>
<p>
If I love God with all my hear soul and mind, and my neighbor<br>
as myself, why would I be hitting someone with a stone during<br>
a heated quarrel?  Ironically Ex 21:23,24 are the life for life, eye<br>
for eye, tooth for tooth... verses.  I think Jesus says some different<br>
stuff in the New Testament.  If we continue the thinking that<br>
pre-incarnate Christ was "God" leading in OT, then either God<br>
is contradicting Himself or these laws should be read in context<br>
of time and culture.<br>
<p>
Same goes for the rest of the OT passages you site.<br>
<p>
I couldn't help but think of a phrase Ellen White uses in Selected<br>
Messages.  I remember it because she repeats is to often:<br>
"truth for our time".  This is different from the principles in scripture<br>
which are for all time.  Some people call it the "spirit of the law."<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
