<title>Jun_1993: Re: sex changes, divorce</title>
<h1>Re: sex changes, divorce</h1>
Darius A. Lecointe (<i>dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Jun 1993 08:11:15 -0500 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#112">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#112">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#112">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#112">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0113.html">Dan Drazen: "Sex Changes: Another Perspective"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0111.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0083.html">Steven Timm: "Re: sex changes, divorce"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0085.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Religious liberty dangers from the new left:"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The following post illustrates my point.  Apparently we operate on<br>
expediency.  Raises the question of whether our leaders really allow Jesus<br>
into their counsels or whether we simply follow along with what is<br>
popularly discussed among mainstream churches.  We do not look much like<br>
leaders.<br>
<p>
If church policy is not consistent then why do we simply drop the issue of<br>
church discipline.  After all church membership or participation is not<br>
the test for entrance into the kingdom.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; In-Reply-To: &lt;199306070043.AA59808@garnet.acns.fsu.edu&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Darius suggests that offering baptism to the transexual person would be the</i><br>
<i>&gt; same as offering baptism to the remarried (improperly) person in a divorce.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Such a statement assumes that there are still any teeth in the church's </i><br>
<i>&gt; policy on divorce and remarriage.  Such is not the case.  It is not unheard</i><br>
<i>&gt; of today for man and wife to divorce, both remarry, and both remain in </i><br>
<i>&gt; the SDA ministry, not to mention membership.  Perhaps the policy was </i><br>
<i>&gt; ill-advised from the start, but as far as I can tell it is now non-existent.</i><br>
<i>&gt; I've not heard of anyone being under church discipline for divorce and </i><br>
<i>&gt; remarriage for the last ten years.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Perhaps this is why the homosexual argument now has more hearing than it </i><br>
<i>&gt; once did.  If the church could say that it really treats all of what it terms</i><br>
<i>&gt; adultery the same way, then there would not be so much accusation of </i><br>
<i>&gt; singling one group out.  But divorce, even among the ministry, has become</i><br>
<i>&gt; so common that the rationalizers have rationalized "the majority do it, </i><br>
<i>&gt; so it must be OK."</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
