<title>Jun_1993: Sexual Immorality</title>
<h1>Sexual Immorality</h1>
Darius A. Lecointe (<i>dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Jun 1993 08:35:19 -0500 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#114">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#114">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#114">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#114">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0115.html">Steven Timm: "Spirit of the law"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0113.html">Dan Drazen: "Sex Changes: Another Perspective"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dan Crowe &lt;dcrowe@puc.edu&gt; writes:<br>
<i>&gt; On Fri, 4 Jun 1993, Darius A. Lecointe wrote:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Dealing with homosexuality in the church is not as huge a problem as we</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; make.  It must be dealt with the same way as we deal with any other sin. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Agreed.  We must love the sinner but hate the sin.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; The church has never been given any authority to punish sin</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; for God has reserved to Himself the right to decide to whom He will</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; impute iniquity (Rom. 4:8).</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The preceding statement is false.  Consider the following texts:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 	Exodus 21:12-36			1 Corinthians 5</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	Exodus 35:2			2 Thessalonians 3:6-15</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	Leviticus 18:22,29</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
You need to read those passages again, *then* read my statement.  In  fact<br>
seems like you need to read the entire NT also.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt; Sex in the context of marriage cannot be wrong.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The Biblical passages refer only ambiguously to "sexual immorality", but</i><br>
<i>&gt; the following Spirit of Prophecy quotes are quite clear that even within</i><br>
<i>&gt; the context of marriage, sexual excess is sinful:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 	AH 121-8		2T 391, 472-3, 480</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Certainly you noticed *you* are the one who used the word excess.  Excess<br>
is always wrong, no matter what the act--good or bad.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt; This is where we have shot ourselves in the foot.  We teach that even if a</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; marriage would not have been sanctioned by God He blesses it based on its</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; civil legality.  That argument is often used to deny valid divorces to</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; those who may have married for the wrong reasons.  What that argument does</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; is force us to be duplicitous.  How do we relate to a homosexual marriage</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; in a state where the civil laws allow it?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Paul (not the Lord) says not to divorce an unbeliever if the unbeliever is</i><br>
<i>&gt; willing to stay, but that the unbeliever should be allowed to initiate the</i><br>
<i>&gt; divorce (1 Corinthians 7:12-6).  This position is tenable if the married</i><br>
<i>&gt; couple does not engage in improper sexual activity (see EGW references</i><br>
<i>&gt; above).  Since homosexual activity is improper, the application of this</i><br>
<i>&gt; principle to homosexual marriages is inappropriate.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Here you misinterpreted Paul.  My point had nothing to do when a partner<br>
in a marriage decides to leave.  I am speaking of when the union is<br>
entered into by people of two different belief systems.  Let us not<br>
confuse issues here.<br>
<p>
I have left my original posts so you can react to them in the proper context.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Darius Lecointe                        God is the answer to a question.
dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu
dlecoint@freenet.scri.fsu.edu
</pre>
