<!-- body="start" -->
[Archau writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; 1.  There is no reference in the New Testament scripture of christians </i><br>
<i>&gt; resisting persecution by "defending themselves."</i><br>
<p>
This has persuaded me.  However, re historical examples such as:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Would Hus, for example, have been better of arming himself against</i><br>
<i>&gt; the Bohemian authorities?</i><br>
<p>
Re Bohemians (most of them Sabbatarians, btw), check out Wylie re the<br>
blind general Ziska.  Re Waldenses:  Many times they retreated into<br>
mountain hideouts, but sometimes they defended themselves (e.g. an instance<br>
late in their history involving Henri/Enrico Arnaud).  Re Huguenots:<br>
Similar sort of thing, altho more self-defense.  Evidently they all wrestled<br>
with the issue of whether to defend themselves with arms.  For further<br>
reading, those from my generation will probably recognize the titles<br>
"Strangers in the Land", "Brave Men to the Battle", "The Wrath of the King",<br>
"Home to their Valleys (?)".<br>
<p>
While we probably cannot determine conclusively if God's best was for<br>
them to defend themselves with arms, it is evident that in many cases<br>
God gave them victory by means supernatural.  Finally, I note that<br>
Luther repeatedly implored the German princes to let God be their<br>
defender, not their arms.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
