<title>Jun_1993: SDA particulars</title>
<h1>SDA particulars</h1>
Dan Crowe (<i>dcrowe@puc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Jun 1993 13:39:04 -0700 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#122">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#122">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#122">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#122">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0123.html">Dan Blake: "Church discipline"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0121.html">Woody Baker: "Re: sex changes"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0061.html">LAINIE@delphi.com: "Re: Notes on the day of Penteco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am a convert to Seventh-Day Adventism.<br>
<p>
Several factors influenced my decision to be baptized.<br>
<p>
First, there is a sense of family within the Adventist church.  This<br>
effect is most pronounced when meeting fellow Adventists while travelling.<br>
The shared beliefs, especially in the areas of eschatology and lifestyle,<br>
create a bond that is difficult to describe but easy to recognize.<br>
<p>
The most important theological idea in Adventism is the unity of Bible. <br>
Many Christian churches teach that the Old Testament is obsolete and that<br>
the Father of the Old Testament is only worried with punishment while the<br>
New Testament Jesus is only concerned with love; Adventists belief that<br>
the gospel is the same in both the Old and New Testaments, that the only<br>
real changes were that the sacrificial system is no longer necessary and<br>
the theocracy of Israel no longer is a part of God's plan.  Justice and<br>
mercy are both evident in both the Old and New Testaments.  I understand<br>
that Steve has sent you a copy of the 27 fundamental beliefs.  If you have<br>
any questions regarding those or any other aspect of Adventism, feel free<br>
to ask again.<br>
<p>
Yours in Christ,<br>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
