<title>Jun_1993: Sex Changes: Another Perspective</title>
<h1>Sex Changes: Another Perspective</h1>
Dan Drazen (<i>drazen@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Jun 1993 20:38:35 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#113">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#113">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#113">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#113">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Sexual Immorality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Re: sex changes, divorce"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Darius Lecointe asks a valid question concerning attitudes toward those<br>
who have undergone sex change operations.  Some of the replies, however,<br>
have been somewhat glib.  The unspoken assumption is that the person<br>
in question underwent the operation of their own free will in their<br>
adult years.<br>
<p>
This does injustice to the problem of intersexuality, which is a<br>
developmental disorder.  On that level, it becomes a little like asking<br>
how to witness to someone with a developmental disorder that did not<br>
involve gender, such as a club foot or a cleft<br>
palate.  You get into a situation like John 9 where the disciples asked<br>
whether someone was born blind because of a sin they themselves<br>
committed or a sin their parents committed.  <br>
<p>
I can't say I have an easy answer to this one -- that's when you know<br>
you've got a good question.  But let me stir up the mix with something<br>
from the Out Of The Mouthes of Babes Dept:<br>
<p>
     'Stephen' was referred at the age of 5 years [to physicians; a<br>
     clinical diagnosis confirmed that while the child had the external<br>
     appearance of being a boy it was in fact a girl].  A plastic<br>
     surgical procedure was carried out...and Stephen became Stephanie....<br>
     The mother's immediate reaction on learning of the child's true sex<br>
     was to leave matters as they were, but after urging from the family<br>
     doctor she finally agreed to accept the advice that the sex should<br>
     be changed.  The child on being told what was to be done ran<br>
     delightedly out of the house calling into houses down the street<br>
     that God was turning him into a girl.... [from: Dewhurst and<br>
     Gordon, _The Intersexual Disorders_, 1969, London, pp. 128-129].<br>
<p>
Make of it what you will.<br>
<p>
Daniel J. Drazen<br>
Editor, SDA Periodical Index<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
