<title>Jun_1993: an extract from Steve &amp; Darius' exchange (fwd)</title>
<h1>an extract from Steve &amp; Darius' exchange (fwd)</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  8 Jun 1993 20:57:21 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#110">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#110">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#110">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#110">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0111.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0109.html">Steven Timm: "Re: sex changes, divorce"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0134.html">Steven Timm: "Mixed marriages"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com (Fred Christiansen) writes:<br>
<i>&gt; [Darius A. Lecointe writes:]</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; We teach that even if a</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; marriage would not have been sanctioned by God He blesses it based on its</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; civil legality.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Doesn't ring a bell with me.  The closest I can come is two concepts:</i><br>
<i>&gt; 1) If a guy and a girl became one flesh (i.e., had sexual intercourse),</i><br>
<i>&gt; then that required them to get married.  This I did hear, but it was not</i><br>
<i>&gt; based upon civil law (at least in my day); and no one suggested that they</i><br>
<i>&gt; then have God's blessing (as in the blessing one gets in living righteously).</i><br>
<i>&gt; [The OT civil laws in this regard have broader purposes than is at first</i><br>
<i>&gt; apparent to us.]</i><br>
<i>&gt; 2) If the one you marry is not in God's best will, you do not perforce</i><br>
<i>&gt; sever yourself forever from God's grace.  Indeed, God's grace is always</i><br>
<i>&gt; available to those who humble themselves under God's hand (James 4:6,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 1 Pet 5:5b,6).  God's amazing grace can work miracles in changing lives.</i><br>
<i>&gt; However, this is distinct from the blessings that come from living in</i><br>
His will.<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; God uses permanent relationships to illustrate eternal principles.</i><br>
<p>
It seems Fred has been listening to the wrong bells.  I was not referring<br>
to OT times.  The SDA church was not around then.  We accept as valid a<br>
marriage between a Seventh-day Adventist and a "non-believer" even though<br>
we will not allow our ministers to conduct the ceremony in an SDA church. <br>
(At least that was true when I was in the active ministry).  I am not<br>
speaking of situations where the situation changed during the marriage. <br>
With our strong reactions to un-wed pregnancies every woman who got<br>
pregnant in a marriage like I described would have to be disciplined.  We<br>
*do* recognize marriages the state recognizes.  In fact that is why we<br>
require a marriage license.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Darius Lecointe                        God is the answer to a question.
dlecoint@garnet.acns.fsu.edu
dlecoint@freenet.scri.fsu.edu
<p>
[Again, this is a custom that is falling by the boards.  Our pastor has
performed several "mixed marriages" in our SDA church, one SDA, the 
other not.  Also it is not uncommon to see SDA pastors go to churches 
of other denominations to wed one SDA and one not.  SCT]
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
