<title>Jun_1993: Spirit of the law</title>
<h1>Spirit of the law</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  8 Jun 1993 21:10:54 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#115">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#115">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#115">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#115">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "RE: Sexual Immorality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Sexual Immorality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
When I think of the question of what is the spirit of the law, <br>
I look to the sermon on the mount, Matthew 5.  This is where Jesus<br>
was showing how one needs to go beyond the written requirements<br>
of the law  "He that looks at a woman to lust after her hath committed<br>
adultery in his heart."  <br>
<p>
So we should not assume that the spirit of the law is any more lenient<br>
than the letter of the law.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "RE: Sexual Immorality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Sexual Immorality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
