<title>Jun_1993: God loves you, but....</title>
<h1>God loves you, but....</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  8 Jun 1993 21:15:17 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#107">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#107">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#107">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#107">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0108.html">Fred Christiansen: "RE: Big brother"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0106.html">LAINIE@delphi.com: "Re: Religious liberty dangers from the new left:"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0138.html">Dan Blake: "Re: God loves you, but...."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seems that those who say "God loves the sinner, but hates the sin"<br>
spend most of their time hating the sin in such a way that it is hard for<br>
the sinner to tell whether the hate is aimed at him or his sin.<br>
<p>
I propose that when the words "God loves you, but" are spoken, it doesn't<br>
matter what follows the "but".  All effect of the "God loves you" is <br>
subsumed in the "but".  The phrase "God loves the sinner, but hates the sin"<br>
is not to be found in the Bible.  (God does hate some things as described <br>
in the Bible and this is an interesting side-study).<br>
<p>
How about:  God loves you enough to accept you just the way you are,<br>
and too much to let you stay that way.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0108.html">Fred Christiansen: "RE: Big brother"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0106.html">LAINIE@delphi.com: "Re: Religious liberty dangers from the new left:"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0138.html">Dan Blake: "Re: God loves you, but...."</a>
</ul>
