<title>Jun_1993: Church discipline</title>
<h1>Church discipline</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 9 Jun 93 0:43:42 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#123">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#123">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#123">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#123">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0124.html">Tony Dyson: "TV violence"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0122.html">Dan Crowe: "SDA particulars"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0109.html">Steven Timm: "Re: sex changes, divorce"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; So. Steve, these two people are still under church discipline</i><br>
<i>&gt; and they are very regular and punctual in church also!</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Bill Oblitey</i><br>
<p>
So, where is the church discipline?  How can they still attend<br>
church?  In Matthew 18:17, Jesus says to treat them as one would<br>
a pagan or a tax collector.  In I Corinthians 5:11-13, Paul<br>
instructs us not to associate with them, not to eat with them,<br>
but to expell them from among us.<br>
<p>
Would they attend a potluck?  Don't they feel strange sitting<br>
alone at a table set for ten?  What happens when, as they take<br>
their seat in Sabbath school, the teacher pronounces judgment<br>
against them and suspends the class?  Read Numbers 16:23-26.<br>
In the worship service, what happens when all the people near<br>
them (say +/- three pews) vacate their seats, and the pastor<br>
pronounces judgment against them?<br>
<p>
Church discipline, like God's judgment, is a terrible thing.<br>
We, like God, go to great lengths to avoid it.  But when<br>
necessary, it must be enforced, like God's judgment.<br>
<p>
Dan<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
