<title>Jun_1993: religious liberty and the left</title>
<h1>religious liberty and the left</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 9 Jun 93 10:10:47 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#118">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#118">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#118">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#118">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0119.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Spirit of the law"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0117.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Helpful Reading"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0128.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  religious liberty and the left"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Well, before picking on the left, I would advise you to have a look at</i><br>
<i>&gt; the publication "Church and State" which is published by the</i><br>
<i>&gt; American's United for Separation of Church and State. The board of</i><br>
<i>&gt; directors boasts MANY SDA and Baptist clergy. It identifies the real</i><br>
<i>&gt; enemy of church and state separtation as the Relgious Right.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; [The SDA establishment has done nothing but pick on the religious</i><br>
<i>&gt; right for the last 16 years.  This, however, represents quite a shift</i><br>
<i>&gt; from the early 1960's, when the gloom 'n doomers were predicting that</i><br>
<i>&gt; John F. Kennedy, a Catholic, would sell the country over to the Pope.</i><br>
<i>&gt; The plots of the religious right are regularly discussed on SDAnet.  I</i><br>
<i>&gt; thought perhaps it was time to look at the left (and I speak as a</i><br>
<i>&gt; Democrat).  SCT]</i><br>
<p>
I think the SDA establishment is wrong on two counts.  First of all,<br>
anytime you become obsessed with one danger you become blind to<br>
others.  For example, no one actually knows how the Sunday Law will<br>
come into being at the end of time.  I could come up with plausible<br>
scenarios involving the Right, the Left, or the Middle.<br>
<p>
Second, in political terms worldwide the Left has typically been more<br>
coercive than the Right.  A typical Left philosophy is "we own you<br>
body and soul";  examples are Communist countries and to a lesser<br>
extent places like Sweden.  The Right, on the other hand, says "we<br>
don't want any political competition from you".  Examples are Asian<br>
countries like Taiwan and Korea (which have since liberalized), and<br>
South American countries such as Chile and Argentina (also<br>
liberalized).<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
