<title>Jun_1993: God loves you, but...</title>
<h1>God loves you, but...</h1>
Raylene Dyson (<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>09 Jun 1993 15:41:30 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#125">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#125">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#125">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#125">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0126.html">Steven Timm: "Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0124.html">Tony Dyson: "TV violence"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0160.html">David P. Harris: "Re: God loves you, but..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;subsumed in the "but".  The phrase "God loves the sinner, but hates the sin"</i><br>
<i>&gt;is not to be found in the Bible.  (God does hate some things as described </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;How about:  God loves you enough to accept you just the way you are,</i><br>
<i>&gt;and too much to let you stay that way.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
Good point Steve.<br>
<p>
In my reading of the Old Testament I've had a few thoughts on these matters.<br>
I think what I conclude is that God, although hating sin, really isn't as<br>
concerned about perfection or our good acts as we often act like he is.<br>
What he really wants is a state of mind. A willingness to learn, to be<br>
corrected (by him), a love for him. <br>
<p>
God knew David was bloodthirsty and had too many women and was a bad father.<br>
But he called him a man after his own heart.<br>
<p>
It just goes to show that we really can't judge because we only see the<br>
outside. A persons motivations are hidden from us but not from God.<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
