Thanks for the bibliography, Marcus.  Librarians are always looking for<br>
bood bibliographies to assist in collection development.  I checked our<br>
catalog, and found that we already own about 2/3 of these (hope some are<br>
read by seminarians and others).  The others I ordered.  It's really<br>
wonderful to be able to do all this from my desk.  I simply use the<br>
telnet command for multiple logins so that I can flip from e-mail to the<br>
online catalog search menu and the electronic ordering menu.  Really<br>
great.  Takes a lot less time than it used to also (won't talk about the<br>
time it takes to set this thing up and clean up the database--just spent<br>
the better part of a day straightening out the subject headings for<br>
books of the Bible, would be too bad if we couldn't find those!)<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<p>
Just yesterday I had the dean of the School of Graduate Studies at the<br>
Adventist International Institute of Advanced Studies (what a mouthful)<br>
in the Philippines in my office talking about Internet possibilities, especiallyhow we might share library resources.  Somehow we will need to find ways<br>
for many small entities to share these resources, but that will take<br>
some leadership.  We really need to get the GC interested in these<br>
issues.  Great possibilities.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
