<title>Jun_1993: Seventh-day Wimps</title>
<h1>Seventh-day Wimps</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  9 Jun 1993 22:16:38 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#126">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#126">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#126">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#126">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0127.html">Geelan / Bradley John: "What I Believe as an SDA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0125.html">Raylene Dyson: "God loves you, but..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0129.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I fail to understand how someone can read 1st Corinthians 4 through 6 and<br>
still say that the church is not supposed to judge.  There are warnings<br>
in 1 Corinthians 4 against premature judging, that's for sure.  But<br>
1 Corinthians 5 is telling the corinthians that they ought to be judging<br>
a certain brother, and 1 corinthians 6 says that the believers should <br>
judge matters within the church and not the secular courts.  <br>
It's one of the most strident calls to judgment in the Bible.<br>
<p>
Why don't we have the situations such as Ananias and Sapphira happening <br>
anymore?  Judging in the NT church happened early and often.  Should it <br>
grow out of a Spirit-based authority?  I think so.  We should be careful<br>
to recognize the difference between dumping guilt on someone and<br>
condemning them  (bad) and thwarting the unchecked spread of evil in the<br>
church (good).<br>
Just because we cease condemning people does not mean that there ceases<br>
to be right and wrong.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
