<!-- name="Dan Drazen" -->
<!-- email="drazen@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Seventh-day Wimps" -->
<!-- id="9306101226.AA16553@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Ag5da6i00VpQ45cfZy@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<title>Jun_1993: Re: Seventh-day Wimps</title>
<h1>Re: Seventh-day Wimps</h1>
Dan Drazen (<i>drazen@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Jun 1993 08:26:33 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#131">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#131">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#131">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#131">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Notes on the day of Penteco"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0130.html">Steve Hix: "Re: &gt; Re: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0126.html">Steven Timm: "Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; i fail to understand how someone can read 1st Corinthians 4 through 6 and</i><br>
<i>&gt; still say that the church is not supposed to judge.  There are warnings</i><br>
<i>&gt; in 1 Corinthians 4 against premature judging, that's for sure.  But</i><br>
<i>&gt; 1 Corinthians 5 is telling the corinthians that they ought to be judging</i><br>
<i>&gt; a certain brother, and 1 corinthians 6 says that the believers should </i><br>
<i>&gt; judge matters within the church and not the secular courts.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; It's one of the most strident calls to judgment in the Bible.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Why don't we have the situations such as Ananias and Sapphira happening </i><br>
<i>&gt; anymore?  Judging in the NT church happened early and often.  Should it </i><br>
<i>&gt; grow out of a Spirit-based authority?  I think so.  We should be careful</i><br>
<i>&gt; to recognize the difference between dumping guilt on someone and</i><br>
<i>&gt; condemning them  (bad) and thwarting the unchecked spread of evil in the</i><br>
<i>&gt; church (good).</i><br>
<i>&gt; Just because we cease condemning people does not mean that there ceases</i><br>
<i>&gt; to be right and wrong.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Steve:<br>
<p>
I've tried to sort through this issue and I keep coming back to the same<br>
personal roadblock: my perception of judgment.<br>
<p>
Used in context, it has to do with the behavior of a member of the<br>
group.  The sticking point is not the particular behavior, but how to<br>
react to it.  In this area of life, my skills have been compromised.<br>
<p>
Face it, the first experience any of us ever have with the subject of<br>
judgment is what we receive at the hands of our parents.  In the case of<br>
my dad, it was always an instinctive reaction: he'd freak out, yell,<br>
smack us or get his belt -- a wide, black leather number.  The older we<br>
got the less crudely physical he got; intimidation alone was enough to<br>
keep me and my two brothers in line.<br>
<p>
[Disclaimer: I converted to Adventism in my teen years after my folks<br>
were divorced and my dad was out of the picture.  We had no formal<br>
religious upbringing when I was a child, and whenever my dad used the<br>
name of God when I was growing up he appended it with terms that would<br>
get me thrown off this BBS].<br>
<p>
I used to think that, once my folks got divorced and my dad was out of<br>
the house, I could get on with my life.  I know better now.  One of the<br>
lasting scars for me has been a problem with the subject of judgment.<br>
In fact I found the SDA belief in instantaneous non-existence (rather<br>
than perpetual torment) for someone who comes out on the wrong side of<br>
the judgment of God to be something of a comfort.<br>
<p>
But back to judgment.  I find myself unable to get into the topic of<br>
someone else's sin.  I'm comfortable with the notion that "if you know<br>
something's wrong and you do it anyway, it's sin" (to paraphrase, I<br>
believe, James).  I have more trouble condemning someone else's behavior.<br>
Not because I'm such a generous and liberal guy, but because I<br>
instinctively can't bring myself to sit in judgment of another human<br>
being the way my dad sat in judgment on me.  And that model of behavior<br>
was so burned into my circuit boards that it takes a real effort to<br>
learn alternative ways of acting.<br>
<p>
And so I had to find a safety net.  I developed the habit of judging<br>
people's ideas and philosophies rather than their actions.  It was a way<br>
I could get it out of my system in displaced and dispassionate forums:<br>
Letters to the Editor columns, radio call-in shows, even this BBS.<br>
There's that emotional distance between people that makes me feel more<br>
comfortable.  God forbid I should confront anyone face to face, even<br>
with open sin!<br>
<p>
But that's just me.  <br>
<p>
Daniel J. Drazen<br>
Editor, SDA Periodical Index<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
