<title>Jun_1993: Re: Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh?</title>
<h1>Re: Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh?</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Jun 93 12:50:45 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#153">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#153">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#153">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#153">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0152.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Church discipline"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0059.html">Steven Timm: "Heroes:  Desmond Doss, Ronald Tull, or David Koresh?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: Steven Timm &lt;st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I am deeply disturbed by the tone of conversation of the pro-gun forces</i><br>
<i>&gt; on SDAnet.  </i><br>
<p>
Careful, it's not a monolithic statement, and several issues have<br>
been addressed.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It is merely another reflection of the militarism that is </i><br>
<i>&gt; overtaking our church, and perhaps an effect of twenty years of non-stop</i><br>
<i>&gt; TV violence.</i><br>
<p>
Perhaps.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; When I was a kid, they pointed to Desmond Doss as an SDA hero.</i><br>
<p>
Still do (at least around here, and at my home). Also Keith Argraves<br>
(a WW2 non-combatant paratrooper, if you can imagine such a thing), and<br>
fellows like my father who served non-combatant who were never decorated.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; He worked</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the face of war to save the lives of others, refusing to touch a gun</i><br>
<i>&gt; himself.  For saving 75 lives in Okinawa during the 2nd World War, he won</i><br>
<i>&gt; the Congressional Medal of Honor.</i><br>
<p>
No. He was awarded the Medal of Honor. No Congressional about it.<br>
(Sorry, I'm a compulsive tech writer.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The youth I teach now get to read about Ronald Tull, an SDA who went</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the Persian Gulf during Desert Storm to shoot.  It was clear editorially</i><br>
<i>&gt; where the SDA publications stood:  Saddam was EVIL, the USA was RIGHT,</i><br>
<i>&gt; let's go bomb Iraq (notwithstanding SDA believers right in the thick of</i><br>
<i>&gt; bombs).  Ronald Tull "The first SDA casualty of the war" was put forth</i><br>
<i>&gt; as a hero.</i><br>
<p>
It didn't come across (to me) as one who was a hero for volunteering to<br>
fight, but one who was doing some admirable things in spite of being in<br>
service in an active cambat arm.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; As sickening as I find that attitude, I find the current attitude expressed</i><br>
<i>&gt; by the various proponents of guns even more distressing.  Nothing said</i><br>
<i>&gt; about whether it is moral or not to have a weapon of lethal force.</i><br>
<p>
*I* thought that the discussion was specifically on that point (at least<br>
the self-defense parts of the thread.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Nothing said about whether Christians ought to be learning to use a weapon</i><br>
<i>&gt; of force against fellow man.</i><br>
<p>
??? "Does scripture permit it?" and "under what circumstances?" don't<br>
apply?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Only political arguments "got to defend ourselves against the government."</i><br>
<p>
Sorry, but it's probably true.  At best, we have to live in a cautious<br>
alliance with governments. A government should have a bit of healthy<br>
caution about its citizens, should it cross the line to oppressing them.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; These are the attitude that turn SDA doctrine-spouters into David Koreshes.</i><br>
<i>&gt; It sounds like Koresh would be a hero to some of you.</i><br>
<p>
Fortunately, I have yet to speak to anyone (much less any SDA) who saw<br>
Koresh as a hero.  A *lot* of people, though, who believed that the <br>
government actions in Waco were wrong, ill-advised, illegal and worse.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Does the idea of self-defense have any Biblical support?  It does have some,</i><br>
<i>&gt; particularly in the book of Esther.  But nobody has mentioned that.</i><br>
<p>
I thought that some of my previous posts on the topic mentioned some<br>
other support (just re-read the last part of Esther yesterday), such<br>
as Exodus 22:1,2 and Luke 22:36,36.<br>
<p>
I believe that there is a separation between the use of offensive and<br>
defensive force.<br>
<p>
I wouldn't (and didn't) volunteer for military service (but would have<br>
gone, like my father) if drafted. Training for combat looks to me very<br>
like preparing to project offensive force.<br>
<p>
 From my reading of scripture, defensive force is something else entirely,<br>
but a tool to be used with extreme caution, like fire.<br>
<p>
Defense against criminal attack I have no problem with, but defense against<br>
government action against me, say for my religious practice, for me would<br>
go over the line.  Maybe it's an arbitrary line, it's the one I currently<br>
hold.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If we want to deal with the issues of self defense or killing in the</i><br>
<i>&gt; name of God, then let's continue.</i><br>
<p>
I hope you don't mean self-defense *as* "killing in the name of God". <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; But SDAnet is not the place to rehash political hubris that is peculiar</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the USA.  I'm not interested in what the constitution says, I am</i><br>
<i>&gt; interested in what God says.</i><br>
<p>
So no more discussions involving the First Amendment?<br>
<p>
I don't think we can always keep things so neatly-compartmented, Steve.<br>
<p>
Governments and politics have a nasty tendency to intrude on our private<br>
lives.<br>
<p>
But if that's what you mean, OK.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
