<title>Jun_1993: Re: Church discipline</title>
<h1>Re: Church discipline</h1>
Bill Oblitey (<i>OBLITEY@grove.iup.edu</i>)<br>
<i>11 Jun 1993 09:40:33 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#151">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#151">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#151">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#151">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0152.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Church discipline"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0150.html">K-leb D'Cat: "Shooting at Big Brother"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0152.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Church discipline"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; So. Steve, these two people are still under church discipline</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; and they are very regular and punctual in church also!</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; Bill Oblitey</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;So, where is the church discipline?  How can they still attend</i><br>
<i>&gt;church?  In Matthew 18:17, Jesus says to treat them as one would</i><br>
<i>&gt;a pagan or a tax collector.  In I Corinthians 5:11-13, Paul</i><br>
<i>&gt;instructs us not to associate with them, not to eat with them,</i><br>
<i>&gt;but to expell them from among us.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Dan</i><br>
<p>
Perhaps this is an instance of hating the sin but loving the sinner.  The<br>
church did not sanction what the brother and sister did.  The church took<br>
action.  I was vocal in all that was done.  I now see the brother and sister as<br>
outsiders who choose to come to our church.  Why should we turn them out?<br>
<p>
As a matter of fact, this is a key feature of the on-going debate in the church<br>
as to whether they should be baptised of not.<br>
<p>
Supposing that these people (the disfellowshiped ones) move to your vicinity<br>
and attended your church.  Would you kick them out?  Suppose now that you tell<br>
me that there's a couple attending your church and I relate their background to<br>
you.  Now, would you kich them out?<br>
<p>
If they go to another SDA church and request baptism, wouldn't the pastor<br>
baptise them?  Is the pastor requested to pry into someone's past before<br>
baptising the person?  We go into prisons to baptise people, so why treat<br>
others differently.<br>
<p>
Now, why wouldn't they be baptised in our church?  We do not feel they they are<br>
sorry for their sin.  If we baptise them, then we are encouraging what they<br>
did.  We will be sending the message that anyone can get between a wife and<br>
husband, request disfellowship, marry in court, and come back to be rebaptised.<br>
<p>
We love them.  They have done wrong.  We have not forgotten it.<br>
This brings up that side of the argument which raises the issue of forgiveness<br>
and I'm not touching that.  All I say about that is that it encourages the<br>
situation where I step over you to get what I want and then turn around to<br>
blame you when you complain that you rather have the problem - you have not<br>
learned to forgive.  You mention the previous time I did the same thing to you<br>
and I remind you that you have not forgotten.<br>
<p>
If we are all sinners and sinner are welcome in our churches, provided they are<br>
making efforts to hold on to Christ, why should we not have these brethren in<br>
church?<br>
<p>
Bill Oblitey<br>
[OBLITEY@OAK.GROVE.IUP.EDU]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
