<title>Jun_1993: Re: Children of God</title>
<h1>Re: Children of God</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Jun 93 13:53:26 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#146">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#146">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#146">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#146">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0147.html">Steven Timm: "SS ideas"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0145.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0133.html">Dan Blake: "Children of God"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Dan Blake writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; &gt; [Jesus] saw all people as children of God.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Would anyone care to defend it in the light of John 1:12.</i><br>
<p>
{other verses:  Rom 8:14, Gal 4:7, Phi 2:15, 1 Jn 3:1,2}<br>
<p>
Yes, the statement does appear to be convey the bland flavor of "all are<br>
children so all will inherit the kingdom".  If that's the meaning, I don't<br>
think that's supportable.  If the statement was modified to read:<br>
  "saw all people as potential children of God if they would just ...", or<br>
  "saw those who believed on Him as ..."<br>
the statement would be Scripturally sound, I reckon.<br>
<p>
An alternate meaning for children of God in the writer's minds might be<br>
"descendants of God's creation (Adam)".  Perhaps they were struggling<br>
with expressing how Jesus felt towards people.  I note the word "compassion"<br>
occurs 14 or so times in the (KJV) gospels in this regard.<br>
<pre>
