<title>Jun_1993: Re: God loves you, but....</title>
<h1>Re: God loves you, but....</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Jun 93 15:04:25 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#143">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#143">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#143">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#143">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0144.html">Steven Timm: "Church Discipline in light of 1 Corinthians 5"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0142.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0138.html">Dan Blake: "Re: God loves you, but...."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Dan Blake writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; &gt; How about:  God loves you enough to accept you just the way you are,</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; and too much to let you stay that way.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Neither is your phrase or its equivalent to be found in the Bible.</i><br>
<i>&gt; What you do find is:</i><br>
<i>&gt;    Jn 3:3 .. Jn 3:16 .. Jn 5:14 .. Rom 5:8</i><br>
<p>
If we understand "accept" to mean "accept into God's kingdom, regardless",<br>
that would make repentance and reformation unnecessary, and that would<br>
be un-Scriptural.  I believe that is Dan's point.  If we understand "accept"<br>
to mean "willing to help", that would apply universally.  I note that a<br>
person must want to be helped by God (be repentant, be sorry) for the<br>
relationship to be mutual, for God will not force; but clearly He wants to<br>
help us (Rom 5:8, above; Jer 31:3).<br>
<p>
Expanding further,<br>
    JOH 6:37 All that the Father giveth me shall come to me; and him that<br>
    cometh to me I WILL IN NO WISE CAST OUT.<br>
And who does the Father want to save (remembering that the Father and Son<br>
are one in this regard)?<br>
    PE2 3:9 [The Lord is] longsuffering to us-ward, not willing that any<br>
    should perish, but that all should come to repentance.<br>
I note that repentance is a gift:<br>
    ACT 5:31 Him hath God exalted with his right hand to be a Prince and a<br>
    Saviour, for to GIVE REPENTANCE to Israel, and forgiveness of sins.<br>
    (note also Rom 2:4, 2 Cor 7:9,10, 2 Tim 2:25, Heb 6:6)<br>
The Father knows that most will not heed His calls, despising His provision:<br>
    MAT 7:14 Because strait is the gate, and narrow is the way, which leadeth<br>
    unto life, and few there be that find it.<br>
    MAT 22:14 For many are called, but few are chosen.<br>
He pleads with us not to harden our hearts (Heb 3:8,15, 4:7, Ps 95:8):<br>
    To day if ye will hear his voice, harden not your hearts.<br>
<pre>
-- 
