<!-- name="Tony Dyson" -->
<!-- email="PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- subject="Prophets and prophets?" -->
<!-- id="01GZ99H1EM7M9EECJH@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Jun_1993: Prophets and prophets?</title>
<h1>Prophets and prophets?</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>11 Jun 1993 15:33:36 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#155">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#155">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#155">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#155">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0156.html">Steven Timm: "The White Lie:  11 years later:"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here's a hypothesis for you all to ponder. This is something I have referred<br>
to a couple of times, but this particular post was prompted by someone's<br>
reference to "truth for our time" a few days back.<br>
<p>
This is _only a hypothesis_, so no artillery please! Disagreement is welcome<br>
as long as it's friendly! Here goes...<br>
<p>
God's communications to mankind through his servants the prophets are almost<br>
always contemporary. Even in instances where inspired writings are clearly<br>
"prophetic" in the popular sense, the message is often a contemporary one as<br>
well as being predictive. If we define a prophet as an individual who is<br>
chosen by God and acts as a medium of communication between God and mankind,<br>
then we could say that a prophet is usually sent to his or her contemporaries.<br>
<p>
This applies to all true prophets throughout the ages. Which people<br>
each of us would include in our list of true prophets is a separate issue,<br>
although related. For the purposes of discussion, let us assume that the list<br>
of true prophets includes all the Bible writers along with Ellen White, whilst<br>
other modern prophets such as Joseph Smith and Mary Baker Eddy are not<br>
included. Most SDAs would agree that this would constitute a subset of the<br>
true prophets of God throughout history (!).<br>
<p>
Now God being God, and people being people, everlasting principles of truth<br>
are contained within inspired writings, even those writings which are<br>
obviously contemporary. Hence we benefit in the twentieth century from<br>
writings which date back thousands of years, and which were addressed to<br>
groups of people significantly different to ourselves. Also, many diverse<br>
groups throughout the world today can make this claim.<br>
<p>
Some people claim that the ancient prophets wrote for all time, while modern<br>
prophets write for their own time only. This seems to be an artificial<br>
distinction, __unless there is a significant difference between the <br>
inspiration of an ancient prophet and the inspiration of a modern prophet__.<br>
<p>
Assuming that this is not the case, we must ask the question: what differences,<br>
if any, should there be in hermeneutics when it comes to reading the Bible <br>
and the writings of Ellen White? If the hypothesis I have presented has some<br>
measure of truth, then there are certain practices which need to be addressed<br>
and probably changed. Two which come to mind:<br>
<p>
1... Ignoring the counsels, directives and testimony of Ellen White because<br>
she was presenting truth for her time - which has long since passed - while<br>
paying lip service to the belief that she was a true prophet of God. <br>
<p>
2... Applying the counsels, directives and testimony of Scriptural prophets<br>
directly, as given, with no serious attempt to discover the principles<br>
involved. (This problem is not at all trivial (!), since we all have<br>
different ideas as to what is "case" and what is "code"... take Paul's<br>
words regarding women and the church as an obvious example.)<br>
<p>
3... Applying the counsels, directives and testimony of Ellen White directly,<br>
as given, with no serious attempt to discover the principles involved. <br>
(Again, a minefield, for similar reasons to those given above.)<br>
<p>
I am aware that some Christians do not think that *any* inspired message<br>
needs to be "contextualized", so I would not expect agreement from that<br>
quarter.<br>
<p>
I would, however, like to hear some reactions to these ideas. For those of<br>
you who say, "yes, Ellen White was a prophet, but I like to stick with God's<br>
Word", I ask again: what differences do you see between God's word through<br>
a prophet n centuries ago, and his word through Ellen White 1 century ago?<br>
<p>
There are lots of related questions, but I think I've written enough for<br>
now!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
---------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
