<title>Jun_1993: Re: Seventh-day Wimps</title>
<h1>Re: Seventh-day Wimps</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Jun 93 16:29:03 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#141">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#141">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#141">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#141">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0142.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0140.html">lsusers: "Truth for our time"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0135.html">lsusers: "Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0142.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Seventh-day Wimps"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Tony Dyson writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; .. this discipline/judgment thing ..  when it comes to public condemnation</i><br>
<i>&gt; and ostracism.</i><br>
<p>
I am puzzled why church discipline (generally, but not always, meaning<br>
disfellowship) is construed to mean public condemnation and ostracism<br>
(yes, I know there are people who do it that way).<br>
<p>
Some points:<br>
1)  Disfellowshiping does not perforce preclude one from obtaining<br>
    salvation.  We are not Catholics, so we are not talking excommunication<br>
    here (excommunication prevents you from receiving the sacraments,<br>
    whence, allegedly, God's grace/salvation).  Humans may err in<br>
    judgment, but God does not (Jer 17:10, 1 Sam 16:7b, Ps 9:8, Rev 16:7).<br>
<p>
2)  Disfellowshiping is the last resort after much effort (Gal 6:1) and time.<br>
    Note the extensive probation periods given by God to the Jews<br>
    (e.g., Jer 25:11,12, 29:10; cf Dan 9:24) before sending severe trial.<br>
    Note how He worked to draw them (e.g., Hos 2:14) in the meantime.<br>
<p>
3)  Matt 18:15-17 directs the offended one (!) to seek reconciliation with<br>
    the offender (note parallel to Gen 3; also the plan of salvation).<br>
    If we apply this method to church discipline, we must note that the<br>
    first imperative is to reconcile and restore (cf Gal 6:1; and note<br>
    the required attitude of meekness and humility on the part of those<br>
    making the approach; note also the tie-in of v.2).<br>
<p>
    Going before the church is *not* for public shaming but to ensure a<br>
    fair hearing and righteous judgment (this latter command is repeated<br>
    many, many times in OT, for extra emphasis).  While it takes two or<br>
    three witnesses for a charge to have any weight, it takes just one vote<br>
    to veto (Deu 17:6, 19:5; note application in 2 Cor 12 &amp; 13).<br>
<p>
4)  If someone is disfellowshipped, what does it mean to treat that one<br>
    as a pagan or tax collector (Mt18:17)?  Ostracism?  Shunning (as the<br>
    Amish call it)?  Think!  Did Jesus shun?  Or did Jesus woo?  Probation<br>
    has not yet closed!  Win them anew! (2 Cor 5:18-20, Col 1:20-23, Jer 31:3)<br>
<p>
5)  The judgment we are told not to make is that which involves someone's<br>
    eternal destiny, particularly their condemnation.  In the courts,<br>
    a judge sentences, or condemns, one to a specific punishment.<br>
    We are not to judge whether someone is worthy of eternal life or<br>
    eternal death.  However, church discipline is something quite distinct.<br>
<p>
    If we see church discipline as punishment to hurt or shame someone,<br>
    as if it were some kind of catharsis for the "saints", we do not<br>
    understand the purposes of discipline. {Btw, the same could be said<br>
    of child discipline).<br>
<p>
    The purpose of church discipline is to (re)teach the one under<br>
    discipline how to be a true disciple of Christ.<br>
    <br>
    Before we can teach effectively, I submit we must first understand and<br>
    live the disciplines of the Christian life ourselves, we must know how<br>
    to be a true &amp; loyal disciple of Christ.<br>
<p>
6)  It is worth my while and yours to study into what sort of church<br>
    discipline God has ordained.  For example, in Christ's Object Lessons,<br>
    re the wheat and the tares, EGW indicates that persisting in open sin<br>
    is a valid basis for disfellowshiping.  The operative words are<br>
    "persisting" (see my comments above re probation, note the many refs<br>
    to God as long suffering) and "open".  Speculation re hidden sin is<br>
    called evil surmising.  Seeking out "tares" to pick on is<br>
    countermanded (Mt 7:3-5) and counterproductive (Mt 13:29).<br>
<p>
    God's Word is full of balances:  justice vs mercy, authority vs<br>
    appeal, etc.  Godly church discipline also has balance.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
