<title>Jun_1993: Biases and homosexuality</title>
<h1>Biases and homosexuality</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Jun 1993 18:19:37 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#148">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#148">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#148">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#148">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0149.html">Harvey Brenneise: "GC Location"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0147.html">Steven Timm: "SS ideas"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0173.html">Raylene Dyson: "Re: Biases and homosexuality"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It is with some trepidation that I re-open this subject, but it's Friday<br>
afternoon and I'm tired of working (being an SDA institution, everyone<br>
else has long since left).  I've been thinking about several statements<br>
and unanswered questions that have arisen in the last month or so.  Let<br>
me take a stab at some of them (this may be somewhat disjointed).<br>
<p>
First, I think our biases are largely based on our personal past<br>
history.  My own views of homosexuality have changed by knowing a number<br>
of gay men and lesbians.  One of these was my own cousin, who never<br>
"came out" to his family and who died of AIDS several years ago.  I'm<br>
not quite sure what is meant when people use the term "homosexual<br>
lifestyle" because the gays and lesbians I know seem to have a wide<br>
divergence is their lifestyle.  One thing they do seem to have in common<br>
is a great deal of empathy for each other.  I do not believe most people<br>
would "choose" a position in society with so many difficulties unless<br>
there was a pretty powerful impetus.  What that is, no one seems to know<br>
for sure.  It is true that some gays and lesbians (probably a higher<br>
percentage of gay men than lesbians) choose to be hedonistic and have<br>
multiple sex partners (perhaps as exemplified by gay bars and the wilder<br>
aspects of a Gay Pride parades, you know--the kind of thing that gets on<br>
the news, for example, the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence).  However,<br>
many gays and lesbians are "turned off" by such antics.  Somehow the<br>
public seems to believe this is the way "they" all live just because it<br>
makes better "copy."<br>
<p>
The people I know are either in a long-term committed relationship or<br>
desire one.  However, our society is not set up to support this as it is<br>
for heterosexuals.  Why else would gays and lesbians want to get<br>
married?  There seems to be in inborn need for stability and commitment.<br>
It's dangerous to generalize, but it seems that this desire is stronger<br>
in women than in men, and this appears to be true of lesbians.  Gay men,<br>
like their heterosexual brothers, seem to have a greater temptation for<br>
"conquest."  <br>
<p>
Steve, I expect you know more gays and lesbians than you think.  There<br>
is no way to know for certain how many there are in society, but if all<br>
gays and lesbians were green for a day, we would probably all be<br>
surprised at how many there are and who they are.  It is, of course,<br>
complicated by the fact that gender orientation does not appear to be<br>
100% one way or the other, or even necessarily to stay the same<br>
throughout life.  Psychosexual behavior is indeed a mysterious thing.<br>
When I was in college, I was naive and often didn't recognize what was<br>
going on about me.  Quite a number of the people I knew then, I now know<br>
were and are gay.  There are probably others as well.  Gays and lesbians<br>
often don't "come out" in a hostile environment (for obvious reasons)<br>
and to those who they think will be unfriendly.  I shouldn't be<br>
surprised that a number of people at your place of employement are gay<br>
or lesbian.<br>
<p>
It would be interesting to know how the student affairs offices of the<br>
SDA colleges deal with gay and lesbian students.  I expect there are<br>
significant differences between institutions and over time.  I do not<br>
believe Andrews University is particularly supportive of gays and<br>
lesbians.  However, I understand that there are gay students at other<br>
SDA colleges who are "out."<br>
<p>
Marcus asked for SDA literature that would be supportive and<br>
non-judgmental for a gay person.  I'm not sure what he was asking for.<br>
While the church no doubt does publish spiritually uplifting materials<br>
(is that what you wanted?), I do not think it publishes anything that<br>
would be particularly supportive for an Adventist homosexual (for that,<br>
you would have to go to SDA Kinship).  It seems the church feels more<br>
called to judgment than to personal support (just read the archives of<br>
this list).<br>
<p>
Len Archer stated that all truth is contextual.  I'm waiting to see if<br>
there's any response.  I tend to agree with him.  It seems that we often<br>
have a desire for "absolute" truth (context-independent) as a standard<br>
for behavior.  The older I get, the more questions I have and the more<br>
abiguities I see.  Of course, materials written in other times and<br>
cultures (including the Bible and Ellen White) have to take into account<br>
their context, to the best we can understand it.  The Bible contains<br>
enough information for salvation for even the illiterate.  There is a<br>
tendency in Adventism (and probably Christianity generally) to<br>
understand the unknowable--for example, David Koresh's obsession with<br>
the 7 seals or the early Adventists' belief that they knew when Christ<br>
would come).  In the end, it's not important.  I tease my colleages in<br>
the seminary by calling the study of theology "idle speculation."<br>
People tend to pick and choose what parts of the Bible they accept as<br>
relevanat today and reject those that don't.  For me, I see pretty much<br>
all of Leviticus as part of an ancient culture, including the statements<br>
on unclean meats.  I don't choose to eat them (or much other meat)<br>
because of health principles not because of Leviticus (I sometimes<br>
wonder what lobster tastes like, though!).<br>
<p>
I believe the thread originally got started over female homosexuality<br>
(lesbianism).  It certainly existed in the classical world (after all,<br>
the island of Lesbos is in Greece) and probably the ancient world as<br>
well.  There are probably a number of reasons why it doesn't merit<br>
biblical attention.  First, the Bible is largely a male book.  Women<br>
were marginalized in those societies.  But I think there may also be<br>
something else at work.  Even today, I think male homosexuality seems to<br>
be more of a "threat" to society than lesbianism.  Is it because<br>
lesbians are fewer in number?  Tend to have more committed<br>
relationships?  Or does it have to do with a perhaps unspoken definition<br>
of intercourse?  Is a sexual relationship the same as having<br>
intercourse, and does intercourse require at least one party having a<br>
penis?  "Boston marriages" (2 women living together) have been around<br>
for years, including in the Adventist community.  People might look a<br>
little funny, but it's not the same as 2 men living together.  Perhaps<br>
the underlying belief is "What could they possibly be doing together?"<br>
It's none of my business, and I don't care to know.  Probably nothing.<br>
What level of intimacy is required for it to be a "sexual relationship"?<br>
Kissing, handholding, and other forms of intimacy appear, even among<br>
members of the same gender, appear to have been socially acceptable in<br>
ancient cultures, and is still true in some non-Western cultures.  In<br>
the West, we seem to have an inborn fear of this kind of intimacy.  I<br>
wonder if repression of this "need" in some who may feel it the most<br>
strongly may be a "cause" for homosexuality (alluded to by Steve<br>
already).<br>
<p>
I have also noticed that men seem to be more threatened by male<br>
homosexuality than women appear to be.  Is it possible that this is a<br>
feeling of "letting down the side"?  Giving up the traditional<br>
patriarchal dominance of women?  <br>
<p>
There are probably many reasons why heterosexuals fear gays and<br>
lesbians.  Most of us tend to fear what we don't know/understand.  There<br>
may be a fear of sexually-transmitted diseases.  There appears to be a<br>
fear that "they" might turn a straight person into a gay one (though<br>
there appears to be little evidence to support this).  Perhaps on a more<br>
personal level, there is a fear of any homoerotic thoughts they<br>
themselves may have had.<br>
<p>
As I stated when I began, I have few answers and many questions.  I hope<br>
this has stimulated some thought.  I'm not out to flame anyone on this<br>
list (and hope the flames don't get too hot!).<br>
<p>
For now--<br>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
