<title>Jun_1993: Church Discipline in light of 1 Corinthians 5</title>
<h1>Church Discipline in light of 1 Corinthians 5</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Jun 1993 20:13:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#144">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#144">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#144">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#144">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0145.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0143.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: God loves you, but...."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Someone asked if Dan Blake's post about "where is the discipline"<br>
was facetious.  If we look at church discipline in the light of 1 Corinthians<br>
5, where the man has his father's wife, they say "with such a one no, not<br>
to eat."  It does involve for that particular case excising that person<br>
from the community.  It should be noted that this is a case where <br>
the person continued in his wrong, not one where the person confessed his<br>
sin and asked the congregation for forgiveness.<br>
<p>
I am not prepared to say that this tactic should be applied in every case<br>
(certainly not) or that it should be applied to any case.  But any discussion<br>
of the theology of judging should take 1 Corinthians 4-6 into mind, as <br>
well as 1 Corinthians 13.<br>
<p>
Let's return to the case of Indiana, PA mentioned by Bill.  Many would <br>
agree that this is a flagrant case of adultery which ought to fall <br>
under church discipline.  Now suppose instead that this episode of <br>
adultery had happened before either of them was a church member, and<br>
they come into church for the first time, wanting baptism.  What happens then?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
