<title>Jun_1993: The White Lie:  11 years later:</title>
<h1>The White Lie:  11 years later:</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Jun 1993 21:05:43 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#156">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#156">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#156">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#156">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0157.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  SS ideas"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0155.html">Tony Dyson: "Prophets and prophets?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0162.html">Fritz Guy: "Re: The White Lie: 11 years later:"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks to Jerry Wiley I obtained a copy of Walter Rea's book:  "The White <br>
Lie"  On receiving it I discovered that he wrote the foreword to it,<br>
summarizing the book well without saying anything our SDAnet members <br>
would consider "heretical."  I also discovered that Rea's book was published<br>
in 1982, after the confrontation had already happened and he had already <br>
been stripped of his ministerial position.  He writes as a man who has<br>
nothing to lose, afraid of nothing or no one.  It is intriguing to hear<br>
his <br>
claim that he was one of those who gave early warnings to the church officers<br>
about the Davenport financial affair, several years before it happened.<br>
Theology does not occur in a vacuum, and this book tells you almost as <br>
much about the man Walter Rea as it does about his work.  He also proved <br>
to be much older than I had thought.<br>
<p>
He relates how early in his ministry he compiled several volumes of <br>
Ellen White quotations as they related to the Bible.<br>
Walter Rea claims that Ellen White was a creature of her times.  But he<br>
is also a creature of his time.  His book is crafted in the classic style<br>
of the late 40's in which he began his ministry, namely, a polemic with<br>
a lot of EGW quotes to back it up.  It's not designed for the open-minded,<br>
rather it is designed for Whiteholics like himself, first to goad them <br>
into blinding rage, then read his book to try to prove it wrong,<br>
and (the way he has it set up) likely fail to do so and come to the <br>
same rejection he did.<br>
<p>
There is a lot of careful work done in the comparison of Ellen White's <br>
books with other sources.  But tying it together is a web of unsubstantiated<br>
accusations.  The thesis of the book is not only that E.G.White copied,<br>
but that it was done premeditatedly and maliciously, that the idea of<br>
a prophet was promulgated at the beginning of the movement with intent<br>
to deceive, that EGW did not have control over her various copyists,<br>
and that a cover-up has been promulgated to hide these facts.  For most<br>
of these accusations he gives little documentation, and none at all <br>
for the various intent he subscribes.   <br>
<p>
In Michigan and Illinois we are rather far removed from Southern California,<br>
where all this action was.  I was in academy at the time when this book <br>
came out.  It seemed from my remote vantage point that the flap over<br>
Desmond Ford's ideas caused much more stir than Walter Rea's did at the time.<br>
Rea in his book likens himself to a guerilla fighter compared to Ford, the <br>
jousting knight.  Nevertheless we must say that Rea's book, more than <br>
any other, has led to more re-examining of the theology of inspiration <br>
than most other events.  This re-examination still continues today. <br>
<p>
Unfortunately, it's a re-examination that Rea never made.  Ellen G. White<br>
wasn't the kind of prophet he wanted her to be, so he chose to reject<br>
the prophet rather than his idea of a prophet.  It is clear that<br>
his fundamentalist views have not changed, only his interpretation of<br>
whether EGW met them or not.  <br>
<p>
Maybe it's good that I read this book now rather than 11 years ago. <br>
My response might have been different.  Open-minded folks have nothing <br>
to fear from reading this book.  And no one should be afraid of the facts.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
