<!-- body="start" -->
This is  in reply to Raylene's observation:<br>
<p>
Some of us who grew up in the church, and have been hearing Bible stories<br>
since the Kindergarten, have a distorted picture of the Bible characters.<br>
<p>
David has always been viewed as a great Bible hero, but let's examine his <br>
life, briefly.<br>
<p>
He was an adulterer.<br>
A cold blooded murdered. (Doesn't matter that someone else was the hit man.)<br>
He had a quick temper.<br>
He was a bad father.<br>
He was an exhibitionist. (Dancing naked in the streets.  God loved that.)<br>
<p>
I do not think that there is a whole lot about David that we would admire in<br>
a church or civic leader today.<br>
<p>
David's greatest accomplishments seem to be his prowess and bravery in war.<br>
God loved this man.  David loved God.<br>
<p>
I have always held David up as an excellent example of "God can work with<br>
anyone who is willing."<br>
<p>
-David (His namesake) Harris<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
