<title>Jun_1993: Guns</title>
<h1>Guns</h1>
Ralf Simonsson (<i>/G=Ralf/S=Simonsson/O=Fimnet/@elisa.fi</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 12 Jun 1993 21:33:06 +0300</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#163">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#163">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#163">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#163">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0164.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Dennis Grumbling"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0162.html">Fritz Guy: "Re: The White Lie: 11 years later:"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0181.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Guns"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Re: Guns.<br>
<p>
I am not a theologian, but I will try to clarify my point<br>
<p>
---------<br>
<i>&gt;&gt; the sixth commandment - in my Bible there are no exclusions in that </i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; commandment.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;The Hebrew translates to "murder" in english, not "kill".  There is</i><br>
<i>&gt;*some* difference in meaning.</i><br>
-------<br>
Well I see just juridicial difference - when you buy a gun, is it not <br>
for killing, otherwise a tear gas patron would do.<br>
<p>
--------<br>
<i>&gt;Note also: Exodus 22:1,2; Luke 22:35,36; Esther 8, 9 and 10 (I was </i><br>
<i>&gt;more than somewhat startled to read this last one after a *long* time </i><br>
<i>&gt;of neglecting it for other parts.)</i><br>
---------<br>
Let us look at Luke first:<br>
It was after the last supper - Luke 22:35-38: Then Jesus asked. "When I <br>
sent you without purse, bag or sandals, did you lack anything?"<br>
"Nothing" they answered. <br>
He said to them, "But now if you have a purse, take it, and also a bag, <br>
and if you don4t have a sword, sell your cloak and buy one. It is <br>
written: 4And he was numbered with the transgressors4; and I tell you <br>
that this must be fulfilled in me. Yes, what is written about me is <br>
reaching its fulfillment.<br>
The disciples said, "See, Lord, here are two swords."<br>
"That is enough." he replied.<br>
<p>
The disciples misunderstood Jesus words as we read 12 verses later (Luke <br>
22:51 - But Jesus answered, "No more of this" And he touched the mans <br>
ear and healed him.<br>
 <br>
If I read the text as you do, I have also big difficulties to understand <br>
the sermon on the mount (Matt 5:21):<br>
<p>
You have heard it was said to the people long ago, 4do not murder, and <br>
anyone that murders will be subject to judgment.4 But I tell you that <br>
anyone who is angry with his brother, will be subject to judgment.<br>
<p>
During the persecution that followed in Acts. there is no mention about <br>
casualties. Saul went from house to house dragging people out of the <br>
houses, nobody trying to kill him with any sword.<br>
<p>
The sword mentioned was  more a knife to be used  for cutting bread  <br>
(presumably in the bag).<br>
<p>
Then about the texts in the OT - the text in the sermon on the mount <br>
shows that Jesus did not approve the killing in the OT, and we can leave <br>
them by that instead for a lenghty discussion why God commanded the <br>
Israelites to kill everybody in conquered cities etc.<br>
<p>
------<br>
<i>&gt;&gt; I think one more, still more important reason for not having weapons</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; is that when you kill a person - for any reason - you place yourself</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; in the place of God - who only is the Lord of the living and dead. </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I will have to think about this point again...but I'm initially </i><br>
inclined<br>
<i>&gt;to disagree, at least partially: the majority of non-disease deaths in</i><br>
<i>&gt;this country, at least, are accomplished through automobile accidents.</i><br>
<i>&gt;I don't see how the statement above fits such a situation</i><br>
----<br>
Well to go back to my original point about achieving guns - cars are not <br>
mainly for killing people. If you use them for that you would be <br>
prosecuted - at least in Finland.<br>
--------<br>
<i>&gt;The point of self-defense (the which I believe to be defensible) is</i><br>
<i>&gt;to *stop* the attacker, not to kill him.  The problem is that</i><br>
<i>&gt;*effective* methods of stopping are very often potentially-lethal,</i><br>
<i>&gt;and non-lethal tools are too often ineffective.</i><br>
---------<br>
You got my point! Do not get a gun - you might kill somebody!<br>
---------<br>
<i>&gt;Still, a decision that should be left up to the individual's </i><br>
<i>&gt;conscience.</i><br>
----------<br>
It is *not* on an individual4s conscience. This is not a personal matter <br>
- as eg homosexuality in most of the cases is - by killing or even <br>
injuring an other person you are intruding in his/hers life in a very <br>
drastic way<br>
<p>
God did not order us to use any weapons, instead He said: I will fight <br>
for you. As Christians and especially SDA:s we must stick to that <br>
promise and show our faith in God.<br>
<p>
Ralf<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
