<title>Jun_1993: Shooting at Big Brother (fwd)</title>
<h1>Shooting at Big Brother (fwd)</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Jun 1993 10:29:13 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#167">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#167">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#167">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#167">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0168.html">McCluskey G: "restaurant review"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0166.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: SS ideas"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Randall A Helzerman says:</i><br>
<i>&gt; -------------------------</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;There is entirely too much trust of governments among SDAs.  Its been</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;fortold that the U.S. would speak like a dragon.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I agree, SDAs should pay more attention to prophecy, especially these days.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Some don't seem to believe it, but bible prophecy has never failed, no matter</i><br>
<i>&gt; how unlikely it seemed at the time they were given.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Bible prophecy has not failed, but human interpretation thereof has<br>
failed many times.  In our own church are many examples, beginning with<br>
the 1843/44 fiasco.  In this century, many false interpretations have<br>
been given, particularly around the time of the world wars, but also<br>
having to do with Kennedy's election and even the landing on the moon.<br>
I think it's entirely possible to have too much of an obsession with<br>
trying to figure out enigmatic scriptures while forgetting the sum and<br>
substance of scripture (an obvious recent example is David Koresh).  Is<br>
it necessary to have a "correct" view of prophecy in order to be saved?<br>
Will the Lord judge us on this basis?<br>
<p>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
