<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: K-leb D'Cat &lt;BE7116503@v9000.ntu.ac.sg&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Shooting at Big Brother</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Randall A Helzerman says:</i><br>
<i>&gt; -------------------------</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Yes, evil people can commit all kinds of mayhem with weapons.  But you</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;don't seriously think that the government is composed of all angels do</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;you?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Why should [ the government ] get all the guns?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Rom 13:1-5 [...snip...]</i><br>
<p>
I understand the argument relating to submitting to rightful government,<br>
but I have trouble accepting the view that this should extend beyond the<br>
point that a government's actions begin to interfere with one's duty to<br>
and relationship with God.  Once that point is reached, I feel that one<br>
is (or should be) duty-bound to resist that interference.<br>
<p>
That that resistence should *only* consist of armed, physical force either<br>
initially or other than as an absolute last possible resort I do reject,<br>
however.<br>
<p>
Using Romans 13:1-5 to support an argument that one should *never* resist<br>
a government gone wrong looks, to me, as leading to the argument that, for<br>
example, the German Nazi or Imperial Japanese governments of the 1930's and<br>
40's should not have been resisted. (Oh, nuts...I've gone and brought *him*<br>
into the discussion.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Steve Hix says to Steve Timm:</i><br>
<i>&gt; -----------------------------</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;Who said "put not your trust in princes"? (The concordance in</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;the Bible here at work is *really* pitiful...) It's more true now than it</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;was then, if for no other reason than current "princes" can do more damage</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;that the ancients could.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; At least your "princes" don't feed you to lions for entertainment. So, if we</i><br>
<i>&gt; don't trust princes, who do we trust, our guns i suppose?</i><br>
<p>
I did not say that.<br>
<p>
We (SDA's) put altogether too much trust in our respective governments, and<br>
often (at least here in the U.S.) condemn others who disagree with what our<br>
government may be doing. Sometimes the condemnation is justified, sometimes<br>
it is not.<br>
<p>
Don't make the mistake of assuming that anyone who disagrees with the civil<br>
authority is preaching (or desiring) armed overthrow of that authority.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; Ps 146:3-7 3 Put not your trust in princes, nor in the son of man, in whom</i><br>
<p>
Thanks! :}<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Even Jesus gave his disciples leave to arm themselves for self-defense...and</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;it is equally clear that irresponsible use of them was not part of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;package.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; If Jesus told them to go around armed, why is there no record of any of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; disciples going around armed, or using weapons in Acts, like Paul, who</i><br>
<i>&gt; frequently faced openly hostile, persecuitive people?</i><br>
<p>
Because the apostles understood the difference between a criminal attacking in<br>
the night and a conflict between their message and false philosophies?<br>
<p>
Perhaps because the laws of Rome, which allowed for self-defense, did not<br>
countenance civil unrest, which would have been the result if Paul engaged<br>
in dancing with the rioters?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
