<!-- body="start" -->
Brad,<br>
	While I was at Oakwood College, I worked with the youth division <br>
sabbath school. I learned that people value SS more when they play an active <br>
part in the program. I can't remember a single sabbath were the traditional SS <br>
format was use (prayer, scripture, mission story, ect.). Most of our programs <br>
were active programs. I presented one program where several twins were asked to <br>
give to different versions of SDA doctrine. The audience was to decide which <br>
was truth and which was error.<br>
	We also had skits and plays. We even had a short concert one sabbath. <br>
It's important to be creative and get the mebers involved. Also base your <br>
programs on some items like the one's Jerry mentioned. Especially if there are <br>
youth that you want to interest. Finally, assign various members to be apart of <br>
the planned program . <br>
	By the way, we didn't totally trash the SS school format. In the end, <br>
we found a way to incorporate the mission story in our program and we always <br>
had prayer and scripture. We just changed the way we presented it all.<br>
<p>
God Bless,<br>
Clayton<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
