<!-- body="start" -->
Nicely summarized, Steve.  One small addition:  Rea also sought to<br>
"smoke out" the policy makers by being polemic.  He was daring them<br>
to come to the table with a theology that was different from what<br>
he'd been taught at PUC and what he'd "heard" throughout his ministry.<br>
I think until the Desmond Ford dustup he largely believed that there<br>
was no questioning of SDA theological positions.  A couple of us tried<br>
very hard to get Walter to make the book more scholarly and to avoid the<br>
"bald conclusions" and raw diatribe, but he felt that only by being<br>
accusatory would he get any substantial number of people to look/listen.<br>
By the way, he may have been correct in his assessment of how to be<br>
heard.  I'm by no means sanguine at this point that I was right about<br>
tone given his objective(s).<br>
<p>
He was one of the early identifiers of the Davenport problem.  He brought<br>
two church members to discuss the Davenport "investments" with me.  I<br>
reviewed them and 1)told them that they were modified Ponzi schemes,<br>
and would ultimately fail; 2)went to the local conference president<br>
with another lawyer as a witness and "persuaded" him that the So. Calif.<br>
Conf. could never invest with Davenport [I was on the Executive Committee<br>
at the time, I think] -- So. Calif. Conf. was spared the problem at the<br>
church level although a lot of individual church members were hurt;<br>
3)told Ken Emmerson at the GC, who began to advise all the conferences,<br>
unions and institutions to be very careful; 4)met with Neal Wilson who<br>
thought I was overly concerned and "checked with a union president"<br>
who told him that "Wiley is over reacting;" 5)the union president<br>
nevertheless got his money from Davenport AFTER my conversation with<br>
Neal; 6)the "investments" came unglued.  During this time Walter Rea<br>
was also warning everyone who would listen that the Davenport "investements"<br>
were not real investments and that institutions and members should<br>
stay away from them.  As I recall Rea got "scolded" by some church<br>
officers for that as well.<br>
<p>
So much for a behind the scenes "history" of interesting times in<br>
the church.  I've been fortunate or unfortunate enought to be close<br>
to some of the upheavals we've experienced, and to have been a part<br>
of some good outcomes too.  "War stories"?<br>
<p>
--Jerry<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
