<title>Jun_1993: restaurant review</title>
<h1>restaurant review</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Jun 93 20:06:17 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#168">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#168">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#168">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#168">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0169.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Re: SS ideas"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0167.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Shooting at Big Brother (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I went to Living Springs in Manhattan yesterday.  It's on 60th between<br>
Park and Lexington (near Central Park).  It's run by an SDA group from<br>
upstate New York and is open Sunday through Friday.  They serve about<br>
350 people a day and the style is buffet with seating a cross between<br>
true restaurant style and cafeteria.  Cost for a large lunch was about<br>
$8 and most meals would be closer to $6.<br>
<p>
The food was very good.  They've somehow found a happy medium between<br>
bland and selling out (use of lots of fats and so forth).  I don't<br>
think they use dairy products and am not sure if there are any other<br>
restrictions they follow.<br>
<p>
They push a spiritual message there (literature rack) but it's very<br>
low key.  I don't know if they are financially viable.  I believe<br>
their rent is something like $12K a month and taxes $6K.  A similar<br>
restaurant near Wall Street, Country Life, closed become of economic<br>
problems.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
