<title>Jun_1993: footwashing</title>
<h1>footwashing</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Jun 1993 23:09:54 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#161">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#161">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#161">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#161">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0162.html">Fritz Guy: "Re: The White Lie: 11 years later:"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0160.html">David P. Harris: "Re: God loves you, but..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0178.html">LAINIE@delphi.com: "Re: footwashing"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hello. I am new to this list and have a question that maybe all you<br>
knowledgeable people can answer.<br>
Is the SDA church the only one to practise the 'ordinance of humility'<br>
(footwashing)? Which SDA 'pioneer' introduced the practise in the church<br>
and when?<br>
Thanks<br>
Bruno (gaeta@angis.su.oz.au)<br>
<p>
[Actually footwashing is a well-established Catholic custom, albeit<br>
practiced only by the Pope every Maundy Thursday.  SDA's were not the first<br>
nor are we the only denomination to do it for all the members, however.<br>
Those with more info please shed light (certainly Worldwide Church of God<br>
and Church of God 7th-day do it as well, but I think there are more others<br>
beyond this.)  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
