<title>Jun_1993: Article from Dennis Grumling</title>
<h1>Article from Dennis Grumling</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Jun 1993 23:27:30 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#175">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#175">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#175">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#175">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0176.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  The White Lie:  11 years later:"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0174.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Shooting at Big Brother"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0197.html">Dan Crowe: "Dating outside the faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I just returned from the memorial service for Dennis Grumling, SDAnet<br>
member and member along with me of the Elmhurst, SDA church.   Though<br>
I have conveyed my condolences to the family members (also SDAnet members)<br>
I wish to use the net to do the same.  When Dennis made his views known, <br>
it was often as the voice of reason.  He will be greatly missed.<br>
<p>
I present a reprise of his own words, written on SDAnet about two years<br>
ago.  This post was written in the midst of a dating discussion.  Fittingly,<br>
I received a private query on this topic just on Friday, which the post<br>
addresses quite well, I think.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<p>
[Dennis's words follow below  SCT]<br>
<p>
Another aspect of dating outside of your faith that has not been brought<br>
up is, if you choose to date (and it is a choice!) outside your faith,<br>
and you try to witness to this person, what happens when this person<br>
becomes interested in your faith but you decide that you are not<br>
interested in marriage or continued dating with this person??  Do you<br>
dump the person, knowing full well that it will likely turn them away<br>
from your faith?  Do you keep dating and try to pretend that all is<br>
well?<br>
 <br>
Yes, I realize that ideally you will break up but remain friends and<br>
keep witnessing to them.  I've got news for any idealists on this<br>
conference:  it just ain't so.  I have seen this type of situation<br>
happen all too often.  And, even when the church that the dating couple<br>
has been attending is sensitive enough to try and build bridges to the<br>
individuals involved in the hope that a break up will not mean a loss of<br>
faith to either of them, it is a difficult and tenuous proposition at<br>
best.<br>
 <br>
Perhaps I should phrase the question more bluntly:  Is it a good idea to<br>
mix hormones and Bible study?  How does the giver of the studies, let<br>
alone the receiver, determine who/what is being responded to--the Holy<br>
Spirit or the siren call of love?  How do you keep the two separate,<br>
especially when the two roads (dating and Bible study) diverge?<br>
 <br>
I don't think it is possible to keep the two separate, and therefore<br>
would not recommend dating outside of one's faith, if one values one's<br>
faith and respects the other person as a human with the right to make<br>
faith choices.  However, I would love to hear other views on this.<br>
 <br>
Dennis K. Grumling<br>
Assistant Catalog Librarian<br>
University of Illinois at Chicago<br>
 <br>
EMAIL TO:  U20154@UICVM (BITNET) OR U20154@UICVM.UIC.EDU (INTERNET)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
