<!-- body="start" -->
Relative vs absolute truth.  During my sojourn at Andrews, I was forced<br>
to take a class that I detested.  Taught by Dr. Asa Thoreson, it was called<br>
"Philosophical Biology".  In the intervening years, I have come to <br>
recognize it as one of the most important classes that I have ever taken.<br>
I took a gem of truth from that class, courtesy of Dr. Thoreson that has<br>
helped me in more ways than I can count.  Thanks, Doc.  "All truth is<br>
relative, the only absolute truth is God".<br>
<p>
This allows one to make sense of a great deal of what one encounters in the<br>
world.<br>
<p>
While I'm on the topic of prior teachers, I also owe a great debt to<br>
Dr. Robert Fadely.  Experimental Psych left me with another gem that<br>
has stood the test of time, and been a great confort and stabilizing<br>
influence in my life.  "Things take more time than they do" Dr. R.C. Fadely.<br>
A VERY profound statement the more you think about it, and has helped<br>
immeasurably in my carrer as a Software Engineer.<br>
Cheers<br>
woody<br>
