<title>Jun_1993: Dating outside the faith</title>
<h1>Dating outside the faith</h1>
Dan Crowe (<i>dcrowe@puc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 15 Jun 1993 09:09:25 -0700 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#197">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#197">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#197">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#197">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0198.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Harmful Effects of Tobbaco"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0196.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Biases and homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0175.html">Steven Timm: "Article from Dennis Grumling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dennis (I'm sorry that I never knew him) argued that dating outside the<br>
faith always leads to the confusion of love of the faith and love of the<br>
human partner, especially if the dating partners stop dating.<br>
<p>
I just wanted to relate my own story which contradicts this theory.<br>
My first contact with Seventh-Day Adventism was through a young Adventist<br>
woman I dated just after graduation from college.  I was unaware at the<br>
time that our relationship began that she was Adventist and didn't even<br>
have a clue as to what that meant.  I started attending church with her<br>
soon after our relationship began because I was searching for meaning in<br>
my life and because I sensed that her church was an important part of her<br>
life.  We broke up within three months, but I continued attending the<br>
church, essentially continually, and was baptized about two years later.<br>
<p>
Now I am not advocating that single Adventists should actively seek<br>
romantic relationships with non-Adventists as a form of witnessing.  In my<br>
case, as a non-Adventist I initiated the relationship with an Adventist. <br>
What I am trying to say is that sometimes God works in mysterious ways. <br>
If a single Adventist is asked by a non-Adventist to form a romantic<br>
relationship, I would suggest much prayer and Bible study before<br>
responding either positively or negatively.  In most cases, I would expect<br>
that the answer should be "no", but occasionally the answer might<br>
appropriately be "yes".<br>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
