<title>Jun_1993: Truth and Time</title>
<h1>Truth and Time</h1>
Dan Crowe (<i>dcrowe@puc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 15 Jun 1993 09:51:29 -0700 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#201">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#201">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#201">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#201">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0202.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Thank you"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0200.html">Tino: "Re: Radiation from Tobacco?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Marcus mentioned some time ago that EGW repeatedly used phrases like<br>
"truth for this time".  The implication was that if it was truth for her<br>
time it is not truth for our time, and further that this implication leads<br>
naturally to the conclusion that much of the Bible was truth for the time<br>
at which it was written but is no longer truth for our time.<br>
<p>
I am very uncomfortable with these conclusions and would like to<br>
systematically study the phrases in question.  If Marcus, and anyone with<br>
similar opinions, could post a set of phrases and or references which seem<br>
to imply the conclusions stated above, I will use a CD-ROM version of the<br>
EGW writings to study them and will report my findings to the net.<br>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
