<title>Jun_1993: Re: Guns</title>
<h1>Re: Guns</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 15 Jun 93 10:37:43 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#181">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#181">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#181">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#181">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0182.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Shooting at Big Brother"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0180.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re:  SS ideas"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0163.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: Ralf Simonsson (Tel 90-3930770, f: 773, k 915145499)</i><br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Guns</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I am not a theologian, but I will try to clarify my point</i><br>
<p>
Me neither...but it shouldn't stop us. :}<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; ---------</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;&gt; the sixth commandment - in my Bible there are no exclusions in that </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;&gt; commandment.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;The Hebrew translates to "murder" in english, not "kill".  There is</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;*some* difference in meaning.</i><br>
<i>&gt; -------</i><br>
<i>&gt; Well I see just juridicial difference - when you buy a gun, is it not </i><br>
<i>&gt; for killing, otherwise a tear gas patron would do.</i><br>
<p>
No. That may be end result, but it should not be the intended purpose.<br>
<p>
Ignoring target shooting, hunting, and other legal uses, self-defense<br>
intent is to stop potential rape or deadly attacks. (The *vast* majority<br>
of with-gun defenses in the U.S. result in no injury to either party, nor<br>
discharge of the firearm. The numbers, according to a large number of<br>
studies of the issue range from 500,000/yr on up. *One* significant study<br>
places the number almost an order of magnitude lower, at 80,000/yr, but<br>
its methodology is believed to greatly underreport actual events.)<br>
<p>
Another thing to consider is that in several parts of the country, one<br>
may purchase a handgun for self defense, but things like mace, tear gas<br>
and pepper sprays are *illegal* for civilian use. The justification is<br>
that criminals might get some spray and use it against a police officer.<br>
It's a crazy situation, but it's what a lot of us live with.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; --------</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Note also: Exodus 22:1,2; Luke 22:35,36; Esther 8, 9 and 10 (I was </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;more than somewhat startled to read this last one after a *long* time </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;of neglecting it for other parts.)</i><br>
<i>&gt; ---------</i><br>
<i>&gt; Let us look at Luke first:</i><br>
<i>&gt; It was after the last supper - Luke 22:35-38: Then Jesus asked. "When I </i><br>
<i>&gt; sent you without purse, bag or sandals, did you lack anything?"</i><br>
<i>&gt; "Nothing" they answered. </i><br>
<i>&gt; He said to them, "But now if you have a purse, take it, and also a bag, </i><br>
<i>&gt; and if you don4t have a sword, sell your cloak and buy one. It is </i><br>
<i>&gt; written: 4And he was numbered with the transgressors4; and I tell you </i><br>
<i>&gt; that this must be fulfilled in me. Yes, what is written about me is </i><br>
<i>&gt; reaching its fulfillment.</i><br>
<i>&gt; The disciples said, "See, Lord, here are two swords."</i><br>
<i>&gt; "That is enough." he replied.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The disciples misunderstood Jesus words as we read 12 verses later (Luke </i><br>
<i>&gt; 22:51 - But Jesus answered, "No more of this" And he touched the mans </i><br>
<i>&gt; ear and healed him.</i><br>
<p>
They almost certainly did misunderstand. He was not involving Himself in<br>
a political uprising, nor were they to do so.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; You have heard it was said to the people long ago, do not murder, and </i><br>
<i>&gt; anyone that murders will be subject to judgment. But I tell you that </i><br>
<i>&gt; anyone who is angry with his brother, will be subject to judgment.</i><br>
<p>
*I* have no problem with that. Offensive force is unjustified, while<br>
defensive use of force may be under some circumstances.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The sword mentioned was  more a knife to be used  for cutting bread  </i><br>
<i>&gt; (presumably in the bag).</i><br>
<p>
OK...<br>
<p>
(Now why would that suddenly become important? One could still break<br>
bread by hand.  Such a knife could *still* be used as a weapon...it's<br>
nothing more than a tool, and the critical factor is the use it's put<br>
to.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Then about the texts in the OT - the text in the sermon on the mount </i><br>
<i>&gt; shows that Jesus did not approve the killing in the OT, and we can leave </i><br>
<i>&gt; them by that instead for a lenghty discussion why God commanded the </i><br>
<i>&gt; Israelites to kill everybody in conquered cities etc.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Well to go back to my original point about achieving guns - cars are not </i><br>
<i>&gt; mainly for killing people. If you use them for that you would be </i><br>
<i>&gt; prosecuted - at least in Finland.</i><br>
<p>
Here to, and rightly so.<br>
<p>
Guns *here* (and in Finland, according to Finns that I correspond with<br>
on the net) are not *primarily* used for killing people, either by design<br>
or by intent of purchaser.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;The point of self-defense (the which I believe to be defensible) is</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;to *stop* the attacker, not to kill him.  The problem is that</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;*effective* methods of stopping are very often potentially-lethal,</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;and non-lethal tools are too often ineffective.</i><br>
<i>&gt; ---------</i><br>
<i>&gt; You got my point! Do not get a gun - you might kill somebody!</i><br>
<p>
I still say that one should leave the question up to the individual.<br>
<p>
Other means of defense involve a non-zero risk of death to weilder or<br>
target, even teargas sprays.  In fact, in many cases, the gun is the<br>
least-damaging option, since it is most likely, in the most number of<br>
cases, to cause an attacker to break off his attack.<br>
<p>
In any case, the gun is the absolute *last* resort.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;Still, a decision that should be left up to the individual's </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;conscience.</i><br>
<i>&gt; ----------</i><br>
<i>&gt; It is *not* on an individual's conscience. This is not a personal matter </i><br>
<i>&gt; - as eg homosexuality in most of the cases is - by killing or even </i><br>
<i>&gt; injuring an other person you are intruding in his/hers life in a very </i><br>
<i>&gt; drastic way</i><br>
<p>
A murderer or rapist or armed robber has already gone over the line.<br>
<p>
If you choose to not resist under and circumstances, that is your choice,<br>
and I have no problem with that.<br>
<p>
Some others may, in good faith, choose otherwise (and hope never to have<br>
to deal with such sever problems). If I had no wife or children, I think<br>
I might choose differently, perhaps.<br>
<p>
This is the last that I'll discuss on this issue.  I think that we've<br>
reached bedrock here, and further discussion is unlikely to bring up<br>
anything new or interesting.<br>
<p>
You're still invited for lunch if you visit, though.  :}<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
