<title>Jun_1993: Re: God loves you, but...</title>
<h1>Re: God loves you, but...</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 15 Jun 93 11:11:30 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#184">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#184">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#184">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#184">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0185.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  The White Lie:  11 years later:"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0183.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re: Guns Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0125.html">Raylene Dyson: "God loves you, but..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0192.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: God loves you, but..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[David P. Harris writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Some of us who grew up in the church, and have been hearing Bible stories</i><br>
<i>&gt; since the Kindergarten, have a distorted picture of the Bible characters.</i><br>
                                 ^^^^^^^^^<br>
Shoulda come to my Sabbath schools 8-).  At age appropriate times, there<br>
was no dissembling as to David's faults.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; but let's examine his  life, briefly.</i><br>
Fortunately, there's more to David's life than just what follows.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;   He was an adulterer.</i><br>
<i>&gt;   A cold-blooded murderer.</i><br>
<i>&gt;   He had a quick temper.</i><br>
<i>&gt;   He was a bad father.</i><br>
             ^^^<br>
Not completely.  Note how often Solomon, in Proverbs, said he'd learned<br>
this or that piece of wisdom from his Dad.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;   He was an exhibitionist. (Dancing naked in the streets.  God loved that.)</i><br>
                                      ^^^^^ 2 Sam 6:14 does not support this.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I do not think that there is a whole lot about David that we would admire in</i><br>
<i>&gt; a church or civic leader today.</i><br>
<p>
Scripture paints an honest picture of David.  From the picture, we can<br>
distinguish the times when he was wise and when he was foolish.  From<br>
these examples (cf 1 Cor 10:11), we can receive instruction in wisdom<br>
(Prov 9:9, 1:7, 8:33, 10:17, 12:1, 13:18, 23:23) and what characterizes<br>
Godly living.  Invariably, when David was foolish it was because he was<br>
depending upon his own smarts, when he was wise it was because he was<br>
humble, sought the Lord's advise, and waited for God's timing.  An example<br>
of this is when David "escaped" to Gath, moved into Ziklag, then got caught<br>
in the corner of the war between Achish and Saul (1 Sam ch 29 and 30).<br>
I observe that seeking God's will, ways, and timing is something that church<br>
and civic leaders would do well to emulate.<br>
<p>
When rebuked, David did not resist but accepted the correction (2 Sam 12).<br>
This is praiseworthy; we tend to react and become upset if someone rebukes us.<br>
David understood true repentance and humility (Ps 34:18, ch 51), rare<br>
attributes in our society.  David understood the need to respect leadership,<br>
even when they were messed up; he trusted God to remove faulty leaders<br>
in God's own way and time, so he would not touch the Lord's anointed.<br>
Are these not characteristics which would be valuable in us all?<br>
<p>
David wrote many psalms of praise to God; he frequently stood up in the<br>
congregation to utter praise to God; he spent much time, esp as a youth,<br>
meditating up Scripture.  Without David, major portions of Scripture that<br>
uplift and ennoble character would be missing.<br>
<p>
True enough, David, that the record of the Bible's David is checkered and<br>
that this demonstrates how God patiently works with us.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
