<title>Jun_1993: Goodbye</title>
<h1>Goodbye</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 15 Jun 1993 23:10:10 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#179">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#179">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#179">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#179">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0180.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re:  SS ideas"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0178.html">LAINIE@delphi.com: "Re: footwashing"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0187.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  Goodbye"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi, friends,<br>
<p>
I feel that I have made some good friends electronically through SDA-Net<br>
and to you I say goodbye.  I am leaving<br>
the 'Land of SDA-Net' to begin a new course of study.  I wish that<br>
I would have had more time to contribute to the discussions because <br>
one voice--the male one--is heard loud and clear on this net.  Unfortunately,<br>
the women who do belong contribute infrequently.  I'm curious why that is<br>
so.  Are we too busy?  Are we uninterested in the current topics?  Are we<br>
afraid of the flames?  Do we feel comfortable in this group of people?<br>
I, for one, feel very uncomfortable commmunicating within a group that believes<br>
that they have a "God-given" right to be the "head" of a woman; or where<br>
the full rights of being a human are not acknowledged; or where we <br>
justify women being given the right to work as a minister but not to be<br>
recognized as a full-fledged one.  All of these positions are taken using<br>
the word of the Holy One as justification.<br>
<p>
[Of the 165 members of SDAnet, 18 are women, counting Sue.  The ratio has<br>
been higher in the past.  Perhaps most to blame for this are all those<br>
who steer young women away from technical fields.  As for the lack of <br>
participation, perhaps we should not attribute to fear what may instead<br>
be attributed to good judgment, holding peace whilst the males make <br>
fools of themselves.  Sue's voice will be missed.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
In the latest issue of Ponderings, Merikay made the suggestion that, since<br>
commissioned ministers are, according to Mostert (excuse my spelling), <br>
essentially the same as ordained ones, why not have women be ordained for<br>
the next hundred years and men be commissioned?  What do you think?  <br>
<p>
Personally, I think the ordination issue is a great way to keep us from<br>
focusing on the real problem of women's position in the church.  Women who<br>
are &gt; 60% of the church membership are not represented in the decision<br>
making bodies of the church.  THAT IS A BIG PROBLEM.  THAT IS OPPRESSION!!!<br>
Why is it that men are so determined to keep center stage?  Why are men<br>
so afraid to share the responsibility of making decisions--in the home<br>
and in the church?  Is power that addicting?<br>
<p>
I belong to a list that involves discussions of females and males about<br>
women's position in society.  Some of the men on that list have renewed <br>
my faith in the possibility that men might be able to see the privilege <br>
that is given to them because of nothing more than the genitals with which they<br>
were born.  I am posting with this note a letter from a man <br>
who wrote in response to<br>
the article that appeared in the New York Times on Sunday.  The article<br>
was written by a female graduate student at Princeton.  She knew no one<br>
who had ever been raped, however, she wrote an article attempting to<br>
redefine the concept of rape.<br>
<p>
I hope you enjoy this posting.<br>
<p>
<p>
"Both Roiphe and Camille Paglia share an assumption that has a lot of<br>
theoretical implications:  that male people will not change, that fem-<br>
inism cannot or will not have any meaningful effect on how men behave.<br>
<p>
Given the parameters of what this assumption means, in contrast to its<br>
alternative (that men are NOT like the weather, NOT beyond agentic change<br>
and therefore to be merely coped with), I direct your attention to the<br>
equally problematic first-level simple alternative:  that, yes, feminism<br>
CAN TOO have the necessary effect on male behavior, and, by doing so,<br>
make it possible for women to move beyond adaptive modes of response to<br>
patriarchy.  The problem here is that such a stance leads--or at least<br>
can lead--to a prescription for women to expend their energies trying<br>
to change men, i.e., "giving their female energies over to men" (Daly).<br>
<p>
But I don't think it is either/or.  I think feminism definitely WILL<br>
change men and male behavior, (although I think that at some point, it<br>
must include male ACTIVE, rather than PASSIVE, participation, in order<br>
to result in a widely adopted re-definition of masculinity by males,<br>
and the definition of any group must ultimately be internal), but that<br>
feminism is at its most effective in making changes among men when it is<br>
primarily oriented towards speaking women's truths in women's terms, not<br>
as attempts to placate-and-change a bunch of guys.<br>
Males ARE changing.  I see it, I sense it strongly; to be a nineteen-year-<br>
old guy is qualitatively different from how it was in 1978 when I was 18,<br>
and the differences are in a feminist direction.<br>
<p>
Keep on doing what you've been doing; build on it, but believe that it is<br>
a good work.  I grew up inspired by feminism and it affected who I am for<br>
years and years.  Males will listen and understand (perhaps not universally,<br>
but then, most people of any category within patriarchy do not do their<br>
own thinking; it's strongly discouraged!).  And...keep some space to your-<br>
selves as explicitly womyn's space, but be inclusive sometime and let those<br>
of us who wish to participate play a role in what you are doing; it is our<br>
gender that must be changed, for the most part, and you must sense that in<br>
order for it to ever really take hold, our changes must be heartfelt, from<br>
us, not concessions made by us in the face of commentary from the outside.<br>
A lot of the backlash is fueled by males who wish to define themselves<br>
rather than be defined by women telling them how to be, and unfortunately,<br>
the inarticulate binary-thinking reactionary stuff tends to weigh in first.<br>
They do not, however, speak for our gender, and there are a growing many of<br>
us who have heard you (collectively) and have since then done our own<br>
thinking, and who are enthusiastically ready willing and hopefully able to<br>
play a meaningful role by self-defining manhood outside of patriarchal<br>
patterns.  I don't know if that makes us "feminists" or if some other term<br>
is more appropriate, but whether you call it "feminism" or "ishmakabbible",<br>
I think it means that yes there will be change, and no it is not entirely<br>
the burden of your gender to change all of our gender.<br>
<p>
In light of that, Paglia and Roiphe are "conservative" in the sense of<br>
planning for the worst scenario possible, which I think dampens revolu-<br>
tionary fervor"<br>
<p>
I hope this gives you some joy.<br>
<p>
Sue Harrington<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
