<title>Jun_1993: Animal Sacrifice Supreme Court decision</title>
<h1>Animal Sacrifice Supreme Court decision</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 15 Jun 1993 23:28:50 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#186">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#186">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#186">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#186">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0187.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  Goodbye"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0185.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  The White Lie:  11 years later:"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0191.html">TracyAnne Burtch-Nickless: "Re: Animal Sacrifice Supreme Court decision"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In a decision this Monday, the Supreme Court ruled that a Hialeah, FL<br>
sect  (in the Santeria movement) has the right to do animal sacrifices.<br>
Taken in conjunction with the school prayer and equal access decisions <br>
also announced that day, it seems like there is still quite a bit <br>
of place for religious freedom available in the minds of the Court.<br>
<p>
However, it was interesting to hear Paul Harvey's comment on the decision.<br>
In the Paul Harvey News and Comment (which Good Michigan SDA's all listen to)<br>
he spent several minutes of uncharacteristically xenophobic commentary <br>
on this (it strikes at the mores of this country)  (other countries are<br>
telling the people whose customs don't fit to just stay out.) (If the<br>
justices didn't leave this decision to their law clerks, they should<br>
have).<br>
<p>
What is the feedback that others have heard  on this decision?  I don't think<br>
it even made the Chicago newspapers, at least I didn't see it in the ones<br>
I bought.  Do or should we feel more free because we have the religious <br>
liberty to do animal sacrifice?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
