<title>Jun_1993: Re: Animal Sacrifice Supreme Court decision</title>
<h1>Re: Animal Sacrifice Supreme Court decision</h1>
Stan Macasieb (<i>macasib@rtsg.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 16 Jun 1993 08:42:20 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#204">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#204">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#204">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#204">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0205.html">David Plaisted: "White Lie"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0203.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Goodbye"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The analysis I read on the decision is that a statute that narrowly<br>
defines an otherwise legal behavior as illegal is unconstitutional.<br>
The statute in Hialeah, FL, was passed specifically to prohibit<br>
animal sacrifices. (Flame on) Killing animals for food is not considered <br>
illegal behavior unless you're a member of PETA. (Flame off)<br>
<p>
I wish I had a copy of the editorial. It was from the Scripps Howard<br>
Newspapers line and published in yesterday's _Chicago Tribune_ in the<br>
lower right-hand corner of the op-ed page. <br>
<p>
It went on to say, however, that it doesn't mean that the Smith v. Oregon<br>
case was overturned. As a refresher, the US SC ruled that a religious<br>
ritual that goes against an illegal act of the state is still illegal. That<br>
was the case where that Native American group used peyote, an illicit<br>
substance under Oregon statutes, in their religious ritual and were<br>
charged with using an illegal drug. Thus, the need for the Freedom of <br>
Religion Restoration Act is still urgent.<br>
<p>
Bottom line: The Santeria case is an isolated one. The Supreme Court<br>
did their job on this one, but full freedom of religious expression<br>
still does not exist.<br>
<p>
Guess I won't feel good until I put that lamb on the spit! ;)<br>
<p>
