<title>Jun_1993: Re:  SS ideas</title>
<h1>Re:  SS ideas</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 16 Jun 1993 09:29:29 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#180">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#180">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#180">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#180">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0181.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0179.html">Steven Timm: "Goodbye"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0147.html">Steven Timm: "SS ideas"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Someone is trying to put some enthusiasm into Sabbath School. What a great<br>
idea. Sabbath School has become so boring that I know of two instances<br>
at Avondale this year where noone turned up to take the preliminaries<br>
and the church pastor had to step in at the last minute.<br>
<p>
Here are some ideas that I would enjoy is Sabbath School.<br>
<p>
1.  Involve a lot of people. This guarantees at least a minimum attendence<br>
<p>
2.  Provide alternative study themes. 12 weeks on some topics is just too<br>
    much.<br>
<p>
3.  Explore the use of partipatory arts. Music, drama(tut tut), photography<br>
    literature etc. I read some of Henry Lawson to several Sabbath School<br>
    classes during the lessons on Job. (Henry Lawson is an Australian<br>
    author who wrote some fine australian literature about 90 odd years<br>
    ago. The article I read was "Shall we gather at the River" and gives<br>
    a moving insight into suffering and bitterness in a pioneer Australian<br>
    setting)<br>
<p>
4.  What about things like cooking demonstrations. I took a class on <br>
    Bread baking during the health series of lessons.<br>
<p>
5.  A series on Marriage enrichment, or how to relate to the unchurched<br>
    is another possibility.<br>
<p>
6.  One of the most interesting Sabbath School series I attended was hearing<br>
    from other people about their sense of mission. We heard from Anglicans,<br>
    Salvation Army, youth workers, prison officers, parole officers,<br>
    doctors, teachers, Bible society workers and others. It was a real<br>
    eye opener and made many of us realise that SDAism is not the centre<br>
    of the universe.<br>
<p>
7.  What about a prayer session? It would require some preparation<br>
    so that you don't end up "blessing the missionaries and asking<br>
    forgiveness for unspecified sins" for an hour.<br>
<p>
8.  Target special groups. Put on a Sabbath School specially for children.<br>
    They do it often enough for us.<br>
<p>
9.  Have Sabbath School after the Church service as  a discussion based<br>
    on the service. This arrangement is a great excuse for skipping<br>
    the preliminaries.<br>
<p>
I have said enough. Suffice it to say that I find most ordinary Sabbath<br>
Schools dull and uninteresting, and whenever I get the opportunity I<br>
do something different.<br>
<p>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Avondale College<br>
mashton@moira.cs.su.oz.au<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
