<title>Jun_1993: FW: Colorado Methodists vow to fight Amendment 2</title>
<h1>FW: Colorado Methodists vow to fight Amendment 2</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 16 Jun 93 09:54:41 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#195">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#195">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#195">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#195">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0196.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Biases and homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0194.html">John Ash - CS: "Re: Animal Sacrifice Supreme Court decision"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A few weeks ago, a "lively" discussion about homosexuality filled the<br>
SDAnet-waves.  During that discussion, I asked for suggestions on<br>
how the Church should respond or deal with homosexual members.<br>
<p>
Outside of the usual, love the "sinner hate the sin" responses, I was<br>
given no real answers.  However, a non-SDA Christian friend forwarded<br>
this notice to me.  I share it with you.<br>
===============<br>
The Denver Post<br>
June 11, 1993, pg 5B<br>
<p>
By The Fort Collins Coloradoan<br>
<p>
Colorado Methodists will use television commercials and a letter-writing<br>
campaign in an effort to repeal Amendment 2, the controversial measure that<br>
prevents state and local governments form adopting laws granting civil rights<br>
protection to homosexuals.<br>
<p>
The repeal campaign was OK'd during the recent Rocky Mountain Annual <br>
Conference<br>
of the United Methodist Church at Colorado State University.<br>
<p>
"The book of the church clearly states we affirm civil rights regardless of<br>
race, ethnic background, gender or sexual orientation," said Janet Forbes,<br>
program director for the regional United Methodist Church.<br>
<p>
"The issue was approved by a good majority."<br>
<p>
She said, "This is an example of religious diversity at work.  Many <br>
traditional<br>
churches have taken a stand against Amendment 2."<br>
<p>
Colorado voters passed Amendment 2 last November.<br>
<p>
Forbes said United Methodist Church members do not approve of only one<br>
religious group--the Colorado Springs-based fundamentalists who initiated<br>
Amendment 2--defining Christianity in Colorado.<br>
<p>
The church is applying for grants to help fund commercials about <br>
Amemdnent 2 to<br>
run in Colorado Springs.<br>
<p>
                                                     Reprinted w/o permission<br>
<p>
=====END=====<br>
I know there have to be SDA churches in Colorado, Maine, Tampa FL at this time.<br>
How are these churches dealing with this issue?  Is it a concern to <br>
them?  Is it a<br>
concern with the General Conference?  Do they even know what's going on?<br>
Is SDAnet concerned?  Should it be?<br>
<p>
Marcuss@microsoft.com	Ye ARE the salt of the earth...<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
