<title>Jun_1993: Re: truth and time</title>
<h1>Re: truth and time</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>17 Jun 1993 15:26:15 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#206">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#206">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#206">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#206">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0207.html">Steven Timm: "Post-institutionalism:  Ready or not..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0205.html">David Plaisted: "White Lie"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Daniel Crowe writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Marcus mentioned some time ago that EGW repeatedly used phrases like</i><br>
<i>&gt;"truth for this time".  The implication was that if it was truth for her</i><br>
<i>&gt;time it is not truth for our time, and further that this implication leads</i><br>
<i>&gt;naturally to the conclusion that much of the Bible was truth for the time</i><br>
<i>&gt;at which it was written but is no longer truth for our time.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I am very uncomfortable with these conclusions etc etc</i><br>
<p>
I think one reason is that there is a leap of logic present here. I don't<br>
think the fact that prophets write "truth for their time" means that this<br>
truth is useless once "their time" has passed. As I said in a previous post<br>
myself, God being God and people being people, long-lasting principles are<br>
usually present in any inspired work.<br>
<p>
Although I am of the opinion that prophets always write for their own<br>
contemporaries, I do not agree that the implications Daniel mentions are<br>
a necessary extension of this.<br>
<p>
Unless he is suggesting that a person today should relate to the book of <br>
Corinthians in the same way that a worshipper in Corinth would have related <br>
to the letter at the time it was written. I do disagree with that approach.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
