<!-- received="Thu Jun 17 22:23:02 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Thu, 17 Jun 1993 22:23:02 -0400 (EDT)" -->
<!-- name="Steven Timm" -->
<!-- email="st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Post-institutionalism:  Ready or not..." -->
<!-- id="kg8GQ6m00YUo4Y07g0@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Jun_1993: Post-institutionalism:  Ready or not...</title>
<h1>Post-institutionalism:  Ready or not...</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 17 Jun 1993 22:23:02 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#207">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#207">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#207">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#207">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0208.html">Richard Guy: "Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0206.html">Tony Dyson: "Re: truth and time"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0208.html">Richard Guy: "Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Last week our conference officers called a series of town meetings to <br>
discuss with the members the future of Broadview Academy.  Like many <br>
other SDA boarding academies, it has suffered declining enrollment over<br>
the past few years; it now has 125 students where there were 250<br>
a few years ago.  In a few years the cornfields around it  will all <br>
be part of Geneva, IL, complete with train station, subdivisions, strip<br>
malls, the works.  Land in that region is selling for several thousand <br>
dollars an acre.<br>
<p>
Broadview is different from some other SDA academies in several important<br>
ways.  Its reputation for academics has always been strong, and this is<br>
backed up by certification from the North Central Assn. of Colleges and <br>
Schools (which many SDA academies in this area don't have.)  Their campus <br>
industry is financially healthy and they could employ many more students <br>
than they have right now.  Also some students can work at an electronics<br>
plant just half a mile from the academy.  Broadview is easily accessible<br>
to the homes of students, being only 40 miles away from the lakefront<br>
of Chicago.<br>
<p>
Yet it seems that there are problems of perception of Broadview which <br>
have led to the declining enrollment.  Even as it is being swallowed by <br>
the metropolitan area the complaints are louder than ever that it is <br>
too far away.  Stronger than usual public schools in the suburbs of <br>
Chicago (home for many of the students) contribute to the idea that Broadview<br>
is weak academically (though some alumni of Broadview Academy on this very <br>
list might well dispute that).  <br>
<p>
Added to these are the real problems of a 30+year-old campus in which <br>
depreciation and maintainance have not been funded, and there is $1000000<br>
worth of asbestos to remove.  <br>
<p>
How can one fight against misperceptions?  The best cure for Broadview<br>
would be 100 more students, if this could happen.  Since there are <br>
almost 800 baptized SDA youth of academy age in the Chicago area alone,<br>
the potential population is certainly there.  30 students go to academies<br>
in other states and pay $1000/$2000 a year more, so money, although an<br>
object, is not the only object.  There are many parents who could send<br>
their kids anywhere they want who don't send them there.  They have judged<br>
the church school system which gave them their degree and got them rich<br>
to be not good enough for their kids.<br>
<p>
I have voiced the platitude that the church should be taking more interest<br>
in its youth who do not relate to the institutional system, and I am <br>
doing my best.  I teach a Sabbath school class of ten high-school aged<br>
young people, only one of whom is in church school (and he's not one of the <br>
pastor's kids, either).  What I can give them in a Sabbath School class <br>
is no substitute for what they could be getting in church school.  I am<br>
seeing some of them be drawn away from the church with extracurricular<br>
activities.  It seems that I am only one of the many childless boosters<br>
of Christian education. <br>
<p>
Though we are but five miles from the large "SDA" hospital in Hinsdale, IL,<br>
and but ten from the conference office, the institutional church has<br>
little or no effect on the young people of my church.  Some have never<br>
seen Broadview Academy or heard of Andrews University.<br>
<p>
How can this change?  Should it change?  If the Broadview Academy <br>
subsidy were to disappear, then there would be more than $400 to spend<br>
in the Illinois conference on youth ministry.  But for those that go to <br>
boarding school, it can be such an improvement over the home situation they <br>
are in that it is probably necessary to keep a boarding school open <br>
for that reason alone.<br>
<p>
Broadview Academy is not going to close, but its problems aren't going to<br>
go away anytime soon.  The school needs your prayers and ideas and kids <br>
(they can't hold on for 15-20 years to wait for mine.:)  Ideas?  thoughts?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
