<title>Jun_1993: Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not...</title>
<h1>Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not...</h1>
Richard Guy (<i>guy@ficus.cs.ucla.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 18 Jun 1993 14:22:46 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#208">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#208">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#208">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#208">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0209.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Post-institutionalism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0207.html">Steven Timm: "Post-institutionalism:  Ready or not..."</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0207.html">Steven Timm: "Post-institutionalism:  Ready or not..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0227.html">Michael Merginio: "Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Suggestions w.r.t. Broadview Academy:<br>
<p>
Is BA actively selling itself?  Part of the difficulty is that in the past<br>
SDA education survived solely on "cultural imperative to attend"; now it<br>
must seriously compete, and the system doesn't know how.<br>
<p>
Specific suggestions for Broadview, based on a brief visit out there last<br>
summer, when I was staying in a hotel on the Lakefront:<br>
<p>
1) Figure out where potential students actually live, and show every single<br>
   one of them exactly what the commuting options are: train, bus, EL, and<br>
   so on.  It really isn't very far from the Geneva station to Broadview,<br>
   which suggests that Broadview might want to run a shuttle service from<br>
   the station to the campus.  Train service is remarkably comfortable by<br>
   US standards; the number of folks who commute from Geneva-area suburbs<br>
   to all parts of the city is impressive, so why not promote the reverse<br>
   commute for school kids?  <br>
<p>
   This may mean adjusting BA's class schedule to accomodate trains, but<br>
   there's nothing sacred about 8am-2pm.<br>
<p>
2) After commuting by train, etc., for a year, many students might well<br>
   be enticed to just stay at the campus during the week.  Weekends, for<br>
   most, will be spent at home, which BA should figure out how to view as<br>
   a "good thing", and not a horrible thing.  (During my time at Rio Lindo<br>
   Academy in the mid-70's, weeknite-only boarders were strongly discouraged,<br>
   even when the kids lived a literal 100 yards from campus...)<br>
   Yes, its a different atmosphere, but it beats being out of business.<br>
<p>
3) Schools need to be more flexible with payment options, etc., and at the<br>
   same time uphold the right mix of standards based on principles.  BA is<br>
   just one of many schools that needs to recognize it is fighting for its<br>
   survival, even now.  Downward enrollment trends are enormously difficult<br>
   to counteract, even slow down.  Parents need to perceive that the school<br>
   is responsive to their problems/concerns, a rarity in the past.<br>
   Money and behavior are always at the top of the concerns list...<br>
<p>
4) Pay teachers to go out and recruit on weekends, holidays, etc.<br>
   Promote student-led recruitment activities at their home congregations.<br>
<p>
5) Sponsor parties, etc., at BA, targeting youth from various congregations<br>
   and bringing them out wholesale.  In other words, do whatever it takes<br>
   to develop the perception that BA is "the place" for high school<br>
   students to gather/meet/mix.<br>
<p>
6) Focus on the smaller congregations, which are more likely to be aware of<br>
   their youth, and willing to ante up the bucks as required.<br>
<p>
7) How can BA's strong academic program be advertised?  Where are their<br>
   recent graduates?  How many are in top-notch colleges?  What are alumni<br>
   doing career-wise?<br>
<p>
8) If the Geneva-area public schools are hot stuff, how can BA exploit that?<br>
   Joint field trips, etc.?  Public school bureaucrats are not generally<br>
   known for flexibility, but teachers are usually interested in anything<br>
   which will enhance the learning experience, and will often put out the<br>
   extra effort to make something fly.<br>
<p>
9) It won't be long before the suburbs surround BA.  What are the pros/cons<br>
   of that?  Whether they stay or not, BA should be actively involved in<br>
   county planning, etc.  For example, where is the train extension going<br>
   to run?  Should it be routed close to the school, or a long ways away?<br>
   Imagine the advertising plus if a train stop is 100 yds from the campus.<br>
<p>
richard<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
