<title>Jun_1993: Post-institutionalism</title>
<h1>Post-institutionalism</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 18 Jun 1993 16:58:17 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#209">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#209">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#209">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#209">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0210.html">Gingerlei Tupito: "Re: White Lie"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0208.html">Richard Guy: "Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0261.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Post-institutionalism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Well, it's Friday afternoon again, and I'm sick of editing library records,<br>
so will chat a bit about SDA-net topics.  Steve, it was an interesting<br>
post, probably particularly for those of us employed by an SDA<br>
institution who have a vested interest in the outcome!  You raise issues<br>
that have been raised before, but which the corporate church seems<br>
reluctant to take decisive action.  The U.S. Congress isn't the only<br>
place of political gridlock.  The SDA church as in institution has many<br>
vested interests and geographical and political boundaries which are<br>
zealously defended.  In the Lake Union, I believe you would find Indiana<br>
and Wisconsin academies to be in not an appeciably different position<br>
from Broadview.<br>
<p>
First, I think your conference administration is wise to have town hall<br>
meetings to gather information and input.  Let's hope they're sincerely<br>
listening.  There can seldom be too much communication, and often is too<br>
little.  For the students going elsewhere, you need to find out why.<br>
Talk to the parents and students.  From things I've heard, you may have<br>
an administrative problem at Broadview.  Don't be defensive, but find<br>
out if that's really the case.  You will never please everyone, and it's<br>
good to have alternatives for those who you can't please.  Better that<br>
they go outside the Illinois Conference than to public school.  Focus<br>
group meetings are often a valuable source of information.  <br>
<p>
Somehow many church members no longer have a feeling of "ownership" of<br>
the institutions (this might also apply to the "SDA" health care<br>
institution(s) you mentioned).  Where there are problems, we need to<br>
find ways to work together toward resolution.<br>
<p>
However, I think other factors are at work also.  Many people of my<br>
generation seem infected with the disease of "yuppiedom."  As you noted,<br>
while receiving their education at SDA institutions, it's not "good<br>
enough" for their children.  There are faculty members of Andrews<br>
University who send their children to secular undergraduate institutions<br>
for this reason, and there are many other professionals who do the same.<br>
It would be really interesting to know if they really feel that their<br>
education was inferior.  I have two degrees from Andrews, and a degree<br>
from the University of North Carolina.  I don't feel there was any<br>
overall difference in the quality of education (though to read<br>
"rankings" you would certainly think so).  I had good and poor classes<br>
and teachers at both.  I would say that I should have had a class in<br>
philosophy at Andrews (we're too busy teaching religion to require<br>
that), and more exposure to the great books.  I do not feel I was inadequately<br>
prepared for graduate school or was at a disadvantage.  I wonder how<br>
others feel (including those who send their children elsewhere).<br>
Graduates with good grades from SDA colleges appear to have no difficulty<br>
in being accepted and doing well in top-grade graduate and professional<br>
schools (including Carnegie-Mellon, Steve!).<br>
<p>
There seems to be more going on here.  For one thing, when you really<br>
dig down, in some cases it's a matter of priorities.  Families would<br>
rather have a nicer car/house/you fill in the blank than pay tuition<br>
(though this would not apply to other private schools, which, believe it<br>
or not, might be even higher than ours!).  There seems also to be<br>
something of an obsession with status--the appearance of quality.<br>
Perhaps this is a side effect of a society saturated with marketing<br>
ploys.  Many, many times a year I see students (including ones right off<br>
the plane from overseas who can only speak minimal English) come to the<br>
library for the lists of colleges, including those sources that purport<br>
to "rank" them (that's another topic, which I won't get into here).<br>
It's like--I want to drive a BMW and send my kid to Harvard.  My cousin<br>
(WWC and LLU grad) certainly did that.  Perhaps the parents'<br>
relationship with the church is tenuous enough that they really don't<br>
care if there kids have one or not.  It's hard to say.<br>
<p>
I have seen weak programs continue because of administrative<br>
unwillingness to make the necessary changes.  It is also highly unlikely<br>
that the SDA church has the human or financial resources to operate the<br>
number of institutions that it has at a high performance level.  But the<br>
political structure is such that it would take a major national<br>
dislocation to change it, I'm afraid.  It's not like GM deciding to<br>
eliminate its least efficient facilities.  But the "weak sisters" help<br>
drag everyone down by taking resources that are needed to build better<br>
offerings elsewhere.<br>
<p>
In closing, we probably need to do a better job both of performance and<br>
of marketing (in its positive sense).  Many times, we don't even know<br>
who the market is.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
