<title>Jun_1993: Re: Goodbye</title>
<h1>Re: Goodbye</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 18 Jun 1993 17:34:25 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#213">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#213">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#213">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#213">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0214.html">John Prosper: "Truth and Time"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0212.html">Harvey Brenneise: "TV"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0179.html">Steven Timm: "Goodbye"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm sorry to see you go, Sue.  I hope you come back soon.  I have<br>
appreciated your postings, including your goodbye.  Please don't believe<br>
that all the male members of the list believe we have a God-given right<br>
to be "head" of women, and at least some of us do believe in the ordination<br>
of women.  [I have known Merikay since the heady days of the Pacific<br>
Press lawsuit--I grew up in Mtn. View as the child of a "Presstitute"!]<br>
I would also like to see more female participation in this list, and in<br>
fact have called for it a time or two!  I also suggest to colleages,<br>
male and female, that they might enjoy the list (and I believe I have<br>
talked some into it).<br>
<p>
Now for some speculation (it's Friday afternoon, remember?) about why<br>
the list is male oriented.  I think there are a number of reasons.  I<br>
suspect that perhaps more men than women presently have access to the<br>
requisite equipment.  I have noticed that a number of members are<br>
employees of computer-related companies.  Are the majority of employees<br>
at such places male?  Do more males have access to computers in the<br>
workplace than females?  Perhaps not since the advent of word-processing.<br>
Do women with computers have equal access to networks?  On this campus,<br>
I think the ratio of men and women with network access is dramatically<br>
changing with the installation of a campus-wide network.  Just yesterday<br>
I gave a training session for Seminary faculty and staff of Internet<br>
resources available via telnet.  I believe more secretaries came than<br>
"men" (unfortunately, I believe Nancy Vyhmeister remains the only female<br>
seminary faculty member--though she may also still be the only net<br>
member--good for you, Nancy).  Many males in power (including the<br>
president of this university) seem to think that computers (like<br>
typewriters) are for women.  Recently I saw my rich cousin at graduation<br>
and asked him if I could communicate via e-mail.  He didn't know his address--that was something his secretary did.<br>
<p>
I think there's something of a "boys with the toys" element with<br>
computers (outside word processing).  We certainly see this with<br>
stereos.  Recently there was a discussion of why most expensive stereo<br>
owners and CD collectors were male (this was in a stereo magazine).  For<br>
some reason, it seems to be a male compulsion.  Is it possible that some<br>
men have an easier time communicating "with a machine" than with real<br>
people?  Having worked closely with computing types over the last year,<br>
I would say human communication ability was not a strong point with many<br>
(fortunately, perhaps, the one who I worked with most closely is female<br>
and has been easy to communicate with).  Perhaps many women, even those<br>
with access, have other priorities in their lives.  Perhaps they feel<br>
they don't have time.  Perhaps the topics don't interest them--too much<br>
religion an politics perhaps.  At social events, men and women often separate<br>
and talk about quite different things.  This list hasn't had a lot of<br>
flames, but that could be a deterrent also.<br>
<p>
I believe as an institution the church needs to make a conscious decision<br>
to include women in decsion-making positions and roles.  Working in a<br>
profession with many females shows me quite clearly that men and women<br>
can work together quite harmoniously in reaching common objectives<br>
(though there still seem to be a disproportionate number of men in the<br>
"higher" positions).  <br>
<p>
It seems to me that gender roles are going through a period of<br>
tremendous change, not only the relationship of men and women, but<br>
groups of men and women.  The notions of feminine and masculine are<br>
changing, and that means both men and women.  I have read a number of<br>
recent books on "men's studies," and have found them useful.  Rather<br>
than being anti-female, they are trying to redefine masculinity.  It<br>
seems to me that men and women need both their own space and shared<br>
space, and working these spaces out in an egalatarian way without being<br>
discriminatory.  We will all have to change.  Some groups of men have<br>
ruled over others as well as over women.  The hierarchy (patriarchy, if<br>
you will) is more complex than just men and women.  Techniques of<br>
control and manipulation used by some women (I won't get too specific<br>
here) also need to change.<br>
<p>
I recently heard a report on National Public Radio about women<br>
scientists that indicated that most of them had attended female<br>
colleges.  I certainly feel that there is room in our society for such,<br>
though I would hope that women can achieve their full potential  in our<br>
coed schools as well.  Some interests and tendencies just seem to be<br>
inborn.  My mother and sister tried very hard to interest my son in<br>
dolls.  My daugher later adopted them all.  I have noticed that while my<br>
son and nephew are playing computer, my daugher and neice tend to stay<br>
away, but when the boys leave, the girls happily play with it.  I'm<br>
trying hard to make sure they have equal opportunity (perhaps I should<br>
also say that I need equal opportunity!).  When my daugher says she'd<br>
like to be a teacher (like Mom and Grandma), I also encourage her to<br>
think about doctor and scientist.  We shall see.<br>
<p>
Good luck, Sue, and God bless.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
