<title>Jun_1993: TV</title>
<h1>TV</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 18 Jun 1993 17:43:30 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#212">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#212">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#212">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#212">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0213.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Goodbye"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Truth and Time"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I can't agree with Dan Gill that no one should own a TV.  However, I do<br>
believe that the TV shouldn't own you!  I think I was fortunate that my<br>
parents didn't buy a TV until I was a junior in high school.  By that<br>
time I had found many other ways to use my time than watch TV.  The<br>
public library was only 4 blocks away, and I used it a lot (probably had<br>
something to do with my present profession!).  I do feel handicapped,<br>
however, when playing trivial pursuit type games (or watching Jeopardy!)<br>
because I don't know anything about Gilligan's Island, or whatever!<br>
&lt;grin&gt;<br>
<p>
I do own a TV now because I do have enough time to watch just a bit<br>
(usually time-shifting so I can skip the ads!).  As a reference<br>
librarian, it is useful to know what's in the news.  Believe it or not,<br>
I do enjoy an occasional PBS show (usually Masterpiece Theatre).  On<br>
cable, I find the weather channel useful in planning my day.  Other than<br>
that I've made a little deal with myself--I watch TV and Nordic Trak at<br>
the same time.  It helps increase the exercise and decrease the TV.  I<br>
only watch something like Jeopardy! while I'm tracking.<br>
<p>
I have had to limit the kids' TV.  My son would rather read or play<br>
computer games (an equally potentially insidiously compulsive activity),<br>
but my daughter is in danger of becoming a TV-aholic.  After she<br>
disregarded our summer TV rules, I simply disconnected the cable and<br>
locked up a crucial connection.  She needs to learn to read first.<br>
<p>
As in reading or anything else we do, I think we need to use TV with<br>
discretion.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
