<!-- subject="Truth and Time" -->
<!-- id="9306191717.AA19602@nu.cs.fsu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Jun_1993: Truth and Time</title>
<h1>Truth and Time</h1>
John Prosper (<i>prosper@nu.cs.fsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 19 Jun 93 13:17:52 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#214">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#214">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#214">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#214">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0215.html">Harvey Brenneise: "eulogy for dennis (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0213.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Goodbye"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
According to Dan Crowe:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Marcus mentioned some time ago that EGW repeatedly used phrases like</i><br>
<i>&gt; "truth for this time".  The implication was that if it was truth for her</i><br>
<i>&gt; time it is not truth for our time, and further that this implication leads</i><br>
<i>&gt; naturally to the conclusion that much of the Bible was truth for the time</i><br>
<i>&gt; at which it was written but is no longer truth for our time.</i><br>
<p>
Dan,<br>
<p>
I didn't get the impression that Marcus implied any such thing (something<br>
which he confirmed in a later post).  Nor did I receive that impression<br>
from EGW.<br>
<p>
What I do gather from EGW is a truth which was taught by Paul in 1 Cor.<br>
13: namely, truth (or the relevance of truth) will pass away (1 Cor.<br>
13:8-13).  Only love is eternal.<br>
<p>
This is NOT to say that prophetic words (e.g., the Bible) are meaningless. <br>
Indeed, we are taught that the historical events recorded were designed to<br>
serve as examples for us (1 Cor. 10:6,10), to keep us from setting our<br>
hearts on sinful things.<br>
<p>
Obviously, if we pass on to Heaven, the Biblical admonitions will cease to<br>
have quite the same eternal-life-or-eternal-damnation consequences which<br>
they do in this probationary life.  (Note please, that I am NOT saying we<br>
can do whatever we want in Heaven since, after all, the Law will always be<br>
in effect.  I am merely recognizing that since we would be finally separated<br>
from the influence of the evil one, it becomes so much easier to do the<br>
Father's Will.)   The principles which the prophets have labored to teach us<br>
will have become second nature.<br>
<p>
Nevertheless, there are particular issues which the church must address<br>
that were not prevalent issues in the distant (Biblical) past; AIDS,<br>
thermo-nuclear warfare, black-white-Oriental-female prejudice etc.  Even though<br>
Biblical principles cover all of these, at times we apparently have<br>
difficulties mapping the Biblically recorded events into our present situations.<br>
<p>
As a classic example of this, Jesus addressed the evil of discrimination<br>
for all time when He treated the Samaritan woman by Jacob's well (John<br>
4:1-42) like she was a fellow Jew to the surprise of His apostles as<br>
they returned from buying food (John 4:27).   As EGW reported in The Desire of<br>
Ages,<br>
<p>
	"The Jews and Samaritans were bitter enemies, and as far as possible<br>
	avoided all dealing with each other.  To trade with the Samaritans in<br>
	case of necessity was indeed counted lawful by the rabbis; but all<br>
	social intercourse with them was condemned.  A Jew would not borrow<br>
	from a Samaritan, nor receive a kindness, not even a morsel of bread or<br>
	a cup of water.  The disciples, in buying food, were acting in harmony<br>
	with the custom of their nation.  But beyond this they did not go.  To<br>
	ask a favor of the Samaritans, or in any way seek to benefit them, did<br>
	not enter into the thought of even Christ's disciples."<br>
<p>
Still, Jesus asked the Samaritan woman for water; an act which was most<br>
decidedly unJewish and unSamaritan-ish alike.<br>
<p>
I find it difficult for we white, black, Oriental, Jew, Non-Jew, rich, poor,<br>
heterosexual, homosexual, male, female, SDA, non SDA (or any other<br>
manifestation of bigotry) bigots to read this and not see ourselves.  Yet the<br>
subtle and not-so-subtle hatred exhibited all in the name of God whenever<br>
topics such as homosexuality, masculine dominance, and the like are broached<br>
seems to indicate that the lesson demonstrated by Jesus was not learned, that<br>
we have yet to map this truth about a specific manifestation of one sin to all<br>
manifestations of that sin.<br>
<p>
There are no longer any Samaritans for us to scratch our prejudicial claws<br>
on, so that specific truth is no more.  However, the greater principle<br>
(i.e., truth) of loving others who are different from us, of accentuating our<br>
similarities and common needs rather than our disparities remains.<br>
<p>
Some have attempted to address this using the oft-quoted phrase "hate the sin,<br>
but love the sinner".  Certainly, the phrase is NOT incorrect!  Unfortunately,<br>
I'm afraid that phrase has gone the path of most oft-quoted phrases where it<br>
is used so often that it loses relevance for the listener, becoming an<br>
ideological plant vainly attempting to flourish without any contextual roots.<br>
<p>
Paul teaches us that love is the greatest gift of the Spirit and the only one<br>
required for us to take before gaining entry to the Kingdom (1 Cor. 13).  In<br>
the same discourse, he also teaches that the lesser gifts are no substitute<br>
for love, that the lesser gifts, indeed, have no Divine meaning apart from<br>
love (1 Cor. 13:1-3).<br>
<p>
In the light of the above, may I not-so-humbly propose a corollary to the<br>
"truth for our times" phrasing:<br>
<p>
	Truth (as well as any lesser gift) has no Divine meaning unless it<br>
	is seasoned with Divinely-inspired love.<br>
<p>
(If perchance this phrase becomes oft-quoted enough, it shall probably too<br>
become an ideological plant without roots!)<br>
<p>
What this implies is that we are not use the Bible like a mindless,<br>
Bible-quoting parrot to condemn those stuck in unpopular sins (e.g.,<br>
homosexuality) or to exalt ourselves to a status not sanctioned by the Bible<br>
(e.g., male dominance).<br>
<p>
In the less-than two years that I have been a SDA-ist (having defected<br>
successively from a number of other churches), I must say that Adventists are<br>
the most conceited Christians I have ever met.  We love to brag about being<br>
the "church of truth", yet we suffer from the same sins which afflict other<br>
denominations (including non-denominational entities, whatever those are).  <br>
This makes us all the more worse since we have received more Light than the<br>
others and, consequently, have inherited a greater responsibility to<br>
demonstrate the Love of the Godhead in our lives.  It profits us nothing to be<br>
able to quote the Bible backwards and forwards if we cannot apply It to our<br>
lives and problems.<br>
<p>
I had better close for now as I feel a preaching fit threatening to overwhelm<br>
me.  (Can't you see that I am doing my Father's work?)<br>
<p>
<p>
+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+<br>
<i>|				John A. Prosper                             |</i><br>
+	     Florida State University Computer Science Department           +<br>
<i>|	     Internet: prosper@cs.fsu.edu  prosper@magnet.fsu.edu           |</i><br>
+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
