<title>Jun_1993: eulogy for dennis (fwd)</title>
<h1>eulogy for dennis (fwd)</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 19 Jun 1993 14:46:16 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#215">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#215">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#215">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#215">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0216.html">Steven Timm: "Logos, Ethos, Pathos"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0214.html">John Prosper: "Truth and Time"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0218.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  eulogy for dennis (fwd)"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This is the eulogy for fellow netter Dennis Grumbling, given by a<br>
professional colleague at the funeral.  It had been posted to a library<br>
listserv, and I asked if it could also be distributed to SDA-Net.<br>
<p>
Harvey<br>
<p>
Forwarded message:<br>
<i>&gt; From dlg1@midway.uchicago.edu Fri Jun 18 18:54:14 1993</i><br>
<i>&gt; Date: Fri, 18 Jun 93 17:54:01 CDT</i><br>
<i>&gt; From: deborah lynn gillaspie &lt;dlg1@midway.uchicago.edu&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; To: brneise</i><br>
<i>&gt; Subject: eulogy for dennis</i><br>
<i>&gt; Message-Id: &lt;CMM.0.90.4.740444041.dlg1@quads.uchicago.edu&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Harvey,</i><br>
<i>&gt; I'm delighted to provide you with a copy, thanks for taking care of SDA</i><br>
<i>&gt; net for me. Heidi is in Berrien, so I wouldn't have gotten to it till</i><br>
<i>&gt; she got back. Please feel free to disseminate it to whoever would want</i><br>
<i>&gt; it. I'm compelled to point out that I'm not Adventist, so it may not</i><br>
<i>&gt; meet Adventist doctrinal standards there at the end. The Gaelic poem was</i><br>
<i>&gt; chosen because Heidi spent time in Scotland, and I thought it would be</i><br>
<i>&gt; meaningful for her. It came from a book of old Gaelic prayers and blessings</i><br>
<i>&gt; put out by a Christian press in Edinburgh.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Dennis and I were quite close, and delivering his eulogy is one of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; hardest things I have ever had to do.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Yours, Debbie</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; ***********************************</i><br>
<i>&gt; In Memoriam  Dennis Grumling 1959-1993</i><br>
<i>&gt; Eulogy delivered at memorial service, June 14, 1993</i><br>
<i>&gt; ****************************************************</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I'd like to tell you a little about Dennis' background, then talk a bit</i><br>
<i>&gt; about how much he meant to those of us who knew him as a colleague.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Dennis Grumling was a minister's child, the son of Alvin and Mary Grumbling.</i><br>
<i>&gt; He was born in Stockton, CA, June 27, 1959, so he would have been 35 at</i><br>
<i>&gt; the end of this month. He had one older brother, Gary.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; His parents moved around a lot, as clergy families do. He went to high</i><br>
<i>&gt; school in Newark, Ohio. He began his college degree at Johns Hopkins</i><br>
<i>&gt; University in 1976, and attended there two years on a National Merit </i><br>
<i>&gt; Scholarship, but when we changed his major to Theology he transferred to</i><br>
<i>&gt; Ashland College and graduated from there in 1980. Later that year he </i><br>
<i>&gt; entered Andrews University's M.Div. program. He took a year off in 1981</i><br>
<i>&gt; to be assistant pastor of the Worthington, Ohio Seventh Day Adventist</i><br>
<i>&gt; Church, then returned to the seminary in 1982-83 to finish his degree.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Although his experiences in the pastorate eventually led him to conclude</i><br>
<i>&gt; that it was not the career for him, he remained active in the church as</i><br>
<i>&gt; an Elder and played an important role in providing support for new members</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the church. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; In the fall of 1983, he entered the Library School at Indiana University,</i><br>
<i>&gt; where he was awarded the M.L.S. and elected to the library honor society</i><br>
<i>&gt; Beta Phi Mu in 1984.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; On June 17, 1984, he and Heidi Vyhmeister married. They went to Puerto</i><br>
<i>&gt; Rico on mission at Antillian College later in 1984, where Dennis was </i><br>
<i>&gt; head of Technical Services at the library until they came to Chicago</i><br>
<i>&gt; in Dec. 1986. In Puerto Rico he learned to snorkel, a passion that stayed</i><br>
<i>&gt; with him all his life.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; In January 1987 he entered the PhD program at the now closed Graduate</i><br>
<i>&gt; Library School of the University of Chicago, on a full tuition scholarship.</i><br>
<i>&gt; He was two chapters from the end of his dissertation at the time of his</i><br>
<i>&gt; death.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; His professional specialty was cataloging, which is the art of putting</i><br>
<i>&gt; information away so that reference librarians like me can find it again</i><br>
<i>&gt; when somebody asks for it. His professional life was extremely active</i><br>
<i>&gt; and varied. In addition to working as a cataloger at Antillian, University</i><br>
<i>&gt; of Illinois - Chicago, and DePaul, he did a lot of consulting. Many of </i><br>
<i>&gt; you probably aren't aware that much of his programming work was done for</i><br>
<i>&gt; community programs serving indigents, and he donated a lot of his time or</i><br>
<i>&gt; worked as substantially reduced consulting rates. He also did a lot of</i><br>
<i>&gt; consulting for Adventist mission churches overseas, acting as a resource</i><br>
<i>&gt; for those often isolated librarians. He was librarian and programmer to</i><br>
<i>&gt; Mortimer Adler of the Institute for Philosophical Research, and while</i><br>
<i>&gt; there worked on the last revision of the Great Books Series. He taught</i><br>
<i>&gt; cataloging at Indiana U's Gary campus, and participated in the Professional</i><br>
<i>&gt; Development Program run by academic libraries here in Chicago. He was active</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the American Society for Information Science, the Association of Seventh</i><br>
<i>&gt; Day Adventist Librarians, and the American Library Association. At the</i><br>
<i>&gt; time of his death, he was Book Review editor for the professional journal</i><br>
<i>&gt; Cataloging and Classification Quarterly, and was head of the Cataloging</i><br>
<i>&gt; Department at DePaul University's Library.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Those are the basics. I could also add that he was honest, trustworthy,</i><br>
<i>&gt; loyal, brave, and loving, but it begins to sound like a Scout Oath, and</i><br>
<i>&gt; none of what I've said so far really tells you anything about why those</i><br>
<i>&gt; of us who were in library school with him and worked with him loved him</i><br>
<i>&gt; so. The way he enriched my life will probably strike a chord among many</i><br>
<i>&gt; of you, so I'd like to talk a little about it.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Dennis and I were the last two PhD students admitted to the Graduate</i><br>
<i>&gt; Library School, and we got caught in the pipeline as it closed. Because</i><br>
<i>&gt; the other doctoral students were far ahead of us in the program, and far</i><br>
<i>&gt; from us geographically, we became close friends. It's a lot like being</i><br>
<i>&gt; two soldiers in a foxhole; you either come to love or to hate the other</i><br>
<i>&gt; person in the foxhole.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; We sat glazy-eyed through the same courses and complained about professors' </i><br>
<i>&gt; expectations. Once we started working in libraries, we joked about mounting</i><br>
<i>&gt; a hostile takeover of some academic library, since between us we felt we</i><br>
<i>&gt; had the reference and technical services skills to run it "right." We read</i><br>
<i>&gt; each other's proposals and papers, a process always referred to as</i><br>
<i>&gt; "trashing," our code word for the ruthless editing we felt we owed each</i><br>
<i>&gt; other's work. Though time consuming, it was always fun because Dennis </i><br>
<i>&gt; possessed a wit as sharp as his editing pencil, and we never failed to</i><br>
<i>&gt; enjoy the jokes and absurdities that doctoral students and academics</i><br>
<i>&gt; everywhere must endure.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Most important, however, we provided a safety net of emotional support</i><br>
<i>&gt; for each other in situations that ranged from academic frustrations to</i><br>
<i>&gt; problems at work to attending each other's sessions at conferences so</i><br>
<i>&gt; we'd be assured of ONE friendly face (and where we'd turn each other's</i><br>
<i>&gt; overheads and make faces when the audience couldn't see, in an attempt</i><br>
<i>&gt; to reduce tension for whichever of us was facing the audience.)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; There is no greater love that one doctoral student can have for another,</i><br>
<i>&gt; than to hold the hand of that colleague before a dissertation proposal</i><br>
<i>&gt; defense at the University of Chicago. That's the BIG one, the defense </i><br>
<i>&gt; where your work can be stalled forever due to real or perceived problems</i><br>
<i>&gt; (or the mood of the faculty that day.) For about four weeks before our</i><br>
<i>&gt; respective ordeals, we were simply impossible to live with -- ask our</i><br>
<i>&gt; spouses! Only your foxhold buddy will put up with you during something</i><br>
<i>&gt; like that, because he knows exactly what you are going through. We both</i><br>
<i>&gt; defended successfully, and celebrated with the chocolate he loved so</i><br>
<i>&gt; much.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; And now he's gone. And there's a big emotional hole in my life. And there</i><br>
<i>&gt; is one for all of us who knew we could call Dennis and get an answer</i><br>
<i>&gt; to questions like, "How do I get this file to print right?" or "How</i><br>
<i>&gt; do I catalog THIS thing?" or even just "I'm having a bad day -- got any</i><br>
<i>&gt; chocolate?"  We miss him now, and we will keep on missing him, even after</i><br>
<i>&gt; the sharp pain of loss has faded to the gentle grief that the passage of</i><br>
<i>&gt; time brings to those left behind. This old Gaelic blessing may bring us</i><br>
<i>&gt; comfort, reminding us that both birth and death are important to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; ever-renewing cycle of life:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 			As it was</i><br>
<i>&gt; 		 	As it is</i><br>
<i>&gt; 			As it shall be</i><br>
<i>&gt; 			Evermore,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 			O Thou Triune of Grace!</i><br>
<i>&gt; 			With the ebb,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 			With the flow,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 			O Thou Triune of Grace!</i><br>
<i>&gt; 			With the ebb</i><br>
<i>&gt; 			With the flow.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Deborah L. Gillaspie, June 14, 1993</i><br>
<i>&gt; **************************************************************</i><br>
<i>&gt; The poem is entitled "Fragment," and it comes from Alexander</i><br>
<i>&gt; Carmichael, THE SUN DANCES: PRAYERS AND BLESSINGS FROM THE GAELIC,</i><br>
<i>&gt; Edinburgh: Floris Books, 1960. ISBN 0-903540-07X, p. 117</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; ******************************************************************</i><br>
<i>&gt; * Internet: d-gillaspie@uchicago.edu OR dlg1@midway.uchicago.edu * </i><br>
<i>&gt; * Bitnet:   dlg1%midway@uchicago                                 *</i><br>
<i>&gt; *                                                                * </i><br>
<i>&gt; ******************************************************************</i><br>
<i>&gt;   </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<!-- body="end" -->
