<title>Jun_1993: Logos, Ethos, Pathos</title>
<h1>Logos, Ethos, Pathos</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 20 Jun 1993 08:59:18 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#216">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#216">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#216">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#216">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0217.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Logos, Ethos, Pathos"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0215.html">Harvey Brenneise: "eulogy for dennis (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'd like to spend a thought or two discussing how it is that a certain <br>
thought comes to be perceived as truth by a person or a group of people.<br>
This relates to several of the discussions we have had lately.  (Note,<br>
I'm not a Greek scholar, but I study about lots of particles with fancy <br>
Greek names :))<br>
<p>
Pathos, as I understand it, deals with the domain of the feelings and <br>
emotions.  This is the gut-level emotional "yes" that comes with the <br>
conviction of truth, and is part of faith and the conversion experience<br>
whether we would like to think so or not.  Believing in God necessarily<br>
requires pathos.  (As does believing in [no God]).<br>
<p>
Logos is the Word (and in the context of the Bible, the word of God).<br>
It is the Word that gives us guidance as to what to believe about God<br>
and how to believe in God.  Pathos without reference to Logos is bound<br>
to go astray.<br>
<p>
Ethos deals with the set of ethics:  what is right and wrong, and why.<br>
Most Christians believe this too should be rooted in the Logos.<br>
<p>
When cognitive dissonance occurs, it's often due to the fact that one<br>
is convicted with _pathos_ that the current interpretation of logos <br>
and ethos is wrong.  To those who do not share the life experience or the<br>
background and feelings of this person, they do not and cannot see the<br>
moral imperative to change that is based on pathos.  Furthermore, they<br>
only see the pathos and often have difficulties understanding the <br>
underlying logos and ethos, if any, that drives the demand of this <br>
person.  <br>
<p>
How can people who feel there is a moral imperative communicate their<br>
logos and ethos to the SDA church as a whole?  Or should they have to do<br>
this?  Is "I feel that this action is right and therefore we must accept<br>
it"<br>
enough?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
