<title>Jun_1993: Child Guidance &amp; Sabbath</title>
<h1>Child Guidance &amp; Sabbath</h1>
Dan Crowe (<i>dcrowe@puc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 20 Jun 1993 11:01:49 -0700 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#226">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#226">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#226">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#226">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0227.html">Michael Merginio: "Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0225.html">K-leb D'Cat: "Sex Changers.  Please do not reply.  My A/C is about to close."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yesterday afternoon (Sabbath) I was fellowshipping with some of my church<br>
family when a sister, a mother of a four-year-old boy, asked a question about <br>
children playing on Sabbath.  We began a study of the chapter "Sabbath -<br>
The Day of Delight" in Child Guidance (pp. 527-37).  I had never read this<br>
chapter before.  I highly recommend that all Adventists who have contact<br>
with children on Sabbath read this chapter.<br>
<p>
To summarize the main conclusions, EGW advises us to spend time on<br>
Sabbath with our children, especially studying God's goodness as expressed<br>
in nature.  They should not be left to play secular games on Sabbath.<br>
I plan to modify my Sabbath activities with my six-year-old son.<br>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
