<title>Jun_1993: Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not...</title>
<h1>Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not...</h1>
Michael Merginio (<i>merginim@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 20 Jun 1993 17:33:51 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#227">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#227">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#227">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#227">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0228.html">Steven Timm: "4340 messages and counting"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0226.html">Dan Crowe: "Child Guidance &amp; Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0208.html">Richard Guy: "Re: Post-institutionalism: Ready or not..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Netters,<br>
<p>
Richard had some suggestions concerning BVA, and being an alumnus of<br>
Broadview I felt that some comments should be made concerning those<br>
suggestions.  Of course not having really been active around BVA since<br>
1991 (the year my youngest brother graduated from BVA), the information<br>
stated herein may be inaccurate.  But was accurate up until at least 1990.<br>
<p>
On Fri, 18 Jun 1993, Richard Guy wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Suggestions w.r.t. Broadview Academy:</i><br>
<i>&gt; Is BA actively selling itself?  Part of the difficulty is that in the past</i><br>
<i>&gt; SDA education survived solely on "cultural imperative to attend"; now it</i><br>
<i>&gt; must seriously compete, and the system doesn't know how.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
	First let me say, before I went to BVA, and up until my graduation, <br>
they actively recruited among the churches and church schools in Illinois. <br>
Since my graduation I have no idea if they are still recruiting.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 1) Figure out where potential students actually live, and show every single</i><br>
<i>&gt;    one of them exactly what the commuting options are: train, bus, EL, and</i><br>
<i>&gt;    so on.  It really isn't very far from the Geneva station to Broadview,</i><br>
<i>&gt;    which suggests that Broadview might want to run a shuttle service from</i><br>
<i>&gt;    the station to the campus.  Train service is remarkably comfortable by</i><br>
<i>&gt;    US standards; the number of folks who commute from Geneva-area suburbs</i><br>
<i>&gt;    to all parts of the city is impressive, so why not promote the reverse</i><br>
<i>&gt;    commute for school kids?  </i><br>
<i>&gt;    This may mean adjusting BA's class schedule to accomodate trains, but</i><br>
<i>&gt;    there's nothing sacred about 8am-2pm.</i><br>
<p>
	Well, being a BVA alum (and proud of it),  I must say this would<br>
be a very _large_ problem.  Extra-curricular activities such as band,<br>
gymnastics and choir are at the extreme ends of the class schedule<br>
(starting at 6:45 a.m. for band and 5:00 p.m. for gym &amp; choir).  I haven't<br>
seen a schedule lately, but the schedule hasn't changed much in many<br>
years.  Also, having a schedule like Richard suggests would cause havoc on<br>
the work schedules of the students.  I mean its those working dollars from<br>
industries which come from outside the church which have helped keep the <br>
school on somewhat better ground than a lot of other academies.  Being<br>
able to count on labor to help pay my tuition was a great thing to have<br>
considering my parents really couln't afford to pay for my "academy<br>
experience."  But if you're planning on just catering to the "well off"<br>
then by all means go ahead with an 8-3 schedule.  But the majority of<br>
young people that went to BVA when I attended were not rich, although<br>
there were always those few who were.  If I remember correctly, though,<br>
there were a lot of kids that were there from broken homes &amp; other unique<br>
situations.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 3) Schools need to be more flexible with payment options, etc., and at the</i><br>
<i>&gt;    same time uphold the right mix of standards based on principles.  BA is</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
	Amen!  It seems that the same thing needs to go for the Universities &amp;<br>
hospitals in the Adventist system as well.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 4) Pay teachers to go out and recruit on weekends, holidays, etc.</i><br>
<i>&gt;    Promote student-led recruitment activities at their home congregations.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
	Hey, why not pay students as well. <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 6) Focus on the smaller congregations, which are more likely to be aware of</i><br>
<i>&gt;    their youth, and willing to ante up the bucks as required.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
	I don't know about your church, but the "small" congregation that<br>
I came from pretty much only focused on the adults &amp; children.  The teens<br>
&amp; young adults were pretty much left to their own devices.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 9) It won't be long before the suburbs surround BA.  What are the pros/cons</i><br>
<i>&gt;    of that?  Whether they stay or not, BA should be actively involved in</i><br>
<i>&gt;    county planning, etc.  For example, where is the train extension going</i><br>
<i>&gt;    to run?  Should it be routed close to the school, or a long ways away?</i><br>
<i>&gt;    Imagine the advertising plus if a train stop is 100 yds from the campus.</i><br>
<p>
	Actually the railroad already runs 200 yards from the academy's<br>
entrance.  Currently, however, there are no passenger trains that go beyond<br>
Geneva on those tracks.  I think it would be a great idea to have the train<br>
go as far as BVA, even if it was only 2 or 3 times each day.  It would not<br>
just be a great way to comute to school, but also for parents to come and take<br>
part in some of the activities or even Sabbath School and Church.<br>
<p>
<p>
Anyway, that is how I remember things being at BVA.  If this adds to the<br>
discussion, then great, if not, life will go on.<br>
<p>
<pre>
--
Wishing you the best in your Walk With Christ,
Michael B. Merginio
merginim@andrews.edu
<p>
James White Library, Periodicals Dept., Berrien Springs, MI 49104-1300
======================================================================
I believe that in our world, this is one rule that everyone
	should follow, and that is - TELL IT LIKE IT IS!!!!!
	The truth may hurt, but lies, or witholding the truth 
	makes it hurt even more.    --M.B. Merginio
Another key to life is to ask yourself-- Would Christ be happy 
	if I did this?  If you don't think so, then don't! 
Disclaimer--Only blame ME for the Opinions Expressed in this message.
