<title>Jun_1993: SDAnet fellowship</title>
<h1>SDAnet fellowship</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>21 Jun 1993 11:03:17 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#222">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#222">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#222">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#222">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0223.html">Steven Timm: "Are you afraid of Ghosts?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0221.html">lsusers: "Truth for our time"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dear fellow net members,<br>
<p>
I just wanted to say how much I enjoyed reading Friday's SDAnet<br>
mail. There have been times during my year-or-so on SDAnet when I have felt<br>
as though I have all-too-little in common with "good" SDAs, and when I have<br>
felt discouraged by it all, but these times are balanced out by other instances<br>
where I feel some weird sense of companionship. With people I haven't even met!!<br>
<p>
So to Fred, Harvey, John, and all the rest of you, thanks for taking the time<br>
to share how you feel. I for one, and I think I speak for most of us, do<br>
appreciate the fellowship.<br>
<p>
Steve wrote:<br>
<i>&gt;When cognitive dissonance occurs, it's often due to the fact that one</i><br>
<i>&gt;is convicted with _pathos_ that the current interpretation of logos </i><br>
<i>&gt;and ethos is wrong.</i><br>
<p>
I have also had the one where my head tells me that my current<br>
position is inconsistent or incorrect, but my heart tells me it's right.<br>
<p>
Both these forms of cognitive dissonance are difficult to deal with as a<br>
Christian. Even before you try to convince anyone else, you have to have it<br>
sorted out for yourself! My problem has often been related to confusion over<br>
how the Holy Spirit works. On the one hand, some tell me that "higher<br>
education" and "higher criticism" are damaging to my faith, and cannot help<br>
me discern spiritual truth. Then others use debates and points of logic to<br>
show why such and such is the correct understanding. Does the Holy Spirit<br>
move the heart, the head, or both? Is he usually a "still, small voice"<br>
distinguishing right from wrong, or a dove moving upon the soul? If this<br>
question had a once-for-all answer, then logos/pathos dissonance would be<br>
easy to resolve. Providing the still small voice always spoke up!<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;How can people who feel there is a moral imperative communicate their</i><br>
<i>&gt;logos and ethos to the SDA church as a whole?  Or should they have to do</i><br>
<i>&gt;this?  Is "I feel that this action is right and therefore we must accept</i><br>
<i>&gt;it" enough?</i><br>
<p>
I like to see open communication occur in such a situation. "I feel that this<br>
action is right, but I cannot explain why. What do you think?", maybe. An<br>
attempt to convey the concrete thoughts behind the feeling is usually<br>
worthwhile, even if it is impossible to give all the experiences leading up<br>
to those thoughts.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
