<title>Jun_1993: Re: Post-institutionalism</title>
<h1>Re: Post-institutionalism</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 25 Jun 1993 18:10:56 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#261">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#261">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#261">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#261">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0262.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Self-supporting institutions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0260.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Mission to Russia?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0209.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Post-institutionalism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0275.html">Bill Nickless: "Re: Post-institutionalism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
After having read both Richard's and Michael's postings to the net (and<br>
having also talked to Michael--it is handy he works in the same<br>
building!), I have a few more comments/questions about Broadview<br>
Academy.  They center around whether or not BVA wishes to become in part<br>
or even in its entirely a commuting school.<br>
<p>
I went to Mtn. View Academy, a day school in California.  For all of its<br>
history (and it's now 70 years old) it has drawn commuting students from<br>
San Francisco, San Jose and elsewhere.  Many of these came by Southern<br>
Pacific commuter train.  A typical day for a SF student was to get up<br>
very early (5-ish), get a bus to the train station, and take the train<br>
down the Peninsula, picking up additional students along the way from<br>
places like Burlingame and meeting the students coming north at the old<br>
Mtn. View train station and walking the 5-7 blocks to the school.  They<br>
then reversed the process in the evening.  At least they could study on<br>
the train.  Others came by auto and bus from much of the Bay Area.  A<br>
long day for many of them, to say the least (I was lucky enough to live<br>
3 blocks from the school).  Unfortunately, Mtn. View Academy has also<br>
fallen on hard times, partially due to the exodus of the Pacific Press<br>
and the conference office to cheaper locales (there are some<br>
disadvantages to being squarely in the middle of "Silicon Valley"--I<br>
really can't stand that name for my native Santa Clara Valley, but<br>
that's another story!).  This mix of students worked quite well for MVA<br>
partly because all of the students were day students.  I would add that<br>
many of these students were from ethnic groups that enhanced the<br>
diversity of the school.  They also had a 10-grade school in SF, so at<br>
least the younger students didn't have the long commute (although those<br>
from Burlingame did).<br>
<p>
One issue would be, Is it possible to successfully mix large contingents<br>
of day and boarding students.  In the past, many boarding schools<br>
(Monterey Bay, for example) tried hard to avoid this.  As Michael<br>
mentioned, running a "split schedule" for the sake of the industries<br>
does not work well with day students, although solutions might be found.<br>
I believe social issues also contributed to this.  I suspect it would be<br>
difficult to have the sort of control over the boarding students when<br>
there are many day students around who are much freer.  I believe this<br>
was a problem as far back as Battle Creek College, and was a major<br>
contributor to the move to the more rural location in Berrien Springs!<br>
There are academies which have managed this.  Thunderbird comes to mind.<br>
It's located in suburban Phoenix, AZ, and has (or at least used to have)<br>
both boarding and day students.  Auburn may be another.  I'm not sure;<br>
I've never been there.  There may be other examples.<br>
<p>
When I was teaching elementary/junior academy grades, I noticed a real<br>
trend for parents wanting to keep their children at home through the 9th<br>
or 10th grade before sending them away to school (epecially a boarding<br>
academy).  This has also had its impact on the academies they eventually<br>
attend.<br>
<p>
Just a few thoughts on a Friday afternoon.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
